abstract: The United States steamship John Rive, Commander HARRIS, which arrived at this port yesterday, reports having experienced a hurricane on the 22d of October, soon after leaving New-Orleans. They arrived at Port Jefferson on the 24th, and found that some government buildings had been blown down and the Post Quartermaster killed.
lead_paragraph: The United States steamship John Rive, Commander HARRIS, which arrived at this port yesterday, reports having experienced a hurricane on the 22d of October, soon after leaving New-Orleans. They arrived at Port Jefferson on the 24th, and found that some government buildings had been blown down and the Post Quartermaster killed. On arriving at Key West they learned that every ship in the harbor had been sunk or driven ashore. A man-of-war lay on the reefs. On leaving Key West they spoke the schooner D.W. Warner fo Brookhaven, Conn., which reported having lost the Captain overboard.

abstract: FATAL ACCIDENT. -- About noon yesterday, while a laboring man named DANIEL KEENAN, was employed in digging down to the sewer in Leonard-street, near Ainslie, E.D., for the purpose of connecting a main pipe, the earth thrown up gave way and completely buried him up. His lifeless body was brought to the surface after an hour's digging. KEENAN resided at the corner of North Fifth and Seventh-streets, and leaves a wife and five children. His remains were taken to his late residence by Officer HENDRICKS, of the Forty-sixth Precinct. Coroner BARRETT will hold an inquest to-day, and investigate the cause of the accident.

abstract: The sudden removal of the British Premier from human affairs will probably facilitate the peaceful settlement of our difficulties with England. Though not in direct charge of the Foreign Department, beyond all doubt he had a large part in the practical shaping of its policy. That policy never more unmistakably bore his personal impress, even during the long years when he was the Foreign Secretary.
lead_paragraph: The sudden removal of the British Premier from human affairs will probably facilitate the peaceful settlement of our difficulties with England. Though not in direct charge of the Foreign Department, beyond all doubt he had a large part in the practical shaping of its policy. That policy never more unmistakably bore his personal impress, even during the long years when he was the Foreign Secretary. The one thing which, above all others, ever marked his diplomacy, was his eagerness to form revolutionary alliances, and at the very earliest stage. He began with the French revolution of July, 1830, but had no chance to deal with that in advance, since it was accomplished almost as soon as it was attempted. But he played no small part in the subsequent revolutionary movements of Belgium, Spain and Portugal, and ever afterward meddled, at every opportunity, on the continent in favor of the party of subversion. His attachment to liberal principles was not the motive, as was proved by his quickness to approve and recognise Louis NAPOLEON's coup de etat, for which he was compelled to leave office. The practice came from two other traits -- one, his constitutional fondness for troubled waters, and ingrained love of mischief, and the other his intense nationality of spirit, and consequent anxiety to build up British influence. These qualities not only shaped his policy toward revolutionary governments, prompting him to form the most intimate relation with them at the earliest stage, but continually manifested themselves in his ordinary treatment of foreign nations. There has hardly been a Cabinet in Europe, when he was in power, which he did not manage to offend by gaining some undue advantage. Nothing suited him better than to be walking on the giddy brink of war; and he habitually carried the spirit of war into the relations of peace. He always, whenever occasion offered, manifested this disposition toward our own country, whether out of power or in. Thus he made his famous onslaught upon the Ashburton treaty, stigmatizing it from his seat in Parliament as the "Ashburton capitulation." The fact is notorious that the United States have had no serious difficulties with England for the last quarter of a century that were not attributable to his policy. It was he that made the frivolous claim to the possession of the Bay Islands and the Mosquito protectorate; and he that persisted in a purpose to make enlistments in America for the British service, contrary to our laws. His whole tone and temper toward us, and his mode of applying principles to facts, as they arose, was always unfair and irritating -- in marked contrast with the manifestations of the Tory leaders, when they were in power, although every reason would have justified our expecting from each party precisely the reverse.

abstract: Intelligence Offices and Servants
snippet: Intelligence Offices and Servants
lead_paragraph: An article in the Nation on the much-vexed subject of "Servants" makes the excellent suggestion of a higher kind of "intelligence office," similar to one recently started in London, which shall be supported solely by the ladies. The present intelligence offices are, for all practical purposes, utterly useless to families. The servants recommend are often entirely untrustworthy; they make engagements to go to a place in the city or country, and then, without warning, coolly leave the employer in the lurch and the family unprovided for. They are no better fitted for their work, frequently, than girls that could be picked up in any tenement-house. The office never seems to pay the slightest attention to their references, and one may get a thievish or even a drunken servant from such an agency, without the slightest redress, and knowing that from that or some other office she will secure a good situation, as soon as she leaves you. The "help" that are furnished by many of the intelligence agencies are by no means worthy of their name. They are often ignorant of the simplest details of housekeeping; they cannot cook a steak or dust a room properly, or bake bread that can be eaten, or make up a bed. They are frequently slatternly, irregular and lazy. The choice in an office is worse than a ticket in a city lottery. One's chances of a prize are infinitesimal.

abstract: Some time ago JAMES SHAUGHNESSY, master of the sloop Sarah & Hester, applied to Capt. WILLIAM J. BABCOCK, of No. 223 Bay-street, Jersey City, requesting him to indorse a note for $200, and offering a bill of sale of the sloop as security. He subsequently asked Mr. BABCOCK to advance money for repairs, and Mr. BABCOCK expended $523 on the vessel, SHAUGHNESSY continuing to run her to the Kills for sand, and one day last week she was sunk at the Kills and abandoned by her master. Capt. BABCOCK raised the sloop and took possession, and on Saturday night, it is alleged, SHAUGHNESSY went to Capt. BABCOCK's pier with a junk-dealer and attempted to take away the vessel's rigging, but was surprised and driven off by the night watchman. Not to be balked thus, SHAUGHNESSY is alleged to have gone on board the sloop on Monday night, and with JOSEPH DUFFY to have stolen her at 1 o'clock yesterday morning. Cruising round the harbor, yesterday, Capt. BABCOCK discovered the Sarah & Hester moored at King-street. He thereupon applied at the Greenwich-street Police-station, and Roundsman HENRY V. abstract: By the City of Boston at this port, and the Damascus at Father Point, we have five days' later news from Europe. The most important intelligence is that of the death of Lord PALMERSTON, which occurred on the 18th ult. A sketch of the life and publics services of the great statesman will be found in another column. At last advices from London, his successor had not been appointed, owing to the absence of the Queen in Scotland, but it was rumored that the vacancy caused by his death would be filled by Earl RUSSELL. The London Times caused a momentary sensation by the publication of a rumor that Mr. SEWARD had sent an ultimatum to the French Government on the Mexican question; but the canard was immediately exposed. According to the Paris Temps, the number of deaths from cholera in the Department of the Seine, (Paris,) was averaging about 300 per day.

abstract: SUSPICION OF FOUL PLAY.--ANTOINETTE JUDSON, a young colored woman, left her place and friends in New-Haven, on the 9th ult., by the 10 o'clock train, for New-York, by arrangement to live in the family of a well-known clergyman in this city. Instead of taking the accommodation train, on which she was to meet him at Milford, she by mistake went with the express train, which starts about the same time, and so missed him altogether.
lead_paragraph: SUSPICION OF FOUL PLAY. -- ANTOINETTE JUDSON, a young colored woman, left her place and friends in New-Haven, on the 9th ult., by the 10 o'clock train, for New-York, by arrangement to live in the family of a well-known clergyman in this city. Instead of taking the accommodation train, on which she was to meet him at Milford, she by mistake went with the express train, which starts about the same time, and so missed him altogether. Nothing since has been heard from her by any of her friends, though inquiries have been made in every direction. It is feared that there is foul play in the case. She is a highly respectable woman and is greatly esteemed. She had no friends or acquaintances in the city, and had not the address if she remembered even the name of the gentleman she was to meet. Any information which could shed light on this case will be most thankfully received by her distressed family, and may be communicated to Rev. J.M. SHERWOOD, No. 5 Beekman-street, of this city.

abstract: Securities Abroad
snippet: Securities Abroad
lead_paragraph: -- The news by the Damascus assures us of the restoration of confidence abroad in the "good intentions" of our national rulers, and, consequently, in American securities. At an early hour, yesterday, the City of Boston reached this port, with advices of panic and depression in the money and stock circles of London, and a fall of 1 1/2@2 per cent. in United States 5-20s, under a false report which appeared in the London Times, to the effect that our government had sent "threatening letters" to France, and that indifference to our threats would assuredly lead to "a breach of the public peace." The one day later intelligence, by the Quebec steamer, indicates that the monied interests of the British capital had been convinced of the utter absurdity of such a mischievous rumor, and that there would be no danger -- save the seductive peril of making money -- in locking up hard cash in United States securities at the ruling figures in the London market. The quotations for Five-Twenties by the Damascus show that the ground lost prior to the departure of the City of Boston had been fully recovered. The market comes now reported as strong and buoyant. The probability is that decided improvement will be reported by the steamers now on their way hither. The latest London figures for United States Five-Twenties are 64 1/2@64 3/4, without the November coupon, representing three per cent in gold, the addition of which would make the closing prices, as reported by the Damascus, 67 1/2@67 3/4, or with gold at 146, equal to something over 107 1/4 in the home market.

abstract: Among the different new militia organizations now being raised in this city is a Zouave regiment, to wear the same uniform as that worn by the Fifth New-York, so favorably known during the late war as Duryee's Zouaves. abstract: -- The recent order of the government in reference to the Veteran Reserve Corps is of a perfectly satisfactory character. It simply gives to each man the right of declaring whether he desires to continue in the service. Those who say they do not, are at once mustered out, and those who say they do, are retained for the future action of Congress upon the corps. We doubt not that both the officers and men of this body who were disabled in the service of the country, will be generously dealt with. The pensions they receive when mustered out are very small, and go but a small way in their support. On the other hand, their availability for many of the military duties required in times of peace is equally great with that of those who are physically whole and healthy. It is an economy of the forces of the nation to retain such men in the service.

abstract: Thanksgiving Proclamation, for Dec. 7
snippet: Thanksgiving Proclamation, for Dec. 7
lead_paragraph: Never before had a people so much cause for thanksgiving. Every toiler in the realm of honorable industry is inspired with new encouragement and confidence. The moral, intellectual and religious interests of society have been steadily advancing, and the annals of the State and the nation have been consecrated by heroic achievements and patriotic devotion. The unhallowed disturbance of the nation's rights and security has yielded to the healthful calm of peace, resulting in the salvation and extension of the public liberties. And while the nation has been engaged in a civil war without parallel in spirit and dimensions, in our own State we have sowed and reaped undisturbed. A period of comparative prosperity, with trade and resources undiminished, has enabled us to bear, with enduring fortitude, the severe burdens imposed by war; presenting a chapter in human experience unexampled in the history of civil strife. We acknowledge the Providence of God, and rejoice in our prosperity as the triumph of a Commonwealth of freemen in the cause of Republican government.

abstract: Palmerston, Lord; the death of; Palmerston, Lord, Sketch of his Life
snippet: Palmerston, Lord; the death of; Palmerston, Lord, Sketch of his Life
lead_paragraph: The intelligence of the death of Viscount PALMERSTON, and which reached this city too late for publication in the morning papers of yesterday, will naturally be received by many persons with painful surprise. The deceased statesman had for some time been seriously ill, but, to all appearance, had completely recovered; it was said, indeed, that, after suffering a more than usually severe attack of gout, a more vigorous condition of body and mind was vouchsafed to him than he had enjoyed for years. His last illness was very brief, and the same telegram which announces it closes with the news of a fatal termination. And thus the fame of PALMERSTON, nay, the name itself, for, dying childless, his title becomes extinct, passes into history.

lead_paragraph: THE LATE HIGHWAY ROBBERY. -- JOHN LAIRD, who went by the name of McLEAN, when arrested, and JOHN DOUGHERTY, were brought before Justice CORNWELL yesterday for examination on the charge of having, on Sunday night last; committed a felonious assault upon EDWARD WILSON, and an aged man named HAMILTON, while passing the corner of Fulton and Columbia streets. Mr. WILSON was, at the same time, robbed of a watch worth $40. LAIRD was pursued by an officer and taken into custody. DOUGHERTY was arrested next day. The accused were fully identified, but in order to give their counsel time to procure some witnesses, the examination was adjourned till this afternoon.

abstract: At 2 o'clock yesterday afternoon, the funeral of Mr. FRANCIS J. LYON and his wife, who were scalded to death on board the St. John, on Sunday morning last, was solemnized at St. Luke's Church. The fact that on Thursday last the youthful couple were married in the same church, and that they had lost their lives while on their bridal tour, lent additional interest to the ceremonies. About noon the coffins were carried into the church and the coverings being removed, the bodies were seen habited in their bridal attire. A very large assemblage of friends and relatives of the deceased were present. The services were performed in a very impressive manner, by Rev. J.H. TUTTLE, the same clergyman who had officiated at the marriage ceremony.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The new opera of "Crispino e la Comare" has become so great a favorite with the public that it is a pity it should be withdrawn from the programme. The attendance last evening -- notwithstanding the inclemency of the weather -- was all that could be desired; the applause was sometimes more. Let us hasten to add, however, that the singers were in excellent voice, and that the orchestra and chorus (under Signor TORRIANI) have never been heard to such advantage. The rendition, indeed, was perfect. At the ripest moment of the work Mr. MARETZEK unfortunately cut off its performance. It is well to give variety, but it is indiscreet, we think, to meddle with content. The policy of neglecting a thoroughly successful opera in the midst of its successful career is one which we think the manager ought to speedily reconsider.

abstract: Terrible Gale at; Every Vessel Sunk or Driven Ashore
snippet: Terrible Gale at; Every Vessel Sunk or Driven Ashore
lead_paragraph: The United States steamship John Rice, Commander HOWES, arrived from New-Orleans yesterday and reports, Oct. 22, experiencing a tremendous huricane from the northeast At 5 P.M., the wind blew so heavy that the ship could not be kept head to the sea, and finding that the centre of the hurricane would pass directly over us if we did not change our position, we accordingly, at the above-mentioned hour, bore away to the southwest and ran across the path of the storm until 8 A.M. on the following morning, when the wind hauling to the westward, we bore away on our course with a fair wind, and arrived at Fort Jefferson, Oct. 24, at 12 M. Found that the hurricane had blown down a large brick building at Fort Jefferson and killed the Post Quartermaster, also severely injuring several others. Buildings inside the fort were unroofed, chimneys blown down, and trees torn up by the roots. After landing convicts steamed out of the harbor. Arrived at Key West on morning of 25th inst., where we found that the gale had been intensely severe, it having nearly desolated the island.

abstract: REOPENING OF THE DRIGGS' UNITED STATES WAREHOUSES.--It will be remembered that the immense United States Bonded Warehouses of Messrs. M.S. DRIGGS  Co., were destroyed by fire in April last. They have been rebuilt with great care, and were opened to public inspection yesterday. The fire...
lead_paragraph: REOPENING OF THE DRIGGS' UNITED STATES WAREHOUSES. -- It will be remembered that the immense United States Bonded Warehouses of Messrs. M.S. DRIGGS Co., were destroyed by fire in April last. They have been rebuilt with great care, and were opened to public inspection yesterday. The fire by which the stores were destroyed, originated in the cooperage factory opposite, the intense heat from which burst the shutters on the bonded stores from the fastenings. To guard against this in future double iron shutters have been added, separated by an air-chamber of 20 inches; the inside shutter, being suspended on rollers, can only be opened by sliding. Messrs. DRIGGS have introduced, as an additional protection, a duplex steam fire engine of great power and capacity -- built by the Woodward Steam Pump Manufacturing Company -- throwing four 1 1/2-inch streams simultaneously, or 2,500 gallons of water per minute. The water is carried to the Water-street front through a 4-inch iron pipe, so as to prevent any damage by water to goods in store in case of a fire in the rear. The steam boiler is placed in a separate and thoroughly fire-proof compartment, built under the supervision and direction of the Rate Committee, of the Board of Underwriters. It would be difficult to suggest any additional precautions, and the enterprise commends itself to the patronage of the public.

abstract: Gen. SLOCUM's mother, Mrs, MARY O. SLOCUM, died in Syracuse on Monday evening. Mr. SLOCUM was born in the City of Albany, and moved with her, husband to Onondaga County in 1818. She was 72 years of age. The funeral services were held at the residence of Judge LE ROY MORGAN yesterday afternoon. Gen. SLOCUM is borne down by this irreparable loss, and will not be able to fill any more appointments during this canvas. -- Albang Argus, Nov. 2.

abstract: Address to War Democracy of N. Y.
snippet: Address to War Democracy of N. Y.
lead_paragraph: FELLOW-CITIZENS: Five years of terrible convulsion and deadly strife have just closed--years replete with anxieties, with agonies, with sorrows, but irradiated by shining examples of patriotic devotion and unfaltering faith. If we loved our country in her previous prosperity and gladness, we have learned to love her better and serve her more zealously by seeing her tried in the furnace of affliction and struggling against thinly-disguised foreign hostility and openly-avowed domestic hate. Poorer in material wealth than she recently was, our country is richer than ever before in the love and admiration of her sons.

abstract: And Northern Capital and Enterprise--Cooperation of
snippet: And Northern Capital and Enterprise--Cooperation of
lead_paragraph: We hear of quite a number of extensive business ventures and planting enterprises undertaken of late in the Southern States, upon the plan of combining in them the capital and enterprise of capable Northern and Southern men. Gen. TAYLOR, a son of President ZACHARY TAYLOR, brother-in-law of JEFF. DAVIS, and formerly prominent as a rebel commander in the Gulf States, is reported to be now at the head of a cotton-planting association, possessed of heavy Northern capital, and proposing as the field of its future operations the State of Louisiana. Gen. HETH, of Virginia, is trying to interest Northern capitalists in an extensive Southern project; and Gen. JO. JOHNSTON has just been chosen President of an express company which originated in Richmond, but which, it is intended, shall have ramifications alike over the States of the South and North, and shall combine the capital, enterprise, industry and interests of both sections. There are numerous other schemes more or less analogous in character and purpose to these; and there are few Northern capitalists but have been approached by Southerners with projects for the profitable employment of their surplus means in the planting States.

abstract: CAVING IN OF AN EMBANKMENT -- ONE MAN KILLED AND ANOTHER INJURED. -- About 5 P.M. yesterday, while some workmen were engaged digging a cellar for a brewery at the corner of Myrtle-avenue and Wyckoff-street, Eastern District, the embankment suddenly caved in, and buried JOHN LOWDENSTEIGER and JOHN ARITZOG. The latter was rescued from death, but he was seriously injured. The body of the former was recovered after some difficulty, and it is supposed that he was instantly killed.

abstract: At the meeting of the Board of Education last evening. President McLEAN in the chair--the Finance  Committee's report of the apportionment for 1866 was adopted; a communication was received from Mayor
lead_paragraph: At the meeting of the Board of Education last evening. President McLEAN in the chair -- the Finance Committee's report of the apportionment for 1866 was adopted; a communication was received from Mayor GUNTHER, nominating Ex-Judge HENRY HILTON, of the Court of Common Pleas, as commissioner for the Sixth District, in place of Dr. FRANCIS LIEBER, resigned; the Finance Committee reported that it is inexpedient to advertise the board's proceedings in the Transcript and Leader after the 31st of December next, and the board adopted the report and instructed the clerk to give the daily press timely notice of the commissioners' meetings; a report was made censuring the School Trustees of the Seventh Ward for prodigal expenditures; Miss MARY MCLEAN was elected Vice-Principal of the Female Department of Grammar School No. 21, in the Fourteenth Ward; and the fourteenth annual report of the Faculty of the Free Academy was received. The board estimate the cost of maintaining schools in this city in 1866 at $2,454,327 54.

abstract: ratification meeting in this city, in October, 1862, in the very darkest period of the war, JOHN VAN BUREN made a Southern sympathizing speech, in which he used these memorable words: "Take Richmond, and then, if they insist, let them go." The speaker had not boldness enough to advise a surrender to the rebellion outright, but did not hesitate to advertise the rebels, in the name of his party. that if they would satisfy the pride of the North by giving up Richmond, they might have their Confederacy if they pleased. This man is now a candidate for the Attorney-Generalship of this State. Ought a place of such honor and trust to be bestowed upon one who was untrue to the country in its day of need? Does the spirit which would thus give way to treason deserve reward?

lead_paragraph: NEW STEAMSHIP. -- The fine new steamship Henry Chauncey, sails for Aspinwall at noon to-day, with 300 cabin passengers, the Fourteenth United States Infantry, numbering 500 men, and a full steerage. The Chauncey was built by Mr. WM. H. WEBB, and launched in November last. She is 336 feet in length 43 feet in breadth, and measures 3,300 tons. Her engines, which were built at the Novelty Works, have 105-inch cylinders. Her water tanks hold 20,000 gallons, and she can condense 3,500 gallons daily, and her pumping machinery, equipment in life-boats, &c., are like those of her consort, the Colorado, a description of which appeared in the TIMES several months ago. The Chauncey's officers are: Captain, A.G. GREY; First Officer, C.G. Haywood; Second Officer. R. Thomas; Third Officer, H. Sergeant; Purser, C. Mallory; Surgeon, W.F. Cushman; Storekeeper, L. Jerome; Chief-Engineer, J.K. Matthews.

abstract: Election; Democratic Party, Disorganization of the
snippet: Election; Democratic Party, Disorganization of the
lead_paragraph: Neither party is putting forth any great effort. Not for years has there been so little political excitement during the last week before the election. This comes from two opposite causes -- the confidence of the Union party, and the utter hopelessness of its opponents. When the two tickets were first put into the field, there was some prospect of a brisk struggle. The marvelous change of front which the Democratic Convention made in adopting the main principles of the Union party, its resorting to; the Union party for some of its most important candidates, and its audacious claim to the peculiar championship of President JOHNSON, made it appear that possibly a rally and dash might be made which would severely test our strength. But soon it became obvious that the tactics of the convention had really made the party less formidable than ever. The number of War Democrats who were induced to return to their old ranks was exceedingly small, while the very shifting of ground produced profound dissatisfaction among all the Peace Democrats who had any regard to consistency. What the Freeman's Journal says of its party in its last issue, is strictly correct: "The Democracy are disorganized; they have neither the spirit nor the organization of the old party." The attempt which has been made by some of the party prints to make up a false issue of freedman suffrage against the Union party, has amounted to nothing, for the simple reason that in no State Convention has the Union party declared itself in favor of imposing that suffrage upon the South against its will. It is true that the most of the Union party would be pleased if the Southern States would admit the freedmen, at least the most intelligent and deserving portion of them, to the ballot box. In that they agree fully with the frankly declared sentiments of President JOHNSON. But that is a very different matter from insisting upon the government of freedmen suffrage by the Southern States, as a sine qua non to restoration. The people understand the difference, and have not cared a button for all the Democratic rant upon the subject.

abstract: Stumping for Gen. Slocum
snippet: Stumping for Gen. Slocum
lead_paragraph: it in this State for the Slocum ticket. He is chiefly remembered in these parts for his speech before the "Democratic Association" in this city in the Winter of '63, devoted to the plan of leaving New-England "out in the cold." It was at the time when both the copperheads and the rebels were using every art and device to alienate the West from the East -- shortly after BRAGG's famous march to the Ohio, and his "proclamation to the Northwest," and JEFF. DAVIS' speech before the Mississippi Legislature, when he proclaimed that "from the Northwest would come the first gleams of peace." Gov. SEYMOUR had just delivered a message, of which columns were devoted to the attempt to alienate loyal States from each other. COX and VALLANDIGHAM and PENDLETON were sent for by the "Democratic Association" to help on in this work of division, and both delivered speeches, which were applauded by every Democratic journal in the State. It was a crusade in the direct interest of the rebellion. The people of this State have not forgotten it. "Sunset Cox" can teach them nothing about their duties in the present canvass.

abstract: estate of the late EDWARD MOYT ROBINSON is inventoried at $5,700,000; and the estimate of the appraisers is undoubtedly a low one. The amount given to his daughter, the contestant in the will case set down for trial at the November Term of the Supreme Court, in this city, is $910,000 in cash, and a parcel of real estate in San Francisco valued at $90,000, together with the profits and interest of the residue. $4,700,000. By the express terms of the will, the rents, interest and profits are to be paid over by the trustees to the daughter, without any direction, interference or control of her husband -- if she should have one. Miss ROBINSON must, therefore, have from her father's estate the comfortable income of the least $350,000. By her aunt's will, which she now seeks to set aside, she is entitled to the interest of at least $1,000,000 more, making her total income over $400,000. What munificent charities might the possessor of such an income dispense! -- New-Bedford Mercury.

abstract: Newtown, Queens Co., Extensive Seizure at
snippet: Newtown, Queens Co., Extensive Seizure at
lead_paragraph: DISCOVERY OF A COUNTERFEITING DEN -- DIES, PLATES AND CHEMICALS SEIZED BY THE POLICE AND ARREST OF ONE OF THE GUILTY PARTIES. -- A manufactury of counterfeit United States postal currency and greenbacks was recently discovered in the vicinity of Newtown, Queens County, by Inspector FOLK and detectives attached to his office. It appears that about two months since a party of five Italians rented a two-story frame house, about one mile from the village, which they have since occupied. As there were no women about the place the neighbors grew suspicious and the light there must be something wrong. A noise similar to that made by a sewing machine was frequently heard. Three savage dogs were kept on the premises, and very few persons cared to visit their new neighbors. It was also ascertained that they had two guns and a revolver, which were constantly loaded and placed in such positions that they could be easily reached. It was likewise discovered that the farmers in the vicinity were relieved of considerable quantities of corn, beans, &c., and taken all together, it was deemed proper to inform the authorities. Accordingly, on Thursday of last week, a delegation waited upon Inspector FOLK, and related all the circumstances within their knowledge. The Inspector visited the place, and becoming satisfied that all was not right, made preparations for a more thorough examination. Accordingly, on Monday night last, he proceeded to Newtown with nearly his whole detective force. Arriving at the house some time before daylight on Tuesday morning, they rapped at the door, but receiving no answer, forced their way inside. Ascending to the second story they found a man asleep. He was soon awakened, however, and made aware of the object of their visit. The sole occupant of the premises feigned ignorance, but had sufficient self-possession and knowledge of the English language to make them understand he was engaged there as cook. As for anything else he knew nothing. The officers then proceeded to the garret, where they found a quantity of note paper (blank) and a number of cords stretched across from beam to beam, which they inferred were used to dry the paper after printing. A lot of chemicals, red and green fluid, gold dust of superior quality, and instruments used by engravers. were found in the closets. They then descended to the cellar, and observed new ground which had apparently been taken from the garden. Procuring the necessary implements, they dug down about two feet, when they struck some wooden boxes, all carefully wrapped up in cloths. Exhuming these they discovered a small printing press, and a large number of platea and dies. Several plates contain 42 dies, each of 25 cents postal currency, others plates were engraved for $5 and some for $20 greenbacks, and still others for 50 cents postal currency and $30 Treasury notes. The engraving had been obs[???]rated on some of the plates, but the 25 cent dies were perfect, and of superior workmanship. From the appearance of the dies it is believed that impressions taken from them cannot be distinguished from the genuine. No printed bills were found, but from the amount of paper cinders in the stoves (of which there were two) it is believed that the manufactured [???] still on [???] had been burned so as to destroy all the [???] possible of the guilt of the counterfeiters. With this view the plates were defaced, but it seems they had not the requisite time to finish the job. The parties doubtless had an intimation of what was going on, and made preparations accordingly. The principals left the neighborhood the previous day and are still at large. The man arrested gave his name as GIOVANNI GUCHERI. Some of the officers believe him to be one of the party who were, some months since, arrested on the charge of being implicated in the murder of ANTONIO DIODATI, but he denies it. He was brought, to Brooklyn, and is now confined in the Forty-first Precinct Station-house. The press, and all other materials seized, are in possession of the Inspector of Police, where they will remain until demanded by the United States authorities.

abstract: Peace Convention of June, 1863, Resolutions Against the War
snippet: Peace Convention of June, 1863, Resolutions Against the War
lead_paragraph: month before the battle of Gettysburgh that the great Democratic Peace Convention in this city, under the auspices of FERNANDO WOOD, issued an address to the people declaring that "the war was the curse of the age in which we live" -- that "the hand of God is uplifted against us" -- and that "the war cannot succeed; we have been beaten; we cannot conquer the South." The Cooper Institute was crowded inside and outside with men who greeted with acclamations these sentiments, as expressed in resolutions and confirmed in harangues from six different platforms. While the bolder wing of the party were thus clamoring for an absolute surrender to the rebels, the more wary portion were engaged in denouncing the conscription law as intolerable tyranny, discrediting the national currency, magnifying the public debt, holding out the bugbear of foreign intervention, and racking the English language for terms of abuse against President LINCOLN for not recalling to the chief command the most backward and timid of all living generals. The party thus made up, now that the war has ended in the most magnificent of triumphs, solicits the approbation and trust of the people. Party presumption never went further.

abstract: Suppression of
snippet: Suppression of
lead_paragraph: -- We have already called attention to the fact that sufficient energy and promptitude are not being displayed by the authorities in securing the punishment of counterfeiters of the national currency. A very great number of arrests of guilty parties have been reported within a few months, but so far we have heard of only one case of conviction. In the meantime the counterfeiters are evidently actively carrying on their work in this city and in many other parts of the country; for bogus notes of the smaller denominations, and some of large denominations, are continually being put in circulation. The losses to honest parties are heavy, and of course they fall mainly upon the poor. Faith in the currency is also thus shaken, and much other damage done.

lead_paragraph: The telegraph lately advised us that Mr. CHAVEZ had been elected delegate to Congress from New-Mexico, but it afforded us no idea of the meaning of the election. By mail, however, we have full advices, from which we learn that this election was a severe contest between the Republican and Democratic parties, resulting in the complete triumph of the former. CHAVEZ, the Republican candidate, had over 2,300 majority, beating PEREZ, who was the late member. The vote appears to have been an unusually large one, CHAVEZ polling over 8,000. Eight of the ten counties in the Territory elect Republican delegates to the Legislature, so that we shall have a decided majority in that body.

abstract: Exports, Large Transactions in
snippet: Exports, Large Transactions in
lead_paragraph: from the Custom-house, for the week ending on Tuesday evening, make up the extraordinarily heavy aggregate of $6,608,467 in currency, or about one hundred per cent. more than the total for the corresponding week of last year. Included in the week's exports have been 14,621 bales of cotton, valued at $3,523,735 in lawful money. Of this amount 12,450 bales, of the currency value of $3,001,-449, were shipped to Liverpool; 1,741 bales, valued at $430,898, to Cork, doubtless "for orders," as the freight brokers phrase it; and 430 bales, valued at $91,398, to Havre. These enormous shipments of domestic produce must favorably affect our foreign trade balances, increase the supply of exchange, lessen the demand for gold, and vastly aid the chief financial agent of the government in his commendable efforts to restore the national finances to a specie basis.

abstract: the, Hatred of Copperheadism
snippet: the, Hatred of Copperheadism
lead_paragraph: which have occurred since the close of the war, the disbanded soldiers have voted with the Union party with the same general accord as when under arms. They have everywhere, East and West, treated with scorn all the wooing of the Democratic party to support its tickets. The trick of making military nominations to win their confidence in Pennsylvania, Ohio and Iowa, has been unavailing. The soldiers are implacable against the party which nursed Copperheadism, and which pronounced the war, wherein they were pouring out their blood, "a failure," the party, too, which did its best to bar them from the ballot-box. The army was the embodiment of the war spirit against the rebellion; and it is a moral impossibility that those who composed it should now turn themselves over to that party which was the conglomerate of everything that had any measure of sympathy with the rebellion. It is not in human nature for an organization of men who have poured out their blood for any cause to fraternize afterward with those who sought to betray that cause. Every day's perils encountered for the flag only made the soldier all the more devoted to it; and he worshiped it the most when most rent by the battle's rage From the beginning, the army hated all factionists and malcontents. That hatred has never known abatement, and never will. The return to civil life will make no difference. So long as a soldier breathes, Copperheadism will have a mortal enemy.

abstract: MURDER AT FORT HAMILTON. -- Coroner LYNCH was informed yesterday that a soldier had been murdered in the village of Fort Hamilton, and on proceeding to the place ascertained the following particulars: The proprieter of a shoe-store named LAKE, had for some time been annoyed by a dog, owned by a soldier's family, residing in the vicinity. The animal having killed a number of LAKE's ducks, he gave notice that he would shoot him if he committed any more depredations. No heed was paid to the warning and the dog again making his appearance, LAKE carried his threat into execution and killed the dog. Some six or eight soldiers soon after came into his store and after abusing him roundly, one of them, named UNDERWOOD, beat him severely. LAKE seizing a club, dealt UNDERWOOD a blow upon the head, fracturing his skull. Another of the soldiers drew a sword, when LAKE made his escape into another apartment. The injured man was carried away by his companions, and died in a few hours thereafter. LAKE was committed to jail by Justice C.W. CHURCH, to await the Coroner's inquest. A post-mortem examination will be made this morning.

abstract: our anxiety for a Republican victory in New-Jersey, is that thus only can we secure the ratification by that State of the Constitutional Amendment. The ratification was refused by the Legislature last year by a strict party vote; and there is no doubt whatever that if a Democratic Legislature be again chosen, the amendment will again meet with the same fate. Only by electing a Republican Legislature can the ratification of the Constitutional Amendment, by New-Jersey, be secured. This raises the present political struggle above a mere local contest, or a contest for place or in favor of individuals. A great principle is involved, in which the whole country is interested, and the success of which is essential to the honor and permanent welfare of the nation.

abstract: Maretzek vs. Cauldwell >amp; Whitney (Sunday Mercury); Libel
snippet: Maretzek vs. Cauldwell >amp; Whitney (Sunday Mercury); Libel
lead_paragraph: MAX MARETZEK, the operatic manager, having brought a criminal libel suit against Messrs. WILLIAM CAULDWELL and HORACE P. WHITNEY, publishers of the Sunday Mercury, as was stated in yesterday's TIMES, these gentlemen were taken into custody yesterday by Capt. JOHN JOURDAN, of the Sixth Ward, and required to recognize in $10,000. Having complied with the requirements of the court, the prisoners were released from restraint. The charge accuses Messrs. CAULDWELL and WHITNEY of having published eight scandalous and malicious libels, which were calculated to injure the complainant in his business, and to impair his credit socially and in commercial circles.

abstract: Hopelessness of the Party
snippet: Hopelessness of the Party
lead_paragraph: Notwithstanding all the art of the Democratic Convention in framing a platform of Union material, the party have taken their place upon it with very much the same air that the culprit stands in the stocks -- as different from the "unterrified Democracy" of other days as can well be imagined. They know that they are on trial for the worst of public crimes, next to open treason itself, and that there is no chance for breaking down or evading the evidence. They do not attempt to make even a show of defence, but only beg, with a hangdog look, that the past may be forgotten. If they had the manhood to plead guilty outright, and penitentially throw themselves upon the mercy of the people, they might not be held to their responsibility. As it is, they cannot escape it, for they ask what is simply impossible. Without repentance there can be neither forgetting nor forgiving.

abstract: Yesterday Messrs. J.W. CORLIES & Co. had a formal opening of their new range of offices for the proposed negotiation of the new Mexican loan, at No. 57 Broadway. During the afternoon the rooms were crowded by a miscellaneous collection of bankers, brokers, military men and representatives of all the professions. Refreshments were liberally provided, and well patronized by those present. Conversation naturally ran upon the new loan and the prospects of the Liberal party gaining possession of the Mexican Government, and the tone of remark was earnest and hopeful. The offices are now open for regular business, and the enterprise may be considered as fairly launched.

abstract: The Chamber of Commerce held their regular monthly meeting yesterday. The proceedings were made interesting by the presence of Seffor D'AZAMBUJA, the Brazilian Minister at Washington, and Rev. Mr. FLETCHER. Both gentlemen spoke on the com-...
lead_paragraph: The Chamber of Commerce held their regular monthly meeting yesterday. The proceedings were made interesting by the presence of Seffor D'AZAMBUJA, the Brazilian Minister at Washington, and Rev. Mr. FLETCHER. Both gentlemen spoke on the commercial relations existing between the two nations, and especial mention was made of the warm sympathy expressed by the Government and people of Brazil for the United States Government daring the war. A new line of steamers, just established between New-York and Rio Janerio, will, it was said, tend to keep up the friendly relations existing between the two countries.

abstract: In the time that intervenes between now and the session of Congress, a month hence, when the President's message and the reports of the heads of departments will be given to the public, we shall doubtless be favored with abundance of information from the "knowing ones" as to the contents of those forthcoming documents, and their recommendations upon important points or measures of policy. We have generally had such advance information in previous years, and the fact that it has nearly always subsequently proved to be all bosh, is not likely to make it less greedily received this year. How easy it would be, for example, for O.P.Q. or X.Y.Z. to telegraph from Washington to some of our sensational journals that "President JOHNSON, in his forthcoming message, will take decided ground in favor of a peremptory enforcement of our claims for damages upon England;" and what a nice sensation it would be for Wall-street and for the Fenians. How cheap it would be to forward a telegram that the "Secretary of State had just sent in his report to the printer, and it contains his very latest dispatches, which will exhibit to a startled country the extremely critical condition of our relations with France;" or a dispatch that the Secretary of War would, in his report, favor the maintenance of our army at a strength of two hundred thousand, as it was necessary to overawe the still rebellious spirit of the South. In fact, we are already beginning to have such alleged foreshadowings of departmental reports. One of our cotemporaries has a Washington dispatch announcing the highly important news that the Secretary of the Treasury, in his forthcoming report, will advocate the abolition of the present Internal Revenue system, and the substitution for it of a tax upon sales. Now, this would be highly important if true. But we think it would be safe to add to the announcement that its author did not learn the news by reading it in Secretary MCCULLOCH's forthcoming report, or from any one who had read said report, or from Secretary MCCULLOCH himself, or from any one to whom the Secretary told it. to He probably either "saw a man" who told it to him, or found it among the sediment in the depths of his own consciousness. In either case it is neither important nor true, and should have been "suppressed before it was published," as it is calculated only to do harm.

abstract: CRISPINO IN BROOKLYN. -- This opera was given last night in Brooklyn to the most brilliant audiences we have ever seen at the Academy. The general features of the performance varied only in great excellence from those which characterized the same at the New-York house. Miss KELLOGG sustained her role admirably, finding it somewhat difficult only in the necessary descent from the altitude of dignified propriety which she ordinarily occupies. The honors of the evening were divided between ROVERE and BELLINI, were simply superb, from the first to the closing scene. Encores were thick as blackberries, and applause as generous and constant as the Summer sun. Such a success should encourage the manager to repeat the opera.

abstract: The news from Mexico indictes no improvement in the condition of that unhappy country. Gen. ESCAVEDA, it is reported has scattered his forces.
lead_paragraph: The news from Mexico indictes no improvement in the condition of that unhappy country. Gen. ESCAVEDA, it is reported has scattered his forces. consisting of about 600 men, over the States of Coahuila and New-Leon, a ting on the defensive and annoying the French by bushwhacking. Five French officers had been captured and hanged in retaliation for the recent order issued by MAXIMILIAN, threatening with death every Liberal soldier captured with arms in his hands. Further advices contain reports of various skirmishes at different points between the Imperialists and the Juarists, but no battle of real importance had taken place.

abstract: Navy-yards and Custom-houses; The Law on Offences in
snippet: Navy-yards and Custom-houses; The Law on Offences in
lead_paragraph: -- A case before the United States Circuit Court, in Brooklyn, is reported in our columns this morning, in which is involved a very interesting question of law. It seems that a man named PHILIP DONLON, who was working in the navy-yard, having a grudge against one of his fellows, one day pushed him off into the dry-dock. The man escaped with his life, however, otherwise DONLON would have been tried for murder. As it was, he was indicted for an assault with intent to kill, and this indictment his counsel moved to quash, arguing that the courts of the United States could take cognizance only of offences declared to be such by the statutes of the United States, and that no such statute had ever been passed making such an act an offence against those statutes.

abstract: Republic, Steamship, Particulars of Loss, Passengers, >amp;c.; Description of the Field
snippet: Republic, Steamship, Particulars of Loss, Passengers, >amp;c.; Description of the Field
lead_paragraph: It will be remembered that the steamer Republic, running on Cromwell's New-Orleans line, between that city and New-York, was wrecked off the coast of Georgia, on the 18th of October, in a heavy gale of wind, proving a total loss. When the ship was on the point of going down, four boats and a raft put off from her. So far as learned, only three of the boats have been heard from. The first was is charge of Capt. YOUNG, of the Republic, who was picked up by the brig J.W. Lovitte, of Nova Scotia, and carried into Charleston, S.C., arriving there on the 28th of October. It contained fourteen persons. The second boat was in charge of the first officer, with twelve persons, and after terrible sufferings it arrived in Charleston on Monday last, the 30th of October, having been at sea for six days. The third boat was commanded by Capt. HAWTHORNE, an experienced sailor, who was passenger on board the ill-fated vessel. He succeeded in arriving safely at Hilton Head, with twenty-four passengers, all in good health. The remaining boat and the raft have not, as yet, been heard from, and fears are entertained of their safety.

abstract: Between 1 and 2 o'clock yesterday morning, a servant employed by Mr. JOHN OSPREY, of No. 203 West Nineteenth-street, heard some person in the front basement, and on looking in saw a man. The hastened to awake Mr. OSPREY, and he leaped from bed and caught a view of the burglar as he was leaving the house. Mr. OSPREY pursued the fugitive, crying "Stop thief!" The alarm was heard by Policeman AUGUSTUS S. MORING, and he, seeing a man flying up Eighth-avenue, chased him into a saloon between Nineteenth and Twentieth streets, where he was captured. Mr. OSPREY, who arrived at the heels of the fugitive, identified him as the burglar. It appears that the burglar entered the house by removing the bolt from one of the basement windows, and had packed up silver, ware, &c., of the value of $65, with which he was about to leave at the time of the discovery. The prisoner, who describes himself as JAMES MCLAUGHLIN, of No. 271 West Thirteenth-street, boiler-maker, employed in the Delamater Iron Works, says that he is a respectable, hard-working man, and supports his family by his daily labor. He stoutly asserts his perfect innocence. In default of $1,000 bail, he was committed for trial at the Court of General Sessions.

abstract: the Liquidating Process
snippet: the Liquidating Process
lead_paragraph: According to the official statement of the public indebtedness on the 31st of October, there has been a further decrease of $4,092,967 in the national liabilities since the close of September. The total debt on Tuesday last was $2,740,854,759, as against $2,744,947,726 a month ago, and $2,757,689,571 on the 31st of August -- showing a clear reduction of $16,834,812 within the last two months, or at the rate of $101,008,872 a year. The debt on the 31st of October stood as follows: Coin-bearing, $1,161,137,692, and currency-bearing, $1,191,819,787; the annual interest charge on which is given at $67,670,341 in coin and $71,267,738 in lawful money; making the total of the yearly interest, $138,938,079. In the coin-bearing portion of the debt, an increase is discernible, and in the currency interest portion, a corresponding contraction, traceable to the recent funding of compound interest notes into five-twenty gold-bearing bonds.

abstract: And a Question of Veracity
snippet: And a Question of Veracity
lead_paragraph: BUREN follows the example of Comptroller ROBINSON, raising a question of "personal veracity" with Mr. DEPEW. But the misfortune is that everybody who knows "JOHN" said, upon reading Mr. DEPEW's revelation, "that's JOHN and no mistake." Two gentlemen said to us that "JOHN" had used the same language in their hearing. Indeed, without Mr. DEPEW's continuation, the spirit of the conversation would have been lost. We are bound to accept Mr. VAN BUREN's denial; but, somehow, people go out believing that Mr. DEPEW is not smart enough to imitate "JOHN" with such surprising accuracy.

abstract: Our only danger is in excess of confidence. It is taken too much for granted that the Union ticket is sure to prevail by a large majority. Undoubtedly there is the best ground...
lead_paragraph: Our only danger is in excess of confidence. It is taken too much for granted that the Union ticket is sure to prevail by a large majority. Undoubtedly there is the best ground for the assurance that it can be so; but we have no right to assume that it will be so. A thousand times in our political history has over-confidence defeated itself by taking away all stimulus to effort. However noble the object, success can never be insured except by adequate effort. But even were an inspired seer to foretell the election of the Union candidates, it would not at all justify inaction. The fortunes of the Union candidates are nothing. Good men though they all are, we are not striving for the purpose of their personal preferment. There are hundreds of men in the State just as deserving. Nor is the difference in the fidelity with which the ministerial duties of the State offices would be discharged by the two series of candidates a matter of great consequence. Either of the candidates for Secretary of State, doubtless, would keep the public records truly; any of the candidates for Treasurer, doubtless, would keep the public funds securely; any of the candidates for Judge of the Court of Appeals would, we are sure, discharge his high duties with great learning and perfect probity. So far as the mere material interests of the State are concerned, we are not at all afraid to concede that the election of most of the nominees on the so-called "Democratic" ticket would produce no serious damage.

abstract: UNION MASS MEETING. -- A mass meeting of Union Republicans took place at Washington Hall, last evening. There was quite a large attendance of ladies and gentlemen. At 8 o'clock the meeting was called to order by Alderman BLISS, who nominated Hon. JOHN A. CROSS for Chairman. Mr. CROSS was elected amid cheers, and made a brief address. DANIEL L. NORTHRUP, Esq., read the resolutions, which were unanimously adopted. Gen. VAN WYCK was introduced by the Chair, and delivered a lengthy and eloquent address. He was followed by Judge SANFORD and Gen. SWIFT. The latter stated that he had just left campaigning in New-Jersey, and related his experience in that State. The meeting adjourned at a late hour.

abstract: ciety organized in April, 1863, for the purpose of searching for the essential elements of Christian unity, held a meeting yesterday afternoon, in the University. Rev. Dr. FERRIS presided. Rev. Drs. CRAVEN, VERMILYE, R.D. HITCHCOCK, PORTER, JOHN COTTON SMITH, CHURCH and many others were present. The declaration of views presented and accepted affirmed the spiritual unity of the Holy Catholic Church, the truth of the Apostles and the Nicene Creed, and proposed agitation as a remedy for sectarianism. A third series of sermons on this subject is projected. A new paper is to be started, if plans under consideration succeed.

Ortega, the Vice-president and President-elect of the Mexican Republic, for about $7,000, which the plaintiff claims ie due for services rendered and money advanced by him. abstract: New-York, steamer Atalanta at Quarantine with Cholera on Board
snippet: New-York, steamer Atalanta at Quarantine with Cholera on Board
lead_paragraph: About 7 o'clock on Thursday evening the steamship Atalanta arrived at this port from London and Havre with a number of cases of cholera on board. The vessel sailed from London with about 150 passengers, and on arriving at Havre received about 400 more, most of whom were Germans. On the second day out a child of one of the passengers shipped at Havre died from exhaustion produced by diarrhea, as was supposed, and shortly afterward several other persons were attacked, fifteen of whom died. The disease, the nature of which was then unknown to the passengers, was confined entirely to the steerage, none of those in the cabin suffering in the least.

abstract: Senate District is being sharply canvassed, and as the relative strength of the candidates develops, there is every reason to anticipate the election of the Union candidate. Mr. MURPHY is decidedly and deservedly popular. He has never been a candidate for office, nor does he seek it. With a large Democratic majority in the district, nobody supposed that a Republican could win. But the Democratic vote is to be divided between two strong men. In this aspect of the question, by an active, vigorous effort, all Republicans taking the field zealously, Mr. MURPHY can be chosen. And such a result would be one that the district and the city might well rejoice over.

abstract: Democratic paper the report of a Democratic speech, which was interrupted by "laughter" thirty times. As we judge by the length of the speech that about half an hour was occupied in its delivery, there was just a "laugh" a minute. As a peal of laughter from a "large audience," such as we are fold was present at this meeting, occupies about a minute, the cachinnatory exercise of the multitude must have been kept up continuously from the beginning to the end of the speech. The scene must have been a very lively one. We advise the Democracy to keep up this sort of entertainment until next Tuesday, for it will then surely be brought to a close.

abstract: Andersonville, Obituary Record of
snippet: Andersonville, Obituary Record of
lead_paragraph: ary record, which we publish to-day, is one of the saddest ever published. It is well enough to forget the past, when forgetting is not a crime against the memory of the martyred dead. The story of Andersonville can never be forgotten. Here, in this bald list of names and dates, we have that story. There is no other such infamy in the times of civilization. While we were feeding, clothing and nursing hordes of ragamuffins captured in DAVIS' service, here were our poor loyal soldiers murdered by the thousand. These things ought not to be forgotten -- until we know that hereafter it shall be impossible for men bearing the American name to be participants in such crimes.

abstract: Republic, Steamship, Wreck; Missing Boat Arrived
snippet: Republic, Steamship, Wreck; Missing Boat Arrived
lead_paragraph: The missing boat which put off from the wreck of the steamship Republic, was picked up on Sunday last by the schooner Harpar, of Roxbury There were eleven men on board, as follows: Edward Ryan, second mate; Capt. Ryer and Maj. Sauvenant, United States Volunteers; John Fleming, Charles Conway, James Crellan, James Nash and James Quinn, seamen; Patrick Maloney, officers' mess-man; a fireman named Charley, and Joseph Willis, saloon-steward, our informant. The boat was picked up twenty-five miles from Cape Romain. Her occupants had not tasted food since the 25th ult., the date of the wreck up to the time of their rescue, being of course thoroughly exhausted and in considerable suffering. The clothing of most of them was left on board and they were scantily clad.

abstract: In old times, the office of State Senator was regarded as one of the most honorable and responsible in the government. Latterly, New-York City has been disgraced in the halls of the State capital by men who neither respected themselves or their constituents--by men recking in debauchory and corruption. It is high time that ...
lead_paragraph: In old times, the office of State Senator was regarded as one of the most honorable and responsible in the government. Latterly, New-York City has been disgraced in the halls of the State capital by men who neither respected themselves or their constituents--by men recking in debauchory and corruption. It is high time that the voters of New-York took an interest in reforming this disgraceful state of affairs. A government of the people cannot last long when its official representatives fail to respect themselves, and to honestly discharge the responsible duties of the offices to which they are elevated by their fellow-citizens. No man should be elected to the Legislature of the State whose necessities or whose past life are not a guarantee that he is above the reach of the robbers and jobbers who swarm around the State capital every Winter. What we require is, that only men of unswerving enterprise shall be elected. Office-seekers -- men who are the paid agents of "rings," corporations or legislative speculators -- ought to be avoided by honest voters, as they would contact with the plague or the small-pox. This is a duty the people owe to themselves. No rogue can ever misrepresent any of the Senatorial or Assembly Districts if the people do their duty.

abstract: the Democrats' Last Ditch
snippet: the Democrats' Last Ditch
lead_paragraph: ly the last ditch of the enemy now in the field. The prospect of our carrying that work is not only hopeful, but morally certain. Let the other States, whose elections comp off next Tuesday, as far outdo their own achievements in the past as New-Jersey is about to do in hers, and the Opposition party may be regarded as annihilated. Its recovery is an impossibility. Its leaders, and even the rank and file will perceive the folly of attempting to thwart manifest destiny, and will give up the attempt, resigning themselves as gracefully as possible to the dissolution which awaits them. On the other hand, let Unionists be apathetic, and they prolong this controversy until the next year and the year following, and possibly till the next Presidential contest, when another "era of good feeling" should have set in for the more full development of our nation's industry and the restoration of its currency to the specie standard.

abstract: Several of the Paris journals publish comments on the dispatches exchanged between Mr. ADAMS and Earl RUSSELL, and seem to look on them as mere diplomatic sparring, and nothing more. The Press declares that all idea of hostilities between America and England on such a futile cause is simply preposterous, and that the rapidity with which the Cabinet of Washington has disbanded its troops, and restored its peace establishment, proves that it has not the slightest intention of assuming a belligerent attitude. The writer adds: "Mr. SEWARD and Mr. ADAMS are too intelligent not to comprehend that although their complaints are serious, although their demand possesses an incontestable character of equity, if considered in the strict point of view of the existing right of nations, still there has not been on the part of the British Government any precise material violation of national and international law. It is certain, on the other hand that the said Cabinet has not acted with respect to the Union, in a straightforward and friendly manner -- has observed a neutrality more apparent than real." Our cotemporary believes that the Government of the United States has a more elevated object in view than any pecuniary reparation, namely, to call the attention of the civilized world, and of all the governments concerned, to the omissions and imperfections of the present law of nations, and to provoke from general good sense, and the force of public opinion, a legislation on the subject of a more extended and equitable character, and more in conformity with the progress of civilization.

abstract: The steamship Atalanta, Capt. PINKHAM, arrived at this port on Thursday night with several cases of cholera on board. She left Havre with 452 passengers, mostly German, of whom fifteen died on the voyage, and four after reaching this port.
lead_paragraph: The steamship Atalanta, Capt. PINKHAM, arrived at this port on Thursday night with several cases of cholera on board. She left Havre with 452 passengers, mostly German, of whom fifteen died on the voyage, and four after reaching this port. She was sent by the Health Officer to the lower bay, and the floating hospital ship Florence nightingale was dispatched to receive the patients, of whom there are now about twenty. A meeting of the Commissioners of Health was held yesterday, and a committee was dispatched to Washington with a memorial to the government asking that a suitable site may be set apart at Sandy Hook for the detention of vessels arriving here with cholera patients on board.

lead_paragraph: BILLIARDS -- THE CARME-KAVANAGH MATCHES. - - The second of this series of matches is announced to come off at Irving Hall this evening. This game is 1,500 points up, with 2 5-16-inch balls, on a second-sized Phelan & Collender carom table, the push shot barred. It is understood that Mr. CARME has been out of health since his last match, and therefore has had little time to practice for the four-ball game, which is an entirely new one to him, and on receiving his physician's certificate, Mr. PHELAN desired to have the match postponed. This proposition was, however, refused, as CARME must play or forfeit this evening.

abstract: to a report of the appearance of cholera in the harbor -- brought hither by the steamship Atalanta, from London via Havre. There is good reason at all times to be on guard against imported pestilence. But we see nothing whatever to cause even momentary alarm in the cases of ship cholera thus far reported. Overcrowding is the usual agency at work on shipboard. And looking to the number of steerage passengers crowded into the holds of the ocean steamers, it is altogether marvelous that epidemics on board do not rage ceaselessly [???] land to land. We have far more to fear, [???] New-York every day from typhoid and other [???]rs, than from Asiatic cholera. We think, therefore, that the officials are making quite as much fuss as the occasion calls for. Passenger vessels that come here overcrowded must have disease on board.
lead_paragraph: to a report of the appearance of cholera in the harbor -- brought hither by the steamship Atalanta, from London via Havre. There is good reason at all times to be on guard against imported pestilence. But we see nothing whatever to cause even momentary alarm in the cases of ship cholera thus far reported. Overcrowding is the usual agency at work on shipboard. And looking to the number of steerage passengers crowded into the holds of the ocean steamers, it is altogether marvelous that epidemics on board do not rage ceaselessly [???] land to land. We have far more to fear, [???] New-York every day from typhoid and other [???]rs, than from Asiatic cholera. abstract: o'clock, a youth named MICHAEL FITZGERALD, was shot and instantly killed in a tavern at Paschaliville, in the Twenty-fourth Ward, kept by Mr. JOHN NEILD, From an eye-witness of the affair, we learn that the young men of the neighborhood dressed themselves in fancy costume, and assembled at the tavern of Mr. NEILD, to celebrate Hallow Eve. While all was merriment and jollity, three men entered the place for the purpose of getting some liquor. After they had been waited upon by the bartender they disputed about paying, and commenced a quarrel with one of a party of boys who came there to give a serenade. This created quite a confusion and uproar. JOHN CONNER, one of the three, started for the door, and just at this moment the boy FITZGERALD made his appearance at the door. JOHN CONNER levelled a pistol at deceased and fired, killing him almost instantly. Officer HILL, of the Twenty-fourth Ward Police, was in the neighborhood and soon on the spot. He arrested JOHN CONNER, PATRICK, his brother, and LOUIS VESSELS. On the way to the station-house PATRICK CONNER and LOUIS VESSELS made their escape. After this occurred the officer accompanied JOHN CONNER to his house, for the purpose of informing his parents of what had occurred. On reaching the house CONNER went into a second-story room and made his escape from a window while the officer was below. The officer then obtained assistance, procured a carriage, and tracked his former prisoner to the Gray's Ferry Bridge, and succeeded in again capturing him on the east side of it. CONNER was disguised about the face with a heavy pair of false whiskers. The accused was taken to the Twenty-fourth Ward Station-house, and, subsequently, PATRICK CONNER and VESSELS were captured, and confined in the same place to await the action of the Coroner. The deceased is represented as being a very inoffensive boy. He resided with his parents in Darby, and was about 18 years of age. JOHN CONNER, the alleged murderer, is apparently about 30 years old.

abstract: --Sundry citizens of the parishes of Caddo and Bossier. Louisiana, have memorialized Gov. WELLS to the effect that there are indications of serious difficulty among the negroes. They state that it is known that on some of the largest plantations in the hill lands, especially of Caddo, nearly all the negro men are armed with guns, pistols, etc., which they do not attempt to conceal, and that they are even now exercising ...
lead_paragraph: -- Sundry citizens of the parishes of Caddo and Bossier. Louisiana, have memorialized Gov. WELLS to the effect that there are indications of serious difficulty among the negroes. They state that it is known that on some of the largest plantations in the hill lands, especially of Caddo, nearly all the negro men are armed with guns, pistols, etc., which they do not attempt to conceal, and that they are even now exercising themselves in the use of them. They nave in some way got the idea that, after Christmas, the plantations are to be divided among them; and their prejudices against the whites have been so excited "that a well-grounded apprehension pervades the country population, and many persons are already preparing to abandon their homes in the country before the Christmas holidays, and will do so, unless some action is taken to disabuse the negro of his present sanguine expectations, and assure the white man against the danger of assassination, and even greater horrors than assassination itself." The petitioners want arms, ammunition and permission to organize for mutual protection.

abstract: Health Bill, T???
snippet: Health Bill, T???
lead_paragraph: There is no one public matter which can come before the consideration of our citizens this Winter, half so important for their interests or lives, as the Health Bill to be presented to the next Legislature. We say their interests as well as their health, for an epidemic of cholera in New-York would produce a frightful loss in business as well as human lives. Had the bill passed last Winter, we should now be in a proper state of defence against the approaching enemy, and, without doubt, could lessen his ravages greatly, if not entirely drive him away. The experience of next Summer will not unlikely show that thousands of lives and millions of property would have been saved, if some of the members of the last Legislature had been less corrupt or less negligent of public interests.

abstract: Freedmen; Perry, Gov. on Protection of, >amp;c.
snippet: Freedmen; Perry, Gov. on Protection of, >amp;c.
lead_paragraph: Carolina, states in his message that he has appointed a commission for the purpose of preparing and submitting to the Legislature for their adoption, a code of laws for the protection and government of the freedmen and colored persons. The idea of establishing such a measure is a good one; and we cannot doubt that under this system the blacks will be allowed to give their testimony before the courts of justice. The necessity for such a measure arises from the fact that the present laws of the State relating to negroes are all based on the doctrines of slavery, and still more from the peculiar circumstances and antecedents of the great body of the negroes. For example, the laws made for the whites in regard to the marriage and family relations, their duties and responsibilities, cannot at once, in their entirety, be applied to the blacks, for the reason that the marriage and family relations of the latter, have heretofore been, and still are, in the greatest uncertainty and confusion. So with the laws relating to their holding of property and many other laws. We hope to see a code bearing upon all these matters, of such justice and humanity, established in South Carolina, as to be a model for all the other States of the South.

abstract: We have now to inquire what statesman there are who may hope to combine the requisite Parliamentary support with those qualities of ability, experience and position which are essential to the due discharge of the office of first minister of the Crown. The first...
lead_paragraph: We have now to inquire what statesman there are who may hope to combine the requisite Parliamentary support with those qualities of ability, experience and position which are essential to the due discharge of the office of first minister of the Crown. The first candidate in age and experience is undoubtedly Lord RUSSELL, to whom, we believe, Her Majesty has intrusted the task of reconstructing the Cabinet. He has himself held the office of Prime Minster for six years, and has served the crown in a number of important and difficult, offices. He is one of the last of those who took part in passing the first Reform Bill, for death has been very busy among these for the last few years; he was at one time the acknowledged head of the Whig party, and has an European reputation second to no other British statesman. With so many recommendations, it may be thought that we need look no further than Lord RUSSELL, and that his task would be comparatively easy. These great recommendations are, however, cancelled by still greater defects. Lord RUSSELL is a member of the House of Lords, and it is a source of weakness to any government to separate the office of Prime Minister from the leadership of the House of Commons. The two positions mutually strengthen each other. The Minister is more powerful from his Influence over the House, and the Leader has more authority from his position as Minister. To separate the two is a waste of power. Lord RUSSELL is, besides, considerably past seventy years of age, and though we have been recently governed with vigor and success by a Minister of upward of eighty, it may not, perhaps, be wise to give to this preference for antiquity the strength of two successive precedents. The accession of Lord RUSSELL to power will weaken the government by detaching from it a considerable number of Irish supporters. The Ecclesiastical Titles Bill has not yet been forgotten, and the same cause which has expelled from Parliament almost every Irish Liberal member who supported that measure, would deprive the government of a considerable part of the support which it now expects from Ireland. But there is more to be said. A new generation has arisen since Lord RUSSELL was Prime Minister, his name has lost much of its influence, and the association connected with it are becoming obsolete. The reputation gained by one Reform Bill has been somewhat impaired by three futile attempts to pass another. Nobody knows what Lord RUSSELL's present position with regard to reform is. Besides, it cannot be denied that the unfortunate events of the year 1855 would prevent Lord RUSSELL from rallying round him the full support which a leader of the Liberal party ought to count on. The declaration by which he broke up the government of Lord ABERDEEN, and the unfortunate circumstances connected with his mission to Vienna, which occasioned his resignation of the seals of the Colonial-office, have not been forgotten, and may probably be found to tell unfavorably in the reconstruction of the Ministry under his auspices.

abstract: Palmerston's, Lord, Successor
snippet: Palmerston's, Lord, Successor
lead_paragraph: The succession to the Premiership of England, become vacant by the decease of Lord PALMERSTON, is the prevailing subject of discussion among the statesmen and politicians of Europe. In the United Kingdom, the occasion would naturally make this topic paramount, but at least as much anxiety prevails on the continent to ascertain who is the coming man. It is not, perhaps, too much to assert that the demise of this influential personage has attracted more attention in foreign countries and given rise to greater anxiety than the loss in either of one of their own Cabinet Ministers or diplomatists would have done. In France, LOUIS NAPOLEON is deprived of one of his staunchest and most serviceable friends, while the Liberal cause in Europe, despite some indefensible inconsistencies on the part of the deceased Viscount, has undoubtedly experienced the loss of one of its most valuable supporters. It is to be hoped that the loss to the party of advanced ideas will stop here, and that despotism may not have also an active gain through the choice of a successor holding less enlightened views.
