abstract: A few evenings since, after a "Democratic" meeting at Hackensack, some gentlemen met in the barroom of the hotel in that place, among whom were several very warm "Democrats." One of them was particularly severe in the General. "He couldn't fight -- never did fight! Ran horse races with his men among a parcel of women and children. No body but women and children to fight with where he went. Took good care to keep out of the way of men! Small body -- sandy hair -- nothing to make a man of!" &c., &c. After this strain had been indulged in for some time, a gentleman who had sat quietly by, listening to the conversation, turned around and said: "My dear friend, give every man his due. I fought KILPATRICK nine times. I fought him in nine battles, and he fought like the d -- l!" The speaker further defined his position by saying he was from Charleston, S.C., and had gone into the war with the rest. He had been a prisoner: was only a few days out of prison, and knew what he was talking about. This was a shell at "short range," and was followed by a prolonged silence, during which the General's assailant found safety in a prudent retreat from the field. -- Soldiers' Friend.

abstract: The Board of Supervisors met yesterday. A communication was received from the Corporation Counsel, Stating that vacancies in the lists of Inspectors and Canvassers of Election can be filled, only by the Police Commissioners, and not by the Board of Supervisors.
lead_paragraph: The Board of Supervisors met yesterday. A communication was received from the Corporation Counsel, Stating that vacancies in the lists of Inspectors and Canvassers of Election can be filled, only by the Police Commissioners, and not by the Board of Supervisors. A preamble and resolution were adopted instructing the Committee on Volunteering to prepare ballots for citizens desiring to vote on the question of extending the time of redemption of the State Bounty Loan of $30,000,000 for a term of twelve years. The Board adjourned to the 14th instant.

abstract: -- We hope every  Union voter in the Seventh District will cast his vote for the regular Union candidate, THOMAS MURPHY. AS a general thing, it is a safe and wise rule to vote for the regular nominee of the Union party, even where the chances of success seem doubtful. But in this case it is especially important. Two Democratic candidates are in the field, each strong with his section of the party, and they are almost certain so to divide the Democratic vote as to render Mr. MURPHY's election, with proper effort, reasonably certain. In any case, it would be important, if possible, to secure a Union Senator: -- and in this it is doubly so.

abstract: Freemasons' Reply to the Pope's Allocution; Wallace, W. Vincent, Composer
snippet: Freemasons' Reply to the Pope's Allocution; Wallace, W. Vincent, Composer
lead_paragraph: While Mr. ADAMS and Earl RUSSELL are squabbling about the want of cordiality displayed by their respective countries to one another of late, the vexed question of the popularity of the Yankee nation in England has been settled by those certain indicators of public opinion -- the street boys of London. The notion that "Confederate sympathy" ever prevailed in this country is not altogether absurd, perhaps, though it is declared to be so by at least one of the morning papers: nevertheless there is significance in the different reception now given to the war-songs of the combatants. It is true that "My Maryland" and "The Bonnie Blue Flag" may still be heard in the abodes of unfortunate but spiteful sufferers by the "Cotton Loan;" but the great Federal war-song is the favorite of the people -- of those who sing in the highways. The somewhat lugubrious refrain -- "Glory, glory, hallelujah!" -- has excited their admiration to a wonderful degree, and almost threatens to extinguish that hard-worked, exquisite effort of modern minstrelsy -- "Slap Bang." The slight flavor of blasphemy which "Old John Brown" contains does not apparently give offence to the popular appetite -- rather the contrary effect is observable.

abstract: Erie; Collision; Rev. Mr. Romeyn Killed
snippet: Erie; Collision; Rev. Mr. Romeyn Killed
lead_paragraph: ACCIDENT ON THE ERIE RAILWAY -- ONE MAN KILLED. -- An accident occurred on the New-York and Erie Railway on Friday night, resulting in the death of Rev. Mr. ROMEYN, Pastor of the Methodist Episcopal Church at Sloatsburgh, and injury to two others. As far as ascertained, the particulars are as follows: The way-passenger train from Jersey City at a quarter past four o'clock on Friday night, on arriving at the water tank about a mile west of Ramapo, crossed over on the eastern-bound track for the purpose of taking in water, and, as is alleged, flagmen were sent out to warn approaching trains. While engaged taking water, No. 22 freight train came down on the eastern-bound track, and it appears did not discover the signal until it was too late to avoid a collision. The engineer of the western-bound train, with great presence of mind, at once commenced to back his train, and by so doing undoubtedly prevented a terrible accident. As it was, the collision was of sufficient force to do considerable damage to the engines, and break up the baggage-cars and platforms of a number of the passenger-cars. Rev. Mr. ROMEYN, who was standing on one of the platforms at the time, was crushed to death. A German, whose name could not be ascertained, had one leg crushed and the other badly injured, and another man had his ancle badly bruised. It is said that no persons in the cars were injured. The German was taken to Turner's Station, where his leg was amputated by Dr. GENOA, of the New-York Hospital, who was a passenger on the train. His recovery is doubtful.

abstract: Apprenticeship System, the
snippet: Apprenticeship System, the
lead_paragraph: There is no question more important or more worthy the attention of the mechanic classes of this country than that of the future of the rising population, which has to live by the labor of its hands. We see every day great numbers of boys, smart, intelligent, capable of achieving an honorable livelihood, and yet whose habits, occupations and desires appear to be aimless, without benefit to others and injurious to themselves. Some boys step into employments in which their time is lounged away, and wherein laziness is the only lesson learned, unless indeed, the leisure of which they soon weary tends toward positive sin; others there are who turn to a dozen different occupations in succession, until, having arrived at man's estate, with perhaps the rashly contracted responsibilities of married life hanging upon them, they are useless except as mere seekers of odd jobs and powerless to raise themselves and those around them from poverty and its attendant evils.

abstract: In many of the districts the inspectors were kept quite busy throughout the afternoon and evening; but in the majority there was little work to do. In one district only three electors registered, and in another but five appeared during the day. Our figures show the last Presidential vote in every district in the city, as compared with the total registry thus far. The figures for the Third Ward are those of Friday night -- the inspectors not having returned yesterday's work. If we had received these figures our report of the entire registry would have been accurate and complete. The total for the whole city, at the closing of the registry offices on Friday night, was 74,685, and the total at the close last night was 84,320, showing that 10,135 names were recorded yesterday. This is much better than was expected.

lead_paragraph: -- The quacks are already taking advantage of the threatened approach of the cholera, and expect to reap a rich harvest if it really comes. All sorts of nostrums and specifics, liquid and solid, in pills and powders, are making their appearance, each warranted to cure. The intelligent public need not be warned against these dangerous medicaments. Some of them may be harmless, but far the greater part are really injurious. There is no medical specific for the cholera; but good care and the advice of a good physician should always be availed of, in case of danger.

abstract: Justice Miller, of the Supreme Court, has rendered an important decision in the case of Charles Luling et al. vs. the Atlantic Mutual Insurance Co. The defendants issued policies to the plaintiffs, the premiums and also the losses on which were payable in gold. At the end of the year the defendants issued certificates of profits, in which all their customers participated.
lead_paragraph: Justice Miller, of the Supreme Court, has rendered an important decision in the case of Charles Luling et al. vs. the Atlantic Mutual Insurance Co. The defendants issued policies to the plaintiffs, the premiums and also the losses on which were payable in gold. At the end of the year the defendants issued certificates of profits, in which all their customers participated. The plaintiffs received their certificate, which was calculated on a currency and not on a gold basis, and they then commenced an action against the company to compel them to readjust the dividends. Justice Miller rendered a decision to the effect that the plaintiffs are entitled to a certificate for an increased amount, so as to place them on an equality with the bolders of certificates of currency policies. A referee is to be appointed, to whom the defendants must render an account of the manner in which they have made up their statement of dividends for the years of 1863 and 1864, and estimated their profits, and the statement of dividends readjusted in accordance with the suggestions here made. In the meantime the defendants are enjoined from redeeming any of the certificates issued for the year 1863, and from issuing any new ones for the year 1864, until they have corrected and readjusted the declaration of dividends made.

abstract: MEYERBEER'S opera of "Robert le Diable," produced successfully at the Academy of Music on Friday evening, and to one of the most brilliant audiences of the season, will be repeated to-night for tho second and "last" time. The veracity of the latter...
lead_paragraph: MEYERBEER's opera of "Robert le Diable," produced successfully at the Academy of Music on Friday evening, and to one of the most brilliant audiences of the season, will be repeated to-night for tho second and "last" time. The veracity of the latter statement, as well as its necessity, may well be questioned. The sternest managerial duty hardly justify the withdrawal of a work which the public demands. Our confidence in this Spartan resolve is somewhat shaken, too, by noticing that the come opera of "Crispino e la Comare" which was played for the "last" time on Tuesday of the past week, will be repeated to-morrow night. At the time we ventured to suggest that it was a pity to shelve this very agreeable work. It is with entire satisfaction, therefore, that we hear of its restoration to the programme A satisfactory demonstration of the popularity of the music was made on Saturday, when, notwithstanding the terrible storm, a brilliant and large audience assembled at the matinee, and seemed to enjoy itself in defiance of the elements. Mr. MALETZEK's announcements for the week are full of interest. They are as follows: Tonight, (Monday,) "Robert le Diablo" to-morrow (Tuesday,) "Crispino e la Comare:" Wednesday, "Rigoletto:" Thursday, opera in Brooklyn; Friday, "Fra Diavolo;" Saturday, a grand combination matinee, and on Saturday evening, a grand extra performance for the benefit of the Benevolent Dramatic and Musical Association. (What is this? -- something with a "strike" in it?)

abstract: LAYING THE FOUNDATION STONE OF A ROMAN CATHOLIC ORPHAN ASYLUM IN BROOKLYN.--Yesterday, shortly after 12 o'clock, noon, various temperance and other societies assembled in the neighborhood of Clinton and Atlantic streets, for the purpose of marching in procession to take part in the ceremony of laying
lead_paragraph: LAYING THE FOUNDATION STONE OF A ROMAN CATHOLIC ORPHAN ASYLUM IN BROOKLYN. -- Yesterday, shortly after 12 o'clock, noon, various temperance and other societies assembled in the neighborhood of Clinton and Atlantic streets, for the purpose of marching in procession to take part in the ceremony of laying the foundation stone for the Male Roman Catholic Orphan Asylum of Brooklyn. Extensive preparations had been making for some time past by a convention of delegates from the societies, which were brought to a close in the latter part of the week by the selection of JOHN WALL, Esq., as Grand Marshal, who issued a programme for the guidance of those wishing to take part in the procession. The societies represented were: St. Ann's T.A.B., St. James' R.C.B. Society, Young Men's F.M.T.A.B., No. 1, and St. Paul's, No. 2, Father Mathew, No. 5, A.O. Hibernians, Assumption, Shamrock, Laborers' Union, and St. Patrick's Societies. The line of march was from Atlantic, through Clinton, to Joralemon to Fulton, Concord to Jay street, to Myrtic-avenue, to Court-street, Atlantic-avenue, New-York-avenue, Wyckoff-street, to Albany-avenue. When the societies arrived at the site of the building they formed in front and on the sides, and with the crowd already congregated could not have numbered much less than twenty thousand persons.

lead_paragraph: presents several revolting features. It is equally discreditable to the Democratic party, and the political "skedadlers" upon its ticket that these deserters, as soon as they reach the enemy's camp, should be rewarded with promotions. The British Government pensioned ARNOLD, but they did not put him in office. Though the exhibition is disgusting, it is perfectly natural that apostate nominees should have apostate champions. Mr. BLAIR himself is a shameful political deserter. He has no reason or excuse for going over to the "Peace" Democracy, but that of disappointment in obtaining office. Though but a third or fourth-rate lawyer, he demanded from Mr. LINCOLN the office of Chief Justice! That was very properly refused, and here he is abusing and slandering men for whom he professed friendship until he failed to obtain an office which required all his impudence and mendacity to ask for. How very low the Democracy has fallen, that it seeks refugees for candidates, and for its "heavy business" on the stump, a played-out office-seeker!

abstract: The investigation into the cause of the explosion of the St. John boiler was continued on Saturday, before Inspectors WEEKS  HOPPER, of the Local Board of Engineers, The testimony of the boiler.
lead_paragraph: The investigation into the cause of the explosion of the St. John boiler was continued on Saturday, before Inspectors WEEKS HOPPER, of the Local Board of Engineers, The testimony of the boiler. makers and engineers examined does not show entire unanimity in opinion as to the proper construction of the boilers. One manufacturer puts thirty pounds to the square inch as the maximum pressure which could safely be carried, while the safety-valve of the exploded boiler would not blow off under 33 pounds. Another thinks the boilers insufficiently braced, and the iron too thin. The inspectors will probably continue the investigation two or three days more. The testimony on Saturday was substantially as follows:

abstract: -- The Democracy do not condescend to tell us in what respects they desire to alter the course of the present Republican administration. The magnanimous policy of the administration toward the South they profess to approve. The policy of the Secretary of the Treasury in reducing the aggregate of the public debt, and economizing the public expenses, they do not find fault with. The foreign policy of the Secretary of State they have not assailed. The disbandment of the army and the naval forces, by the Secretaries of War and of the Navy, they do not complain of. In short, the administration of the Republican party seems to suit them in nearly all its features. Under these circumstances, they should all vote the republican ticket.

abstract: -- The Union men of Kings County have no more worthy man nominated for place than the candidate for Senator of the Second District, Mr. HENRY R. PIERSON. He is an old citizen, well posted by active service, and his record as a Union man is untarnished. His energy and consistency are admitted on all hands, and his opponents have only one charge which they make against him, which is, that he is President of the Brooklyn City Railroad Company. The answer to this is, that under Mr. PIERSON's management that institution has been greatly improved. He is beloved by his men as being kind, giving them liberal wages, and lightening their duty when he can. He is attentive to all complaints, and promptly remedies them when possible. He has popularized an institute always open to abuses, and has [???] himself sagacious and faithful. Mr. [???]ON will be elected, we think, but let every Union man vote for him. His opponent, CALVIN E. PRATT, is running on his military reputation. He was a militia General, and being a strong MCCLELLAN man, left the army when he did, and has since spent his time in denouncing the Administration, until the last somersault of his party, and now claims to be elected upon such a record.

abstract: Carme and D. Kavanagh
snippet: Carme and D. Kavanagh
lead_paragraph: Undoubtedly one of the most brilliant billiard matches which ever occurred on this continent came off at Irving Hall, in this city, on Saturday evening last. It was the second of a series of three games between DUDLEY KAVANAGH, who for nearly two years was champion of America, and PIERRE CARME, a renowned expert from France. The first game, which was the three-ball carom game, was played in the hall adjoining the Fifth-avenue Hotel on the 5th of last month, and on that occasion CARME was successful by 26 points in a score of 250 up. Immediately after this CARME commenced practice for the four-ball game, which was entirely new and very perplexing to him; yet in a day or two, while he was progressing finely, he was seized with a pulmonary attack, from the effects of which he has scarcely recovered at the present time. As this completely interrupted his training, and as it was deemed certain no postponement would be allowed, he had almost determined to forfeit; but a few days since, being enabled to resume practicing, his progress was so rapid that his friends advised him to play the match. Yet his full determination to do so was only arrived at on Friday evening.

abstract: Rebel Loan; Bondholders' Report at London Meeting
snippet: Rebel Loan; Bondholders' Report at London Meeting
lead_paragraph: The report of the Committee of Confederate Bondholders, which was read to a small meeting of those unfortunates at the London Tavern on the 18th of October, contains so many extraordinary, and even ludicrous positions, that we hardly know where to begin to discuss them. It opened by setting forth a correspondence with the house of ERLANGER & CO., the contractor of the loan, the amount of which was that that shrewd house announced that it had no property whatever of the rebel government, or anything else which could help the bondholders. It would seem as if that fact made any further report utterly useless, but the committee seem not to have been at all discouraged by this fact, but proceed with as long a report as if there were millions of property within their reach.

abstract: PRISONERS. -- We have intelligence this morning from South America that in the war between Paraguay and Brazil, the latter power has made a capture of five thousand prisoners, who were immediately disposed of by being drafted into the Brazilian or allied army, to serve against their own country. This in not an absolutely novel mode of disposing of prisoners of war; but the expedient has generally worked very badly, and has frequently been the cause of disasters in the field. The allies will doubtless distribute their five thousand Paraguayan prisoners through their army in companies, or else will totally break up the organization and sprinkle them individually among their own forces.

lead_paragraph: We are glad to see the grwoth of a more hopeful spirit in the South, as to its future prospects and condition. We have given articles in this vein from the journals of Richmond, New-Orleans, Charleston and other cities. The country papers of the South are getting to be no less hopeful than those of the cities. The Charlottesville Chronicle says: "We are going to be richer and more prosperous than we ever were. We are going to be populous, going to have great cities, going to grow alive with all the forms of industry. With wealth will come knowledge and culture, literature, science, art." abstract: Registry in Four Wards and the Last Election
snippet: Registry in Four Wards and the Last Election
lead_paragraph: There are four wards in this city upon which the Democratic party have for years drawn for any required amount of majority. They are the first, fourth, sixth and four-teenth. Last year they gave MCCLELLAN 12,266 votes, and LINCOLN 1,835 -- in all 14,103. To keep up their strength, the party this year have been active in bringing up their men to be registered, yet thus far the whole number of voters of all parties recorded in those wards is but 9,128. Say that only 1,500 of the 1,835 Unionists are recorded, and we have the significant fact that only 7,628 Democrats have been raked up, while MCCLELLAN had counted out for him 12,266. Now where are the 4,638 last year's Democrats not yet registered? Would it be presuming too much to guess that there might have been the least touch of illegal voting in these precincts? Compare the three strongest Union words with the above and see the difference:

MURRAY, of No. 25 West Houston-street, for registering his name in the Third District of the Fifteenth Ward, after he had registered in the Sixth District of the Eighth Ward. Mr. GEORGE M. abstract: SLUNG-SHOT IN A RAILWAY CAR. -- At about noon, yesterday, Mr. THOMAS MCCARTNEY, of No. 104 Cannon-street, stood talking with the conductor of a Canal-street car near the Grand-street ferry, and gave the conductor a $10 bank-note, for which he received smaller notes. As he took the money, one of a gang of thieves standing near the car said to the conductor, "Shove that fellow off the car, and we'll see how long he has that money!" They then attacked Mr. MCCARTNEY as he was entering the car, and one JAMES DAVRIN, it is alleged, knocked him down with a slung-shot, and the other fellows kicked him and beat him unmercifully while he lay on the floor. Policeman ANDERSON, of the Thirteenth Ward, reached the spot in season to arrest DAVRIN. The prisoner, on being taken before Justice MANSFIELD, said that he was intoxicated. He is a native of Ireland, dwells at No. 390 Madison-street, and has no reputable occupation. Justice MANSFIELD committed him for trial on charge of attempt to rob.

abstract: There is one question to be decided by the vote to-day which has commanded far less attention than it deserves. The people are called on to vote "for or against a State debt to pay bounties." Many will very naturally suppose that by voting against it, they will save themselves and the State from incurring a debt.
lead_paragraph: There is one question to be decided by the vote to-day which has commanded far less attention than it deserves. The people are called on to vote "for or against a State debt to pay bounties." Many will very naturally suppose that by voting against it, they will save themselves and the State from incurring a debt. But the debt has already been incurred, and the only question to be decided now is, whether it shall be paid this year, or converted into a debt and paid by yearly installments running over the next twelve years.

abstract: -- On Sunday evening Patrolman CLINCHY, of the Eighth Ward, apprehended a drunken and disorderly negro in Sullivan-street, near Broome, and a gang by whom the prisoner was accompanied, thereupon fell upon the officer, seized his club, knocked him to the pavement, and there kicked him in the face and on the body, and at length left him unconscious on the sidewalk. Two civilians subsequently found the officer apparently dead, and took him to the Wooster-street Police-station, where he was attended by Surgeon POOLER. The officer's left eye is closed, and he is seemingly seriously injured internally.

abstract: -- WILLIAM CHASE BARNEY, a clerk in the Custom-house, and one BENTHAM FABIAN, formerly a clerk in the ~Treasury Department, were taken before Justice DOWLING, yesterday, and Mr. NELSON K. WHEELER, Deputy Collector of the Port, appeared and made affidavit that they had attempted, by executing three spurious bonds, to withdraw from the Custom-house three hundred barrels of whisky, which were in bond, and the duty on which amounted to $40,000. The accused were defended by ROBERT D. HOLMES, Esq.; and he made an argument before Justice DOWLING, contending that the case should be removed to a United States court, and JOHN SEDGWICK, Esq., for the government, held that Justice DOWLING had full jurisdiction. Decision is to be rendered this morning; meantime the accused were held for examination. BARNEY was arrested many years ago, on charge of being engaged in certain gold-dust frauds.

abstract: -- The cholera has already menaced the city, and it is widely feared that we shall have a visitation of it next Spring, if not sooner. To ward it off, or to limit its ravages, it is essential that the city should be put under healthy conditions. It might have been in a fair way toward this by the present time had not the Democracy defeated the Health Bill in the Legislature last Winter. The need of such measures as the bill provided for is now more imperative than ever, and whether or not we shall have them in operation by next Spring, depends upon the kind of men who are now sent by us to the Legislature.

abstract: Godfrey vs. Sun Mutual Insurance; Concealment by Insurers
snippet: Godfrey vs. Sun Mutual Insurance; Concealment by Insurers
lead_paragraph: Jonathan Godfrey vs. The Sun Mutual Insurance Company. -- This case came on to be tried before Judge NELSON and a jury, on the 31st day of October, and resulted, late on Friday afternoon, in a verdict for the defendants. The plaintiff sued on a policy dated the 24th of June, 1863, issued to him as part owner of the bark Tycoon, for the amount of $10,000, being $8,000 on the hull and $2,000 on the freight, covering only the risk of capture by Confederate cruisers. The defence was rested upon these two grounds: that the plaintiff, when he applied for and procured the insurance, concealed a fact material to the case, which he knew, but which was unknown to the company, and represented that another company (the Atlantic) asked six per cent. premium for doing it, when they had, in fact, refused to take it at a much higher rate.

abstract: Yesterday afternoon a meeting of the NewYork Musical Protective Association, was held at the Germania Assembly Rooms. The meeting was numerously attended. As the reporters of the press were rigidly excluded, no authentic report can be made of the proceedings.
lead_paragraph: Yesterday afternoon a meeting of the New-York Musical Protective Association, was held at the Germania Assembly Rooms. The meeting was numerously attended. As the reporters of the press were rigidly excluded, no authentic report can be made of the proceedings. From conversation, however ever, with some of the members of the association, it was learned that, after a stormy session and some debate, the society resolved to levy a tax of one dollar on each member, to support the strikers, so it only remains for time and the longest purse to determine the winning side in the contest.

abstract: Registry, Result of the
snippet: Registry, Result of the
lead_paragraph: As we suspected, there was a bold push made yesterday to increase the Registry roll for the purpose of getting in a large Democratic vote. Nearly 14,000 names were recorded, most of them doubtless legal voters, but a large number notoriously not so. For instance, from one house in the Eighth Ward thirteen persons were registered, but upon close inquiry after the books closed only six of them proved to be residents there.

abstract: Union Course. George Wilkes and Com. Vanderbilt, for $2,000; Atlantic vs. Athletic at Brooklyn
snippet: Union Course. George Wilkes and Com. Vanderbilt, for $2,000; Atlantic vs. Athletic at Brooklyn
lead_paragraph: In the previous match contest in harness between these champion stallions of the trotting turf, when the driver of Wilkes pulled into Vanderbilt and broke him up badly, Wilkes was the winner. Without meaning to imply that this accident was intentional; on the contrary, believing that it happened by a mistake of Wilkes' driver, who endeavored to get his horse down from a bad break by pulling him on the wrong side; yet the result of the accident was the same for Vanderbilt, who never recovered the effects of that break throughout the remainder of the race. The return match between these two horses to wagons was set down for Thursday last, but The weather on that day proved too bad for frotting purposes, and the conditions being "fair day and good track," the match was postponed from day to day until yesterday, when it came off. The rules of the trotting turf are definite and conclusive enough, and certainly imply that when a match is made for a certain day, with the conditions of "a fair day and good track," if lack of these conditions compels its postponement, all bets are off; and that when the match comes to an issue, it has to be regarded as a new race; so, however, do not argue the judges of the Union Track. On Thursday last, prior to the setting in of the storm which precluded the trotting of the match, the usual toss for choice of places took place, and Wilkes won the pole -- a considerable advantage in a close race, as all trotting men are fully aware. The judges yesterday without any foundation decided by a vote of two to one, that the chances of last Thursday should hold good for yesterday, when the former was a past and undecided event. By what process of reasoning they arrived at this conclusion, is best known to themselves. Perhaps the umpire judge could best explain this matter, and not the one appointed either by the owner of Wilkes or Vanderbilt. Nevertheless the old adage of "judge knowing the best" was acted on, and the dictum of the judicial trio was submitted to not, however, without some just murmurings on the part of the malcontents. The betting had been for several days previously strongly in favor of the stallion Wilkes, and prior to the start it stood at $100 to $30 on him against his opponent.

abstract: -- If only to put it out of its misery, the Copperhead Democracy should be settled to-day. It got knocked on the head when the rebellion fell, but ever since then it has been attempting by its wriggling to make the people believe that it possessed in full all the elements of vitality. It was defeated in the elections in Maine and Vermont in September, in Pennsylvania and Ohio in October; and it only awaits its final deliverance from further infamy, at the hands of New-York and New-Jersey, in this month of November. Of course Massachusetts and the Western States, in which elections will also be held, will do their duty. After to-day the history of the entire career and bad end of Democracy can be completed.

abstract: Information has been received by the Toronto Leader, of the safe arrival in Glasgow, of Capt. BENNETT G. BURLEY. abstract: -- One chief reason why the Democratic party will be voted down to-day, is that the great body of the American people are very well satisfied with the administration of the Republican party. They find that the present Republican Administration is vigorous and successful in the days of peace, as it was patriotic and true during the time of war. They find that it is economical in the management of our domestic affairs, temperate in the conduct of our foreign policy, conciliatory toward the South, and equally just in its dealings with all sections and interests of the country. They dread the sort of changes which many of the Democratic leaders are proposing. They do not desire that the national credit should in any way be tampered with, or that we should become the blusterer among the nations, or that the government should be administered in the interest of a section or a faction, or that we should indulge in extravagant or wasteful expenditure. And as the country has learned that an administration which is reasonably satisfactory to all parties, is a rare thing, and a difficult one to be obtained, they will show their approval of our Republican Administration by sustaining it with their votes.

abstract: Mr. Jacob Patterson, of Munroe, Orange County, N.Y., had been suffering for years from Consumption with a severe putrid infections sore throat, to make new of his own words, a hurried respiration, hot and offensive breath, the skin of a burning and disagreeable heat, without the least moisture; the pulse quick, hard and irregular, averaging from 100 to 140 strokes per minute; the month and throat presenting a fiery appearance, the palate and glands painfully swelled; combined with a pain in the chest, the whole countenance presenting a ghastly, cadaverous look; the white part of the eye had [???]pearly, unnatural appearance, and, strange to say, the eye itself beamed with sparkling animation and lustre; the expectoration was copious and frequent; white, frothy and sometimes tough opaque substance, solid, of a yellow or green color, having a fetid smell when thrown on bursting coals. In this infected state he was treated by the most eminent physicians he could find, but the excruciating pain in his side and chest, which became insupportable, so much alarmed his friends, that in this last dismal waste of life, he was taken to the well-known Dr. Von Eisenberg, of our city. At the doctor's office he complained of weakness at the least bodily exertion, and when placed in the examination chair, the breathing was fearful, the pulse was small and quicker than natural; he complained of a tightness, as if a cord were drawn across the chest. The doctor, with his usual care, made an accurate diagnosis of the case, expressed willingness to undertake to treat him, and to attend to him to the best of his ability. The doctor declared himself to be always impressed with a decided belief that our wise and beneficent Creator has placed within the reach of his feeble creature man, a cure for all diseases; that he has often cured this fatal complaint by assiduous attention and careful judgment. lead_paragraph: Mr. Jacob Patterson, of Munroe, Orange County, N.Y., had been suffering for years from Consumption with a severe putrid infections sore throat, to make new of his own words, a hurried respiration, hot and offensive breath, the skin of a burning and disagreeable heat, without the least moisture; the pulse quick, hard and irregular, averaging from 100 to 140 strokes per minute; the month and throat presenting a fiery appearance, the palate and glands painfully swelled; combined with a pain in the chest, the whole countenance presenting a ghastly, cadaverous look; the white part of the eye had [???]pearly, unnatural appearance, and, strange to say, the eye itself beamed with sparkling animation and lustre; the expectoration was copious and frequent; white, frothy and sometimes tough opaque substance, solid, of a yellow or green color, having a fetid smell when thrown on bursting coals. In this infected state he was treated by the most eminent physicians he could find, but the excruciating pain in his side and chest, which became insupportable, so much alarmed his friends, that in this last dismal waste of life, he was taken to the well-known Dr. Von Eisenberg, of our city. At the doctor's office he complained of weakness at the least bodily exertion, and when placed in the examination chair, the breathing was fearful, the pulse was small and quicker than natural; he complained of a tightness, as if a cord were drawn across the chest. abstract: -- We earnestly trust the intelligent people of New-Jersey will make a manly effort to carry their State for the party which will secure the ratification of the Constitutional Amendment by the Legislature. It is exceedingly important that this great measure should receive the indorsement of all the States, and the more promptly this is done the better. The Republican administration and the Republican party favor it with all their hearts. The Democratic party of New-Jersey voted against it in the last Legislature, and are still opposed to it, though some of them pretend to favor President JOHNSON's policy, one of the chief aims of which is to secure the ratification of the Constitutional Amendment.

abstract: Party, Last Resort to Be Tested
snippet: Party, Last Resort to Be Tested
lead_paragraph: To-day the last resort, the forlorn hope, of the Democratic party is to be tested. All other means having failed, it is now to be seen whether there is any saving power in the unheard-of expedient of going to the opposite party for a platform and ticket. Never, in the political history of the country, has there been found such another succession of desperate devices to gain power as the Democratic party has practiced for the last four years. It would have puzzled MACHIAVELLI himself to have conceived a greater variety of expedients for accomplishing a political end.

abstract: The Musical Protective Association held a special meeting yesterday afternoon, at the Germania Assembly Rooms, in the Bowery, to consider the present features of the strike now in progress among the theatrical orchestral performers of this city. Owing to the exclusion of reporters, no record of their proceedings can be given; but it is ascertained that they resolved to tax each member of the association $1 per week to help the strikers to hold out.
lead_paragraph: The Musical Protective Association held a special meeting yesterday afternoon, at the Germania Assembly Rooms, in the Bowery, to consider the present features of the strike now in progress among the theatrical orchestral performers of this city. Owing to the exclusion of reporters, no record of their proceedings can be given; but it is ascertained that they resolved to tax each member of the association $1 per week to help the strikers to hold out. Some slight modifications in their scale of prices were made, but no action was taken on the salaries of members of orchestras. It is understood that the leaders of the different orchestras have retired from the association to enable them to recruit their orchestras from abroad.

abstract: The jury in the sanders conspiraey case, which was recently on trial is Montreal, were discharged on Monday, the Judge specially remanding the prisoners to jail till the March term. Judgo MONDELET addressed the jurors in very strong language.
lead_paragraph: The jury in the sanders conspiraey case, which was recently on trial is Montreal, were discharged on Monday, the Judge specially remanding the prisoners to jail till the March term. Judgo MONDELET addressed the jurors in very strong language. He told them in substance either that they were too ignorant to understand the evidence or they have perjured themselves, as the case was not one admitting of doubt. From the subsequent conversation between the Judge and Mr. RAMSAY, the papers say they suspect some tampering with jurors.

abstract: Republic, Steamship; Chief Officers' Boat Rescued
snippet: Republic, Steamship; Chief Officers' Boat Rescued
lead_paragraph: Yesterday morning the steamer Gen. Hooker arrived in port, bringing twelve of the passengers and crew of the ill-fated Republic. The history of these people is truly distressing, they having suffered everything but death. The boat under the command of the chief officer, S.[???]. YOUNG, left the Republic just as she was going down, and in a few minutes swamped; but owing to the energy and coolness of those on board, the boat was cleared of water and kept head on the sea till daylight. By a singular good fortune, Capt. GEO. W. MCNAIR, late of the ship Inspector, was on board the boat, and as the chief officer was exhausted by his efforts to save the steamship, Capt. McNair took the management of the boat, so as to give Mr. YOUNG some time to rest; and the passengers kept rowing with a desperation which only the fate before them could inspire. The demijohn containing the only water on board got broken before one drop of it was used -- thus thirst, more terrible than anything that can be describe, was added to their other calamities. The boat had no provisions except salt meal and ship bread, which got saturated with salt water, with [???] exception of three cans of preserved fruit. T[???] may be said to have saved the lives of the people[???] the boat, and were kept to the very last. On [???]day, every one having become so much exhausted that it was impossible to make headway by rowing, a table-cloth was found in the boat, and they extemporized a sail, and with that the boat was kept on her course to the westward, as well as could be done with nothing but sun and the stars to guide them. Thursday night was one of intense suffering, and insanity, the invariable result of exposure, want of sleep and thirst, began to exhibit itself. Friday morning came, and no sail, no land in sight. It was water -- water everywhere. The imagination of all on the boat began to conjure up sights and sounds which were only imagination. Insanity was dawning upon every mind. At about 10 in the morning of Friday, a sail in the distance was discovered, and, as the breeze had died away, the sail in the boat was taken down, and the oars again assumed for a pull for life. They kept on for hours, but could not gain on the sail in the distance, and finally gave up. Having worked in the sun with all the energy possible so long, and yielding the chase in disappointment at last, the sensation of thirst now seemed, at this time, to be unendurable. Men's throats were swollen, their jaws set, and speech began to be difficult. As a last resort, the whole party jumped into the sea to bathe and absorb moisture externally. It seemed to allay the burning thirst. Soon another soil came in sight in the opposite direction, and, as a last effort, the boat was reversed and they began to pull for it. The sail proved to be the barkentine Horace Beals, from New-York, commanded by Capt. JOSEPH BLANKENSHIP, who picked them up at 6 o'clock P.M., after they had been in the water for fifty-one hours; and every thing that could be done for their comfort was done by Capt. BLANKENSHIP. They could not stand when they were hoisted upon his deck, but were soon restored by the use of stimulants and water. If ever a man was a nobleman by nature, who held his patent direct from his Maker, that man was Capt. JOSEPH BLANKENSHIP. The survivors cannot say too much in his praise. From the time they were taken on board till Sunday evening, they remained upon his ship, when the steamer Gen. Hooker came up and took them off, and brought them to this port yesterday morning.

abstract: State Election, Vote by Wards
snippet: State Election, Vote by Wards
lead_paragraph: Never was the verity of an adage more clearly demonstrated than was yesterday that which says, "clouds and darkness are the friends of the Democracy; a bright sun and clear sky will bring fortune to their opponents." The polls were opened as the genial sun rose clear as a bell, and with it rose the hopes of the Republican managers throughout the city. Quite early the voters appeared at the polls, and without trouble, annoying delay or provoking challenge, deposited each his ballot and retired. So signal a victory is rarely won as that gained by the believers in the efficacy of the Registry Law. Its beneficial influence was felt at every poll and by every inspector; the labors of the officials were wonderfully lightened, the delay so vexatious to business men was entirely obviated, frauds were effectually guarded against, and peace, quiet and good order reigned throughout the borders of a city, whose election days have been memorable for rows and riots since their earnest date.

abstract: doubt that the general operations of the Freedmen's Bureau have been eminently favorable to the restoration of order and labor in the Southern States. The existence of the Bureau was limited by Act of Congress to one year after the termination of the war, so that, unless further special legislation is taken by the coming Congress, it will cease to exist next Spring. In the meantime the Legislatures of all the Southern States which will be in session this Winter -- and they will all be in session except those of Florida and Texas -- should promptly take up the question of the Freedmen's rights and relations, and establish such laws and regulations as are demanded by justice and humanity. It would be much better that the whole matter should be in the hands of the Southern people and the respective States; and if they evince a purpose to treat the question as the circumstances demand, Congress will leave it entirely to their jurisdiction, by taking no measures for perpetuating the existence of the Freedmen's Bursau.

abstract: MURDER IN THIRTY-NINTH STREET. -- At about 8 o'clock yesterday morning JOHN GOODMAN, of No. 139 East Thirty-ninth-street, and DANIEL MCDONALD, otherwise "Yankee Dan," of "Dutch Hill," engaged to a political wrangle in MICHAEL FAY's liquor-store, at the intersection of Second-avenue and Thirty-ninth-street, and GOODMAN stabbed MCDONALD in the neck with a common pocket-knife. The blade penetrated about three inches, and severed one of the main arteries. MCDONALD's life-blood spirted forth in a fearful stream, and he died before his friends could reach Bellevue Hospital. GOODMAN, fled to STEPHEN GEOGHEGAN's house, at the intersection of Third-avenue and Fortieth-street, and sought to conceal himself in a bed; but his hiding-place was discovered by Sergt. BARNITT, of the Twenty-first Precinct police, and taken to the Thirty-fifth-street police station, where he was held to await the action of Coroner COLLIN. Both men were under the influence of liquor at the time of the killing, and there had been a quarrel of long standing between them. GOODMAN is said to have threatened to take MCDONALD's life. An inquest is to be held to-day at Bellevue Hospital.

abstract: State Election Results
snippet: State Election Results
lead_paragraph: We hope Mr. MONTGOMERY BLAIR feels better. We trust he will return to the bosom of the Blair family a wiser if not a better man. We hope JOHN VAN BUREN is satisfied that the people of this State have not the slightest inclination to force him again into the same hole he came out of twenty years ago. We hope Messrs. SLOCUM, ROBINSON & CO. are content with the rewards they receive for deserting the party that has trusted them hitherto, and for consenting under temptations of office to betray it into the hands of its enemies. And we commend to the Democratic leaders at large the lesson inculcated by this election, that no party which discards all show of honesty, and trades wholly on stolen capital, can command the confidence or secure the indorsement of the people of this State.

abstract: As early as 6 o'clock in the evening crowds commenced to assemble round the TIMES and other newspaper offices, anxiously waiting for news from the various districts. Of course no returns were received at so early an hour, yet the public were on hand, and waited with exemplary patience for the figures which were to show whether or not their favorite candidates had been elected. For the first few hours, the returns came in slowly, and it was not until after 10 o'clock that the total vote of any ward was known. The TIMES had made ample provision for bulletining the returns as received, and immense crowds congregated in and around the office, those who could not catch a sight of the figures depending on their friends in front to keep them posted up. Here were the merchant and the banker, the resident of Fifth-avenue and of the Bowery, the man who owns a fast team and the one who drives a butcher's cart, touching elbows, and all apparently equally interested in watching the magic figures, which told of hopes realized or of aspirations dashed to the ground. The little work girl, who had spent the weary day in some dark left toiling until hands and brain were weary, stopped as she passed the newspaper offices to see who was the fortunate candidate. The telegraph boy with his message, the porter with his load, the fast man fresh from his carouse, pater familias hurrying home to his family and fireside, could not resist the opportunity of one glance at the bulletin. Many were the means adopted by the crowds around the offices for passing the time. The qualities and chances of success of the various candidates were of course freely discussed. Men bet greenbacks, boys bet peanuts on their favorites. The operations of the Registry Law offered a never-ending subject of discussion. The Democrats appeared to be, for some reason not particularly clear, entirely opposed to it. "This law," said a resident of the Second Ward, "was evidently intended to choke off the Democratic vote. It's only of another piece with the census swindle. At the last Presidential election our district (the first) cast 144 votes for MCCLELLAN, and now the district only gives, according to that bulletin, 147 votes in all. Can anything be plainer than that this law was meant to kill the Democrats?" "But," said a Republican, "the law bears just as hard on us as on you. Our vote in that district for LINCOLN was 127, and now we only give BARLOW 66. You see the proportion is about the same. Besides, you must look at the good effect of the law. This time voters had not to wait for hours before they could get a chance to deposit their ballots. You just went up and voted. Last year many were kept away from the polls altogether, and there's no doubt many illegal ballots were cast. This year there will be few votes given that are not legal." The Democrat, however, could not be made to see it in this light, and went away grumbling that his party had been robbed of many thousand votes by the new Registry Law.

abstract: E.M. DOOD. -- Exceedingly interesting services were held in Bloomfield, N.J., on Sunday last, commemorative of the late Rev. EDWARD M. DODD, a missionary of the American Board, who died a few weeks since of cholera, in Marsovan, Turkey. Rev. C.E. KNOX, the present pastor of the church of which the deceased was formerly a member, preached an able and eloquent sermon, giving in connection with it a sketch of the life of Mr. DOOD; and Dr. WOOD, Secretary of the American Board, followed with some remarks upon the missionary life of the deceased. Measures were initiated to secure the erection of a suitable monument to the memory of Mr. DODD.

abstract: among us this Winter. It is a week since the Alalunta, arrived in our harbor with the decease on board, but even on the ship it had not spread, and no cases are reported in the [???]y or suburbs. A single case was reported in Brooklyn, but it turned out not to be Asiatic cholera. Otherwise New-York is about in its usual health, which is not saying much in its favor. Typhus is chronic, in a large and profound sense, and will continue to be so until law can be effectively brought to bear upon the tenement houses, the streets and the drainage. We earnestly hope that will be before the arrival of next Spring; and we trust that, in view of what may be anticipated in the future, parties will be able to agree upon some intelligent legislation applicable to our case.

abstract: Prof. Boynton's Wedding Trip at N. Y.
snippet: Prof. Boynton's Wedding Trip at N. Y.
lead_paragraph: For some days the curiosity-loving portion of the New-York public have been all agog with the latest sensation -- a projected marriage in a balloon. This extraordinary event promised to be fully as exciting as the famous, "Diamond Wedding," or even the Tom Thumb nuptials, for there was something peculiarly novel, not to say ridiculous, in the idea of a wedding taking place amid the clouds, with all mundane witnesses shut out by fleecy vapors, and the epithalamium sung by the rattling cordage of the aerial ship. The ladies naturally evinced considerable interest in the details of the affair, and yesterday they seemed determined to satisfy their curiosity to its full extent. For this unique marriage the most elaborate preparations were made. It was to have come off on Saturday last, but owing to the indisposition of the fair and daring bride it was postponed until yesterday afternoon. The rain-storm on Saturday would have postponed it at any rate, so no fault can be found on that score.

abstract: statistics made up at the War Department, of the casualties to our general officers during the war, it appears that we had eight Major-Generals and seventeen Brigadier-Generals killed outright in battle, while two Major-Generals and nine Brigadier-Generals died of wounds received in action, and seventeen Generals of the two ranks died of disease. In the year 1862, our losses of general officers in battle were very heavy, numbering no less than fifteen, while during the present year, or from the end of 1864 to the close of the war, we lost but one General, though the fighting was great and decisive. There is abundant material for reflection in these facts.

abstract: Rebel Debts, the Repudiation of
snippet: Rebel Debts, the Repudiation of
lead_paragraph: The debts of the Confederate Government, contracted for the purposes of war, and for all other purposes, were swept away when the Confederacy fell. All its currency, bills, bonds, treasury notes, and "promises to pay" of every kind, became worthless to the holders, even though those holders had given for them real property or services of a positive value. After the fall of Richmond, hundred-dollar bills, based on the faith and credit of the Confederacy, were sold for a nickel cent a piece, and thousand-dollar notes were exchanged evenly for three-cent shinplasters. There is little if any talk in any part of the South about assuming any part of this debt. Its magnitude is appalling, and the States of the South did not become responsible for it in their individual capacity. On its face it was declared to be payable upon the establishment of the independence of the Southern Confederacy -- thus linking its fortunes with that of the rebel government; and it was but logical that the Confederacy's credit should cease to have a value when the Confederacy itself ceased to have an existence.

lead_paragraph: Attorney-General JOHN COCHRANE attended police trials yesterday morning, and was much pleased with the entertainment. Of the eighty-five cases of the day that were investigated by Commissioners ACTON, BERGEN and McMURRAY, the complaint of Mr. EDWARD D. McCARTHY, a Pine-street lawyer, against Patrolman JOHN COOPER, of the Fifteenth Ward, was the most conspicuous. A dispute occurred between Mr. MCCARTHY and another gentleman, in the vestibule of Wallack's Theatre, on the evening of the 25th ult, and the officer interfered, in obedience to orders from his superior officers. The board sustained their subordinate. A curious story of alleged betrayal was told by an attractive little miss of sixteen summers; but she spoiled it all by revealing the fact that she had once been an inmate of the "Bowery Belle."

abstract: The Washington correspondent of the Cincinnati Commercial telegraphs as follows to that paper, under date of Nov. 6: "Chief-Justice CHASE has notified the President that, after a thorough and careful examination into the whole question, he can not preside over the court for the trial of JEFF. DAVIS in the City of Richmond. The reason he assigns is, that there is no regularly organized court in that city. Thus the government is all at sea again in regard to his trial. The President maintains that he cannot be tried at any other place. The impression is that he will be released, with the understanding that he is to go to Europe and not return, or in other words, to be expatriated."

abstract: Democratic Defeats Blessings in disguise; The late Election
snippet: Democratic Defeats Blessings in disguise; The late Election
lead_paragraph: eracy was on its last legs, one of its newspaper organs pronounced the great Confederate defeat at Wilmington to be a "blessing in disguise," and the phrase became very popular in the country after each successive rebel disaster. The Democratic party, in these latter days of its existence, seem to be adopting the fine philosophy of the expiring Confederates. The Albany Argus of yesterday says of the great Democratic defeats of Tuesday: "The Democracy who have lost nothing, can afford, as a party, to wait. Indeed, in a party point of view, it is better that the day of Democratic victory should be thus postponed; and that their opponents should involve themselves in the inextricable dilemmas which they have contrived." Thus our great Republican victory of Tuesday is confessed to be a blessing in disguise to the Democracy; and in this belief we have the pleasure of agreeing with them.

abstract: the, of Tuesday
snippet: the, of Tuesday
lead_paragraph: The result of the elections of Tuesday adds to the evidences, furnished so abundantly throughout the last five years, of the steady adherence of the people to the principles and policy sanctioned by their deliberate judgment. In 1860 they pronounced their verdict against the political domination and the territorial extension of slavery, by the election of President LINCOLN. When they found that this decision was to be contested by arms, instead of shrinking from the issue they met it boldly, and through four long years, disdaining all appeal to their fears, all considerations of convenience, all party attempts to swerve or seduce them from the path they had chosen, they prosecuted the war against rebellion with a steadiness and heroic courage unsurpassed in the annals of the world. Their devotion was crowned by a signal and decisive victory.

abstract: Maj.-Gen THOMAS FRANCIS MEAGHER reached Bannack City, Montana Territory, Sept. 23. Two days later, Gov. SYDNEY EDGERTON, who was about to leave the Territory for some months, proclaimed Gen. MEAGHER Acting Governor. On the 30th of Sept. Gov. MEAGHER was given a public reception by the Irish Americans and other residents of Virginia City.
lead_paragraph: Maj.-Gen THOMAS FRANCIS MEAGHER reached Bannack City, Montana Territory, Sept. 23. Two days later, Gov. SYDNEY EDGERTON, who was about to leave the Territory for some months, proclaimed Gen. MEAGHER Acting Governor. On the 30th of Sept. Gov. MEAGHER was given a public reception by the Irish Americans and other residents of Virginia City. The honorable gentleman made a most eloquent response, acknowledging the kindness of his friends, reviewing his past history, especially through the civil war, explaining the duties of all law-abiding citizens of the Territory towards the National Government, announcing his own resolute independence of party ties, and his devotion to what he considered the best interests of his country; and invoking in behalf of his administration of the affairs of the Territory, in the two-fold capacity of Governor and Secretary, the confidence and support of all the inhabitants of Montana, whose inestimable resources and glorious prospects he set forth in glowing language. On Monday, Oct. 2, Gov. MEAGHER formally entered upon the discharge of his official duties.

abstract: The steamship Circassian, from Southampton Oct. 25, arrived at this port last evening. Her news was fully anticipated, but she brings papers three days later. We give, in another column, an interesting article from the London Times, on the alleged dispatch from Secretary SEWARD to the French Government on the question of sending African troops to Mexico. The Times emphatically condemns the project, as one tending to increase the civil discord already existing in Mexico, and says that Mr. SEWARD was justified in remonstrating against it. The Times criticises Lord RUSSELL very sharply, and plainly intimates its want of faith in his ability to satisfy the demands of the nation as the successor of Lord PALMERSTON.

lead_paragraph: ARRESTS FOR ILLEGAL VOTING. -- Officer KENALLY, arrested an Irish laborer, named BERNARD GUNN, of 65 Willett-street, on a charge of attempting to vote illegally at the third poll district of the Thirteenth Ward. Justice MANSFIELD committed the accused in default of $l,500 bail....Officer ZEIGER, of the Eighteenth Precinct, arrested a man named FRANK McNIEE, charged with attempting to cast a fraudulent vote at the Twelfth poll district of the Eighteenth Ward. He gave the name of JOHN MAFIT, and said that he lived at No. 282 First-avenue. MCNIBB was committed to prison for examination....Officer PABER and FORBES, of the Twelfth Precinct, arrested MICHAEL KENNY, an Irish laborer, on a charge of illegally registering his name and voting, he not being a resident of the district in which he registered.... LAWRENCE REILLY was arrested by Officer LOUNSDALE, of the Fifteenth Precinct, on a charge of attempting to vote illegally in a poll district of the Fifteenth Ward. It was subsequently ascertained that REILLY was a deserter from the army, and he was given into the custody of the military authorities.

lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC -- VERDI's ever fresh and delightful opera of "Rigoletto" was revived here last evening in a thoroughly acceptable manner. Signor MAZZOLENI has seldom been heard to such advantage. The role of the Duke suits him as perfectly as that of Glauco, in "Ione." As an acting part it is even better, although it must be contessed that this admirable artist leads a somewhat disreputable life in both works. Signor BELLINI, as the poor, wronged Court Fool, was dramatic; but his voice lacked its usual resonance and vigor. Mlle. ORTALANI was the Gilda, and sang the light and agreeable music of the part with nice, artistic feeling and finish. In the second act the lady was heard to the best advantage; her voice subsequently being somewhat depressed in intonation. Miss ADELAIDE PHILLIPS was the Magdalena, and contributed largely to the success of the fourth act -- the only one in which she appears -- an act which the united opinion of the musical world has pronounced perfect. The freshness of the entire work is remarkable. Its performance is a boon to the public.

abstract: The Means of Checking; Advice to on the Late Elections
snippet: The Means of Checking; Advice to on the Late Elections
lead_paragraph: It is not at all certain that the enemy whose coming has been so long predicted and which seems now at our doors, will attack us this Autumn. It is late in the season, and not improbably cholera may smoulder in New-York during the Winter to burst forth with power in the Spring. Time may yet be given us for preparation. If the Health Bill should pass at an early day of the session in its original form, that is, with the Police Commissioners forming a part of the board, we may yet be able to throw up our intrenchments and stand a siege, though with but a poor defence, compared with what would have been made a year earlier. Under that benficent act we could even this Winter clean the city and purify tenement-houses and break up "fever nests" and remove nuisances, and no doubt save thousands of lives.

abstract: Women Clerks in the Departments
snippet: Women Clerks in the Departments
lead_paragraph: It would seem that the employment of women as clerks in the government departments at Washington has proved a failure. In the Department of the Interior, the dismissal of all the female clerks is being effected as rapidly as possible, and it is understood that the Treasury Department, which employs the largest number of any, is about to adopt the same course. The services of women, instead of being more economical than those of men, are found to be more expensive. Individually their wages may be less, but, in the aggregate, they accomplish less labor than an equal number of men. It is alleged in Washington that the mania for extravagant dress is one of the principal drawbacks to the efficiency of the women at their duties in the departments. abstract: Character of, and Precautions
snippet: Character of, and Precautions
lead_paragraph: It is a mistake to suppose that the cholera is a disease difficult to manage, or peculiarly dangerous. It is especially the sickness of the poor and the filthy. The more comfortable classes are comparatively little affected by it. Bad sanitary conditions, and nuisances which are obvious, influence it immediately. So clearly is this the fact, that many persons look upon it as a direct Providential punishment for want of cleanliness and carelessness of sanitary provisions. It rules most where other diseases which science can prevent are accustomed to rage; so that the fever nests and the homes of diphtheria and typhoid and scarlet fever are the favorites of the cholera. Scientific writers tells us that certain courts in English cities, where all the great pestilences have made fearful havoc, are still the chosen seats of this modern epidemic. The first cases in this city in 1849, were in Orange and Baxter streets, near the Five Points, in infamous dens of filth; it raged especially first in the Sixth and Fourth Wards. When it appears during this year or next, it will seek out the same districts. "Rotten Row," in Laurens-street, was a centre of the pestilence then; it will, undoubtedly, continue to be so now. The districts near the pig-styes, and the bone-boilers, and the exposed offal of slaughterhouses, suffered most in the former attacks; they will again. Open privies, cess-pools, heaps of garbage, crowds of inmates in dirty rooms, are what especially stimulated the disease before; they will still operate. It will be remembered by some of our citizens, that a butcher, whose daughters were in the habit of dressing the entrails of swine at night, though living in Seventh-avenue, quite apart from the scenes of the pestilence, was attacked with all his family.

lead_paragraph: The Democratic organs, as a general thing, take their recent defeat with a fair degree of resignation. They feel the necessity, to a certain extent, of representing it as a defeat of the President and of his policy; but this point is not urged with any special emphasis or warmth. From the same motive they predict all sorts of disaster from the assumed ascendancy of "the Radicals" in Congress, and are trying very hard to excite themselves and the public into a fever of apprehension on this subject. This mood, however, will soon pass away.

abstract: on Southern prospects, >amp;c.
snippet: on Southern prospects, >amp;c.
lead_paragraph: Gov. PARSONS, of Alabama, has spent several days in this city and in Boston, seeking to ascertain the tone of public sentiment toward the South, and to interest capitalists and others in the development of Southern wealth and prosperity. He urges especially upon Northern men who have movable capital which they seek to invest, the wisdom of going South and joining the owners of large plantations in making them available. There are many men at the South who have large farms, but are utterly unable to work them, for lack of capital. In many respects it is not desirable, for them or for the country, to sell these farms outright to Northern immigrants, as the latter would thus lose the skill and experience essential to their profitable cultivation; but if the Northern capitalist and the Southern landowner would go into partnership, the best material results would be attained, and a harmony of sentiment and opinion would grow up, which would be highly serviceable to the State and the nation at large.

abstract: two or three firms in the Third Ward have, within a few days past, paid considerable sums of money to men professing to be connected with this paper, upon promise of having certain notices or other valuable favors in our columns. It ought not to be necessary to say that all such persons are swindlers; and we ought not to be compelled to form an opinion of the intelligence and morality of men who deliberately pay such bribes, with an idea that they can use this paper by so doing. Let it be understood, once for all, that while our business columns are open to all respectable patrons in the usual way of advertising, any one who promises to use the paper out of the regular course of business is a knave. And we may add that the publishers of the TIMES will be thankful to any one who will give at this office such information as will lead to the detection of these rascals. The near approach of Winter has prompted the order of chevaliers d'industrie to active service to provide for cold weather, and the newspapers will, as usual, be their first victims.

abstract: House-building in New-York
snippet: House-building in New-York
lead_paragraph: shown that it was no good reason against capitalists building the houses and residences of which this city is so greatly in want, that the prices of material and labor are high at present. Building houses, even at present rates, to be rented out to tenants, would yield large returns; and would continue to do so, even though the country were able to return next month to a specie basis, and the prices of rents were to fall one-half. Yet the Tribune again declares and argues that the present "currency inflation makes building unadvisable" and unprofitable, and speaks of house-building only being resumed when the currency is at par. Such arguments as this are wide of the mark, as house-owners and house-renters well know, and as not a few capitalists are beginning to realize. If builders should stop their operations and wait for the currency to reach par, the poor would in a few months be packed even worse than they are now, and the exactions upon tenants would become even more intolerable. House building in New-York, at present, is assuredly as profitable an investment of capital as can be devised.

abstract: New-Jersey; Collision at Jersey City
snippet: New-Jersey; Collision at Jersey City
lead_paragraph: SERIOUS RIOT AT PATERSON -- ABOUT A DOZEN WOUNDED PERSONS CARRIED OFF THE GROUND. -- Between 9 and 10 o'clock on Wednesday night a riot occurred at the New-York and Erie Railway Depot at Paterson, between some thirty roughs on one side and some railroad hands and soldiers on the other, which resulted in serious injury to a dozen or more persons. It appears that for some time past a party of Paterson roughs have been in the habit of riding on the 8:30 emigrant train from Jersey City, and when the conductor came around to collect the fare, would refuse to pay it, and use abusive and insulting language. Conductor DAVID DOREMUS, together with the men employed on the emigrant train, have on a number of occasions ejected these men, and for so doing gained their enmity, which finally culminated in a serious riot. As the train arrived at Paterson, on Wednesday night; upon which there was a regiment of soldiers. Conductor DOREMUS stepped out upon the platform, when a man, backed by about thirty of these rowdies, stepped up and arrested him. Conductor DOREMUS demanded his authority, which, as is alleged, was refused, when the man, who, it was subseqently learned, was a constable, was knocked down by some person. A general melee then commenced between the rowdies and the hands belonging to the train, in which the soldiers, who were on their way to Dunkirk, joined in against the rowdies. Bayonets, knives, pistols, stones, clubs and other weapons, were freely used, and the battle raged fiercely for about ten minutes, when the rowdies were worsted and driven away, carrying with them about a dozen injured men. One man was stabbed in the temple with a bayonet, and another had a railroad lantern broken to pieces over his head, and was badly cut with pieces of glass. None of the railroad men were badly injured. Further trouble is anticipated.

All applicants for admission to the bar, are requested to take notice. The examination will commence at 3 o'clock on the above-named day, and will be held in the General Term Room, in the new Court-house. The names of the examiners, and also the names of the Committee on Character, were published in the TIMES of Thursday. The following gentlemen, connected with the bar of other States, were yesterday, on motion, duly admitted to practice in all the courts of this State: JAMES CLARK, of Ohio; WM.D. HENNEN, from Louisiana; also, LEWIS O. CORBIT, from the Law School of Columbia College.

abstract: the Price of Democratic Voters in
snippet: the Price of Democratic Voters in
lead_paragraph: organs vociferously insist that the States of New-York and New-Jersey were carried against them by the free use of money. In Syracuse they say, the Republicans "paid as high as twenty-five dollars for a single vote." While we are sure that these stories are exaggerations, we cannot help suggesting to our friends of the other side that such a public confession of the mercenary character of their voters is not calculated to elevate the party in the estimation of honest men. After the lofty flourishes preceding election about integrity, patriotism, the spurning of bribes, and all manner of heroic virtues, the direct charge that thousands of their rank and file were bought up at twenty-five dollars per head, like cattle in the shambles, is, to say the least, undignified. Some satirical Timon once said that "every man has his price." We have the authority of the Argus that the price of Syracuse Democratic voters is twenty-five dollars a piece, in greenbacks.

abstract: Magazines for November
snippet: Magazines for November
lead_paragraph: -- Harper's New Monthly Magazine, (New-York: HARPER & BROTHERS;) opens with a well written and exceedingly well illustrated account of an "Ascent of Popocatepetl," the volcano whose snowy cone towers over the plane of Mexico -- the king of the Mexican Andes, and the loftiest point of the North American Continent, by WILLIAM W. WELLS. The other noticeable papers are, "The Great Westminster Canvass," a graphic and spirited account of the humors of an English Metropolitan election, by M.D. CONWAY, who witnessed the late return of JOHN STUART MILL to Parliament. "Pozzuoli and Vesuvius," pages from a diary of Italian travel. "Recollections of Gen. ROUSSEAU," with a fine portrait, and the usual variety of short stories, besides the monthly installment of the stock novels "Armadale" and "Our Mutual Friend." One more number will complete DICKENS' last work. Like all his late books it leaves a mixed impression on the readers' admiration, for many of the scenes and characters being combined with distaste for the awkward and ill managed plot, whose incongruities and inconsistencies show an entire want of construction in a writer who professes so fine an eye for individual eccentricities and personal traits.

abstract: obliged to the Richmond Bulletin for a late compliment to the North. It says that "it is not merely in 'wooden nutmegs,' brooms, clocks, stoves and a thousand other 'notions,' that this dependence [of the South upon the North] has existed, but also in matters of a higher kind, such as the publication of books and periodicals. Much noxious trash, indeed, issues from the Northern press; yet nothing but prejudice can deny that much valuable literature comes from the same source." We did not know that even prejudice denied this interesting fact; we fancied it was only ignorance and that of the incorrigible kind. We believe that so far as the country has a literature at all, it originates almost exclusively from New-York, Boston and Philadelphia. We shall be glad to see authors, publishers and books abound in Richmond, Charleston and New-Orleans; but we fear they will be dependent for some time yet upon the North. Literature is a plant of slow growth. The manufacture of "notions" and nutmegs may be quickly learned.

abstract: A fire occurred at about 1 o'clock yesterday morning in the commission provision warehouse of F.P. WOODBURY, No. 14 Water-street. The three upper floors were destroyed. They were stored with flour, tallow, lard, and seeds. The loss was $7,000, which is covered by insurance in the Market Insurance Company. It is supposed that the fire was caused by a stove in the second story. ISAAC STICKNEY & CO., commission produce dealers, occupied the first floor. Their loss was $500, on which there was no insurance. The building, which is owned by the Whitney estate, was damaged to the extent of $8,000. It is fully insured.

lead_paragraph: NEW TEMPERANCE MOVEMENT. -- A new benevolent organization has lately been formed, called the "National Temperance Society and Publishing House." Mr. WM.E. DODGE, of this city, has been chosen President, and among the Vice-Presidents are Gen. Howard, Gen. Carey, Gen. Dow, Gov. Buckingham, President Asa D. Smith, Bishop James, Henry Ward Beecher. Wm.A Booth is the Treasurer. Its pecuniary resources will consist of the following: Annual members to contribute one dollar each; life members twenty dollars; life directors one hundred dollars; and life patrons five hundred dollars. Collections will also be solicited in the various churches. The money will be used in publishing books and tracts and engaging able advocates of the temperance cause. In the Board of Officers all the great temperance organizations in America are represented. The society will have a central publishing house, which they will endeavor to make the rallying point for all friends of total abstinence.

lead_paragraph: THE FORT HAMILTON HOMICIDE. -- Coroner LYNCH commenced an investigation on the 8th inst., and continued it yesterday, into the circumstances attending the death of a boy named HEENRY UNDERWOOD, who was killed by a blow with a club in the hands of JAMES LAKE, a shoemaker, residing at Fort Hamilton, on Wednesday, the 1st inst. The deceased belonged to the drum corps attached to the garrison of the fort. The corps owned a dog, which annoyed the neighbors by chasing their fowls. LAKE shot the animal, and the drummers, on learning the fact, became greatly excited. A deputation called upon LAKE and demanded pay for the loss of the dog, which was refused. They then threatened to lick him, when LAKE seized a club and struck deceased a tremendous blow on the head, fracturing the skull and causing death shortly thereafter. The investigation will be concluded this evening.
