abstract: Legislature, Political Complexion of
snippet: Legislature, Political Complexion of
lead_paragraph: Our Democratic opponents do not seem to have made much by their determined effort to get possession of the State Legislature, in either branch. Although returns are not precisely settled, we may calculate that of the thirty-two Senators not more than four or five are of the Democratic faith. Last year (including Mr. NIVEN, of the Sullivan district, subsequently ousted by Judge Low,) the Democracy mustered eleven members. They have lost more than half of their powerless minority. Mr. MURPHY, of Brooklyn, Messrs. BENJ. WOOD and CHAS. G. CORNELL, of New-York, and Mr. SUTHERLAND, of Westchester, comprise all of that party certainly elected. Two of their most eminent and characteristic representatives from this city remain at home -- LUKE F. COZANS and THOMAS C. FIELDS -- the latter giving place to a good Union man -- THOMAS MURPHY -- and the former having been set aside by Street Commissioner CORNELL, whose patriotic anxiety to serve the public is only limited by the number of offices in the gift of the people. Mr. SUTHERLAND, of Westchester, takes the place of SAXTON SMITH, of Putnam, and will probably be a more active member; indeed, he may be the minority leader, since it is an even chance that Senator HENRY C. MURPHY will incline strongly to silence, if not to the Union side. It will puzzle Lieut.-Gov. ALVORD to distribute these four remnants of the late Democracy so as to give each committee a proper party representation.

abstract: Finances of the Week
snippet: Finances of the Week
lead_paragraph: The income of the government from internal revenue this week has averaged one million one hundred and forty thousand dollars a day, or equal to a weekly aggregate of nearly seven million dollars a week. The total receipts of the National Treasury from this source, thus far in the current fiscal year, commencing with July 1, have amounted to the enormous sum of one hundred and thirty-eight million dollars, or equal to a weekly average of about seven million two hundred and sixty-three thousand dollars, which average, carried through the whole of the current fiscal year, would yield an income of nearly three hundred and seventy-eight million dollars.

abstract: This problem has been accomplished at last. Dr. COLTON has devised a plan of extracting teeth by the pleasant operation of putting the patient so soundly to sleep that his decayed teeth are taken out without his knowledge, and he wakes up in the course of a few minutes or seconds, according to the length of the operation and the dose of gas required, feeling as bright and sound as ever, and freed from his troublesome molars, grinders, or incisors. This is performed by simply administering nitrous oxide, or "laughing gas," as it is commonly called.

abstract: A meeting in the interest of Italian Protestantism will be held in Plymouth Church on Sunday afternoon. Philanthropists and Christians may find interest in the objects of this meeting, viz.: 1. A full relation of the four last years' extraordinary Protestant Evangelical movement in Italy will be given by Rev. Prof. A. TACCHELLA, of Milan. 2. A means of evangelizing twenty-five millions of Italians will also be explained. 3. Rev. Prof. HITCHCOCK will introduce the matter of a popular petition to be presented to the King of Italy, in order to obtain, as a gift, for the 4,000 newly-converted Protestants residing in Milan, and who have no place of worship, a large central church.

abstract: British gunboat Bulldog Blown up off Cape Haytien
snippet: British gunboat Bulldog Blown up off Cape Haytien
lead_paragraph: Capt. POTTER, of the brig Henry and Louise, from Port-au-Prince, arrived to-day, reports: News had reached that city that the war-ship Bull Dog, of 12 guns, was blown up by her Commander on the 25th at Cape Hayti. It appears the British Consul had some Haytiens under his protection, and SALNANE, the rebel, made a demand for them, which the Consul refused, and he broke in the doors and took the Haytiens out and shot them. The British ship Bull Dog was lying in port, and her Commander asking for satisfaction and receiving no answer, commenced to fire on Fort Peckelet, which the fort returned. By some mismanagement of the Commander he got his ship on a reef, and after getting his men into the boats he set fire to the ship and she blew up. It was reported that the Commander got on board one of President JEFFRARD's boats and left for Jamaica.

abstract: "the whole question of finance" appeared editorially yesterday in a local morning journal. In the course of the lucid disquisition, the writer contradicted himself rather pointedly. In one paragraph, he sagely affirmed that "it is a mistake to suppose that the national bank notes are national promises to pay;" and in the very next paragraph he as dogmatically asserted that the circulation of the national banks "is actually nothing more than the Federal bonds divided and subdivided into convenient sums for the ordinary operations of traffic." While urging this latter point so emphatically, the writer was evidently oblivious of the fact so familiar to all subscribers to the government loans, that "Federal bonds are actually nothing more than national promises to pay." In so elaborate and profound a treatise on financial science, however, self-stultification was probably unavoidable.

abstract: cratic placard in front of Tammany Hall flaps mournfully in the Autumn wind, and the names of their late candidates glare monumentally from the marble-colored canvas. When a gallant and honorable enemy has suffered the sad reverse of war he gracefully strikes his flag and files to the rear. But a piratical crew, having no reasonable expectation of mercy in case of defeat, abandon their craft with the sails set and the colors flying. Tammany's paramount idol, Old Hickory, once said: "Those who trade on borrowed capital ought to break." The Democracy borrowed (or stole) Republican capital for a platform and Republican capitalists for candidates. They have signally failed; and now it seems that none are left who have sufficient regard for the proprieties of society to hide away the emblems of their shame and defeat.

abstract: and the Missouri Convention Oath
snippet: and the Missouri Convention Oath
lead_paragraph: lican has a long story to the effect that when Major-Gen. F.P. BLAIR came the other day to vote in St. Louis, he repudiated the oath proscribed by the State Convention, and offered to the judges an oath of his own manufacture. Of course the judges were compelled to refuse it; and on that refusal we have whole Niagaras of indignation in the aforesaid paper. Passing by the legal merits of the case, in the abstract, we may be permitted to say that ostentatious defiance of law, in any case not justified by military necessity, by a high officer of the army, is not an example that should commend itself to good citizens. The cheap resource of voting under protest, might, in this instance, have soothed a tender conscience; or, if that sacrifice for the country was too great, it is possible that even entire absence from the polls might have been endured by the people without disarranging the internal or external economy of the Commonwealth. During our dreadful war the State of Missouri was the theatre of some of the most atrocious crimes, and generally of the most reckless lawlessness, that ever blackened a nation's history. That the reaction should be severe, and that it should seem unreasonable to some extent is quite possible; but has not the great suffering of the past furnished ample reason that every loyal citizen should heartily join in the good work of restoration, even at the temporary sacrifice of some peculiar crotchets in regard to oaths and forms of loyalty?

abstract: Mr. SCHADE again called on the President this morning, to make a final effort to save Capt. WIRZ from the death penalty, but at that time, unknown to him, the prisoner had been hanged. abstract: Serenaded at his residence, New-York, and Speech
snippet: Serenaded at his residence, New-York, and Speech
lead_paragraph: One of the most pleasant of the many compliments now paid to the veteran journalist and statesman, was tendered Mr. THURLOW WEED, at his residence in West Ninth-street, last evening. A few of his friends deeming the successful close of an arduous campaign a fit time to indicate their regard, express their gratitude and manifest their esteem, called at the place above mentioned, about 10 o'clock last night, accompanied by the superb band of the gallant Seventh Regiment, numbering in all some forty pieces. The first intimation granted Mr. WEED of the intended compliment was delicately conveyed in the graceful melody of choice selections from "Martha." Standing in front of the house the band played for something like an hour a carefully selected programme of the choicest and most popular operatic selections, after which the crowd clamorously called for Mr. WEED.

abstract: The Execution of
snippet: The Execution of
lead_paragraph: alty of the law was yesterday visited upon this man. There was much excitement around the place of execution, but the most perfect order was maintained, and in the short space of an hour the last demands of earthly justice were satisfied. We note, as an indication of public sentiment, that a large crowd of people gathered outside of the prison, out of sight but within hearing of the solemn work, when the drop fell and WIRZ was sent to his final account, gave loud and repeated cheers. WIRZ persisted to the last that he was innocent of most of the charges proved against him, and intimated, as indeed he has all along insisted, that Gen. WINDER was the immediately responsible party. There is a curious story to-day made public, that WIRZ's wife a few days ago conveyed poison to him, and in spite of detective watchfulness, actually put in his mouth, while apparently kissing him, a bolus of strychnine; but the prompt interference of an officer prevented him from swallowing it. The public will feel sensibly relieved that this terrible affair is ended, and that the long strain of excitement over the awful disclosures of the trial is among the events that all good men will hasten to forget.

abstract: And Northern Characteristics
snippet: And Northern Characteristics
lead_paragraph: -- A Southern paper protests against all attempts to "de-Southernize the South, to bleach out its tone and color, to emasculate its mind and character, leaving it neither one thing nor the other." We should oppose any such attempts as strongly as our Southern cotemporary. There are many distinctive phases of life and character in the South which are admirable. The climate of many of the States has induced habits of less activity than prevail in our Northern regions, and from this have arisen marked personal characteristics, which it is beyond our power to change. The easier conditions of life in the South have originated and developed traits in the Southern man which are less prominent in the Northern man; and these we would not change. The chief pursuit, in planting, of the dominant class of the Southern people, has made prominent differences between them and the commercial class, which is the most powerful in the North; and the Southern features we would not have changed. The thinking people of the South have given more attention to politics, and the thoughtful people in the North have given more attention to literature; and from this circumstance has sprung intellectual varieties, both of which have their value, and neither of which we would alter. In short, whatever there is distinctive in Southern modes of life and phases of character that has an inherent value, or is adapted to their distinctive pursuits, proclivities or conditions of existence, we would retain, and protest against attempts to change. We do not desire that the Southern people should be "de-Southernized," or that they should assimilate in characteristics or costume to the people of the New-England States, or the Western States, or even of this admirable city.

snippet: Johnson, William, brother of the President
lead_paragraph: War has broken out between Spain and Chili, in consequence of demands made by the former power, to which Chili could not honorably accede. The Admiral in command of the Spanish fleet in South American waters has proclaimed the blockade of the Chilian ports, giving neutral vessels ten days to clear in. Chili takes up the gauntlet with great spirit. The people subscribe liberally for the support of the government. Letters-of-marque have been issued by the Chilian authorities, and there is every prospect of a very lively time in that part of the world.

abstract: Names of New Cities
snippet: Names of New Cities
lead_paragraph: establishment of another town in the West under the name of Washington. The Father of his Country is now sufficiently commemorated in every State of the Union in this way; We may make the same remark of the Fathers of the Country, as FRANKLIN, JEFFERSON, ADAMS and HAMILTON. In every State we are again and again reminded of their existence by the names of towns and counties. We suggest that a new series of names can now be found by the founders of cities -- the names of the great heroes and statesmen who have lately made themselves immortal as saviors of the republic -- such names as LINCOLN, GRANT, FARRAGUT and SEWARD, SHERMAN, STANTON and ROSECRANS, and hundreds beside. Thousands of cities are yet to be laid out between the Alleghanies and the Rocky Mountains, and beyond the Rocky Mountains; between the Potomac and the Rio Grande, and perchance beyond the Rio Grande; and the hint we now throw out may relieve those who will lay them out from much painful thought.

lead_paragraph: The habeas corpus case of Packer vs. Packer, before reported, was up again yesterday in the Supreme Court, Chambers, before Justice CLERKE. The writ was obtained by the wife, for the purpose of securing the custody of two children who are now under the father's care, and are kept a short distance out of the city. After considerable argument, the matter, upon the suggestion of the court, and by consent of counsel, was arranged so that the wife and mother should have the company of her children for forty-eight hours each mouth, until the further order of the court; and for this purpose the father is to bring them to the city. There are two suits pending -- one brought by the wife against the husband, and the other by the husband against the wife -- both of them to obtain a decree of divorce on the ground of adultery.

abstract: Elected Governor of N. C.; Constitutional Amendment; Official Vote on
snippet: Elected Governor of N. C.; Constitutional Amendment; Official Vote on
lead_paragraph: The Troy Times says: "Talk about war and cholera as depopulators -- neither of them are half so destructive of Democratic life as the mountebank VAN BUREN. When it was announced that he would take the stump for the Democratic ticket, the fate of that ticket was regarded as sealed. It was felt that what he supported must fail. He spoke, and spoke often, and whenever he opened his mouth hundreds and thousands of Democrats vanished in thin air. In Troy, hundreds of Democrats who were are not. In Syracuse, Buffalo, Albany and elsewhere, his presence was as destructive as a raging pestilence. You can trace his trail over the State by the Demcoratic chasms in towns and counties. It is very evident that if the Democrats do not contrive some way to keep JOHN's bead under water, there will not be enough of them left by the next election to make a decent fight."

abstract: whose parents reside in West Haven, was yesterday arrested in that village by Officer TARBOX and Detective MARSH, of this city, on suspicion of his having been connected with the cowardly attempt to destroy life and property by throwing the night express train on the New-York and New-Haven Railroad from the track, on the night of Sept. 19 last. The lad THOMPSON is a cousin of the ruffian MILLER, recently sent to the State Prison for an attempt to aid the horse-thief WELLS in breaking out of jail; and it appears from the boy's confession, made after his arrest, that MILLER was at the bottom of this other and worse piece of rascality. It appears that the two were in company on the night in question, in the western part of the village mentioned, and started for home about 10 o'clock, taking the track. At fifty rods this side of the West Haven depot there is a curve in the road, with a ledge of rocks on one side and a steep embankment on the other; and down this embankment MILLER proposed to his cousin to throw the train, by placing a rail across the outside track nearest to the south side of the road. They were then to rob the dead and disabled passengers.

abstract: BRIG.-GEN. WRIGHT. -- Col. DRUM yesterday received intelligence of the recovery of the remains of the late General WRIGHT at Bay Flat, near Shelter Cove, Mendocino County, 150 miles from the scene of the Brother Jonathan disaster. The remains were badly decomposed, but have been fully identified from clothing and otherwise. The remains of Mrs. WRIGHT, which were recovered soon after the disaster, are now at GRAY's, on Sacramento-street, awaiting the arrival of those of her gallant husband by the Del Norte last night. The body of Major EDDY also came down on the Del Norte. -- San Francisco Alta., Oct. 11.

abstract: A PLEASANT PARTY.--On Wednesday evening the members of the Tunisian Embasey were entertained by Mr. GEORGE W. CHILDS, proprietor of the Philadelphia Ledger, at his residence in Locust-street, Philadelphia.
lead_paragraph: A PLEASANT PARTY. -- On Wednesday evening the members of the Tunisian Embasey were entertained by Mr. GEORGE W. CHILDS, proprietor of the Philadelphia Ledger, at his residence in Locust-street, Philadelphia. Among the other guests were Gens. MEADE and PATTERSON, COM. HULL, Chaplain BILLINGER,Capt. FAIRFAX, of the Navy, the Mayor elect, MORTON MCMICHAEL, editor of the North American, Col. FORNEY, of the Press, Messrs. PEACOCK & WELLS, of the Evening Bulletin, L.A. GODET, G.H. BOKER, HENRY C. CAREY, S. HORSTMAN, _____ WELCH, W.B. LEWIS, ALFRED S. JESSUP and GEORGE JONES, of New-York. During the evening the guests were entertained with some charming music, executed by the fair hostess. and the conviviality was maintained until a late hour, after which a number of the guests made a call at the mansion of Mr. HORSTMAN, where time flew so fast that they were overtaken by the small hours. The Mayor elect, Mr. MCMICHAEL, was appealed to to read the riot act and disperse the assemblage, but declined on the ground that he had not yet entered on the duties of his office. The guests finally bid their host adieu, and wended their way homeward with the impression that a more delightful evening had seldom been passed by any of them.

abstract: Meek, Judge, of New-Orleans
snippet: Meek, Judge, of New-Orleans
lead_paragraph: Judge MEEK, whose death at New-Orleans has just been announced, was a South Carolinian by birth, born at Beaufort in 1814, but removed to Alabama five years after with his father's family. He was graduated in the University of the State, admitted to the Bar in 1835, and soon became the editor of a Democratic journal. He served in the Seminole war in 1836, and was appointed Attorney-General of Alabama. He left that office to edit the Southron, and in 1842 was made Judge of Tuscaloosa County Court, publishing a useful Digest of State laws during his term of office. He held the post of law clerk in the office of the Solicitor of the Treasury at Washington in 1845, and for four years from 1846 was United States District-Attorney for Southern Alabama, residing at Mobile. For the next five years he was one of the editors of the Mobile Register, and went to the Legislature in 1853. He has the credit of originating and carrying into effect a free school system, in the State. Next he was a Judge of Probate, and in 1855 published his poem, "The Bed Eagle, a Poem of the South " -- a work showing some ability, but too romantic and poorly arranged, as well as too deficient in original power, to hold on abiding place. He was a Democratic Presidential elector in 1856, and in the next three years published a volume of miscellanies, entitled "Romantic Passages in Southwestern History," besides "Songs and Poems of the South." He was reelected to the Legislature in 1859, and chosen Speaker. He also wrote a history of Alabama.

abstract: Valentine's Corporation Manual; Valentine's N. Y. Corporaton Manual

lead_paragraph: The corporation manual of this city for the present year, compiled by the Clerk of the Common Council, Mr. DAVID T. VALENTINE, has just been issued. Beside the usual valuable information in regard to all the departments of the City and County Government, it contains an abundance of antiquarian lore, selected with great judgment, and of real interest to every inhabitant of the metropolis. The book is embellished with numerous colored lithographs of interesting localities in and near the city, among which are the Audobun estate, the old bastion near St. Vincent's Convent, the old Dutch farmhouse in Seventh-avenue, near Fiftieth-street; the Croton cottage in Fortieth-street, and the Keyser estate, corner of Fourth-avenue and Fortieth-street. Portraits of RIP VAN DAM, senior member of the King's Council, and Provisional Governor of this city in 1831-2, and his wife SARAH, will also be found in this volume.

abstract: Planters and Revival of Industry
snippet: Planters and Revival of Industry
lead_paragraph: We are almost daily hearing of some prominent Southern planter who but lately was a large slaveholder and landowner, and who felt for a time as if finally crushed in the great revolutionary catastrophe which closed the war, taking hold again upon the activities of life, and determining to see what can be accomplished by effort and energy under the new order of things. He sees the fertile soil still before him; he sees the laborers still in existence around him; he knows the eager demand for that which is the staple product of the soil; and he foresees a prosperous future if he can but bring into proper relations the conditions of profitable production. He has, in its sphere, the assistance of a beneficent government; he enjoys the benefits of public order and the protection of law; and there are no restraints upon the exercise of his legitimate freedom. There is but one difficulty which appears to him formidable, and that is the securing, under fit conditions, of the labor of those who formerly did his will as slaves, but who are now entitled to exercise their own will as freemen. Formerly he could enforce labor; now he has to negotiate with it. Formerly there was but one side to all questions on the plantation; now there are two sides to every question. Can the new relations and the varied interests be so harmonized as to work out profitable and effective results?

lead_paragraph: There is some uneasiness in Richmond about alleged preparations for an insurrection making by the 25,000 or 30,000 negroes huddled in tents on the York River Peninsula, between the towns of Hampton and Williamsburgh. These negroes have been notified that on Jan. 1 the lands they now occupy will be turned over to their former owners, and if the reports are true, the dissatisfaction caused by a knowledge of this fact has been increased by the presence among them of free negroes from the North, who incite also a spirit of insurrection and revenge. The proposed plan is said to be to cross York River and sweep through the counties of Gloucester, King and Queen, and those adjacent, increasing their ranks as they move onward by the volunteer or forced addition of such negroes as may be laboring or idling in the section of the country through which they pass.

abstract: Confederate Colony in
snippet: Confederate Colony in
lead_paragraph: learn from a gentleman who lived formely in Lexington, in this State, something of the prospects of the Confederate colony which is being established in Mexico. The one to which he belongs, and to which he will return, as soon as he can dispose of certain property in this State, lies near Cordova, a town on the road between Vera Cruz and the City of Mexico, and about a hundred miles from the former place. It consists of about a dozen large haciendas of apparently good land, capable of producing cotton, coffee, cocoa and tobacco. The land will be given to the settlers by the Emperor's government, in parcels of six hundred and forty acres to families, and in smaller allotments to single men. STERLING PRICE, Gen. JO. SHELBY, Ex.-Gov. HARRIS, of Tennessee, and Judge PERKINS, of Louisiana, were there at the time of his departure, with other proposed settlers of less note. Lieut. MAURY, formerly of the Naval Observatory at Washington, was also there, and actively engaged in furthering the scheme, by drawing up a report to be circulated in the Southern States, with a view of inducing parties of colonists to come over and join them. The work of tilling the soil had not been fairly commenced, and would be postponed until there was a suitable accession to their numbers. This they expected to obtain in reasonable time through the medium of MAURY's report, and the influence of the newspaper which ex-Governor ALLEN, of Louisiana, has commenced publishing in the city of Mexico. MAXIMILIAN, our informant thinks, is secure enough on his throne, provided the Monroe doctrine be not broadly asserted by the United States. The armed resistance of the Liberals will soon be overcome, and the opposition to him be confined to the Church party alone. This opposition, however, is not apt to take the form of a revolution, inasmuch as the Liberal party first confiscated the Church property, and MAXIMILIAN's offence consists only in refusing to restore it. -- St. Louis Republican.

abstract: Capt. Sidney Smith Lee, of the late rebel navy, is cultivating a farm in Maryland. Hon. Gustavus A. Henry, called the "Eagle Orator," and now the "Eagle Bird" of Tennessee, and formerly of the Confederate Senate, is practising law at Dover, the scene of the battle of Fort Donelson.
lead_paragraph: Capt. Sidney Smith Lee, of the late rebel navy, is cultivating a farm in Maryland. Hon. Gustavus A. Henry, called the "Eagle Orator," and now the "Eagle Bird" of Tennessee, and formerly of the Confederate Senate, is practising law at Dover, the scene of the battle of Fort Donelson. Gen. C.C. Dibbrell, who commanded the escort of Mr. Davis, is in Nashville. Gen. Luciuo Polk, a nephew of the late Bishop-General, and a resident of Arkansas, is also in Nashville. Capt. Raphael Semmes, of the Alabama, is practising law in Alabama, his son, S.S. Semmes, late Paymaster in the Army of the Tennessee, being his partner. Gen. J.T. Hotzelaw has declined to be a candidate for the Alabama Legislature, and practices law in Montgomery. The Alabama Generals are all peacefully engaged. H.D. Clayton is at home farming in Barbour County; Alf. Baker is practising law in the same region; Cullen A. Battle has opened a law office at Tuskegee; John T. Morgan has done the same at Selma; Peter Roddy has settled in. Lauderdale; S.A.M. Wood in Florence, at the law, and Jonas M. Withers and Zacharias C. Deas are in Mobile.

abstract: Exposition, Universal in 1867; Exposition; Plan of American Participation
snippet: Exposition, Universal in 1867; Exposition; Plan of American Participation
lead_paragraph: It was some time ago made known from the Department of State, that Mr. J.C. DERBY, United States Dispatch Agent in this city, had been appointed the agent of our government, for the Universal Exposition which is to be held in Paris in 1867; and by a notice, generally published, all persons interested in the exhibition were directed to apply to him for information and advice. We learn from Mr. DERBY that our countrymen have entered fully into the spirit of an enterprise which is the greatest of its kind ever projected, and that he has already received innumerable applications from inventors, artists, artisans, and others interested in the industrial and esthetic arts, for knowledge as to the means of procuring the admission of their works. Indeed, there has been so great reason to believe that the space allotted to the United States, by the Commissioners of the Exhibition, would be, although vast, insufficient to represent all our interests seeking admission to it, that the government has decided to apply for a grant of ampler room. It is hoped that the space of 3,346 square metres originally given us will be again assigned, instead of the surface of 2,788 metres afterwards reserved to us; and we need scarcely incite those more particularly interested among our citizens to take advantage of this expectation. The whole nation is concerned in the display of our industrial greatness in such a place.

abstract: Madagascar, Dispute with; Paris Letter, Oct. 27
snippet: Madagascar, Dispute with; Paris Letter, Oct. 27
lead_paragraph: The ssmewhat obscure quarrel between France and Madagascar is explained by the Paris correspondent of the London Times. It appears that some two or three years ago certain privileges and concessions were granted to a Frenchman named LAMBERT by the King of that island, on condition that he should found a company for the "regeneration of the country." The company was got up, funds were collected, and on the faith of the promises, first of the King, and afterwards of the French Government, a large sum was expended. An insurrection broke out in the island, however; the King was murdered, and a new race reigned in his stead. These last refused to carry out the terms of the treaty, whereupon the French Government demanded the repayment of the sums advanced by the company. Alter a time compliance was promised with this demand, but an insurrection having broken out at Tananarivo the payment was delayed for a fortnight. A French journal, commenting upon this affair, deprecates the idea of a war with the natives of Madagascar, but urges that there is a necessity for such a display of strength as may preclude all ideas of resistance on their part.

lead_paragraph: A show-case, containing seven hundred dollars' worth of jewelry, was stolen from in front of the store of THOMAS B. BYNNER, NO. 189 Broadway, on Friday evening. Officer DWYER, of the Third Precinct, subsequently found the property in the possession of JAMES MCKENNA and CHARLES HENRY, who were drawing the show-case through Greenwich-street in a hand-cart. The men said that the goods belonged to them, but the officer arrested them on suspicion. The owner soon appeared at the station-house and identified the property. On Saturday Justice DOWLING committed the prisoners to the Tombs for trial.

abstract: London Letter, Oct. 28
snippet: London Letter, Oct. 28
lead_paragraph: Europe is a little agitated this week about a ifference of opinion between His Holiness the Pope, and the Arab Emir, ABD-EL-KADER. It is on a question long since settled in America, but still an exciting one in Europe. The Pope it seems, is an Anti-Mason. He took occasion the other day to renew some papal condemnations of masonry in connection with other secret societies, while ABD-EL-KADER is not only a Mahommedan, but an enthusiastic freemason. In a lodge in France he said: "I consider freemasonry as the first institution in the world. In my opinion every man, who does not profees freemasonry, is an incomplete man. I hope that one day all the principles of freemasonry will prevail throughout the whole world, and then all the nations will be at peace." Certainly, if nations could be bound over to keep the peace by all joining a lodge of Free and Accepted Masons, I think the Pope might be induced to withdraw his objections, which are much the same as those of the old Anti-Mason party, which, in my younger days, was not at all of this learned Arab's opinion.

abstract: It is a matter of congratulation to this journal that the two most thorough and scientific works on the economics of slavery, appeared first in its columns. We refer to the letters...
lead_paragraph: It is a matter of congratulation to this journal that the two most thorough and scientific works on the economics of slavery, appeared first in its columns. We refer to the letters of Mr. SEWELL on "Emancipation in the West Indies," and of Mr. OLMSTED on the "Cotton and Seaboard States." In the former, it will be remembered that Mr. SEWELL showed conclusively that the so-called "failure of Jamaica emancipation" was merely a diminished production, resulting not from the idleness of the negro, but from the entanglements of the estates, and especially from the prejudices and rancor of the planters against the freed blacks, showing itself especially in efforts to continue a kind of serfdom, and to cheat the negroes of their wages or to under pay them. The result was, that a great gulf was created between capital and labor, which has not, to this day, been fairly bridged over in Jamaica. The freedmen abandoned their old masters' estates in distrust and with hostility, and squatted on unoccupied lands, raising enough for their own wants, but letting the large estates go to ruin, and causing the production of sugar, which depends much on a combination of labor and capital, very largely to fall off.

abstract: The Twenty-second Regiment opened their promenade concert season last evening, at their armory, in Fourteenth-street, near Sixth-avenue. abstract: Emigration from
snippet: Emigration from
lead_paragraph: time a large emigration in progress from the Southern provinces of the Italian Kingdom to Egypt, consisting chiefly of skilled laborers, artisans and mechanics. The movement is not, we are told, like the Irish exodus, the departure of poor, uneducated people, but it is the very bone and sinew of the Italian nation that is emigrating, the exact material that a country rallying into new life needs and demands. The reason assigned for it is the usual reason assigned in all times for all popular migrations -- the desire and expectation of a better condition. The material prospects of Old Egypt are actually at this moment better than those of Young Italy. "The Italians of to-day," writes a correspondent from Italy, "are beset with immeasurable difficulties. They have a hostile clergy, a discontented peasantry, a landed proprietary groaning under heavy taxation, seaports without trade, and capital without movement; brigandage in the south, beggary in the north, a ruined exchequer, and a not very reputable court." And beside all these internal troubles they are in constant peril of war with Austria, and of difficulties with the Pope or the party of action. Egypt on the other hand, under the new stimulus of the greatly enlarged cotton culture, the prospective commercial advantages of the Suez Canal, and the liberal policy of the existing Viceroy, is giving grounds of belief that she will speedily attain a high and permanent prosperity.

abstract: Address to the Public
snippet: Address to the Public
lead_paragraph: The difficulty now existing between the theatrical managers and the musicians seems to be misunderstood by the public at large, who, Judging from the crowded state of those places of amusement, appear to take no interest in it, thus facitly encouraging the managers' combination in their endeavors to withhold a fair remuneration from a large number of their employes. It cannot be denied, we think, that the members of the musical profession, as a class, can justly claim the respect and support of the community at large, for they materially contribute, by their genius and untiring industry, to cater to the entertainment of those who patronize places of public amusement. We are satisfied that if an unvarnished and candid statement of the reasons which induced them to demand a fair remuneration for their services (and that is all they ask) were given to the people, the verdict of the people, which is always the arbiter of justice and humanity, would be unanimouslv opposed to the despotic action of a set of men who have combined in their endeavors to forward their own selfish interests, regardless of the claims of a too generous public. This "close corporation" of rapacious theatrical directors affords another striking illustration of a truth which is familiar to the working class by bitter experience -- viz.: that capital is almost invariably combined against labor. In the light of this truth we believe that we are not asking too much of laboring men of every class to stand by the musicians and support them in their just demands for a fair remuneration for their services.

abstract: Algonquin Controversy; the American Artisan on
snippet: Algonquin Controversy; the American Artisan on
lead_paragraph: We reported last week that the Algonquin was evidently ahead of the Winooski, and for a period of three hours had developed 19 per cent, more power, burning an equal amount of fuel. She continued to gain during fifty-six of the ninety-six hours of the trial. It is alleged by the friends of the Winooski that she then began to lose. On the other side it is alleged that for some hours the Winooski had throttled with her stop-valves, thereby evading the agreement to work with her throttles wide open. In reply to this it is alleged that it is frivolous -- a mere excuse for backing out of the contest; and that the reason for backing out was, that the boilers of the Algonquin were leaking, and other matters were out of order, and she could not have kept at work four hours longer. It is also alleged by Mr. DICKERSON that one of the Winooski's wheels, which had the outer ends of its paddles knocked off by collision with a coal barge, was relieved of much of its resistance; and that when the barge got foul of the Winooski her wheels ought to have been stopped; and the reason they were not stopped was, that the Algonquin had proved herself the superior, and the Winooski managers wished to gain an advantage by knocking off the paddles. To this the Captain of the Winooski replies (to the Tribune's reporter) that had the wheel been stopped it would have been much more damaged.

abstract: State Legislature, political division of
snippet: State Legislature, political division of
lead_paragraph: We must be excused for again urging the World, the Albany Argus and other Democratic organs, to the necessity of a prompt and vigorous support of President JOHNSON'S "policy of reconstruction." Their zeal and enthusiasm on its behalf during the recent canvass, must be our apology. They then proclaimed themselves its only supporters, or at least the only ones on whom the President could rely; and they especially warned him against supposing for a moment that he could put any faith in Republican professions on that point. Since the election we have not observed quite as much interest on their part in the President's political welfare. They seem less solicitous about his "policy." We are loath to believe that this arises from any loss of confidence, or any change of views. They probably have been so busy in studying the election returns, that they have lost sight for the moment, of matters which seemed to absorb their whole attention down to the first Tuesday of the present month. They will thank, rather than blame us, therefore, for recalling them to their notice.

lead_paragraph: INQUEST -- THE CITY AUTHORITIES CENSURED. -- Coroner AVERY, of Hoboken, concluded an inquest yesterday on the body of OWEN GARLAND who was found drowned on Friday morning in the creek over which a new bridge is being constructed at the head of Prospect-street, in the limits of Jersey City. It appears that deceased was in the employ of the Erie Railroad Company, and on his way home to Hoboken on Thursday evening, fell into the creek in consequence of the bridge -- which is but partially completed -- being left in an unsafe condition. The bridge is being constructed by day's work by the authorities of Jersey City. The jury in their verdict censured the authorities for neglecting to cause proper precaution to be taken to guard against accidents during the nights. Deceased was 32 years of age, and leaves a wife in poor health and destitute circumstances, and one child.

abstract: The Tunisian Ambassadors and suite, with Consul PERRY, arrived here this morning by steamer from New-York, and took rooms at the City Hotel. During the day they received courteous attentions from Mayor DOYLE and President JONES of the Board of Aldermen. This afternoon they rode about the city, stopping at the Reform School to witness the Sabbath exercises of the inmates. To-morrow they will visit the University, the Atheneum, and several of the large manufacturing establishments, and be entertained in the evening at the Mayor's residence. It is expected that they will remain in this vicinity until Friday.

abstract: Examiner foresees the greatest danger to the Mexican Empire in the American emigration to Mexico, which MAXIMILLIAN is at this time encouraging. These American adventurers and pioneers are assuredly a restless set, and, when they become strong enough, are not likely to be satisfied with any other rule than their own rule, any other form of government than the free republican form under which they were "raised," and which is so eminently adapted to their character. The idea that such a man as STERLING PRICE, formerly the great Democratic leader of Missouri, and now residing in Mexico as an agent of the bureau of immigration, has become a reliable convert to the system of imperialism, is preposterous. HENRY W. ALLEN, the late Governor of Louisiana, and who, though now resident in Mexico, was only a few weeks since put forward again prominently as a candidate for the executive chair of that State, is not likely to be long contented with any other style of government than the American style. We would not predicate such ideas of MAURY and MAGRUDER, who would accept anything that secures them position and pelf; but of the forty or fifty thousand Americans now resident in the Mexican Empire, we venture to say that very few expect to die under the government of MAXIMILIAN.

lead_paragraph: FIRES AND SERIOUS ACCIDENTS. -- About 4 o'clock on Saturday afternoon a fire occurred in the frame dwelling-house No. 268 Bridge-st., caused by the overheating of a stove-pipe which passed through the roof. The building was damaged by fire and water to the extent of $1,000. The second floor is occupied by Mr. FRANK M. PAGE. Damage to furniture $150, insured. The first floor was occupied by Mr. SMITH WING. Loss on contents $150, supposed to be insured....Sunday morning about 8 o'clock a fire broke out in a shed in the rear of a large brick building, corner of Adams and John streets, one part of which is occupied as a Tube manufactory, and the other as a Button manufactory. The flames communicated to the main building and destroyed the upper portion of the Button factory and ruined the contents. The premises are owned by Messrs. BENTON & CO. Damage about $3,000. The proprietor being out of town the amount of insurance could not be ascertained. About 10 o'clock on Sunday morning there was an alarm of fire in the Third District, caused by smoke issuing from St. Paul's (Roman Catholic) Church, corner of Court and Congress streets. It appears that too much wood had been placed in the heater. Some of the congregation, becoming frightened, raised an alarm of fire and ran out. The excitement which ensued was almost instantly allayed by the announcement of the cause of the smoke....About noon there was an alarm of fire in the Second District, caused by throwing burning cinders among some refuse oil in the yard of the glass-works foot of State-street. No damage. In answering the alarm, Hose Company No. 5, with seven persons on the reel and three or four at the tongue, proceeded down the railroad track in Bridge-street at a fearful rate. Perceiving a railroad car coming from the opposite direction on the same track, the guides tried to switch off, and in so doing broke the tongue. One of them named PATRICK FLYNN, was thrown under the wheel, which ran over him and upset the carriage, throwing all on top with great force upon the pavement. One of FLYNK's legs was crushed. EDWARD LEDDY and WILLIAM MCFARLAND were dreadfully injured about the head and spine. ROBERT CRUMMY was pitched head foremost against a tree and was badly bruised. Three others were slightly hurt. Drs. REGAN and FARLEY attended to several of the sufferers. MCFARLAND and LEDDY were subsequently taken to the City Hospital. The others were conducted to their residences.

abstract: and the use of Private Correspondence
snippet: and the use of Private Correspondence
lead_paragraph: Whatever else of value there may be in the book just published by Ex-President BUCHANAN, there is one commendable feature presented in the Preface. Mr. BUCHANAN says that, "from the use of private correspondence he has resolutely abstained." It has become too much the habit with our public men to use for so-called public or partisan ends what was spoken or written in the freedom of personal acquaintance. The temptation to do this is constant, and often the highest moral courage is required to avoid yielding to it. Tested by a strictly ethical rule, the violation of personal or private confidences has the evil effect of making men insincere, hypocritical and double-faced in the intercourse of daily life. There surely ought to be a license for frankness of conversation in private, between men of opposite party views; otherwise society must resolve itself into mutually inquisitorial factions, every man doing the duty of a detective upon his neighbor.

lead_paragraph: A large number of prominent and influential gentlemen in the Democratic party have just completed the organization of a club to be called the Manhattan. The objects of the members are to advance the doctrines of their political Creed, promote social intercourse and provide themselves with the conveniences of a club-house. The number of the resident members is limited to five hundred, and the initiation fee is fixed at $150 and the annual dues at $50, with power vested in the management to assess individual members for an additional fifty dollars. The rules for the government of the organization are not dissimilar to those enforced to other respectable clubs -- two black balls excluding any candidate for membership.

abstract: Fabian, B., Fraud on Custom-house
snippet: Fabian, B., Fraud on Custom-house
lead_paragraph: On Saturday afternoon, Officer HUNT, of the Sixth Precinct, arrested one STEPHEN H., alias Reuben, BROWN, on a charge of setting fire to the grocery store owned by HERMANN SCHORLING, at No. 8 Elizabeth-street. The accused was committed to await the result of the Fire Marshal's investigation. It subsequently appeared, by the evidence adduced in the presence of that official, that the accused had rented a room adjoining the grocery store, in which stood a barrel containing some thirty-two gallons of kerosene, leaving the same a few minutes afterward in a rather hurried manner. He closed the door of the room, and asked a young man named EDWARD GRACE to accompany him to the front part of the building. GRACE followed him, and they had scarcely reached the front of the store, when the alarm was given. Mr. SCHORLING rushed into the adjoining room, and found that the barrel was surrounded by flames, and the faucet so burned that the oil was pouring forth and igniting as it tell upon a box on which the barrel was placed. With great presence of mind, Mr. SCHORLING at once dragged the barrel from the room, burning his hands in a shocking manner, and extinguished the flames by means of a few buckets of water. The testimony of Mr. GRACE further showed that the accused had been in the room about half an hour previous to the occurrence, and it is supposed that during that time he made all preparations and applied the match. BROWN denies having even entered the apartment, and Mr. SCHORLING can assign no cause for the act. Fire-Marshal BAKER still has the matter under investigation before Justice DOWLING.

abstract: Pol cy and the Democratic Party; Should Now Fulfil their Support of the President; the late, a Lesson to the South
snippet: Pol cy and the Democratic Party; Should Now Fulfil their Support of the President; the late, a Lesson to the South
lead_paragraph: If the Southern people desire an early restoration of their old relations to the Union, it behooves them to mark well the Northern will as evinced in the late elections. The Democratic party, as of old, sets itself up as their particular friend. Its manner of doing this was different in different States. In Pennsylvania, its convention resolutions deplored the war and denounced the manner in which it was prosecuted by the government. In New-Jersey, the main rally was made against the Constitutional Amendment interdicting slavery. In New-York, the canvass was conducted chiefly on a claim of special approval of the policy of President JOHNSON, which was falsely represented to have for its end an immediate and unconditional restoration of the Southern States. In every Northern State where an election has been held, the Democratic party has taken a position that it believed to be specially agreeable to the South. It has everywhere been beaten. It has been thrown deeper into the dust even than when striving to hamper the government in the war. In every State, from Maine on the Atlantic to Oregon on the Pacific, this party, which has tried to be the special patron of the South, now lies prostrate and powerless.

abstract: Fanwood vs. Alert, at Washington Heights
snippet: Fanwood vs. Alert, at Washington Heights
lead_paragraph: On Saturday afternoon a spirited game was played between these two clubs. The Fanwood Club is composed of pupils of the Institution for the Deaf and Dumb at Washington Heights; the members of the Alert are students of the Fort Washington French Institute, The game took place upon the laws of the Institution for the Deaf and Dumb, and lasted about two hours and a half. The deaf and dumb boys showed that though they make less noise in their play than other boys generally do, they know how to wield the bat and perform all the necessary evolutions. They won the game by a score of-43 to 33. During the first five innings, the French boys were ahead, and disappointment and disgust were painted upon the faces of their deaf-mute antagonists, but when in the sixth inning, the latter retrieved their fortune, their countenances and gestures expressed their delight. abstract: Shipowners; Ships Sold to Foreign Algonquin and Winooski Trial
snippet: Shipowners; Ships Sold to Foreign Algonquin and Winooski Trial
lead_paragraph: -- We copy from a scientific journal a calm and disinterested article upon the recent trial of these two steamers. It has been quite apparent from the beginning, that the trial was governed much more by the mutual resentments of Mr. ISHERWOOD on the one side and of Mr. DICKERSON on the other, than by regard for the interests of the navy or the spirit and object of the contract. Mr. FORBES agreed to build a vessel for the service which, in the "development of power and economy of fuel," should be at least equal to those which the Navy Department had provided. The agreement was made in good faith and in absolute reliance on similar good faith from the other side. This is shown by the fact that he consented, without objection, that the trial should be made wholly under the direction of the department, assuming, as he had a right to do, that his vessel would be tested as she was to be used, -- in the usual service of the navy. If at sea, running at the usual cruising speed, she proved to develop equal power with equal economy of fuel, as other vessels in the service, he would have fulfilled his contract. It never occurred to him that his ship was to be handed over to parties for a scientific prize-fight and to be subjected to precisely such usage as might suit their purposes without regard to his rights. That she would be tied to a dock, instead of being sent to sea -- that she would be tried, first for power, without regard to economy of fuel, and then for economy without regard to power, when, for all purposes of practical utility, both must go together -- and that her rival should resort to tricks and evasions which would be reacted on a racecourse or at a prize-fight, for the purpose of securing a victory, were in such utter violation of the ordinary modes of transacting business between a government and a citizen, that no one could suppose they would be resorted to. Yet the article from the Artisan shows very clearly that this is precisely what has been done. We trust that the Secretary of the Navy will still see the propriety of placing the acceptance of this vessel on some more equitable basis than that thus far adopted, as otherwise the whole question will inevitably be thrown upon Congress for adjustment.

abstract: London Daily News on United States Securities
snippet: London Daily News on United States Securities
lead_paragraph: attributes the very considerable fall in our securities of late in Europe to the fears there entertained as to the course our government will pursue in the controversies that are pending with France and England -- with the former on the Mexican question, and with the latter on compensation for damages. It is natural and common for the holders of a government's bonds to be somewhat timid as to its action upon great public questions -- particularly when war is one of the possible issues. But in the present instance there would seem to be a want of reasonable confidence in the pacificatory disposition and the sagacity of our administration. They seem to fancy that we are looking around the world for an adversary, and are determined to make war our first argument, not our last resort, in every quarrel. It is a mistake. The decision as to war or peace, now and in the future, lies more with England and with France than with us. We have given neither Power any ground of offence, and shall give none to either. We have overlooked wrongs and injuries on the part of both, such as, in other times, have often led to war. It is from this, from the past course of our government, that the people of Europe should judge of its present policy and its future disposition. We could undoubtedly be driven to war; but only after the exhaustion of every means for securing an honorable peace.

abstract: The members of that crack company in the Twenty-second Regiment, with the letter "B," held high carnival last evening, with the double object of having a splendid drill and presenting their gallant captain with a magnificent sword and trappings.
lead_paragraph: The members of that crack company in the Twenty-second Regiment, with the letter "B," held high carnival last evening, with the double object of having a splendid drill and presenting their gallant captain with a magnificent sword and trappings. Both were highly successful, inasmuch as over ninety members appeared in uniform and took part in the drill, which was fully up to their established reputation. The movements were all executed with marked precision and neatness. After the drill was over the members of the company and a numerous party of invited guests adjourned to the refectory. Here the President of the association of Company B, Capt. HART, presented Capt. WILLIAM W. REMMY, who commands the company, a splendid dress sword, sash and belt. Mr. HART's remarks were very happy, and related almost exclusively to the early history and subsequent progress of Company B. Capt. REMMY made a very short speech in reply. He simply but earnestly thanked his command for their splendid gift.

abstract: British Deserters
snippet: British Deserters
lead_paragraph: We have, from apparently trustworthy authority, a rather startling rumor of trouble of a serious character on the Canadian border. It appears that a British officer took the liberty of leading a company of marines across the line into the State of Maine to arrest deserters; that his men themselves, finding they were on foreign soil, deserted him; that application was made to our authorities to have the men given up, which was, of course, refused. The report adds that the Washington Government, on being apprized of the case, immediately ordered HANCOCK's corps, or a portion thereof, to rendezvous in Maine. Such is the story; and this much is certain, that a body of troops left Hartford at midnight on Sunday for Augusta, Me.

Resting on blocks within the vault, the coffin was opened so that the face...
lead_paragraph: THE FUNERAL OF MR. GEORGE ARNOLD. -- A few friends desirous of tendering the last evidence of regard and respect to the remains of the late GEORGE ARNOLD, met at the receiving vault at Greenwood Cemetery, yesterday noon. Resting on blocks within the vault, the coffin was opened so that the face and figure of the dead were easily seen. The face wore an entirely natural expression, the clear cut lines of beauty for which Mr. ARNOLD was remarkable, standing out in bold relief. There was no service, no audible prayer, nothing but the chilly vault, a sorrowing father, a smell retinue of family and professional friends, a few sobs, the closing of the coffin and the final disposition of all that was mortal of one who a few brief weeks since, in all the pride of youth and beauty, and worth, moved among us, industrious, genial and kind.

abstract: of the semi-official London press, it would appear that Lord RUSSELL's task of reorganizing the Cabinet has been a much more difficult one than was anticipated. The distrust of the Foreign Secretary's ability to bring together a compact body of followers, or to hold them together in support of an administration, does not seem to belong alone to the press or the party which has always opposed his policy. It seems to pervade the higher political circles from which Whig or Liberal Ministries are supposed to be chosen; and the probability is that the strongest plea offered to Messrs. GLADSTONE, GIBSON and CARDWELL, to serve under the new Premier, was one founded upon the temporary or provisional character of his administration. There is an irreconcileable difference of feeling, if not of sentiment, between the pure Whig of the RUSSELL-GREY school, and the younger class of politicians that followed the fortunes of FEEL. And when we add to this difference the decided unpopularity of Lord RUSSELL with the great body of Englishmen, it is easy to reckon upon some trouble in store for him -- even before Parliament assembles. It is true we have by the European steamer this morning reference to a speech of Mr. GLADSTONE's at Glasgow, in which he commends his new chief to the working-men of the country. This much was to have been expected. Mr. GLADSTONE having taken office -- even if it is only provisionally under Lord RUSSELL -- is bound to give him, for the time, a loyal support. But this personal fealty can in no manner alter the natural political affinities of the two men. The London Star, it will be seen, calls for a place in the Cabinet for Mr. BRIGHT. But it is more than doubtful, we should think, whether Mr. BRIGHT is not as resolutely opposed to taking office as was Mr. COBDEN. Until class government is far less powerful than it is to-day, in England, Mr. BRIGHT's natural place is on the independent benches. His forte is even far less that of an administrator than was Mr. COBDEN's. And it is unlikely that he could work even with a Ministry led by Mr. GLADSTONE. It is absurd to look for his acceptance of office under the present Cabinet arrangement.

abstract: Emperor Napoleon I. Letters on Political Conspirators
snippet: Emperor Napoleon I. Letters on Political Conspirators
lead_paragraph: A duodecimo volume has just appeared in Paris under the title of Napoleon I. Peint par Luimeme. The compiler is M. RAMDOL, who sat as representative in the Legislative Assembly under the republic. Every one knows that the correspondence of NAPOLEON has for some years past issued in successive volumes from the Imperial printing-office at the public cost, and under the supervision of a committee, of which Prince NAPOLEON is the President. Seventeen volumes have already appeared, and how many more are to appear, may be guessed from the fact that the seventeenth volume only comes down to October, 1808. From this mass M. RANDOT has selected a certain number of letters, with the view of showing out of NAPOLEON's own mouth the means he often has recourse to to maintain his absolute power. The following specimens are taken at hazard from M. BANDOT's little volume:

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC -- "Crispino e la Comare" was given to a very good audience last night, in the same faultless manner as before, and elicited the greatest applause and merriment. The trio of the doctors was duly encored, and the finale of the second act was enthusiastically received. Mr. MARETZEK may congratulate himself upon the success of "Crispino," which, on Saturday last, when it was given at the matinee, attracted a crowd of ladies, which actually filled every nook of the house. In this connection we may mention that Mr. MARITZEK's artists on Saturday last sang at a matinee and at an opera in the evening, while three or four gave a concert in Boston, and that, notwithstanding this rather heavy strain upon the operatic forces, there were still some four or five of the best artists of Mr. MARETZEK's troupe disengaged. This fact alone illustrates sufficiently the strength of the company. To-night "Norma" will be given with its powerful cast.

abstract: By the City of Washington, at this port, and the Belgian at Father Point, we have five days later intelligence from Europe. The Paris correspondent of the London Times, says it is generally reported in Paris, that the French army in Mexico will be withdrawn by installments, and that by the 1st of September next year, the whole will have returned to France. The British Cabinet was complete with the exception of a single officer. It is said that Spain intends to take energetic measures for the surpression of the slave-trade. A large reduction is said to havs been decided on in the French army and navy estimates. The elections in Italy showed a large majority for the government. Among the elected to the new Chamber of Deputies were RICASOLE, GARABALDI, BIXIS, RATAZZI, and other celebrities.

abstract: Slavery Constitutional Amendment Ratified by
snippet: Slavery Constitutional Amendment Ratified by
lead_paragraph: South Carolina, the leader of the Great Rebellion, the first of our constellation to "shoot madly from its sphere," is the first since President JOHNSON succeeded to the Executive chair and announced his reconstruction policy to come back to the Union. Yesterday both branches of her Legislature adopted the Constitutional Amendment, putting an end now and forever to human slavery. She was foremost in error, and drew after her a third part of the stars. May we not hope that her present good example will be as eagerly and as emphatically followed?

abstract: The Sin and the Penalty
snippet: The Sin and the Penalty
lead_paragraph: "She must be blistered, or she will die," said the doctor of the Duchess of MARLBOROUGH, when far gone. "I won't be blistered, and I won't die," she screamed out; and she was as good as her word. The Democratic party, in the same condition, has told the people the same thing, with as much spirit as the other old sinner, but less truly; it has been blistered, and it is going to die. Our work of Tuesday was fine; but the copperhead virus is still there, and kill it must.

abstract: Patterson, N. J., Reynolds' Tobacco Factory
snippet: Patterson, N. J., Reynolds' Tobacco Factory
lead_paragraph: It will be recollected that large sums of money were offered for the detection and arrest of those engaged in the assassination of President LINCOLN, and subsequently for the capture of JEFF. DAVIS. Both matters were accomplished, and the money for the arrest of DAVIS was not long since all paid over to Gen. WILSON and his party. Owing to the large number engaged in hunting down BOOTH and his associates, it was more difficult to tell to whom the reward was due. The Secretary of War consequently appointed a committee to investigate the matter, and make the proper division. The report was made out and sent to the Secretary of War, who approved and sent it to the President for his approval and order to disburse the money. No action has been taken yet by him, and a large number of detectives are now in Washington, awaiting the announcement, to get their share. The amount involved is near a quarter of a million dollars, inclusive of the hundred thousand dollars in gold offered in California.

abstract: The Imposture
snippet: The Imposture
lead_paragraph: well enough for the Fenians to get up a temporary excitement, as a relief from the dullness which succeeded the cessation of hostilities in this country. Patriotic ardor must find vent in some way. But there is some danger of the joke being carried too far; not in the sense of creating international trouble -- for that is altogether out of the question -- but in this regard: Hundreds, and probably thousands, of poor, honest, unsuspecting Irish, living in the unsophisticated sections of this country, have been cajoled into making remittances to the managers of the Order here and elsewhere -- not one tithe of which, they may depend on it, are used for any other purpose than maintaining a set of scamps in idleness. Stories come to us of remittances of Fenian funds to Ireland. Most of these stories are doubtless intended to show that the contributions received are actually expended for some revolutionary end. Even if an honest share of the funds were sent to Ireland, the result would apparently be merely to send a few more ill-advised young people to jail. But we do not believe that the money is used for any other purpose than getting notoriety and patent leather boots for a set of dlers iin this country. It is really time, that those who are in a position to advise the unsophisticated people in the rural districts as to the real nature of the Fenian swindle, should do so. It is a crime to bolster up the concern even as a joke. The clergy, on whose ministrations the Irish-Americans chiefly depend, are probably doing their best to stop the swindle. But every one who wishes well to Ireland and her people should lend a hand in exposing what is really an unmitigated imposture.

abstract: Democratic party were so enamored of loyal officers, that nominations were tendered to any conceivable number, from Captains of companies to Major-Generals commanding full army corps. Since the election there is a remarkable change in the party views of military service and just military rewards. Two distinguished soldiers have been appointed by the President to foreign missions, and here-upon the entire Democratic press uplifts its voice, as if some grave political crime had been perpetrated. They forget having searched every barrack-room from Staten Island to Chattanooga two months ago, to find some respectable military man on whom to bestow their own empty honors. But now that the President finds two accomplished soldiers -honest supporters of his administration -- willing to accept the substantial honor of representing the nation abroad, these disappointed organs howl aloud, and howl very dismally at that.

lead_paragraph: A sad case of destitution was brought to light yesterday in Williamsburgh. A German family, consisting of a man named RAFEL, his wife and four children, lately arrived in this country, found shelter in the basement of a house in Richardson-street. With out friends, the poor creatures fell victims to their poverty. The woman died on Sunday night of starvation, and her husband is reduced almost to a skeleton. The condition of the four children -- the eldest of whom is but five years of age -- was scarcely better than that of their surviving parent.

abstract: Work performed by Sanitary Police
snippet: Work performed by Sanitary Police
lead_paragraph: We commend as sensible, timely and practical the steps that have already been and will be taken by Capt. LORD, of the Sanitary Police, to anticipate the westward march of the cholera. While there is no doubt a great deal of needless parade given to the few cases of supposed cholera on board the Havre steamer Atalanta, the mere appearance of the pestilence, whether on board an overcrowded ocean steamer, or in a port of Western Europe, is an intimation to us that we shall not, judging from past experience, entirely escape the scourge, either during the present Winter or the coming Summer. We may have it in some form during Winter. But the prospect is not one to alarm us unduly; we are simply admonished by it to be thoughtful and, if possible, wise. There is apparently in the present advance of sanitary science no absolute barrier against the march of the disorder. But the mitigating agencies, available in every civilized community, are such as to rob the epidemic in a great measure of its ancient terrors. This very Atalanta case tells the story simply, and with good effect. Not a single case appeared in the clean, capacious, well aired cabins of the vessel -- while only a few feet distant, in compartments barely separated by wooden partitions, but crowded to excess, the disease had sway for several days. That is the whole history of cholera progress since the disease first made its appearance in Europe and America.

abstract: The annual meeting of the Fireman's Ball Committee, to elect officers for the ensuing year, and to make arrangements for the yearly ball in aid of the widows' and orphans' fund of deceased and injured...
lead_paragraph: The annual meeting of the Fireman's Ball Committee, to elect officers for the ensuing year, and to make arrangements for the yearly ball in aid of the widows' and orphans' fund of deceased and injured firemen, was held at KILLDUFF's, No. 1,160 Broadway, last night, at 8 o'clock, the President, Hon. C. GODFREY GUNTHER, in the chair. Our citizens will be glad to learn that notwithstanding the complete revolution made by the new fire law, this charitable organization remains the same as ever. The committee will use every exertion to add as much as possible to the fund, as they anticipate a great increase of calls upon it during the coming year, in the days of the volunteer department the fund netted an income of some thousands of dollars per annum, from the sale of certificates of membership at two dollars each, which source of revenue is now done away with. The allowing officers were unanimously chosen: President, Hon. O. GODFREY GUNTHER; Secretary, JAMES F. WENMAN; Treasurer, A.J. DELATOUR. The ball will take place on the 23d of January, 1866. Messrs. D.D. CONOVER, W.D. BAKER and JAMES L. MILLER were appointed a committee to select the hall for the dance.

abstract: Crop Next Year; Southern Industry and Northern Capital
snippet: Crop Next Year; Southern Industry and Northern Capital
lead_paragraph: It is of great importance to the whole country and all its interests that a large crop of cotton should be raised next year. It would benefit the interests of the Northern States no less than those of the Southern; the interests of the Western States no less than those of New-England. It would benefit labor and capital; the producer and the consumer. It would resuscitate the fortunes of the unfortunate planting States, extend the market of the grain-growing States, enlarge the activity of the manufacturing States, and increase the volume of business in the commercial States. It would lighten our taxation, enlarge our revenues, enhance the value of the currency, lower the price of gold and equalize exchanges.

abstract: Yesterday was a fine specimen of the tree Indian Summer, that unnaturally warm, dreamy season, when all living creatures are overcome with drowsy langour, and the human family seem for the moment to be lotus eaters, as described by the poet laureat , On the north bank of the St. Lawrence,
lead_paragraph: Yesterday was a fine specimen of the tree Indian Summer, that unnaturally warm, dreamy season, when all living creatures are overcome with drowsy langour, and the human family seem for the moment to be lotus eaters, as described by the poet laureat , On the north bank of the St. Lawrence, there is, (or was yesterday,) nearly a foot of snow, and the keen air was musical with sleigh bells; in New-York overcoats were a burden, the sun was uncomfortably hot, and the still, misty air was almost stifling in its deadness. Croakers, whom no deprivation of oxygen can strangulate, delighted themselves by informing everybody who would listen, that it was splendid weather for cholera; bon vivants, who "live while they live," found it splendid weather for horse-backing in the Park, et cetera; the ton of the softer sex were a little miffed because muffs and tippets, all bran new, were uncomfortable, not to say absurd, in such a warm air; the rough world at large, prone to be easily satisfied, thought it a jolly nice day; and the too oft forgotten poor blessed a kind Providence for the temporary postponement of the terrors of Winter. Prognosticating is risky business, but we venture to say, from the ordinary course of similar seasons, that we have reason to count upon a week or two of fine, soft weather.

abstract: Boiler Explosions During October
snippet: Boiler Explosions During October
lead_paragraph: An emigrant named PETER COUGHLIN on Monday evening fell overboard from the Harlem River Navigation Steamboat pier, near the foot of One Hundred and Tenth-street, East River, and was drowned. The body was recovered. An envelope, addressed to JAMES P. FAGAN, Superintendent of Ward's Island, was found in one of the pockets, containing an order from the Commissioners of Emigration to the Superintendent of Emigrant Refuge, Ward's Island, to receive PETER COUGHLIN, 35 years, native of Ireland, arrived in ship Universe, from Liverpool Oct. 28, for treatment for typhus fever. Deceased had been directed to go to the foot of One Hundred and Tenth-street and thence take the commissioners' boat to Ward's Island. It is supposed that he accidentally fell off the pier. An inquest was held on the body by Coroner COLLIN. The jury rendered the following verdict: "That deceased came to his death by drowning, and we suppose by walking off the dock of the Harlem River Navigation Company while laboring under the delirium of fever, and we condemn the practice and strongly censure the Commissioners of Emigration in sending persons with infectious diseases over our city railroad lines to their ferry at One Hundred and Tenth-street, East River, thereby endangering the lives and health of our citizens."

abstract: Test Oath and Readmission of Southern States to Congress; Readmission of Southern States to Congress--the Oath, >amp;c.; Qualifications of late Rebel States to Admission
snippet: Test Oath and Readmission of Southern States to Congress; Readmission of Southern States to Congress--the Oath, >amp;c.; Qualifications of late Rebel States to Admission
lead_paragraph: It is assumed by many that the oath disclaiming all participation in the rebellion is the only obstacle to the admission into Congress of the gentlemen elected by the South. A great many words are spent upon the question whether that oath is constitutional, and whether the Clerk of the House is bound to regard it in making out his roll of members by whom the House shall be organized. Too great consequence is attached to this matter. Even were the oath utterly invalid; had it, in fact, no existence on the statute-book, it would not follow that Southern representatives would be at once entitled to their seats. It will be entirely discretionary with the House whether to admit even the elected representatives who are prepared to take the oath.

abstract: We assure the World that we have not the slightest wish to "badger" it. We accept fully and freely all it says and sustains by quotations from its files, in favor of ratifying the Constitutional Amendment; and we also
lead_paragraph: We assure the World that we have not the slightest wish to "badger" it. We accept fully and freely all it says and sustains by quotations from its files, in favor of ratifying the Constitutional Amendment; -- and we also accept, we trust, with becoming meekness, its sarcasms and rebukes founded on our supposed "truckling to power." But we beg to inform the World that all these sentiments which it quotes now, were uttered before the election, -- when it and its party were "truckling" for power: -- and what we want to make sure of is that the World and its party friends hold now to the opinions they professed to hold before they were defeated.

lead_paragraph: We print below the diary of HENRY WIRZ, which we received last evening from a correspondent at Washington. Several references have been made in our telegraphic dispatches and elsewhere to this singular document. Our readers will find in it little that bears upon his career at Andersonville, except his protestations of innocence. As to the general character of this diary, and the genuiness of the sentiments expressed in it, we shall leave our readers to judge. We have no desire, and it is hardly necessary to argue his case, now that the grave has closed over him:

abstract: of the appearance of the cholera epidemic in Western Europe, it would be well for our Consuls to report promptly all cases of over-crowding at the principal emigration ports. A sailing ship arrived here yesterday with nearly five hundred persons on board. The passage from Hamburg to New-York occupied little more than thirty days, yet there were no fewer than twelve deaths. There is surely quite as much reason to put this craft in qua[???]antine as the Atalanta. The disease on board in each case may not have borne exactly the [???] technical designation; but no one can doubt that in both cases the prime cause of the mortality was overcrowding.
