abstract: The readers of the TIMES are already aware of the presence in this city of Lieut.-Gen. U.S. GRANT,  he having arrived at the Metropolitan Hotel late on the evening of Monday, accompanied by his family and staff. The party consists of Miss NELLIE GRANT,
lead_paragraph: The readers of the TIMES are already aware of the presence in this city of Lieut.-Gen. U.S. GRANT, he having arrived at the Metropolitan Hotel late on the evening of Monday, accompanied by his family and staff. The party consists of Miss NELLIE GRANT, Rev. Dr. CROMERS, Mrs. FREEMAN, Gen. C.B. COMSTOCK, Cols. ADAM BADEAU and O.E. BABCOCK, and the General's father-in-law, Mr. F. DENT. Suitable rooms for the party were provided by Messrs. LELAND & Co., and everything was done to promote their comfort. As usual with the hero of so many successful battles, sieges and campaigns, the movements of Gen. GRANT during the whole of yesterday were quiet and secluded. The morning was spent in a carriage drive about the metropolis, varied with "shopping." In the afternoon the General made several private visits to personal friends, and dined with Mr. J. SMITH, of Harlem. Very few caught eight of him during his movements, although wherever he went the rumor of his presence soon attracted crowds. His rapid way of going about the city, however, precluded any formidable demonstration on the part of his admirers. The health of the Commanding-General of the United States Army la quite robust, and he evidently enjoyed himself while passing from place to place through our crowded streets.

abstract: Cause of Hostility to Mr. Seward; The Death of
snippet: Cause of Hostility to Mr. Seward; The Death of
lead_paragraph: Hon. PRESTON KING, Collector of the Port of New-York, whose nervous system has been seriously deranged for nearly three weeks, left his room at the Astor House on Monday morning at 7 o'clock, remarking that a walk before breakfast world do him good. All day Monday no word of his whereabouts reached his anxious friends, nor until 12 o'clock yesterday could any trace or clue be obtained. Messrs TERWILLIGER and USHER, of the Custom House, then heard that a person was drowned the day before from a Hoboken ferry-boat. Upon visiting the boat they ascertained that a man, answering closely the description of Mr. KING, came from a West-street car to the ferry-boat. Soon after the boat left the dock, two children going to school gave the alarm, they had seen a man jump overboard. The boat was stopped, but nothing could be seen. A hat left upon the deck was subsequently identified as belonging to Mr. KING. The ticket-master saw Mr. KING step from the car, noticing him particularly from his great weight. He describes his person and dress with such exact accuracy as to leave neither doubt, nor shadow of doubt, as to his identity, Mr. KING spoke to him, asked him how long before the boat would start, and what was the fare, and remarked that it was a fine morning.

snippet: Report; Sword Presentation at New-York; St. George's Church (Dr. Tyng's) destroyed
lead_paragraph: About 2:30 o'clock yesterday afternoon a fire broke out on the roof of St. George's Episcopal Church, at the corner of Rutherford-place and East Sixteenth-street, and spread so rapidly that in less than an hour the roof fell in and the building was a complete ruin. The flames were first observed on the Sixteenth-street side of the roof, and there is every reason to believe that the fire was caused by the furnace used by some tin roofers that had been at work on the church.

lead_paragraph: A dispatch to the Philadelphia Ledger, dated Montgomery. Ala., Nov. 10, states that the returns for Governor appear to be closer than was anticipated, and It is now thought that ROBERT M. PATTON has been chosen over Col. BULGER. PATTON is a Douglas Democrat, and has served as member of the State Legislature for over twenty years. In the Second Congressional District, GEORGE C. FREEMAN, a Major in the rebel army, is reported elected, and Gen. BATTLE in the Third District. The latter had three opponents -- a clergyman named HAMILL, Capt. LIGON, and GEO. F. REESE. Owing to the want of proper facilities, reliable returns cannot be obtained as rapidly as could be wished.

abstract: of the Mexican Republicans were never, at any time, so dismal as at this moment. Without an organized army or an exchequer, or a fixed capital, they have little capacity for effective operations. The military and naval power of the French invader has proved altogether too much for them; and though the people can hardly be said to have entirely succumbed, they assuredly now feel that they have little prospect of success. The official term of JUAREZ, too, as President, will soon expire; and the maintenance and respectability of the Mexican cause is so largely owing to his ability, integrity, courage and persistency, that his loss as its chief must be felt to be irreparable. The Mexican Constitution provides for a successor without the form of a popular election, under circumstances such as now exist; but the Chief Justice will assume presidential power under circumstances so adverse as almost to preclude the hope of his long sustaining the forms of a government.

abstract: THE KINGS COUNTY BOARD OF CANVASSERS.-- The Board of Supervisors met in the new Court-house yesterday afternoon, and organized as a Board of Canvassers. Mr. FURY, of the Fifth Ward, was selected as Chairman, and Mr. JOHN J. WHITE officiated as...
lead_paragraph: THE KINGS COUNTY BOARD OF CANVASSERS. -- The Board of Supervisors met in the new Court-house yesterday afternoon, and organized as a Board of Canvassers. Mr. FURY, of the Fifth Ward, was selected as Chairman, and Mr. JOHN J. WHITE officiated as Secretary. The rolls were opened, and imperfections being found in some of the returns, they were referred to the Supervisors of the different wards for examination and correction. The board then adjourned until this afternoon. It is anticipated that the official result will be declared on Saturday.

abstract: Parsons, W. D., Publisher Daily News
snippet: Parsons, W. D., Publisher Daily News
lead_paragraph: OBITUARY. -- Mr. WEARE DRAKE PARSONS, the former publisher of the Daily News, died of paralysis at his residence, No. 71 East Nineteenth-street, on Monday morning last. He was speechless from the moment of his attack. Mr. PARSONS was a native of the State of Maine, from Parsonsfield, York County. The journal with which he was at one time connected thus speaks of him: "In the early part of his career he was a merchant in this city, and subsequently in New-Orleans and Texas, and about fifteen years since was known again as a merchant in the produce trade in Broad-street in this city. Subsequently he became the publisher of the New-York Daily News, in which capacity he drew around him, through his kindly manners and genial department, among all classes of citizens, a large circle of friends. His even temper commended him to gentlemen of every shade of feeling in political life, while he was never known to relinquish a principle or to desert his honest convictions. He was a member of the Masonic fraternity, and enjoyed the respect and esteem of every one connected with that time-honored institution. He has left a wife and three children." The funeral will take place to-day, at 2 o'clock, from his late residence.

abstract: Reception at Union League; Remark on Mexico
snippet: Reception at Union League; Remark on Mexico
lead_paragraph: During yesterday Gen. GRANT'S movements were varied and extensive. He rode out early, accompanied by Mrs. GRANT and Cols. BABCOCK and BADEAU and visited C. H. ROGERS Esq., at Astoria, L. I. On his return to the hotel he had an interview with A. T. STEWART, Esq., and Judge DALY, who came on the behalf of the Committee of Arrangements for the proposed reception at the Fifth-avenue Hotel. After some little demur the Lieutenant-General consented, to defer his departure for the South until Wednesday, thus giving the committee ample time for their extensive preparations. During the consultation, Monday evening next was fixed upon for the proposed reception.

abstract: -- Spain has at last taken active measures to provide for the abolition of slavery; and, as the first step in this great reform, the Spanish Ministry have reported to the Queen that it is the imperative duty of the government to seek the extinction of the slave-trade. To this end, they propose to ask the Cortes during the next session to make the law more rigorous, even to the extent of declaring many of the practices of slave traders, now [???] as [???] to be [???].They also propose to increase the number of cruisers in American waters, for the purpose of exercising greater vigilance over the movements of the slave traders. In answer to this report, the Queen has issued a royal decree ordering that a certain cargo of 103 negroes taken from a Portuguese slaver be transferred to Fernando Po, or other Spanish colony, in the Gulf of Guinea, and thence to be transferred to any other colony or to any port on the coast of Africa they may designate. Any slaves captured in the future are to be treated in a similar manner. The authority formerly possessed by superior civil Governors of colonial provinces where slavery existed of compelling negroes to labor is revoked. Emancipated slaves who can count five years' residence in the islands of Cuba and Porto Rico, and have entered the government depots, may be declared free, and transferred to one of the Spanish possessions of the Gulf of Guinea or a port on the African coast.

abstract: Algerian Revolt, the New
snippet: Algerian Revolt, the New
lead_paragraph: of France had scarcely turned his back on his African dominions, where he had been received by the tribes with the most flattering demonstrations of loyalty, when his ears were greeted with tidings of a sudden and formidable insurrection. The tribes of the province of Oran, in Western Algeria, distinguished for ferocity and turbulence, have revolted again, at the instigation of their leaders, and it is said they have fifty thousand men under arms. Rebellion is not a new feature in Algeria, but in this case a powerful native family, hitherto trusted by the French, have joined the insurgents, and formed an alliance with a confederacy of independent clans in the Southern desert. Though the French army is doubtless equal to the task of putting down the revolt, it will nevertheless require an immense amount of hard fighting, and a long campaign in a country where more men are killed by marches than in ordinary battles. The revolting tribes will no doubt be severely punished, and their lands confiscated and divided among their conquerors; but it cannot be very encouraging to know that all that may be gained by this sacrifice of life and treasure will be a few miles of barren territory and a precarious and temporary peace.

abstract: Labor Question; the two races; The Two Races in the South
snippet: Labor Question; the two races; The Two Races in the South
lead_paragraph: There is too mach of a disposition to treat the labor question of the South and the negro question as identical. We might as well talk of the labor question of the North as an Irish question or a German question. Nowhere in this free land has the question of labor anything to do with the fact that different races exist within its limits. Industry is a universal duty, resting as much upon one race as another. It is the basis of all civil and social prosperity; and every inhabitant of the country, whatever, his color, whatever his extraction, is under the same obligation to be something more than a mere consumer -- something else than a mere drone in the hive. He is bound to contribute personally in some way to the general well-being.

abstract: The United States steamer Memphis, supply-ship of the Atlantic and Gulf squadrons, arrived last evening, bringing favorable reports of the sanitary condition of the naval vessels, and some interesting particulars of the recent furious gale on the East Florida coast. Among the wrecks reported of American vessels are ships Caroline Nesmith and Panamia; barks Waltham, John Wesley and J.M. Harwood, besides two brigs of name unknown. The lost British vessels are the ships Theobold, Mersey and Ossundgo, bark Queen Mab, and schooner Hanover, and two barks of unknown names. The French bark Margerita, a Spanish brig and three unknown schooners are also reported wrecked. The Memphis brings as passengers a large number of these shipwrecked seaman, besides the usual number of officers and men from the blockading fleets.

abstract: Reform Bill; Not Probable at Present
snippet: Reform Bill; Not Probable at Present
lead_paragraph: shadow of a chance that Lord RUSSELL's government, as now constituted, will attempt the introduction of a Reform Bill. Mr. GLADSTONE, in his Glasgow speech, seems to have been exceedingly careful not to commit the new administration to anything beyond the most indefinite promises of liberal measures. What he positively declared was, that there would be no retrograde steps taken -- a promise which any statesman might make without compromising himself in any degree whatever. "Retrograde steps" would simply mean Revolution. And the majority of the recently elected Parliament are, doubtless, of the opinion that Revolution had better be avoided. Therefore, it is altogether unlikely that Lord RUSSELL's administration will be permitted to survive for any length of time. The "rest-and-be-thankful" doctrine was well enough, while a Minister like Lord PALMERSTON was at the helm. But that was a compromise which could only last for a time. It ended with the death of the late Minister.

abstract: Paris Letter, Nov. 3
snippet: Paris Letter, Nov. 3
lead_paragraph: A letter of the Emperor NAPOLEON to Marshal MCMAHON, on the Algerian question, had been published. It concludes as follows: " I would turn to account the valor of the Arabs rather than bear hardly upon their poverty -- render the colonists rich and prosperous, rather than establish settlements of emigrants, and maintain our soldiers in healthy situations rather than expose them to the wasting climate of the desert. By the realization of this programme we shall appease passions and satisfy interests; then Algeria will be to us no longer a burden, but a new element of strength. The Arabs, restrained and conciliated, will give us what they can best give, namely, soldiers; and the colony, become flourishing by the development of its territorial riches, will create a commercial movement eminently favorable to the mother country."

abstract: The steamship Persia arrived at this port yesterday morning, with two days later news from Europe. There is not much of interest from England. Mr. GLADSTONE has made several speeches in Scotland, in all of which he referred to the new Ministry, but in very general and non-committal terms. The special commission for the trial of the Fenian conspirators had been issued. The proprietor of the Irish People had commenced an action against the police magistrates concerned in the suppression of his paper. An insurrection had broken out in the Algerian province of Oran, which may grow into something formidable. The Moniteur says the rumors respecting the insurrection were greatly exaggerated. A note had been received in Vienna from the Frankfort Diet, repeating the refusal of that body to accede to the demands of the great German Powers.

abstract: We present this morning some further details concerning the destruction of St. George's Church by fire on Tuesday afternoon. The fire was first discovered by Mr. GEORGE BRIARLEY, who was in the church at the time. He ran into the street and gave the alarm. Strenuous efforts were immediately made to save the furniture and fixtures of the church, with very little success. The two fine gothic chairs, stationed at either end of the communion table, and the prayer-books, hymn books and Bibles in the chancel were taken out and conveyed into the chapel. When the roof fell in the scene for many blocks around was one of great magnificence. The flames, which for a few moments, seemed to have been subdued, burst forth soon after with greater fury, and all that vast pile of combustible material, including the fine-toned and costly organ, was speedily reduced to ruins. The communion service was preserved, it having been deposited in the rectory. The clocks stopped at precisely 2:55 o'clock. At 5 o'clock one of the bells in the tower struck one -- the sound ringing out loud and clear above the inharmonious din below, as if in solemn requiem of the ill-fated sacred edifice.
lead_paragraph: We present this morning some further details concerning the destruction of St. George's Church by fire on Tuesday afternoon. The fire was first discovered by Mr. GEORGE BRIARLEY, who was in the church at the time. He ran into the street and gave the alarm. Strenuous efforts were immediately made to save the furniture and fixtures of the church, with very little success. The two fine gothic chairs, stationed at either end of the communion table, and the prayer-books, hymn books and Bibles in the chancel were taken out and conveyed into the chapel. When the roof fell in the scene for many blocks around was one of great magnificence. The flames, which for a few moments, seemed to have been subdued, burst forth soon after with greater fury, and all that vast pile of combustible material, including the fine-toned and costly organ, was speedily reduced to ruins. The communion service was preserved, it having been deposited in the rectory. The clocks stopped at precisely 2:55 o'clock. At 5 o'clock one of the bells in the tower struck one -- the sound ringing out loud and clear above the inharmonious din below, as if in solemn requiem of the ill-fated sacred edifice.

lead_paragraph: We have already announced the gratifying intelligence that South Carolina had ratified the constitutional amendment abolishing slavery, by a strong vote, in both branches of her Legislature. snippet: Address to Georgia Voters; Vicksburgh Herald against Constitutional Amendment; Letter Declining Nomination for Governor of Georgia; Messsge and Cor. on Constitutional Amendment
lead_paragraph: The Southern papers are all of them exercised greatly over the result of the recent State elections. The Richmond Times acknowledges that "the Northern Democracy have sustained most crushing and overwhelming defeat." New-Jersey, it informs its readers, has "yielded to the enemy," and although the Democracy fought with the courage of desperation, they have not been successful in a single State. All the consolation the Times can offer the anxious Virginians is that although the Democratic defeat has been terrible, "their firm, manly, noble stand in defence of the constitution, and of a policy of clemency and magnanimity toward the South, forced their adversaries to abandon many of their radical views, and to give apparently a cordial support to the reconstruction policy of the President." The Times thinks it will "soon be able to determine whether the Republican party is irretrievably wedded to radicalism, or has purged itself of the sin of sectionalism, and is prepared to take its position as a national party." It asserts that "if they determine to adhere to their radical policy, they will stand before the nation convicted of having deceived the Northern people by their pledges, and if they imitate the Democracy in conservatism and magnanimity, they will, after all, be able to boast of nothing in the way of original statesmanship."

lead_paragraph: The City of Newark was thrown into a state of great alarm shortly before 9 o'clock yesterday morning, by a report that a terrible disaster had occurred on the New-Jersey Railroad. Reports were circulated that six or seven lives had been lost, and that a large number of persons were injured. On investigation it was learned that the "Washington express train, which left this city at 8 o'clock, had run off the track by the misplacement of a switch in the lower part of the city, and that one man had been instantly killed, one boy mortally wounded, and several other passengers seriously injured.

abstract: HOPE. -- The remarkable results in many of the recent State and local elections -- the success in municipalities like Newark and in States like New-Jersey of candidates signalized not only by patriotism, but by probity and high character -- the large number of able and honorable men elected to the Legislature of this State, and other such indications of the popular current, give ground for hope as to the possibility of success in electing capable and honest municipal representatives in our forthcoming city election. Possibly the bulk of our people are at last really disgusted with the long rule of imbecility and corruption. New-York not only suffers terribly in taxation and in business from this cause, but she is the byeword of the whole country. Such a condition of things is not a necessity. It is in the power of the respectable people of the city to remedy it. Let fit and able men be nominated for the different positions to be filled, and let those of our citizens who have an abiding interest in the city's welfare and fame support them, and we shall next year have a municipal government that will do us credit. There is unusual encouragement at this time to make the effort.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC.-" Fra Diavolo " was given last night in a very satisfactory manner, and was exceedingly well received. The performance was interrupted for a few minutes by the arrival of Gen. GRANT who was enthusiastically greeted. After the
lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- "Fra Diavolo" was given last night in a very satisfactory manner, and was exceedingly well received. The performance was interrupted for a few minutes by the arrival of Gen. GRANT who was enthusiastically greeted. After the first act the orchestra played "Hail Columbia," and three cheers were given for the Lieutenant-General. To-night "Ernani" will be performed in Brooklyn, and to-morrow "Trovatore" will be given at the Academy of Music. The "Africaine" is in active rehearsal, and will be shortly brought out in excellent style.

The First, Second and Third Wards were canvassed, after which the board adjourned until this afternoon. The errors thus far noticed are merely of a clerical character, and easy of correction, and prove that the Inspectors and Canvassers understood their duties much better than those who in former years officiated in the same capacity.

abstract: ficulties that we anticipated for Lord RUSSELL in bringing together a strong party government appear to have been barely overcome at the date of the latest reports by the Persia, which we publish to-day. Even the journals most friendly to the new Premier seem to make Mr. GLADSTONE's leadership of the Commons the excuse or apology for giving the new administration a trial. The London Daily News, which has always had a good word for the late Foreign Secretary, seems to appeal specially to Mr. GLADSTONE, as the backer of the new administration. The words of the Daily News are of much significance. It says: Mr. GLADSTONE has already declared himself in favor of extending the representative franchises of the people, and it is in the full view of this fact that the voice of the Liberal party has designated him as the leader of the government in the House, and but for the claims of veteran service in the same cause, the chief of the party and the Ministry itself. This is the hardest kind of hit at Lord RUSSELL. It simply means that lie is tolerated for the time, and that, to have a strong Liberal government, Mr. GLADSTONE must be not only the nominal but the real, leader. This is, no doubt, the opinion of ninety-nine out of every hundred Liberals in England, to-day.

abstract: Broadway, has just published two songs, one entitled "Tears, idle Tears," and the other "We've drank from the same Canteen." Regarding the words nothing need be said, as those of the song first named are by TENNYSON, and those of the last, which is inscribed to Major-Gen. HOOKER, are by MILES O'REILLY. Mr. E.B. MOORE, of the Brooklyn Union, has set these songs to music, and he has done his work very skillfully. The melodies are exceedingly pleasant and must become popular. A weekly paper which assumes to be an authority in musical matters, not long ago ridiculed the idea of calling "Tears idle Tears," a song. It even went so far as to assert that it could not be set to music. Here we have positive proof to the contrary.

abstract: The Secretary of the Trearsuy seems determined to break up the smuggling which is carried on to such a large extent along the whole Northeastern and Northwestern frontier. The border towns report great activity on the part of the government officials.
lead_paragraph: The Secretary of the Trearsuy seems determined to break up the smuggling which is carried on to such a large extent along the whole Northeastern and Northwestern frontier. The border towns report great activity on the part of the government officials. The Ogdensburgh Journal states that two most respectable ladies of that town have lately been arraigned for smuggling. The Collectors have received instructions to compel the payment of duties on articles of clothing purchased in Canada, by persons residing on this side, and in case of refusal to pay the legal duties, to prosecute for the penalty.

abstract: The recent accident on the New-Jersey Railroad, at Newark, N.J., continued to excite much interest in that city yesterday. The boy, JAMES BRITT, who lost an eye and was otherwise injured about the head, died at 11:48 o'clock yesterday.
lead_paragraph: The recent accident on the New-Jersey Railroad, at Newark, N.J., continued to excite much interest in that city yesterday. The boy, JAMES BRITT, who lost an eye and was otherwise injured about the head, died at 11:48 o'clock yesterday. Neither of his parents saw him after the accident. His father is a boatman, and lives at New-Brunswick. Two of his uncles visited him yesterday morning. The body will be removed to New-Brunswick for interment.

abstract: are the present high prices to be maintained
snippet: are the present high prices to be maintained
lead_paragraph: Food, clothing, rents and labor are all so much higher now than they were five years ago, and there is so little prospect of their return to anything like the old standard, that there begins to be a suspicion that things have permanently settled at higher prices, compared with gold or currency, than formerly ruled. When the war was raging, and when gold was quoted at between 200 and 300, it was held that the cessation of the one and the fall of the other, would cause such a diminution in the cost of living and labor as would bring it to something like what it used to be before the war. But no such result has been realized, though we have had perfect peace for over half a year, and gold has fallen to its present comparatively low rate.

lead_paragraph: In the Board of Supervisors, yesterday, a report was presented by the Committee on volunteering on the bills of the census enumerators. Many of the bills, the report says, have not yet been certified by the Secretary of State. Of those bills to which the proper certificates are appended, many include charges for stationery, interpreting, copying, , which the committee recommend should not be allowed. To the report was appended a resolution appropriating $50,000 for the payment of these bills. After considerable discussion the resolution was lost. A resolution was adopted directing the Committee on Civil Courts to confer with the Surrogate with regard to the recording of some 400 unregistered wills in that department. The board then adjourned.

abstract: A PLEA FOR THE ORPHANS.--The managers of the New-York Orphan Asylum at Bloomingdale make an appeal to the public for aid. They state that it is twenty-four years since, with one exception, they have publicly asked for assistance, but that they are now forced by several causes to resort to this means of increasing the funds of the institution.
lead_paragraph: A PLEA FOR THE ORPHANS. -- The managers of the New-York Orphan Asylum at Bloomingdale make an appeal to the public for aid. They state that it is twenty-four years since, with one exception, they have publicly asked for assistance, but that they are now forced by several causes to resort to this means of increasing the funds of the institution. All the necessaries of life, they say, have risen in price from fifty to one and two hundred per cent. while the subscriptions to the Asylum funds have not increased at all. The State appropriation has been diminished, owing to the increase in the number of institutions sharing the State fund. The Asylum building stands greatly in need of repairs, while there is a mortgage of $6,000 on it beside a temporary debt of $10,000. Under these circumstances the managers confidently appeal to the public for aid in enabling them to care for the many children under their charge, some of whom are in the tenderest years of infancy. All donations and subscriptions will be thankfully received by Mrs. John Authon, No. 47 East Thirtieth-street; Miss Brinkerhoff, No. 36 Union-square; Mrs. J.P. Van Horne, No. 78 East Twenty-third-street; Miss Seton. No. 28 Union-square; Miss Strong. abstract: Police Parade
snippet: Police Parade
lead_paragraph: -- Every law-abiding citizen of New-York who saw the police display yesterday must have been reassured in his personal safety and his worldly possessions. It would be difficult to find another equally efficient body of men, even in our glorious army. The solid results of discipline were never more conspicuously manifested, and the hard-working officers who have brought the force to this admirable standpoint are to be generously commended. It is but a few years since we had a dirty lot of ragamuffins, who plundered rather than protected the people, fellows whose insignia were badges of shame, who hid their shields (good shields to them) at the first symptom of a disturbance, ran into the nearest alley, and cowered until all occasion for their presence had passed. Or, in a notable instance, kept the polls to elect a ruffian to the Common Council and clubbed away from the ballot-box the opponents of their rascally candidate. The change is wonderful; it is honorable instead of being disgraceful to be an officer; the men almost invariably deserve and enjoy the respect and confidence of the people; they are not only respected but feared, for the roughs and lawless robbers that linger in the lowest dens of the town have most keen remembrance of the arms that cracked crowns during the riots of July, 1863. So it happened that at the City Hall their fine parade passed almost unapplauded, for the spectators were mainly those who had no love for law and order. Up town they were better received; but whether better or worse, the display proved the gratifying fact that the Metropolitan Police force is the finest, best organized, best disciplined and most efficient body of men for similar duty in the world.

abstract: SUIT FOR SLANDER -- DAMAGES LAID AT $10,000. -- Supervisor CHESHIRE, of the Thirteenth Ward, has instituted a suit for slander, in the City Court, against MILTON WOOLLEY, a South Seventh-street liquor-dealer, laying his damages at $10,000. The slander consists, as is alleged, in WOOLLEY calling CHESHIRE a thief, in the presence of Harbor-Master WILSON. The conversation during which this charge was made against CHESHIRE grew out of the latter's connection with the late Second District Provost-Marshal's office, where he filled the position of commissioner. It will also be remembered that Mr. CHESHIRE has been recently pardoned by the President from imprisonment in Fort Warren, where he had been incarcerated by order of the Secretary of War, having been previously sentenced to the Albany Penitentiary for alleged wrong-doing in office, by a court-martial convened at Washington.

abstract: Nearly all the Colonels of the different city regiments of the State National Guard, visited Inspector-Gen. BATCHELDER yesterday at his office, No. 644 Broadway, agreeably to appointment. The business transacted was in reference to the issuing of uniforms, in preparation for the approaching parade of the First Division Evacuation Day.
lead_paragraph: Nearly all the Colonels of the different city regiments of the State National Guard, visited Inspector-Gen. BATCHELDER yesterday at his office, No. 644 Broadway, agreeably to appointment. The business transacted was in reference to the issuing of uniforms, in preparation for the approaching parade of the First Division Evacuation Day. Owing to the absence of any appropriation no uniforms can be procured at present, but arrangements have been perfected to issue United States overcoats to regiments deficient in that particular item, the articles to be kept in the arsenals, and the respective Colonels of regiments so supplied being held responsible for the same.

abstract: A semi-annual meeting of the New-York Society for the Relief of the Ruptured and Crippled was held on the 14th instant, at the rooms. No. 39 Bible House, when a report was read by Dr. KNIGHT, Resident Surgeon, in which it is stated that 799 patients have received treatment, and most of them expensive surgical bandages, during the past six months, being an increase of fifty-seven per cent. over the previous six months, and twenty-four per cent. pro ratio, over that of the four year, their institution having been in operation two years and six months. Whole number of patients treated to the present time. 2,5692; those under twenty-one years of age, 1,351; laboring under white swelling, hip disease, humpback, paralysis of the lower limbs, club feet, bow legs, and various other deformities; those over that age mostly laboring under rupture, female relaxations, enlarged veins, ulcerated legs, rheumatic contractions, and casualties of the war. Of the whole number treated, 2,197 have been relieved and many of them enabled to resume labor, who had not been able to work for months and even years previously. General institution, No. 97 Second-avenue. Branch office, No. 168 West Thirty-eighth-street Officers -- JOHN C. GREEN, President. Vice-Presidents -- James Lenox, R.B. lead_paragraph: A semi-annual meeting of the New-York Society for the Relief of the Ruptured and Crippled was held on the 14th instant, at the rooms. No. 39 Bible House, when a report was read by Dr. KNIGHT, Resident Surgeon, in which it is stated that 799 patients have received treatment, and most of them expensive surgical bandages, during the past six months, being an increase of fifty-seven per cent. over the previous six months, and twenty-four per cent. pro ratio, over that of the four year, their institution having been in operation two years and six months. Whole number of patients treated to the present time. 2,5692; those under twenty-one years of age, 1,351; laboring under white swelling, hip disease, humpback, paralysis of the lower limbs, club feet, bow legs, and various other deformities; those over that age mostly laboring under rupture, female relaxations, enlarged veins, ulcerated legs, rheumatic contractions, and casualties of the war. Of the whole number treated, 2,197 have been relieved and many of them enabled to resume labor, who had not been able to work for months and even years previously. abstract: The Tribune reprobates in very emphatic terms the nomination of any Union candidate for Mayor in the approaching election. Whether it may ultimately prove to be wise or not, this advice seems to us decidedly premature.
lead_paragraph: The Tribune reprobates in very emphatic terms the nomination of any Union candidate for Mayor in the approaching election. Whether it may ultimately prove to be wise or not, this advice seems to us decidedly premature. According to present appearances, three or four other candidates are to be presented by the opposition party in its various shapes, and there is no reason to suppose that any one of them will be entitled to support from the great body of those who desire to secure a respectable and responsible administration of the city government. Under these circumstances, it seems worse than folly for the Union party to announce in advance that it quits the field.

abstract: The Appointment of Gen. Logan as Minister; appointment as Minister to Mexico
snippet: The Appointment of Gen. Logan as Minister; appointment as Minister to Mexico
lead_paragraph: The appointment of Major-Gen. LOGAN to be Minister to the Mexican Republic is a new notification to MAXIMILIAN that his Imperial rule is not and will not be recognized. It has the more significance in being made at a period when the Republicans have hardly a foothold left. It is equivalent to a positive announcement that no success gained by force can commend the usurpation to the united States, and that the day of our acquiescence and recognition is as distant as ever.

abstract: The Insurrection in
snippet: The Insurrection in
lead_paragraph: -- The negro insurrection in the parish of St. Thomas in the East, which at one time threatened to involve the whole island with nameless horrors, has been brought to a sudden close. On receiving notice of the outbreak, the military authorities took prompt and most efficient measures to put it down. A strong force was at once marched to the disaffected region, and on its appearance there the insurgents abandoned their attempt, threw away the arms they had collected, and gave themselves up. A large number were immediately put on trial and summarily executed, the commander of the expedition having neither time nor inclination to take them with him. It is a noteworthy fact that the master-spirit of the revolt was a white man, a member of the Assembly, who, for the sake of gratifying a private pique, used his influence to create disaffection among the negro population. The insurrection seems to have been well planned, and but for the premature uprising caused by a local disturbance, it might have been far more disastrous than it was. The disaffected region was still under martial law at last advices, but no further danger was apprehended.

abstract: Mr. JOHN J. ROSS, of No. 381 Greenwich-street, died at his dwelling, on Wednesday, from injuries which he received at the hands of the bar-keeper of the Northern Hotel, Cortlandt-street. From the testimony at the inquest, yesterday, it appears that on the 20th ult. ROSS called at the hotel while partially intoxicated, and ordered a room. Mr. HAZARD, one of the proprietors, refused to allow a strange woman to accompany ROSS up stairs. A dispute ensued between the two men and the bar-tender, JAMES HAMMOND. ROSS was ejected from the hotel, and on reaching the sidewalk ROSS fought the bar-tender, and it is alleged that HAMMOND beat him in a most brutal manner. ROSS was taken to the New-York Hospital, and thence home, where he died on Wednesday, having been unconscious nearly every hour subsequent to the assault. Coroner COLLIN has issued a warrant for the arrest of HAMMOND. Deceased was 60 years of age.

snippet: Tribute Book, the
lead_paragraph: The records of the great struggle just closed would be far from complete did they consist only of the reports of the movements of troops or of accounts of battles by sea and on land. The forces put in the field were simply the result, -- the product, -- of such a spontaneous and sustained exercise of patriotism as the world has never before seen and as it is not likely again to witness. Then, too, there was heroism of as high a type exhibited in the hospital as on the battle-field, and deeds were performed there without some record of which the history of the war would have been sadly deficient.

abstract: DESTRUCTIEE FIRE IN JERSEY CITY. -- A fire broke out about 11 o'clock yesterday morning in the four-story brick building No. 136 Hudson-street, Jersey City, owned by B.F. WOOLSEY, and occupied by Mr. JAMES JOHNSON as a packing-house for general merchandise. The fire broke out in a room on the second floor, where ten girls were at work, and was caused by the giving way of a shelf holding about 3,000 paper bags, which fell upon the stove. The girls at once fled and gave the alarm, but owing to the inflammable nature of the stock, which consisted largely of drugs, tinctures and essential oils, the fire spread with great rapidity, and in a few moments the three upper floors were speedily enveloped. The Fire Department was promptly on hand, but, in spite of their exertions, the entire building and most of the stock was consumed. The firemen had great difficulty in raising their ladders, owing to the telegraph wires, and were not able to work to advantage. Finding it wholly impossible to save the building in which the fire originated, their efforts were mainly directed to the safety of the adjoining structure, and the fire was confined to its original limits. The damage is estimated at about $16,000. The insurance amounts to $14,500, as follows: Jersey City, (stock,) $4,000; Harmony, New-York, (stock.) $4,000; Merchants, New-York, (stock,) $4,000; Hudson County Mutual, Jersey City, (building,) $2,500.

abstract: Sergeant GARLAND, of the Jefferson Market Court Squad, on Tuesday last arrested BEVERLY GIBSON, a young Virginian of 16 years, on a charge of having stolen $920 from WILLIAM W. lead_paragraph: Sergeant GARLAND, of the Jefferson Market Court Squad, on Tuesday last arrested BEVERLY GIBSON, a young Virginian of 16 years, on a charge of having stolen $920 from WILLIAM W. SMITH, of No. 97 Sixth-avenue. Young GIBSON had been stopping with Mr. SMITH, and, while walking in the street, stole money from SMITH's pocket. GIBSON subseqently shipped aboard the ship Good Hope, for California. Sergeant GARLAND arrested him on the vessel, off Bedloe's Island. Two $20 gold pieces were found in his possession. He acknowledged the theft and said that he had lost $600 by playing "Faro," in the gambling establishment of THOMAS MOORE Sergeant GARLAND called upon MOORE and politely requested him to return the money won from GIBSON, but MOORE refused to comply. At the request of Justice DODGE, GIBSON made an affidavit against MOORE, and, on Saturday night, Sergeant GARLAND, with a squad of men from the Fifteenth Precinct, made a descent on MOORE's place and arrested the proprietor and GEORGE FARLEY and LAWRENCE MOORE. The officers also seized all of the gambling paraphernalia found in the premises. Yesterday, Justice DODGE required THOMAS MOORE to find bail to await the result of an investigation, and LAWRENCE MAHER, of No. 38 East Fourth-street, became his surety. The other prisoners were discharged.

abstract: JOHN BROUGHAM'S BENEFIT.--The immerable admirors of this most admirable artist and author will be both pleased and sad to learn that he has a farewell benefit, on Friday evening, at the Winter Garden. We do not like to lose him, for even a few months; but then, how pleasant will be the day of his return.
lead_paragraph: JOHN BROUGHAM'S BENEFIT. -- The immerable admirors of this most admirable artist and author will be both pleased and sad to learn that he has a farewell benefit, on Friday evening, at the Winter Garden. We do not like to lose him, for even a few months; but then, how pleasant will be the day of his return. To-morrow night he plays Captain Cuttle, in "Dombey & Son." But no matter what he plays; it is his benefit, and seats will be scarce. Without the least intention to betray secrets, we may add that a certain company of true friends are going to surprise Mr. BROUGHAM, at his lodgings, New-York Hotel, after the play is over, by a grand serenade, It is hardly fair to publish this, because the conspirators expected to catch their victim unawares, and prove the yet dubitated question whether he was born with a speech in his mouth. No matter; he is apt and timed to all occasions, and any attempt to take him unawares would be both futile and funny. Last night Mr. BROUGHAM enacted Foxglove, in his admirable comedy of "Flies in the Web," to an immense and. immensely delighted audience.

abstract: Macon Telegraph's Report of Conversation of Sec. Seward and Mr. Weed
snippet: Macon Telegraph's Report of Conversation of Sec. Seward and Mr. Weed
lead_paragraph: We find a paragraph in circulation, taken from a letter in the Macon Telegraph, and purporting to narrate a conversation between Mr. SEWARD and Mr. WEED, in relation to JEFF. DAVIS, in which Mr. SEWARD is reported to have said: "We cannot hang him without first convicting him, and I think no impartial jury would do that." We must be permitted to doubt whether Mr. SEWARD over said anything of the sort. We do not believe that he or any loyal man in the country can doubt that an impartial jury would convict Mr. DAVIS of treason without leaving their seats. Mr. SEWARD may have said that no jury drawn in the ordinary way would convict him, for there certainly are great practical difficulties surrounding the question of his trial.

abstract: The news from Mexico is important. Monterey, a city of about fifteen thousand inhabitants, has been captured by the Liberals. The Liberals have a large force in front of Matamoras, which, they claim, is entirely at their mercy, and can be taken whenever they choose to make the attempt.
lead_paragraph: The news from Mexico is important. Monterey, a city of about fifteen thousand inhabitants, has been captured by the Liberals. The Liberals have a large force in front of Matamoras, which, they claim, is entirely at their mercy, and can be taken whenever they choose to make the attempt. It is said that they have offered all United States troops, who will join them in capturing the city, four hours of unrestrained plunder; but this is not credible. An Imperial transport has been captured on the North Rio Grande by Capt. SINCLAIR, of the Liberal forces, formerly a Lieutenant on the Alabama. The transport was handed over to the United States authorities at Brownsville, who placed a guard over her. A Liberal force was marching on Bagdad, which city was defended by a strong detachment of French troops.

abstract: The City's Opportunity
snippet: The City's Opportunity
lead_paragraph: -- It would almost seem as if we had a Providential warning of danger, and providential opportunity to escape it, in the recent approach of cholera to our doors and the intervening of Winter before the season in which it is likely to become epidemic. We have the Winter months in which to prepare for warding off its advent in the Spring. The experience during previous visitations and during the past Summer in many of the chief cities of Europe, show how much can be done by human agencies in keeping back or modifying its ravages; and by the same means we have learned how it is in man's power to create the conditions under which cholera flourishes with the most deadly luxuriance. Where people are huddled together in filthy tenements and amid noisome vapors -- where moral and physical uncleanliness abound -- where are filthy streets and cesspools, and bad drainage -- there are the favorite haunts of cholera. This is a fixed fact, and in common with other journals, we have shown it again and again. We have again and again attempted to convince the people of the city of the necessity of remedying these fatal and threatening evils. There will be an opportunity, this Winter, for their demanding and securing such legislation as will effectually remove them. It is also in their power to defeat such legislation, so that they will find the sanitary condition of the city next Spring, no better than it has been or is now. It is a matter in which they would do well to be wise.

lead_paragraph: At a meeting of the Board of Supervisors yesterday, a report was presented by a minority of the Committee on Volunteering to whom was referred the bills of the State Census Enumerators. The report states that the committee appointed a suitable person to reenumerate the population in the first three districts of the First Ward, and the result was that he found a population of 8,156, while the State Census Enumerators returned only 5,651 -- or a difference of 2,505. The County Enumerators also found that many houses had not been visited by the State Enumerators at all. The report concludes by asking for instructions as to whether the committee should proceed in the work of investigation. A motion to adopt the report was lost. A motion to adopt the majority report was also lost. The board adjourned to Tuesday next.

abstract: Card by the Editor on its Position
snippet: Card by the Editor on its Position
lead_paragraph: A statement loosely made by an officer of the Citizens' Association, and we trust incorrectly reported in the columns of the TIMES, renders it necessary that the position of this paper be distinctly and openly defined. The Citizen is the property of its editor and of him alone, absolute and uncontrolled. It has never received one dollar of subsidy from the Citizens' Association since passing into the proprietorship of its present owner, nor has that owner received one dollar of salary or reward from that Association. At the time of the transfer of the paper to its present editor and owner, an agreement was made by the Citizens' Association for the fulfillment of their unexpired contracts with subscribers and advertisers, at a sum certainly not greater than the mere cost of executing such work; and beyond that original agreement, which was made at the time of said transfer, the Citizen has not received, nor asked to receive, one dollar of help from any quarter. It is no more the "organ" of the Association, in the offensive sense of the quoted word, than the Tribune is or has been the "organ" of the Republican party; and there is not to-day, and never has been, since our assumption of the ownership, any power, save the will and judgment of the editor, in control of the columns or political course of this paper. If it were consistent to-day with our sense of right and self-respect to support FERNANDO WOOD for Mayor and JOHN E. DEVELIN for Corporation Counsel, that support might be as freely given as to the nominees of the Citizens' Association; and it is because we personally believe that JOHN HECKER and RICHARD O'GORMAN are candidates whose election is essential to the welfare of our city, and not because they are the nominees of any body of men in particular, that they receive our support. Such being the state of facts in the past, we anticipate from the Association in the future no dollar that will not be given for value received, just as the same shall be extended to other papers. As to the circulation of the Citizen, it can only be necessary to remark, without wishing to injure by invidious comparisons or figures any other journal, that it has to-day but two papers of its class in the city -- the Sunday Mercury and Dispatch -- with a greater sale of copies.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC -- "Il Trovatore" was given last night in a more spirited manner than we have heard it for some time. The singers seemed to be in excellent voice, without exception, and the public acknowledged this fact by repeated encores. The ensemble also was very satisfactory. There will he no matinee to-day, but "Crispino e la Comare" will be given in Brooklyn. abstract: see that the President has pardoned ANTONIO RASA, who was convicted in the Brooklyn United States Court of counterfeiting, and sentenced to the State Prison for six years, -- two months of which only had elapsed. Upon what grounds this action was taken, we are not aware, as we understand it was done without information from the judicial officers of the district. Of RASA's guilt we believe there was no doubt. He was found sleeping at the house where the business of counterfeiting was extensively carried on, and was proved to have been coming to the house for a long time, and to have been personally engaged in the manufacture. He was ably defended, but the evidence was so clear against him that the jury promptly found him guilty,

abstract: Lecture on the Poets of the War
snippet: Lecture on the Poets of the War
lead_paragraph: Dr. HOLMES lectured at Irving Hall last night, before a large audience, in the course of the Mercantile Library Association, on the "Poetry of the War." He began by citing VON TROIL's celebrated seventy-second chapter, on "Snakes in Ireland," which hapter was as follows: "There are no snakes in Ireland;" and by suggesting that some might think that in like manner there was no poetry in the war. There was, however, very much; and though much of it was bad, said the speaker, I would rather have written the worst stanza the war has produced than be one of those that sneer at it. I shall not seek to find fault with my cotemporaries. I go through the garden to gather flowers.

lead_paragraph: Before Justice Clerke. The People of the State of New-York vs. David Smith and Tunis B. Smith--This was a motion made by ex-Judge Dean, counsel for the defendants, for the purpose of having the trial of the cause removed from the Court of General Sessions to the Court of Oyer and Terminer. The defendents named have been indicted by a Grand Jury of this city, for having indirectly and constructively caused the death of certain individuals at the time the steamboat Arrow exploded her boiler. In other words they are charged with the crime of manslaughter. Ex-Judge Dean, their counsel, yesterday moved that the trial of these cases be transferred from the General Sessions to the Oyer and Terminer, for the reasons that the defendants were not residents of this city, and were not present when the explosion took place; that this was a very important case, and that the trial would probably occupy several weeks; that many new questions would have to be investigated, and that a number of scientific experts must necessarily be examined as witnesse Counsel said that the Court of Sessions was not so constructed that it could give a case of this magnitude that time and attention which the public interests demanded. The Court of Sessions had all it could possibly attend to in disposing of the numerous criminal cases that crowded its calendar. For these among other reasons he asked that this case be transferred.

abstract: The St. Paul Press thus describes the late execution at Fort Snelling of the two Indians, TAH-TA-CHAH-MANNE, alias Medicine Bottle, and SHAKOPEE, alias Little Six, sentenced upon the charge of participation in the massacre of 1862: "Their apparent, indifference to the fate which awaited them was truly astonishing. Unless interrupted by interrogatories, or called upon to perform their devotions by their spiritual advisers, they appeared to manifest no concern whatever at what was transpiring. They sat there looking as unconcerned as when we saw them two or three months ago, and puffing away at their pipes as though their days on earth were yet unnumbered. As seen as the bodies were cut down a great yell went up from the crowd, and such expressions as 'now are you Pennsylvania Quakers.' 'how are you Massachusetts philanthropists,' and other like exclamations could be heard on every side."

lead_paragraph: The New-York branch of the American Temperance Alliance and Band of Hope, held its regular half-yearly meeting yesterday afternoon, in the large hall of the Cooper Institute. The meeting was largely attended by the youthful members of the Alliance, the hall being crowded to suffocation by a host of juveniles, numbering over three thousand. The exercises were deeply interesting, and consisted mainly of short addresses, delivered by several gentlemen identified with the temperance movement, and songs and glees by the children.

abstract: The Baltimore Sun, says of the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad, that there are now over 7,000 persons employed in the various departments. All the double track on the main stem from the Monocacy to North Mountain, and on the western end of the road that had been destroyed during the war, is now replaced, and much more double track and sidelings have been added, between Ellicott's Mills and Martinsburgh.
lead_paragraph: The Baltimore Sun, says of the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad, that there are now over 7,000 persons employed in the various departments. All the double track on the main stem from the Monocacy to North Mountain, and on the western end of the road that had been destroyed during the war, is now replaced, and much more double track and sidelings have been added, between Ellicott's Mills and Martinsburgh. Large workshops at Martinsburgh, Harper's Ferry, and other points, are in rapid course of construction. The average amount of coal brought to that city by the company reaches the extraordinary figure of 70,000 tons per month. The freight trains from the West number seven or eight every twenty-four-hours, and these are filled with all the products of the West and Southwest.

lead_paragraph: Jewellers, says Galignani, will soon have a new artificial stone at their disposal, thanks to a discovery recently made by M. PELOUZE, the well-known chemist. In nature, mineralogists give the name of aventurine to a sort of brownish-red quartz, interspersed with brilliant metallic points; but a happy imitation of this stone was discovered at Venice during the middle ages by an accident, a workman having by some mistake let some copper filings fan into a crucible containing colored glass in a state of fusion. For a long time the process remained a secret; in those days chemists were very careful not to let anything connected with their laboratories transpire, and used to leave their secrets to their heirs by will. Such precautions would be utterly useless in our days, modern chemistry having unravelled all the old mysteries, and effectually rendered all future ones impossible. MM. FREMY and CLEMANDOT many years ago obtained beautiful specimens of aventurine by heating a mixture of 300 parts of pounded glass 40 parts of protoxide of copper, and 80 parts of oxide of iron from a blacksmith's forge, and letting the composition cool very slowly. M. PELOUZE's new aventurine vies in lustre with the finest specimens of Venice, and is much harder than the latter, since it will cut glass. M. PELOUZE's formula is as follows: 250 parts of sand, 100 parts of carbonate of soda, 50 of carbonate of lime, and 40 of bichromate of potash. The glass obtained from this mixture contains from six to seven per cent. of oxide of chromium, about half of which is combined with the glass, the other half being free under the form of sparkling needles contained within the mass. The jewelers who have already seen this new artificial aventurine, and tried it, have declared that it constitutes an important addition to their supply of imitation stones.

abstract: The Shenandoah has not been heard of for some time and the fact is being discussed in naval circles to some extent. One theory is that she has been abandoned and destroyed at sea. Another is that she has gone to Australia where she will be disposed of. It has also been rumored that she is en route for Peru or Chili, where her commander would sell her for a war vessel, and that one of her officers was sent on the mission some time since.

abstract: Planters' Conventions
snippet: Planters' Conventions
lead_paragraph: -- As the next best thing to a general convention of Southern planters, such as was recently proposed, but which proposition has not been carried into effect, we are glad to see a movement in the way of State Planting Conventions. Such a convention of representative planters of the State of Alabama will be held within a few days, and we have little doubt that before the Winter is over it will be followed by many others. There are so many practical topics upon which light might be thrown by a comparison of notes, by contributions of facts, and by discussions, that we augur great benefit from such assemblages. The question of labor, its supply and remuneration; the question as to the practicability of large plantations, and as to their supervision and government; questions relating to new applications of machinery, and to all such novel ideas or appliances as may be adapted to the new order of things, will furnish ample materials for deliberation. Planters from one part of the State will interchange experiences with those from another; those who have been successful in the employment of free negro labor will explain their mode of procedure to those who have been less fortunate, or who have failed, and thus valuable results may be brought out.

abstract: Election Expenses, Particulars of
snippet: Election Expenses, Particulars of
lead_paragraph: We gave some time since some particulars relating to election expenses in England. We have since been pursuing the investigation and find some further interesting items. An examination of the account filed by seventy-six other candidates show that their expenses footed up at 112,174, the average being 1,475. This gives a larger average than the expenses of the fifty-seven candidates of whom we spoke before, by nearly 500, and the expenses are also much further apart, running from the election in Glamorganshire, where two candidates returned a joint expense of 80, to North Staffordshire, where Mr. EDWARD BULLER obtained his seat at an expense of 6,992 2s. 5d. This later election may well be called an expensive one, for the two other candidates paid 7,712 16s. 10d., making the cost of the election not far from $75,000.

abstract: By the arrival of the steamer Henry Chauncey we have later news from South America. But little change has taken place in the state of affairs in Chili since the previous mail. The blockade of the ports by the Spanish Admiral PAREJA still continues; but ...
lead_paragraph: By the arrival of the steamer Henry Chauncey we have later news from South America. But little change has taken place in the state of affairs in Chili since the previous mail. The blockade of the ports by the Spanish Admiral PAREJA still continues; but some few vessels have been permitted to enter and clear at Valparaiso, while others have been ordered off. No further action has been taken by the foreign diplomatic corps in Chili in relation to the illegality of the blockade. PAREJA, with only seven vessels, declares all the ports (over forty in number) closed. The fear which for a time existed that PAREJA would bombard Valparaiso, seems to have subsided. Chili, determined to maintain her national dignity, is making every preparation possible to carry on the war into which she has been forced. Telegraph lines and roads are being opened into the interior and to the frontier, which will in a measure compensate for the loss of communication by sea. All custom duties have been abolished, and thirty-six coast towns are declared ports of Chili. This is done to encourage blockade-running, which will no doubt in a little while be carried on quite extensively. Letters of marque have been issued in large numbers, and already many persons have left Chili to avail themselves of them. Congress has spent its time in devising measures the most useful in the present emergency.

abstract: St. Albans New Episcopal Chapel,N. Y., opening of
snippet: St. Albans New Episcopal Chapel,N. Y., opening of
lead_paragraph: The new chapel of St. Alban's, situated in Lexington-avenue, corner of Forty-seventh-street, an extremely unpretending edifice of pointed Gothic structure, without noticeable exterior ornament, was opened for divine service yesterday morning, by Rev. E. MORRILL, celebrant and preacher, assisted by Rev. Mr. WALTER B. NOYES, priest-assistant of the Parish, and several other reverend gentlemen. The interior of the chapel is equally unpretending, if we except only the presence of some features of construction and decoration unusual in churches of Episcopalians. At the southwestern end of the building, dimly lighted by the prismatic rays from a window of painted glass, is an altar surmounted by a tall gilt cross, having at either side of it an ornamented vase of choice exotics. Between these vases and the cross are two candlesticks of choice workmanship, and to the right and left of the altar, rising from the floor several feet above the heads of the officiating clergymen, two massive tree-shaped candelabras. The altar, approaching it from the gate of the sanctuary, is reached by three steps, and bears upon its front in a lozenge, richly carved and colored, the letters I.H.S. A chalice rests in the centre, under a shade of crystal, and on either side of this the books of the ritual.

abstract: -- We notice that some Northern papers are raking together, from all quarters, all statements and stories of wrong, injustice and bad treatment to blacks in the Southern States. Of course they are able to make up quite a formidable show of material, such as it is, and are able, moreover, to make it appear that the poor negro since his emancipating is in a truly frightful condition. We have no doubt that an equal amount of diligence upon the same thing, if applied to the Northern States, and aided by an equal amount of imagination and malignity, would enable them to make an equally appalling exhibit of negro maltreatment in our own section. If all the Northern newspapers were searched daily for cases of assault upon negroes by white men, for cases in which negroes were treated unjustly, or refused credit, or turned out of house and home because of their failure to pay rent, it would seem to outsiders as if the white men of the North spent the greater part of their time and muscular energy in persecuting the black men and women.

abstract: Constitutional Amendment and Power of Congress to Enforce
snippet: Constitutional Amendment and Power of Congress to Enforce
lead_paragraph: The long avowed objection of the late slaveholding States to the Constitutional Amendment is directly against the second section, which reads thus: "Congress shall have power to enforce this article by appropriate legislation." It is said there is danger that under this, Congress will assume the full guardianship of the freedmen, and that perpetual discord must come of it.

abstract: We have already alluded to the fact that the New-York and Havre Steamship Company--a purely American enterprise--whose operations were suspended by the war, had determined to resume their old place in the Trans-Atlantic carrying trade.
lead_paragraph: We have already alluded to the fact that the New-York and Havre Steamship Company -- a purely American enterprise -- whose operations were suspended by the war, had determined to resume their old place in the Trans-Atlantic carrying trade. The Arago and Fulton, widely-known and favorite steamships with the mercantile and traveling public, are the pioneer vessels of the route, end their trips will begin on Saturday next, the 25th inst. Solely from a patriotic point of view, this enterprise of an American Steamship Company is worthy of support and encouragement. We have too long been dependent upon foreign nations for facilities in inter-oceanic communication, and no true-hearted American can help feeling that we are disgraced as a mercantile people by permitting the vast traffic between Europe and this country to fall exclusively into the hands of England, France and the German States. These nations being fully sensible of the great degree in which well-established and properly conducted steamship lines contribute to their wealth, power and prestige, foster these enterprises by the payment of large subsides, and a generous sum each trip for carrying the mails. Without this governmental assistance the New-York and Havre Company launch boldly into the sea of competition, deeming themselves justified in making the attempt from the very large patronage which they enjoyed before the war put a stop to their enterprise. The reputation of their ships for comfort, economy and sea-going qualities, is already well established, and by prudence in the management, the line was always self-supporting. It would probably have never been suspended had not the perils from Anglo-rebel privateers made the risk of running longer too great. As it was, the Arago was the last American steamship to leave the port of Havre.

abstract: A tragedy took place abont 4 o'clock yesterday morning, at the corner of Eighth and South Third streets, Brooklyn, Eastern District, which, it is feared, will result in the death of a very efficient officer of the Forty-fifth Precinct. It appears that about an hour previous to the occurrence, Officer JAMES LEE, of the same precinct, noticed two men acting in a suspicious manner on his bcat; and he watched them until relieved from duty, and then informed Officer THOMAS LANGAN, who went on duty at that hour. Officer LANGAN in turn informed Sergt. HUNT of the fact of these men being in the neighborhood, and the Sergeant immediately went after another officer, with the view of having sufficient force at hand to act in case of emergency. He had not been absent for this purpose over two minutes when he heard the discharge of firearms, and hurrying back found Officer LANGAN standing at the corner above stated with the blood flowing from his mouth, he having exchanged shots with the two men he had been watching and received their fire. It seems that just previous to Officer LANGAN's turning the corner of South Third into Eighth street, he heard a noise at the door of the residence of Mr. JAMES FERGUSON, and, concluding that burglars were at work, turned the corner and came suddenly upon and hailed them. Without giving any answer they simultaneously discharged their revolvers at him, the officer answering their fire. One ball took effect in LANGAN's nether lip, fracturing his jaw and descending to his throat. He was sent to the station-house by Sergeant HUNT, who in company with other officers started in pursuit of the scoundrels, they having fled, it has since been ascertained, up South Third-street -- but the morning being intensely dark and the lights all extinguished, they eluded the vigilance of the officers and escaped. The wounded man was attended at the station-house by Drs. NORTH and COLT, and afterward was sent to his residence, No. 18 North Second-street. Dr. COCHRAN was called in during the day, and after a consultation it was concluded to send the sufferer to the City Hospital, in Raymond-street, his throat being so swollen that it was found impossible to extract the ball. He was taken there in a carriage by Capt. WAGLOM and Officer TRAVIS, where he now lies in a critical condition. After daylight, some officers traced blood along the route of the fugitives, up South Third-street to Union-avenue, proving conclusively that some of them had been wounded. The police have also learned that a horse and harness were taken from the place in South Fourth-street, near Eleventh, and a wagon from Grand-street, near Union-avenue. This being on the route of the assassins, it is presumed that the they stole this property to facilitate their escape, the officers in that neighborhood having left there to ascertain the cause of shooting. Officer LANGAN, who is considered a very faithful officer, about two months ago encountered a burglar near the corner of Seventh and South Second streets, and was at that time knocked senseless and badly cut about the head by a blow from a slung shot.

abstract: The New-York branch of the American Temperance Alliance and Band of Hope, hold its regular half-yearly meeting Saturday afternoon, in the large hall of the Cooper Institute. The meeting was largely attended by the youthful members of the Alliance, the hall being crowded to suffocation by a host of juventles, numbering over three thousand.
lead_paragraph: The New-York branch of the American Temperance Alliance and Band of Hope, hold its regular half-yearly meeting Saturday afternoon, in the large hall of the Cooper Institute. The meeting was largely attended by the youthful members of the Alliance, the hall being crowded to suffocation by a host of juventles, numbering over three thousand. The exercises were deeply interesting, and consisted mainly of short addresses, delivered by several gentlemen identified with the temperance movement, and songs and glees by the children.

abstract: The new chapel of St. Alban's, Lexington-avenue, corner of Forts-seventh-street, was opened for Divine service yesterday morning--Rev. E.S. MOR  RILL acting as clebrant and preacher, assisted by  Rev. Mr. WALTER NOYES and other clergy men.
lead_paragraph: The new chapel of St. Alban's, Lexington-avenue, corner of Forty-seventh-street, was opened for Divine service yesterday morning -- Rev. E.S. MORRILL acting as clebrant and preacher, assisted by Rev. Mr. WALTER NOYES and other clergymen. The sermon was eloquent throughout, and devoted to the advocacy of the principles of "Free Church," and to the defence of certain peculiarities of ritual and ceremony now introduced. The choir, with organ accompaniment, was highly effective, and the attendance large and respectable. Rev. MORGAN DIX preached at the evening service.

abstract: Illness and Departure for Italy
snippet: Illness and Departure for Italy
lead_paragraph: It is announced by telegraph that Gov. MORTON, of Indiana, whose life has been for some time in jeopardy from the attacks of disease, has turned the duties of his office over to the Lieutenant-Governor, and will leave for Europe to try the climate of Italy. Gov. MORTON is laboring under physical prostration, induced by the great labors of his office during the war. No public officer in the country worked harder than Gov. MORTON, and few had the capacity to work as hard. In raising, equipping and forwarding troops; in providing for their welfare in the field and their comfort while sick or wounded, and latterly in securing their prompt mustering out, and giving to each regiment a joyous welcome, he worked unflaggingly by day and night. He has personally supervised all these matters, down even to details; and, in the exercise of his patriotic duties, has passed to and fro between the State of Indiana, the National Capital, and the field, literally hundreds of times. At the same time he kept up the warlike and patriotic ardor of the State throughout the war, by laboring personally in the several counties, and delivering speeches everywhere. He maintained the credit and financial honor of Indiana, which a Copperhead Legislature had attempted to destroy, by the boldest and most skillful measures, and raised an abundance of money under the greatest difficulties. He was often called to Washington by President LINCOLN as an intimate friend and trusted adviser, and the support he gave to the government in its hour of trial, was profoundly appreciated by the entire administration. We trust that this able and eminent man, now prostrated in the service of his country, will renew his vitality and his power under the genial skies of Italy.

abstract: The parade of the First Division National Guard, S. N. Y., next Friday, will, no doubt, be an exceedingly good one, both in point of numbers and the appearance of the men. Notwithstanding the absence of State uniforms, the different regiments will turn out with fuller ranks than they have done for some years past.
lead_paragraph: The parade of the First Division National Guard, S.N.Y., next Friday, will, no doubt, be an exceedingly good one, both in point of numbers and the appearance of the men. Notwithstanding the absence of State uniforms, the different regiments will turn out with fuller ranks than they have done for some years past. The return of so many old and tried members of the city regiments from the war, has given an impetus to recruiting, and the consequence is that the majority of the commands are rapidly filling up. The Fifth, Sixth, Seventh, Eighth and Twenty-second Regiments have reached their maximum strength. The Seventh will turn out, next Friday, fully 750 men, fully equipped in the new and elegant chasseur uniform, lately adopted by the command. The new company just organized for Col. VARIAN's Regiment, (Eighth,) will not be able to parade with their regiment, in consequence of a failure to supply their uniforms in time. The new regiment, designated as the One Hundred and Twelfth, lately organized by Col. HULL, and more popularly known as Durye's Zouaves, and recently assigned to the Fourth Brigade, will also be kept out of line, because too much red tape is bound about the uniforms which now are lying boxed up in the United States Quartermaster's depot. No doubt these uniforms will be issued during the week, but not in time for the Zouaves to make any proper parade. If the uniforms had been issued in time this veteran organisation would have been able to prepare and so swell the ranks of the Fourth Brigade. We understand that the universal trouble regarding sufficient uniforms will bear heavily upon the gallant seventy-ninth Highlanders, whose surviving members from the battles of the rebellion have swelled the ranks of the home organization to such an extent, that were uniforms only forthcoming nearly four hundred muskets might be paraded. The Fifth Rifles are in a prosperous condition, and make a creditable display. The Fifty-Fifth are also in a proper position at present, although they might be better. The Twenty-Second will surprise their friends by their full ranks next Friday, most strenuous exertions having been made to equip every man enrolled.

abstract: Stephenson, George, formerly of Dr. Kane's Expedition
snippet: Stephenson, George, formerly of Dr. Kane's Expedition
lead_paragraph: On Thursday, aged 39, died GEORGE STEPHENSON, one of the three survivors of the late and lamented Dr. KANE's expedition, and who accompanied Dr. KANE in his search of Sir JOHN FRANKLIN. STEPHENSON was born in Dublin, on the 16th of September, 1827, and early took to the sea. He was a fine seaman, a generous man, and a genial, social companion. While in the Arctic regions his heart became affected, and he has always suffered from it. The government, in recognition of his services, gave him a position in the Custom-house as night inspector, in which capacity he remained up to the time of his death. He was at one time Purser of the Ealtic, under Capt. JOSEPH J. COMSTOCK. Dr. HAYES and Capt. W.W. WILSON, U.S.R.S., are the only survivors of the Kane Arctic Expedition. On Saturday the remains of STEPHENSON were interred in Greenwood.
