abstract: Government, and Indifference of Wealthy Classes
snippet: Government, and Indifference of Wealthy Classes
lead_paragraph: A great deal of indignation is freely expressed by us all at the tyranny of the low and ignorant classes in this city. We feel that we are absolutely trodden upon by the proletaires of the community. We find that ideas of morality and public good have little influence in our municipal affairs, and that numbers are everything. The Government of New-York, its corruption, its ignorance, and even want of decent regard for the opinions of the good, is a proverb throughout the world. We blame emigration for it; we charge universal suffrage with it; we lay the shame of it on Democratic politicians; and no doubt all these are at fault, and especially the latter -- the unprincipled demagogues who lead ignorant masses without sense of shame or a thought of principle. Some of them are certainly the most corrupt characters that ever disgraced any civilization. When Rome was governed by freedmen and gamblers, and was just ready to fall an easy prey to imperial power, it had just so shameless a set of men at the head of affairs; men who thus openly defied the moral sense of the world.

abstract: We regret to announce the death of Mr. JOHN S. VOORHIES, the eminent law bookseller and publisher, which happened on Sunday evening at his residence in Montague-street, Brooklyn, after an illness of some duration. Mr. VOORHIES had been engaged in business 40 years, and during that time had been brought into connection with most of the profession, by whom he was much esteemed. The varied knowledge of the books he dealt in, and the many recollections of luminaries who have passed away added much pleasure to the society of a well educated and intelligent man. Upright in business and a true friend his loss will be deeply felt.

abstract: The steamer Atalanta still remains at the lower Quarantine, but it will be seen from the annexed correspondence that the government has given orders to send the steamer Illinois down to the lower bay, to receive the steerage passengers. Their clothing will...
lead_paragraph: The steamer Atalanta still remains at the lower Quarantine, but it will be seen from the annexed correspondence that the government has given orders to send the steamer Illinois down to the lower bay, to receive the steerage passengers. Their clothing will first be placed on board this vessel and thoroughly fumigated with cholrine gas. The passengers themselves will then pass on board and have to submit to a personal fumigation with bromine and nitrous add gas. After this the steamer will be allowed to come up to the city and the passengers landed. A small vessel has been sent down by the agents of the Atalanta to receive the cabin passengers. After undergoing the necessary fumigation, they will be allowed to come up to the city.

abstract: The levee held last evening at the Fifth-Avenue Hotel by Gen. GRANT, was one of those affairs which must be judged by the intention rather than the actual facts. It was meant as an opportunity to do honor to the distinguished soldier on the part of the representative people of New-York.
lead_paragraph: The levee held last evening at the Fifth-Avenue Hotel by Gen. GRANT, was one of those affairs which must be judged by the intention rather than the actual facts. It was meant as an opportunity to do honor to the distinguished soldier on the part of the representative people of New-York. Citizens of all classed underwent the misery of one of the severest crushes which has ever been known in this city and preserved their equanimity and sustained their enthusiasm to the end. Probably at the lowest computation two thousand five hundred guests poured into the hotel in the course of the evening, completely blocking up the long corridors and thronging the spacious parlors and dining-room. The ladies were out in force, and their toilettes were of the richest description. Unfortunately, however, the close packing made it an utter impossibility to see any of their magnificence to advantage. Gen. GRANT submitted to the trying ordeal of hand-shaking without a murmur, although it apparently taxed his strength severely. The arrangements of the police for preserving order outside the hotel were admirable. The arrangements of the Reception Committee inside could not have been worse.

abstract: Shenandoah; History and Captures of
snippet: Shenandoah; History and Captures of
lead_paragraph: The pirate Shenandoah has at last arrived home, having been absent since Oct. 18, 1864, during which time she has been around the world, sinking, burning, destroying and bonding American vessels. Among her last acts was the destruction of our Northwestern coast whaling fleet. Some months ago she was outlawed, and now has the audacity to seek an asylum under the protection of the flag which aided supported and guarded her in safety until she could place herself beyond the reach of Federal cruisers.

abstract: Grand Reception at New-York
snippet: Grand Reception at New-York
lead_paragraph: The night of the 20th of November will be ever memorable in the social history of the metropolis, as the occasion when the more prominent men of the city open house to the many who desired to greet a hero and shout acclaim in honor of a glorious soldier. When it was first known that Gen. GRANT would, with his, family tarry a few days in this city, it was suggested that a public demonstration of some nature should be made in recognition of the esteem entertained for him by our citizens. Two objections were urged: one, that the visit here would be quite brief, and entirely occupied to private businees; the other, that such a proceedings would be in absolute disregard of the General's reported dislike of parade or show. The project was abandoned for a time, but upon consultation it was ascertained that the General could so arrange his affairs as to find a spare evening for the reception of his friends. Several meetings were held by the gentlemen prominent in the matter, and after a little the project assumed shape and became the topic of town talk. Circulars were issued to one hundred and fifty persons, suggesting that each member of the body subscribe $100 toward defraying the expenses of the reception. The gentlemen invited were only too happy to comply, and having paid their money, were admitted to the General Committee. The following are the names of the subscribers:

abstract: By the arrival of the steamships City of London and the New-York at this port yesterday, we are placed in possession of highly interesting news respecting the notorious pirate Shenandoah. On the 30th of August last, Capt. WADDELL, probably finding the North Pacific growing a little too hot for comfort, concluded to believe the war was over, put his guns in the ship's hold and headed for Liverpool, as the port where he was most secure of a welcome. He arrived there on the 6th inst., and immediately "surrendered" his ship to the Captain of a British man-of-war. He and his crew were subsequently released on parole. The arrival of the notorious corsair chief created great excitement in England. The papers were discussing the question whether he should be given up to the United States, or tried in England for piracy -- opinion inclining to the latter view. There appeared to be no question as to the surrender of the vessel to the United States Government. Capt. WADDELL affected ignorance that the war had closed. He had stowed away a large amount of stolen money and valuables in his ship's hold, intending, he says, to restore the property to its owners.

abstract: THE PRESENTATION OF JEWELRY TO MRS. GEN. GRANT. -- Mrs. Gen. GRANT, accompanied by several members of the General's Staff, called at the store of Messrs. BROWNE & SPALDING, in Broadway, yesterday, to thank them for the elegant gift of jewelry presented to her by that firm some time ago. The jewelry consisted of a comb and ear-rings, made from the wood of the tree under which the terms of surrender of LEE's army were agreed upon, set in gold of exquisite workmanship. The gift was formally presented to Mrs. GRANT by Col. PARKER, one of the General's aids, on behalf of Messrs. BROWNE & SPALDING, at the Metropolitan Hotel in Philadelphia, in the presence of a large number of distinguished persons, on the return of Gen. GRANT and his lady from their Western tour.

abstract: Shenandoah Surrenders to British Man-of-War at Liverpool
snippet: Shenandoah Surrenders to British Man-of-War at Liverpool
lead_paragraph: The steamship City of London, which arrived at this port yesterday morning, brings intelligence of the arrival of the notorious pirate Shenandoah at Liverpool, on the 6th inst., and her surrender to H.B.M.S. Donegal, Capt. WADDELL, the Commander of the Shenandoah, states that the last vessel he spoke was the Barracoula, from Liverpool to San Francisco, from which he learnt that the South was really and truely defeated. On this, he at once stowed away his guns and ammunition in the hold, and steered for Liverpool, stopping at no other port. On arriving near the port he took a pilot on board, and finding the news of the defeat of the Confederacy confirmed beyond all doubt, he desired him to take the Shenandoah alongside a man-of-war, if there was one in the river. The ex-cruiser was in consequence placed alongside the Donegal, and a crew from that vessel placed in charge of her, some customs officers also being in charge with them.

abstract: Louis Spies was tried for stealing a valise on the 25th of October from an express wagon. The driver, Washington Lewis, when driving from Ann-street to Broadway, happened to look around and saw the prisoner trying to get the valise over the end-board of the wagon. He stopped the vehicle, got out and pursued the prisoner, who ran around the corner, where he was arrested by two policemen. The jury found the accused guilty of petit larceny, and he was remanded for sentence.

abstract: The Imperial Rule in
snippet: The Imperial Rule in
lead_paragraph: The Emperor MAXIMILIAN is putting into practice his bloody decree providing for the execution of such of his Republican opponents as may be captured with arms in their hands. The Imperialist account of the recent Republican defeat in the State of Michoacan admits that Gen. ARTEAGA and twelve of his officers were shot after the surrender, and it is further related that Gens. GOMEZ, SALAZAR and PARAPACHOS have suffered a similar fate. When the decree reached us a few weeks ago, it was hardly thought that it would be put into execution; or, at all events, it was imagined it would be modified in some way, as for example, by holding their prisoners without the privilege of exchange, and suspending the death penalty over their heads. It is true there had been executions or assassinations of Republican Generals taken in arms by the Imperialists even before the issuance of the October decree, as in the case of the brave and patriotic Gen. ROMERO; but that such action would be adopted as a policy and established as the permanent order of things, under such circumstances as now prevail in Mexico, seemed utterly incredible to such Americans as had failed to observe the conduct of the "civilized" armies and rulers of Europe under the exigencies of war.

abstract: Work of the State Convention
snippet: Work of the State Convention
lead_paragraph: Gov. MARVIN telegraphs to the President that the Florida State Convention has completed its labors and adjourned. Their work seems to have been earnest and thorough; they annulled the ordinance of secession, emphatically repudiated the wax debts contracted by rebel authority, distinctly abolished slavery, and declared all the inhabitants of the State entirely free; provided for the admission of the testimony of colored persons, where any of that race are concerned, and amended and liberalized the constitution in other respects. It is not to be doubted that the Legislature will work in harmony with these great changes, and that within a brief period this undeveloped, but naturally rich State, will begin a new and promising career. Her ablest men have for years (long before the war) frankly admitted that slavery was their stumbling block, weak in itself as an industrial value, yet politically strong enough to shut out the capital and energy knocking a[???] their doors, and so sinking them down to a miserable appanage of their domineering neighbor on the North. During the war the rebels made good use of the natural wealth of Florida by drawing from her ever-luxuriant pastures a large portion of the beef and corn that supported their armies. Now that she opens her doors to liberty and enterprise, there is good reason that her wonderfully salubrious climate, her generally fruitful soil, her live-oak forests, and especially her favorable situation for trade with the Indies, will attract the stirring blood and busy capital of the North, and speedily bring her into hitherto unknown political and commercial importance.

abstract: Hotel Life in New York
snippet: Hotel Life in New York
lead_paragraph: There are two classes of people among us who have been prosperous during the last four years, are now more so than ever, with a fair prospect for a most extraordinary continuance of fortune for a long time to come. They are the keepers of boarding-houses, and the proprietors of hotels. Life in a boarding-house has been the oft-selected theme of cynics and querulists; it has never been considered a fit topic for levity. It is a serious business, costs a great deal, inculcates lessons of patience, and tends to sour the disposition. With this we have nothing to do, but desire simply to chronicle the fact that every boarding-house in the city averages its absolute fullness from the moderate dens of Water and Pearl streets, where dirty beds and wretched food are served at the small price of $2 50 per week, to the gorgeously gilded and elaborately frescoed salons of Fifth and Madison avenues, where one can sleep on modern bedsteads and endure four or five courses of cookery at prices ranging from $20 to $40 per week.

abstract: Our Mexican news to-day, is interesting and important: MAXIMILIAN has found it necessary to concentrate his troops at three points, thus virtually leaving most of the country open to the Liberals. His...
lead_paragraph: Our Mexican news to-day, is interesting and important. MAXIMILIAN has found it necessary to concentrate his troops at three points, thus virtually leaving most of the country open to the Liberals. His wife has made preparations for an early return to Europe. The Emperor has postponed in indefinitely his proposed visit to Yuctan. From the Western Coast we learn that the local Legislature of Lower California, has passed an act recognizing the Empire, but the Governor refused to sign it, and the people threatened to revelt if the act should be consummated. A letter from Mazatlan says that the French have quite abandoned Sinaloa, except that eight hundred troops held the city, (Mazatlan,) and that a large Mexican force has cut off all communication with the interior, and threaten the town.

abstract: Charter Election, Reform and Nominations for Mayor--the Tribune; On Nominations for Mayor
snippet: Charter Election, Reform and Nominations for Mayor--the Tribune; On Nominations for Mayor
lead_paragraph: We agree with the Tribune that city reform is the main thing to be considered in the coming city election. It makes but little practical difference whether our Mayor for the next two years shall be a Democrat or a Republican; but it may make a great deal of difference whether he be an honest man or an unprincipled scoundrel. We do not think it would be creditable for the city to elect an out-and-out Secessionist to that or any other high office, and we should take a good deal of pains to prevent such a result. But as between loyal candidates, mere party distinctions are of comparatively little consequence. We need in our city government men who will consult the public welfare, and not their personal advantage nor the pecuniary interests of individuals or "rings," in their administration of public affairs.

abstract: The Coming Session of
snippet: The Coming Session of
lead_paragraph: According to present appearances the political prophets of evil concerning the approaching session of Congress, are likely to be quite as much disappointed as they were in regard to our Union State Convention at Syracuse. We see no symptoms of the disasters they so confidently predict. The terrible internal struggle which is to destroy the Union party, overthrow the President and plunge the country into hopeless chaos and confusion, does not yet darken the land with its gloomy shadow. Indeed the Union party seems to be quite as thoroughly united upon all cardinal points of national policy, and quite as harmonious in support of the President, as any party, equally strong in numbers and in popular support, has over been before.

lead_paragraph: The scenes in the street were nothing like those inside the hotel. First, there was more room, and plenty of pure air, which are always the concomitants of quietness and order. There was no pressing or driving, no ill-humor or hot temper, on the part of those who had out-door tickets. The street was far more comfortable than the hotel, notwithstanding the rain, which somewhat dampened the feelings of the crowd. The police arrangements for the arrival of carriages were very fine. There were on the ground about 400 patrolmen, with any number of sergeants. Inspector CARPENTER personally superintended the management, assisted materially by Capts. Brackett, Speight, Copeland, Petty, Thorn and Cameron. Twenty-third-street was kept entirely clear, from Fifth to Sixth avenues, by a heavy line of policemen, thus enabling the almost endless string of carriages to come up in rapid and regular order.

abstract: Officer JOHN DANIEL, of the Eighth Precinct, charged a young man named JOHN MCGINLEY with burglariously entering the premises No. 53 Grand and No. 28 Laurens streets, and stealing therefrom the sum of twelve dollars in copper and nickel coin. The store; owned by DENNIS LYONS, was used as a liquor-store, LYONS, in his evidence as witness, testifying to the fact of his having counted and deposited in a drawer therein the twelve dollars named. The officer stated that about 4 o'clock this morning he saw MCGINLEY come out of the hall door adjoining the store, and suspecting him to be there for no good purpose, he entered, and found a panel broken in the door leading into the hall. He then rapped for assistance, and in a short time MCGINLEY reentering the hall, he took him into custody. The prisoner, on being questioned by the officer, denied having been in the hallway before. On going into the store, the drawer of the counter was found lying upon the floor, and a number of pennies scattered around, and on the calling of LYONS, the twelve dollars was found missing.

abstract: ACCIDENTALLY SHOT ON A GUNNING EXCURSION --INHUMANITY OF RAILROAD CONDUCTORS.--Coroner LYNCH held an inquest upon the body of WILLIAM H. VANDERVEER, aged 16 years, residing with his parents, No. 54 Woodhull-street, who died on Sunday from injuries sustained while on a gunning excursion near Fort Hamilton, on the 1st ult. lead_paragraph: ACCIDENTALLY SHOT ON A GUNNING EXCURSION -- INHUMANITY OF RAILROAD CONDUCTORS. -- Coroner LYNCH held an inquest upon the body of WILLIAM H. VANDERVEER, aged 16 years, residing with his parents, No. 54 Woodhull-street, who died on Sunday from injuries sustained while on a gunning excursion near Fort Hamilton, on the 1st ult. The deceased was accompanied by a boy named WM. DISSEN. In rambling about in search of game they came to a fence, and seating themselves on the top rail VANDERVEER placed his gun in such a position that the trigger was beside his feet, and the muzzle near his head. DISSEN warned him of the danger he was in, and jumping down ran some distance. Hearing the report of VANDERVEER's gun he looked round and saw him falling from the rail. The bullet had perforated one ear, and he fell upon a stone, fracturing his skull. The wounded boy was conducted to the fort by some soldiers, where he was properly attended to by the surgeon. DISSEN was then told to take him home on the cars, but two conductors in succession refused to take him, and he was sent back to the fort, where he remained until the arrival of his father, some five hours afterward. The jury in the case rendered the following verdict: "We find that WM.H. VANDERVEER came to his death by accidental injuries received by the discharge of a gun in his own hands, on the 1st of October, 1865. The jury further censure the Brooklyn City Railroad Company for the inhumanity displayed on the occasion in refusing to allow deceased to be brought to the city in their cars."

abstract: Goodyear vs. Haering; India Rubber Combs Patent
snippet: Goodyear vs. Haering; India Rubber Combs Patent
lead_paragraph: H.B. Goodyear and C. Poppenhusen vs. Robert Haering. -- Robert Haering was brought before the court this morning for a contempt by violating the injunction of the court forbidding him to manufacture india-rubber combs in violation of the Goodyear patent. The case was originally referred to the master of the court, who reported him in contempt. Judge Nelson affirmed the report and issued a warrant for his arrest. Judge SHIPMAN said that as the proofs were not clear as to the extent of the contempt, he would be lenient, and only sentence him to twenty days' imprisonment and a fine of $50.

abstract: Joseph Jansen vs. Eric P. Lindahl. -- This was a claim for $410, the balance of bounty which the plaintiff alleged had been promised him on enlistment. The defence alleged that but $200 had been promised, and that this had been made plain by the enlisting Provost-Marshal to the plaintiff by signs, though defendant had been interpreter, and had stated the same facts; that this amount had been paid, (the plaintiff admitted $190,) and that Lindahl had not personally promised anything. The Court submitted the case as a question of credibility of witnesses, and the jury gave a verdict for defendant.

abstract: The Progress of
snippet: The Progress of
lead_paragraph: There has been much apprehension that, as the sense of defeat lost its freshness, the Southern disposition would grow less reasonable and compliant in the work of reconstruction. The Mississippi and Alabama Conventions, which met three or four months ago, did their business cleanly and expeditiously. They pronounced the secession ordinances to have been originally null and void, discarded all the debts which had been contracted to give effect to these ordinances, decreed the permanent abolition of slavery in the simplest and most direct terms, and imposed upon the next Legislatures the duty of enacting laws which should secure to the freedmen full protection of person and property. They did this with little prompting from Washington, and with little murmuring in any quarter. There was a general sense of what was due to the government, and a cheerful readiness to fulfill it. The later conventions have been less harmonious. In all of them there has been a faction which has been reluctant, perverse, and captious. The speeches of these men, as given in the reports of the conventions, show a great misconception of the actual situation. They all assume, more or less, that whatever the course of the Southern States, restoration will be an easy matter. These men have used the great magnanimity of the government in its amnesty and general policy of reconstruction, to give color to the pretence that, in the view of the government itself, no real crime had been committed, and that preliminaries to restoration were, after all, little else than a matter of form. This idea was strengthened by the position substantially taken by the Democratic party in all the late elections in the Northern States, that the restoration should be immediate and unconditional; and by the misrepresentation of the leaders of that party that this was what President JOHNSON was aiming to effect.

abstract: Lessons Taught by
snippet: Lessons Taught by
lead_paragraph: The British Press has begun to agitate the question whether too much meat is not eaten in England. For one pound of meat the people of Scotland consume, the English consume ten. Yet there is quite as much health and muscular vigor north as there is south of the Tweed. Eighteen thousand head of cattle have been sacrificed this year by the plague, and really good meat is quite as dear in London as it is in New-York to-day. Economy has, therefore, become a necessity even with the well-to-do-classes; and some of the journals are occupied in inditing long homilies upon the subject -- laying down the law as to the quantity (three-quarters of a pound) which each person may wisely use per day. The London Times is, as usual, wonderfully sage. It observes: "In Winter, at all events, there really is no reason why we should not import our butcher's meat from British American and other transmarine pastures." Why this new trade should be opened in Winter, when the only portions of British America where cattle are to be had, are those which are closed to navigation, we do not exactly understand. We think the British Americans generally will be considerably surprised to find that they are to become large exporters of cattle, either in Winter or Summer.

lead_paragraph: The spacious armory of the Twenty-second Regiment, N.G.S.N.Y., in Fourteenth-street, near Sixth-avenue, was last evening crowded by a select audience, composed of friends of the regiment, who, despite the inclemency of the weather, had assembled to witness the interesting ceremony of presenting eight medals of merit to a member from each company, chosen by the respective Captains, as the best soldier in that company for drill, discipline and general conduct. The medals are popularly known as the "Aspinwall Medals," being presented by the Colonel of the regiment, LLOYD ASPINWALL. These beautiful medals were manufactured at Paris, and are composed of silver. On the obverse is the design of a shield, supported on either side by American flags, the whole in bold relief. On the shield is engraved the State arms, the figures "22" being placed beneath. Over the shield is the motto of the State, "Excelsior." On the reverse are the words "Military Merit," with the name of the recipient and date of presentation. Beneath stand Col. ASPINWALL's initials.

abstract: New-York; Cortlandt-street, Hoerles' Boot Store
snippet: New-York; Cortlandt-street, Hoerles' Boot Store
lead_paragraph: On Sunday morning, the boot and shoe store of JUSTUS HOERLE, No. 1 Cortlandt-street, was entered by burglars, at about 6 o'clock, who wrenched off the padlock and forced the bolts and inner lock with a jimmy, and robbed it of between three and four hundred dollars' worth of boots and shoes. A boy, who was returning from the paper office with his papers, saw three young men in the act of forcing open the door, but was afraid to give any alarm. Shortly after, another boy, employed in the barber's shop under the Merchants' Hotel, in Cortland-street, saw three young men as he was taking down the shutters of the shop pass by with boots and shoes in their hands. Capt. HELME, who shortly after visited the premises to ascertain the extent of the robbery and learn by what means the burglars had effected an entrance, learned the above facts from these boys, and also got a description of the dress and general appearance of the three young men, and set to work at once to find them out. He put an officer on the case to work it up, and also directed his officers to drive all the suspicious characters off who might be hanging around their several posts, and in case they did not leave, to arrest and bring them to the station-house. At about 7:30 o'clock on Sunday evening, Officer JOHN MALOY found a number of these characters congregated on his post in Greenwich-street, and ordered them away; two of them refused, and the officer found it necessary to use his club in arresting them, and brought them to the station-house, and the Captain at once recognized them from the description he had received as two of the parties who had been concerned in the robbery. They were detained over night on the officer's charge of disorderly conduct, and in the morning the boys before alluded to were sent for, and recognized them at once as two of the three men whom they had seen with the boots in the morning. They were taken to court and committed by Justice DOWLING, and sent back to the station-house to give the officers an opportunity more fully to work up the case. The Captain having learned that three young men answering their description had been seen on Sunday afternoon to enter the second-hand boot and shoe store of SAMUEL ROSENBERG, No. 121 Baxter-street, with some boots and shoes in their possession, and to leave without them, sent Officer WALKENSHAW to examine the premises for the stolen property. He succeeded in recovering a part of it, and arrested ROSENBERG as a receiver of stolen goods. On being brought to the station-house he recognized the two young men as two of the parties who had sold the shoes to him. Officer HEY arrested, during the day, the third prisoner, with a pair of the stolen shoes on his feet, and a pair of old shoes, found in the store, proved to fit him exactly. The four prisoners, THOMAS JENKINS, PATRICK SWEENEY, THOMAS LYONS and ROSENBERG were taken to court and committed for trial by Justice DOWLING.

abstract: Margaret Butler was placed on trial for stealing $40 from Edwin Binney. The circumstances were, that on the night of the 12th of November the complainant met the accused in a saloon, and after getting pretty drunk went out with her. An officer found them engaged in a dispute, the prisoner claiming to be Binney's wife, and trying to get him to go home; but he told the officer that she had taken his money. The arrest was made, and $25 found in her possession, in bills of the same bank as those the complainant had. Guilty of petit larceny; Penitentiary six months.

abstract: National Policy of
snippet: National Policy of
lead_paragraph: sible courses of policy for this country to adopt -- on the one hand to go to work energetically reorganizing, developing, and consolidating the political freedom, the institutions, the industry, the labor, the commerce, the finances, and the power of the nation; or, on the other hand, neglecting these things, to pick quarrels and get into wars with foreign powers. A few years of time spent in the first mentioned manner will vastly increase our economic forces and our national power, will give us the results of permanent internal pacification and the vigor of renewed vitality. We will lose nothing that we now have, and will acquire much that we do not now possess. The various diplomatic problems now unsolved will become no more formidable by the postponement for a time of their solution, and questions that are now menacing may become harmless in their character. Those who find fault with our diplomacy because it is not sufficiently "fast" or aggressive to suit their views, will do well to consider these things.

abstract: Gen. GRANT took a ride with Mr. BONNER, who had Peerless in a top wagon for the occasion. They first went to the Bloomingdale road, Mr. BONNER driving. Afterward, Gen. GRANT drove, and finally they went to DUBOIS' private trotting track. Here the gray mare was taken out of the top wagon and hitched up to a skeleton wagon. Mr. BONNER drove her a turn in 1m. 16s., timed by Gen. GRANT. The track was heavy, but the rate good. Gen. GRANT then got in and drove a turn, Mr. BONNER timing it. The mare made a break, but nevertheless covered the ground in 1m. 17 1/2s. No stranger ever drove the gray mare better than Gen. GRANT, and Mr. BONNER thinks him an excellent driver. We understand it was the first time he had ever been in a skeleton wagon, and we  are sure Mr. BONNER ought to know what belongs to the art in respect to a gentleman driving on the road, or on a private course, for time. -- Wilkes' Spirit of the Times.

abstract: The Roman correspondent of the Daily News writes: "Archbishop MANNING has left Rome for England. It is generally believed that the Pope has determined upon creating another archbishop in England, and that Dr. ULLATHORNE, now Bishop of Birmingham, will be the new archbishop, and be made titular primate of the North of England. The two prelates will most likely receive the Cardinal's hat together next Summer, when there is to be an immense assembly of bishops from all parts of the world in Rome."

abstract: Fort Washington, Mrs. Langdon's House; $13,000
snippet: Fort Washington, Mrs. Langdon's House; $13,000
lead_paragraph: FIRE AT FORT WASHINGTON. -- We have learned that the owner of the building burned on old King's Bridge road, Fort Washington, on last Saturday, is Mrs. ELIZABETH LANGDON. Mrs. LANGDON was last on the premises up to about 3:30 o'clock on the afternoon of the day, making preparations for the carpenters and painters, the house requiring certain repairs. On leaving, she secured the doors as usual, bringing the keys away with her. The facts, as ascertained through Fire-Marshal BAKER, are that Mr. TELLPIE, who lives in the adjoining house, on going to his bedroom, discovered smoke therein, and on looking out of his window, saw flames issuing from the roof of his neighbor's house, on the south side. The police, under Capt. WILSON, were at hand almost instantly, and finding the front door securely fastened, broke it open, but found the fire to have extended so rapidly as to preclude all access to the second floor, or to save any of the furniture. Mrs. LANGDON estimates the value of the house at $10,000; insured in the Park and New-Amsterdam offices for $6,000. Her furniture she values at $2,500, and on this property she has an insurance of $3,000 in the Lenox Insurance Company. There is no other theory for the fire save as the work of an incendiary. Mrs. LANGDON had noticed when there last, a window of the laundry to have been pushed up, as if some person had entered or passed out thereby, but attached no great importance to this fact at the time. She also states that she caused a fire to be made in the grate of the dining-room, as the house was damp; but that it was quite low when she left it, and she cannot think it possible that the fire could have its origin in this.

abstract: U.S. vs. Smith. Counterfeit
snippet: U.S. vs. Smith. Counterfeit
lead_paragraph: The United States vs. David Smith. -- This was a motion in arrest of judgment -- The defendant was convicted of passing a counterfeit $50 treasury note. The facts of the case as shown by the testimony were that the defendant who lived in New-York, received the bill from a keeper of a grocery, who told him at the time, that it was a counterfeit; a woman who lived with Smith having asked him for money he told her to go to his trunk and she would find some, and she did find this $50 bill, which she took. The defendant and this woman afterward having come over to Brooklyn to a picnic, she passed the bill supposing it was a good one.

abstract: By the steamship China, which arrived at Halifax last evening, we receive intelligence that the British Government have ordered the unconditional release of Capt. WADDELL and the crew of the rebel pirate Shenandoah, on the ground that there was no legal evidence on which they could be held. In a letter to Earl RUSSELL, Capt. WADDELL endeavors to justify his piratical proceedings by asserting that he could place no reliance on the stories told by American sea Captains, and that as soon as he received information through a British source of the conclusion of the war, he desisted from further acts of warfare, and immediately headed for a neutral port, where the rumors, which he considered doubtful, would be verified. On the 10th inst. the Shenandoah was surrendered to the American Consul at Liverpool, who placed her under the care of a Captain and crew of his own selection, to be sent to this port.

lead_paragraph: The United States vs. George M. Drew. -- This man wes indicted for having in his possession counterfeit fifty cent notes, with intent to pass the same. The proof showed that the accused went into the fancy-store of Mr. McElbiney, in Greenwich-street, and bought a pair of wristlets, for which he offered a fifty cent note, which proved to be bad. Mr. McElhiney told him it was bad, and asked him if he had no good money. Thereupon another man came into the store and said he was a detective policeman, and had been watching Drew, and arrested him for passing counterfeit money. As he was taking him out, Drew threw behind the counter a package of seven counterfeit fifty cent notes, which the alleged detective picked up and gave to Mr. McElhiney. Then they went off together, and entered a liquor-store. Mr. McElhiney's suspicions being excited, he followed them, and getting a policeman, went in and arrested Drew in the liquor-store, the alleged detective not being there. On Drew's person were found three other counterfeits and no good money.

lead_paragraph: The departure of Lieut.-Gen. GRANT for Washington yesterday was a very quiet affair. As was announced in the TIMES, considerable preparations were made by the military to give him a fitting escort on his departure from the city, and the Seventh Regiment was ordered out as such. The original programme looked toward a formal progress down Broadway, from the hotel to the foot of Cortlandt-street, the General to be placed in an open carriage, so that all who wished might see the leader of our victorious armies. The preparations were good -- much better than any previously arranged -- but the weather prevented their fruition.

abstract: the Call for in Virginia
snippet: the Call for in Virginia
lead_paragraph: keeps up a lusty demand for labor. This is a wonderful change from the days when Virginia was wont to make merchandise of her surplus labor, by sending her slaves to the markets of the Cotton States. Virginia finds now that she not only needs all the labor she has in her population of freedmen, but that she requires a large importation to enable her to develop her vast resources. A healthier sign than this could hardly be given. It betokens a vitality in her industrial system which apparently but needed the removal of the curse of slavery to enable her to take the rank among her sister States to which her superabounding natural wealth entitled her. But for slavery it is probable that Virginia to-day would have been the most populous State in the Union. She now invites free labor, and we know of no community where such labor will find better recompense, for the next twenty years at least.

abstract: Heroics About Fenianism
snippet: Heroics About Fenianism
lead_paragraph: the Canadian newspapers to exhibit a little more self-possession. They have conjured up an imaginary enemy, whom they are perpetually challenging to "come on," and they will show him what awful fighters the provincials are. As time passes on, and no enemy makes his appearance, they get fiercer and fiercer, and their heroics rise higher and higher. They talk about the everlasting "Sixtieth Rifles," the Toronto Volunteers, the Loyal Orangemen, and the Montreal Chasseurs; and we should think that the mere display of their fierce, though motley force, would be enough to frighten the Fenians -- if it were possible to do such a thing. We suppose their object in getting up the teapot tempest which now rages is to terrify somebody; but its real effect is to show how absurdly terrified they are themselves.

lead_paragraph: By most readers -- fresh from the influence exercised over them by the spell of the author's genius -- the last work by DICKENS will be considered his best. We fancy, however, that more matured judgment would place Our Mutual Friend much lower in the long list of DICKENS' books, if they were ranked according to merit. It would stand undoubtedly many degrees above (perhaps his worst work) Little Dorritt, but also an equal number below David Copper-field, and the older stories to which he owes his fame. The partiality for an involved plot, combined with an entire absence of the skill to manage and unfold it, though characteristic of DICKENS generally, was perhaps never so conspicuous as in his latest work. The crowd of unnecessary persons brought in, and described with singular elaborateness and detail, and then dismissed or forgotten, was never so much in the reader's way before, and yet, curiously enough, the author speaks in his Preface of the pains employed in devising the story, and the ingenuity shown in conducting it. Of course, in every book that DICKENS writes, there must be many characters and scenes that could originate with no one else -- much rich and fanciful appropriate detail founded on the close observation of nature that no one else could give us, and a hearty sympathy with the right, and hatred and cruelty of oppression. These will all be found in Our Mutual Friend. The portrait gallery that we owe to DICKENS is enlarged by the never-to-be-forgotten pair. Mr. and Mrs. BOFFIN, although the simplicity that distinguishes them is strangely at variance by the author's device, by which they assume fictitious characters and language in a plot, even though its object is a good one. There is no occasion to discuss at length a book now in every one's hands. Were it a total failure, its sale would scarcely be diminished, for it takes a long time for an author like DICKENS to write himself down, and of this we happily see no signs.

abstract: there is an attempt being made in England to get up a popular excursion, on a large scale, "from London to America, with a short tour in the States." Those who took the pains to peruse the speeches recently made by Sir MORTON PETO and others of the English capitalists' party, and who observed the simple wonder expressed by them everywhere at everything they saw, can appreciate the profound ignorance of even the most intelligent classes in England concerning everything in America. These gentlemen had had large amounts of their capital invested in this country for years, had had it invested in the very way which of all others was most likely to make them familiar with our material characteristics and development, and, moreover, had been friendly to us during the war, and therefore all the more likely to be well informed about us; and yet CHRISTOPHER COLUMBUS was not more astonished by what he saw upon the continent of America in 1492 than Sir MORTON PETO and party were at what they saw in 1865.

abstract: Rosaca, new Frigate, Launched at Portsmouth
snippet: Rosaca, new Frigate, Launched at Portsmouth
lead_paragraph: The new frigate Resaca was launched at the Portsmouth Navy-yard on the 18th inst. The christening ceremonies were performed by the Misses COLLINS, nieces of Rear-Admiral BAILEY. The Resaca will receive her machinery at the Washington yard. She will be commanded by Lieut.--Commander Jos. M. BRADFORD, late Flect-Captain of Admiral DAHLGREN'S squadron. Her armament will consist of one 60-pound rifle pivot-gun, six 32-pound broadsides, and three 20-pound bronze rifles. At the conclusion of the launch the guests were hospitably entertained by Admiral BAILEY and his lady, also by Capt. PICKERING, the Executive Officer, Paymaster EMERY, Commander HARRISON, and other officers, at their several quarters. The interesting occasion concluded with an inspection of the yard and its many objects of interest.

lead_paragraph: NIBLO's. -- Mr. FORREST has given "Othello" twice this week. Of his own performance nothing need be said; the public know it well; they know that it has a great many noble points, and a few strongly marked and disagreeable peculiarities. It is enough, however, to say that it is a great representation, worthy alike of the artist and the highly intelligent audiences that gather to listen and applaud. The cast of the piece is open to objection. It does not strike us that Mr. MCCULLOUGH is a good Iago. He did not seem to illustrate the wonderful deception and Mephistophiiian subtlety of the part; he was too plain and open in tone, so much so that one could not imagine that even the free and unsuspicious Moor would not at once see through his very flimsy disguise. Iago is one of the very best acting parts in the English drama; it is reasonably a more effective character than Othello, and a customary interchange of these parts by the greatest of actors has given them coequal position. Mr. MCCULLOUGH was accurate in the text, and most carefully elaborated the traditional points; but the inspiration of superior genius was not there. Mr. BURNETT's Brabantio was indifferently begun but admirably ended, and deserved more applause than the brevity of its stage existence gives room for. Of the Cassio of Mr. COLLIER, we have only to say that while evidently appreciating the needs of the part, he was incautious enough to overact it a little, and render it much too melodramatic; a small fault, but one that should be corrected. Mr. BECKS ought to surrender Roderigo to somebody -- anybody, who can appreciate the difference been a well-bred young gentleman, nursing an improper and hopeless love for one who never could have been approached save with most respectful courtesy, and a dancing-jack of a thing, simpering and fidgeting about the stage like a lunatic. There are many parts that Mr. BECKS can do admirably; but this is not one of them. The Desdemona of Miss AGNES PERRY was a very praiseworthy performance, modestly and delicately rendered throughout, in thorough harmony with the general interpretation. It is not a part in which to portray force; the graces of gentleness and simple trustfulness in conscious virtue are its main features, and these were well illustrated. If this be a fair specimen of her abilities she has a hopeful prospect. Mrs. FARREN was the Emilia, and successfully represented that rather tart and uncomfortable female, justly winning applause in the more emphatic lines. Mr. FORREST will give "Virginius" next, and then repeat "Richelieu."

abstract: Barney W. C. and Fabian, Bonds, $40,000
snippet: Barney W. C. and Fabian, Bonds, $40,000
lead_paragraph: WILLIAM CHASE BARNEY, a Custom-house clerk, and BENTHAN FABIAM, a clerk in the Treasury Department, were taken before Justice DOWLING, on the 6th inst., and required to answer for an alleged forgery of bonds to the amount of $40,000. Eminent counsel, namely: Messrs. JAMES T. BRADY, JOHN SEDGWICK, EDWIN JAMES, R.D. HOLMES and T. DUNPHY, were engaged, and the defence moved off by denying the court's jurisdiction, and claiming that inasmuch as the offence, if any, had been committed against the United States Custom-house, the prisoners ought to be heard before a United States judicial officer. It became manifest at once that the court had a tedious trial in prospect, and hence an order of adjournment was entered, to enable the lawyers to make full preparation. The accused, meantime, were committed to the Tombs. At a subsequent hearing it transpired that RICHARD CHAUNCEY also had been accused of complicity with BARNEY and FABIAN in the alleged forgeries, and another adjournment was ordered, to enable counsel to amend the papers by inserting his name therein. The case was set down for 2 o'clock yesterday afternoon, and it was understood that then the counsel would argue the question of jurisdiction, but when Justice DOWLING took the bench a messenger delivered a note from Mr. JOHN SEDGWICK asking an adjournment, because of his being engaged in the Superior Court; and everybody consenting, His Honor named Tuesday afternoon next, at 2 o'clock, as the time when he would listen to such arguments as counsel might offer. FABIAN and CHAUNCEY were thereupon remanded to the Tombs. BARNEY has given $5,000 bail.

abstract: festive Emperor of Mexico has commenced the erection of a national theatre, and has offered two prizes, of a thousand dollars each, for the best tragedy and the best comedy to be performed within its walls. Competition is of course open to Americans of both sexes, as the Emperor has invited them freely to his dominions, with all the rights and privileges of citizenship. We do not suppose that Gen. MAGRUDER will compete, or Gen. PRICE, or Gov. ALLEN, or Mr. MAURY -- so none of their countrymen on this side of the lines need anticipate foul play in the matter. The scene of both the tragedy and the comedy should be laid in Mexico itself; the time should be recent, and, in fact, in the era of MAXIMILIAN; the incidents should appertain to the history of his reign. The tragedy might open at the moment of the imperial apparition upon Mexican soil, and five acts well filled with bloody circumstance and closing with the death of Liberty, might be effectively wrought up. The comedy might be of a fanciful order, with no scarcity of material. What should be the finale of the play will be apparent a few months hence. Would it not be well to get NAPOLEON III. to write the epilogue?

abstract: Mr. Whittaker, jr., and Mr. McGregor, having a private discussion in the chambers of the Supreme Court, relative to the merits of their respective cases, passed from discussion to high words, and from these to violence, resulting in a blow in the face to Mr. Whittaker, not, however, in the immediate presence of the Court. The latter gentleman, with the marks of the contest still fresh upon him, appealed to the Court for an immediate order committing his opponent for contempt. The Court directed him to prepare the proper papers on which to procure such an order.

abstract: Evening Post Attacking National Credit
snippet: Evening Post Attacking National Credit
lead_paragraph: We suppose the last thing that any patriotic or honorable man should do is to weaken the public faith in the national credit, or the national currency. We do not say that the finances necessarily constitute the weak or the dangerous point in our national future; but if responsible men choose to speak as it our debt were unmanageable, our financial system false, and ultimate repudiation inevitable, they will assuredly in time produce a weak and dangerous condition of that public faith upon which cur stability is founded. There are in finances, as in other matters, a vast number of narrow-minded men, who hold an equally vast number of narrow and divergent theories, and each of whom devotes himself to preaching that if his special scheme be not carried out, everything will go to wreck. They generally begin by showing that things are on the verge of ruin already, and that only this or the other measure, of which they hold the patent, can possibly save the country. They are a dangerous class -- not, perhaps, that the theories of all of them are dangerous, but that they all seem to think it necessary to destroy the public confidence as a preparation for their theories. When such men get into Congress or into print, they are able to unsettle the faith of thousands, even though able to give nothing satisfactory in place of that which they take away. The Evening Post gives place to another of these ideologists, who begins by declaring that a careful study of our financial condition and prospects "will make any one sad," and then goes on:

abstract: Avvee, a Chinaman, Stabbed to Death; Nally, James, Killed with Stone by J. Fa ley
snippet: Avvee, a Chinaman, Stabbed to Death; Nally, James, Killed with Stone by J. Fa ley
lead_paragraph: Yesterday an inquest was held, at the Fourth Precinct Station-house, on the body of JOHN AVVEE, a Chinaman, who died of the wounds inflicted upon him by a knife in the hands of a fellow countryman named ABBOT, as previously reported. In the quarrel which arose between the men, it appears that the deceased wished to fight, but ABBOT refused to settle their difficulty in this manner, sitting down in a chair. Shortly after this AVVEE, the deceased, approached ABBOT from behind, pulling him from his seat, kicking and striking him. ABBOT then seized a large knife, which he found in the room, and stabbed AVVEE three or four times about the chest, side and abdomen. AVVEE was removed to the City Hospital, but died before reaching it. Officer ALLEN, of the Fourth Precinct, arrested ABBOT and locked him up.

abstract: Thomas Lynch, aged eighteen years, was charged with carrying burglar's tools with felonious intent, to commit a robbery. All that was found in his possession at the time of his arrest was a burglar's pick-lock, about seven inches long. The officer discovered it accidentally protruding about three inches out of his vest pocket, and for carrying this after dusk he was tried for a misdemeanor. He said he found it, and not knowing its character, he put it in his pocket. This might have been the case, if other evidence had not been brought forward to destroy this theory of innocence. Henry Back, policeman of the Twenty-first Precinct, said he was met by a woman who keeps a store in Forty-first-street, who told him that a young man had just brought a tub of prime butter that he wished to sell to her at 40 cents a pound. She refused to buy it. Afterward the officer learned that a tub of butter corresponding to the one that had been offered for sale had been stolen from Forty-second-street. The officer on meeting the prisoner arrested him on suspicion, and he was identified, as the youth who had attempted to sell the butter, but the tub could not be found; he knew where he had disposed of it, but it was not his business to tell; he was searched, as is usual in all cases, and this pick-lock was found on him. But for these circumstances, he would not have been convicted. Penitentiary three months.

lead_paragraph: THE STORM IN BROOKLYN. -- The heavy rains yesterday and the night previous caused the flood to rise over the string-pieces of the Atlantic Dock, some 18 inches in height, and causing the involuntary emigration of entire colonies of rats from the storehouses, some thousands of which were drowned. When the tide subsided, the wharves were so thickly strewn with their dead carcasses that it was difficult to walk without treading on them. The occupants of the shanties at Tinkerville had a hard time of it. The tide rose some four feet over the door-siils before daylight, compelling the men to evacuate, while the women and children sought refuge on chairs, tables, boxes, or anything else that would bear them. The tide fell during the forenoon, and left them in a better condition.

abstract: Carey, John J., Jurisdiction in Contempt Case
snippet: Carey, John J., Jurisdiction in Contempt Case
lead_paragraph: In re the Petition of John J. Carey. -- This case brought up the very interesting question of how far one court may interfere with the jurisdiction of another in matters of contempt. The petitioner had purchased the mortgaged premises in a foreclosure suit in the Common Pleas, bidding at the referee's sale $15,600, and depositing, in accordance with the terms of sale, ten per cent., viz., $1,560. Subsequently he objected to completing the sale on various alleged defects of title, but his objections were overruled, and from the order overruling them the petitioner appealed. An order was then procured by the plaintiff in the former suit, on the ground, among others, of collusion between Carey and the defendants, that he pay the balance of his purchase, $14,040, with interest from the 25th of September, to the referee. This was afterward modified so far as to allow him to pay the money into court. Failing to comply with either of these orders, the Court of Common Pleas issued an attachment, and, after the usual proceedings by interrogatory, the petitioner, Carey, was committed to close confinement until he should comply with the orders, and pay $30 as costs. Carey then procured from the Supreme Court a habeas corpus, to which the Sheriff made return that he held the relator by virtue of the commitment of the Court of Common Pleas, which he annexed. The relator then asked that a writ of certiorari be issued to the Court of Common Pleas to compel a return from that court of all their proceedings on which the commitment for contempt was based.

abstract: ringing the alarm bells for fires, recently put into operation by the Board of Fire Commissioners, finds favor with all experienced and candid firemen. The combinations in numbering the sixty-three alarm stations are so simple, and devoid of complication that the signals can be easily understood by anybody. During the few days that the telegraph alarm has been in operation, very little confusion or delay has been experienced. As the signal gives the exact neighborhood of the fire the companies property liable for duty proceed at once to the scene. As soon as the department is perfectly drilled into running to fires by the telegraph, bell-ringing will cease, and the wires will be exclusively relied on.

abstract: A mass meeting of the Tobacco trade of the United States was held yesterday at the Cooper Institute for the purpose of organizing a movement looking toward removing the tax on manufactured tobacco and placing it entirely on the leaf, as it leaves the hands of the grower.
lead_paragraph: A mass meeting of the Tobacco trade of the United States was held yesterday at the Cooper Institute for the purpose of organizing a movement looking toward removing the tax on manufactured tobacco and placing it entirely on the leaf, as it leaves the hands of the grower. The large manufacturers and regular dealers have suffered immensely by the operations of irresponsible parties who manufacture cigars by stealth, and so avoid the heavy tax imposed upon such goods. In act they assert that the present condition of the cigar and tobacco trade is such as to demand the united and immediate efforts of all to save it from utter ruin. Though heretofore unsuccessful in getting the tax transferred to the leaf, it is believed there is yet an opportunity for bringing about the change desired, and for this purpose the meeting was held, with the intention of presenting their views to the United States Revenue Commission, now in session, protesting against the present ruinous system of taxation, and renewing their application to Congresa for a transfer of the tax from the manufactures to the leaf.

abstract: CONCERT OF MR. F. JEHIN PRUME.--The expectations which the public had of an artist who bears a name so well known and esteemed as that of PRUME, attracted a large audience to Irving Hall, on Saturday last, and we are happy to state that these expectations were realized to a great extent.
lead_paragraph: CONCERT OF MR. F. JEHIN PRUME. -- The expectations which the public had of an artist who bears a name so well known and esteemed as that of PRUME, attracted a large audience to Irving Hall, on Saturday last, and we are happy to state that these expectations were realized to a great extent. Mr. PRUME is a gentleman who evidently has appeared frequently in the concert-room, and is no novice in his art. His style is eminently French, and of the same school which was best represented by BAZZINI, OLE BULL, BERIOT, PRUME, and which disappears more and more since JOACHIM, LAUB, SINGER, and other classical German players, have returned to the old masters. We therefore must judge Mr. PRUME exclusively from the standing-point of a salon-player; and in this respect he is a very talented and admirable artist. His playing is technically marvelous, and there are no difficulties which Mr. PRUME does not overcome with the greatest ease. His "staccato" is distinct and graceful, his flageolet pure and sympathetic; he plays the chromatic scale perfect, and he renders every "fioritura" and "cadenza" exceedingly well. His bowing also is very good, although not free from coquetry. If the foregoing qualifications alone would suffice to constitute the claim of a modern violinist to the name of a first-class artist, we should not hesitate to call Mr. PRUME so. But Mr. PRUME lacks some essential qualities for such a name. His tone is very small, and he almost incessantly whines whenever he has to play portamento or rostenuto. He phrases well enough, but he never gives the last note of a phrase its full value, but removes his bow with a disagreeable suddenness. He furthermore lacks quietude, and works painfully with his entire body during every variation, as if he wanted to show how difficult it was to get a certain figure out of the instrument. He also very often corrects the composer's work with an amiable "insouciance," which was especially disagreeable in his rendition of ERNST's "Elegy," a piece seldom heard to greater disadvantage. As a result of Mr. PRUME's playing on Saturday last, we have to say that he has nothing more to learn, but a great deal to unlearn, and this he will undoubtedly do, as he is a young gentleman yet. A number of well-meaning, but highly injudicious friends, interrupted every piece by their extremely offensive applause, and evidently embarrassed ths artist. Of the artists assisting Mr. PRUME we mention Mr. MILLS, who played superbly as ever, and Miss ZELDA HARRISON, a very premising young mezzosoprano, who was exceedingly well received.

abstract: THE SINGS COUNTY CANVASSERS. -- The County Canvassers met at 10:30 o'clock yesterday morning, and continued in session until about 3 o'clock, during which time they canvassed the Fifteenth, Sixteenth, and Seventeenth Wards, leaving two city wards and five country towns still to dispose of. The probabilities are that the entire canvass will be completed this week. The board adjourned until this afternoon, at 1:30 o'clock. The City Canvassers will meet this evening, when the vote on the city ticket will probably be declared.

abstract: An inquest was hold yesterday by Coroner COLLIN, at the Lunatic Asylum, Blackwell's Island, on the body of ROBERT HENSCHER, a lunatic, who took away his own life, by hanging himself from the grating above the door of his cell, by his pocket-handkerchief. Life was quite extinct when the suspended body was discovered. The deceased had been a clerk, but losing his situation, and becoming consequently embarassed, his unhappy position so [???] upon his mind as to produce the temporary insanity terminating so fatally. He was taken into the asylum on the 12th inst. Mr. HENSCHER was a native of Scotland, and 57 years of age.

abstract: Carr, >amp;c., vs. Kendall; Napoleon Oil Case
snippet: Carr, >amp;c., vs. Kendall; Napoleon Oil Case
lead_paragraph: Charles H. Carr and others vs. Henry R. Kendall and others. -- This action was brought to recover deposits made with the defendants as margin on the loan of 500 shares of oil stock in the Napoleon Oil Company. The plaintiffs claimed that the Napoleon Oil stock, with $1,500,000 in 300,000 shares, was founded on a portion of the property of the Live Yankee Company, whose capital stock of $250,000 was quoted at 5 cents a share, and was originally worthless. That a corner was arranged by the defendants procuring persons to direct brokers to sell while they and their confederates kept control of the whole stock. That the stock was sold by the brokers, among whom were the plaintiffs, at $2 a share, and then in order to deliver it, at the suggestion of other confederates, they borrowed it from the defendants, making the customary marginal deposits; that from time to time sham sales were made by the confederates, at advancing prices, and more margin demanded, until the plaintiffs had deposited nearly $9,000; that afterward a pretended purchase was made at $32 per share, placing the plaintiffs in debt to the defendants; that an investigation was made by the Board of Petroleum Brokers, resulting in the expulson of Kendall & Co. from the board and the striking of the stock off the list. The plaintiffs in this action demand back their margin with interest.

abstract: Reimler vs. Jewett. Accommodation Note
snippet: Reimler vs. Jewett. Accommodation Note
lead_paragraph: Frederick W. Reimler vs. James C. Jewett, et al. -- This was an action on a promissory note made by the firm of James C. Jewett & Co., to the order of and and indorsed by that firm, to the plaintiff. Two of the defendants -- Jewett and Crockett -- set up defence, denying that the other defendant, Scheamoul, was a partner; also alleging that the note was made for the accommodation of plaintiff, and for a joint transaction, not yet terminated, in shipping preserves to Matamoras, Mexico. The other defendant, Scheamoul, answered separately, denying all the allegations in plaintiff's complaint.

The fire was first discovered by Officer MYERS, of the Eleventh Precinct, who, seeing the flames issue from the premises, gave the alarm. abstract: Brett et als. vs. Milledge et als.--The plaintiffs, shipping merchants in this city, sue for freight on a charter party to bring coal from Cape Breton Island at $6 per ton, per brig Orion, to this city, and also for extra pilotage. The defendants admit the plaintiffs'...
lead_paragraph: Brett et als. vs. Milledge et als. -- The plaintiffs, shipping merchants in this city, sue for freight on a charter party to bring coal from Cape Breton Island at $6 per ton, per brig Orion, to this city, and also for extra pilotage. The defendants admit the plaintiffs' claim, but counterclaimed $1,000 for damages, by reason of unreasonable delay in leaving New-York and deviations on the passage, lengthening the voyage and delaying the delivery of the coal. The defendants claim that through this they lost various contracts, the cargo being intended as a sample. It was shown that the vessel left New-York as soon as the weather was fit for putting to sea, and that the deviations were under stress of weather; and, further, that the coal sold at the full contract and highest market price.

abstract: A convention of tobacco manufacturers was held yesterday at the Cooper Institute, under the auspices of the National Tobacconists' Association. The objects of the meeting was to resolve upon a proper course of action in appealing to Congress to remove the existing tax upon manufactured tobacco and place it upon the leaf, as dishonest manufacturers were ruining honest trade by defrauding the revenue. The convention was earnest in tone, and was addressed by some of the leading men in the trade.

abstract: Objection to the President's Plan
snippet: Objection to the President's Plan
lead_paragraph: If it be true that "where there is a will there is a way," the prime question is whether there is a will. It is the having no will to do a thing that makes what is called an "impracticable," and to be that is to be without any right to moral influence. There are men who have no will that the South should soon be restored. They are full of objections against the President's plan, which spring not so much from opposition to the particular mode of restoration, as to the restoration itself. They are shut up to the "foregone conclusion" that the South ought not, for an indefinite period hence, to enjoy again its full constitutional powers. In many cases, this comes from an honest belief that the Southern whites will not, for years, be fit to be trusted with any power over the race they have so lately held in slavery. In many other cases, it is but the offspring of that old vindictive feeling of the human heart which delights in keeping down a prostrate enemy. In other cases still, it proceeds from a dread of the revived political power of the South, as a mischievous element in the future politics of the country. But however various the motives, the result is the same -- a policy of obstruction and procrastination. The only study of these people is how not to do it. Objections against any plan which proceed from such a condition of mind are but mere pretexts, and have no title to consideration.

abstract: THE PRICE OF GOAL FALLING. -- The combination among dealers to keep up the price of coal appears to have been broken. At the sale of Scranton coal yesterday, grate coal fell from $10 87 to $8 87 per ton, while other descriptions suffered a decline in price from $1 to $1 50. It was observed that buyers were particularly shy at the sale, and that only small parcels were bought. An impression now prevails that a further decline will take place at the next public sale.

abstract: of laborers, white and yellow, or European and Chinese, engaged in constructing the Western Division of the Pacific Railroad over the Sierra Nevada Mountains. The white laborers are paid thirty dollars a month with board, and the yellow laborers thirty-one dollars a month without board. This is an allowance to the latter class of just one dollar a month for their board. It is not a large sum, but, we have no doubt, with the economical habits of the Chinese, it goes a long way toward their sustenance. Rice is cheap, and rats, we have no doubt, are plenty; and from the fibre and farinacious substance in these twain, the Chinaman manages to derive flesh and bones of sufficient strength to undergo the heaviest labors. We do not wish to commend their customs or their economies to our own people; but in these days of high prices and hard living, our nabobs might learn from them a lesson in the reduction of expenses.

abstract: Last evening:, SPAULDING's Billiard Hall, in Court-street, South Brooklyn, was crowded by a highly respectable assemblage of the admirers of the game, who were collected together to witness a trial of skill between Messrs. KAVANAGH end HUMPHREY, in a match of 500 points up, at caroms. KAVANAGH, together with Capt. BOYLE, Mr. EATON, the champion of California, and Mr. HUMPHREY, the noted amateur player, arrived at the hall at 8 P.M., and after the seats were arranged, &c., they began play. HUMPHREY had rather the best of the game at the beginning, he opening with a fine run of 54, and following it up with a beauty of 164, the best of the match. KAVANAGH, however, by some fine play, including pretty runs of 89, 56 and 107, finally came in the victor by a score of 500 to 392, his average being 21. HUMPHREY's was 17. Afterwards Messrs. HUMPHREY and EATON played. The following is the score of the principal match:

abstract: Palmer vs. Terry. -- This was an appeal from an order denying a motion to vacate an order of publication. The original order was granted on the ground that the defendant had property within this State. On the motion to vacate, contradictory affidavits were presented as to this fact, and the court below refused to vacate the order. On the appeal the General Term refused to hear the motion, holding that it could not review in this way the decision of the court below.

abstract: On the morning of the 28th of August last a robbery was discovered to have taken place in the night time on board the steamer Edinburgh, of the Inman line, then lying at Pier No. 45 North River.
lead_paragraph: On the morning of the 28th of August last a robbery was discovered to have taken place in the night time on board the steamer Edinburgh, of the Inman line, then lying at Pier No. 45 North River. A hatchway had been broken open and five pieces of silk, valued at $800 in gold, extracted from a case of goods in the hold. Unable at the time to obtain a clue to the offenders, the case was put into the hands of Detective Officers EUSTACE and FARLEY, who entered the court yesterday morning, having in custody the persons of THOMAS WHITSEY and WILLIAM COOPER, the former having confessed to a shore in the theft, and the latter to his knowledge of it THOMAS F. RASKELL, Captain of the steamer, testified to the abstraction of the property, and to the confession made him by WHITSEY, that he had taken one piece of the silk. WILLIAM COOPER's evidence went to show that on the day above-named WHITSEY came to him in the Quartermaster's office with a piece of silk, which he asked him to wrap around his (WHITSEY's) walst, which he did. He noticed that the silk had a ticket upon it, on which was marked "75 yards," and he thought there were about so many yards in it. WHITSEY, on his voluntary statement, said that he did not take the silk himself from the case, but that the boatswain gave him drink not to tell that he and two others had stolen the five pieces. The piece he took from the boatswain he afterward flung into the river.

abstract: The Quebec Gazette of Saturday contains a militia general order, calling out nine volunteer companies for such period as the Governor deems necessary. One company is to be taken from each of the...
lead_paragraph: The Quebec Gazette of Saturday contains a militia general order, calling out nine volunteer companies for such period as the Governor deems necessary. One company is to be taken from each of the following places: Quebec, Montreal, Ottawa, Morrisburgh, Toronto, Port Hope, London, Hamilton and Woodstock. The pay of the officers per day will be as follows: Lieutenant-Colonels, $4 80; Majors, $3 90; Paymasters, $3 05; Captains, $2 83; Lieutenants, $1 58; Ensigns, $1 28. The pay of the non-commissioned officers and privates will be: Sergeant-Majors, 50 cents; Sergeants, 35 cents; Corporals, 30 cents; privates, 25 cents. This is, in every case, in addition to the rations. There are some complaints that 25 cents per day is too small remuneration for the privates. It is, however, about as much as the British soldiers get. In some, at least, of the towns which are sending companies, no difficulty has been experienced in filling up the companies at that rate of pay. If the country was ever called upon to put a large force in the field, the tax-payers would find the 25 cents per diem a heavy enough burden.

abstract: The Montreal Gazette says that militia of that city is to be recruited to the full strength of the battalions. The English Workingmen's Benefit Society purpose organizing themselves into two strong companies. It is also purposed to organize an engineer battalion, the nucleus of which will be the two fine companies now commanded by Capts. FORSYTH and KENNEDY, and the other companies of which will be raised from the Grand Trunk workmen.
lead_paragraph: The Montreal Gazette says that militia of that city is to be recruited to the full strength of the battalions. The English Workingmen's Benefit Society purpose organizing themselves into two strong companies. It is also purposed to organize an engineer battalion, the nucleus of which will be the two fine companies now commanded by Capts. FORSYTH and KENNEDY, and the other companies of which will be raised from the Grand Trunk workmen. Mr. BRYDGES has taken the matter in hand, and some of the finest "bone and sinew" in the Province will probably soon be added to the effective strength of the militia garrison. Col. COURSOL has been requested by the department to resume the command of the Chasseurs Canadiens. This revival is mainly duo to the presence of the Adjutant-General and his effective staff, whose office by right should be permanently established here -- the largest militia centre in the Province We may add that, by way of enabling the volunteers to get their "prentice hands " in, the sentry is made to pace his lonely rounds at the different armories every night.

abstract: on Pres. Johnson's Policy
snippet: on Pres. Johnson's Policy
lead_paragraph: Last evening, a meeting was held at the Church of the Puritans, in Union-square, for public discussion on the "responsibility, power and duty of Congress in the matter of justice to the rebel States and our colored citizens." The meeting was very slimly attended, and there were some signs of an adjournment. Dr. CHEEVER, however, thought that there were enough present to discuss the questions which are now before the people. He said that the crisis had been before the country for the last six months; and we have seen, with regret, a course pursued by the Executive of the government in relation to the reconstruction of the South, without waiting for the assembling of Congress to decide upon the proper course to be pursued toward the rebel States. We see our Chief Magistrate taking the power into his own hands, when he should have waited until Congress had assembled, to submit the question to that legislative and only proper body.

abstract: John T. McMahon, a tall, stalwart Irishman, aged about 20, respectably dressed, appeared to answer the charge of an unprovoked assault on Mr. Joseph Shadock, who is in the employ of the American Watch Company.
lead_paragraph: John T. McMahon, a tall, stalwart Irishman, aged about 20, respectably dressed, appeared to answer the charge of an unprovoked assault on Mr. Joseph Shadock, who is in the employ of the American Watch Company. Complainant stated that he lived at No. 5 Leroy-street. An evening or two ago he entered a saloon at the foot of Fulton-street, with two friends, to have a drink before parting. While standing at the counter, prisoner got into on altercation with the barkeeper, and swore by the powers that he was a Fenian. Complainant paid very little attention to him, and was standing quietly talking with his friends, when McMahon suddenly turned round, came up in front of him and gave him a sharp poke in the side with his finger, accompanied with the query, "You are a Fenian, ain't you?" Mr. Shaddock said, "No, Sir, I ain't a Fenian." "I am," said McMahon; and as he made this declaration, he followed it up with a very brutal assault on complainant, who was no match for prisoner in a physical point of view, even if he had been inclined to fight.

abstract: Groom vs. Archer; Contract of Sale
snippet: Groom vs. Archer; Contract of Sale
lead_paragraph: Groom Brothers & Co. vs. Archer & Brothers. -- This cause was one brought to recover a difference on a sale of teas. The plaintiffs' counsel, Mr. Dean, opened the case, and introduced testimony which tended to show that some negotiations had been had prior to the 6th day of April, 1864, relative to a sale by the defendants -- a respectable grocers' house in this city -- to the plaintiffs -- who were also respectable grocers -- of one hundred half chests of Oolong tea, in English order, of the value of about $4,300. The terms of sale were to be satisfactory paper at four months, which would sell in Wall-street, without recourse, at 7 per cent. per annum off, or cash, less 2 1/3 per cent. off. The sale was conducted through the intervention of one Wells, a tea-broker, and his clerk, a Mr. Love. The plaintiffs claimed the sale was absolute. The defendants insisted that the contract was never consummated, because the paper of the plaintiffs offered for the teas was not the class of paper they had given the broker authority to take. From the broker's testimony, on the direct examination, it would seem that he understood that the contract was entered into on the 6th of April, and subsequently, on the 9th, the defendants returned him the sale note, and insisted on the cash, and he went over and saw Mr. Washington Archer, who spoke as if it would be all right, but that he would have to see the senior partner of the concern.
