abstract: sirable article in a household is a good sewing-machine. The Wheeler & Wilson is undoubtedly the best, as it is the most popular for family use, and every woman should possess one of these magical agents in the execution of the most tedious and wearisome part of her daily work. It will relieve wives and mothers of the burden of their lives; it will provide them with a wonderfully neat, rapid, obliging and faithful seamstress, who will require neither food nor wages, and execute her work a thousand times better and with more exactness than could be done by the most skillful hands. Before the magic of her fingers, little shirts, aprons, dresses, drawers, sacks and petticoats will disappear like dew before the morning sun, and the time that was once devoted to a slow and wearisome effort to reduce the pile upon the work basket, may be spent in reading or visiting, in gardening, or in teaching the children from books and works of nature, those lessons which are invested with a double charm from the lips of a tender mother. The music of a bright Wheeler & Wilson's sewing machine, telliing in its own silvery, bird-like tones of work accomplished, of order and neatness preserved, of nervous headache saved, of pleasures to be enjoyed, of happiness in prospect, is sweeter by far than the music of a grand piano. -- Demorest's Monthly.

abstract: The Union Mayoralty Convention meets this evening. We presume they intend to nominate Union candidates for Mayor and Corporation Counsel, in the belief that they will be supported by the great body of the Union party, and in the hope that, thus supported, by aid of the divisions among the Democrats, their candidate for Mayor may be elected. How well or how ill founded these expectations may be, we do not care to discuss at present.

lead_paragraph: No case before our courts for many years has attracted greater attention than that of STRONG against STRONG, which was opened yesterday before Judge GARVIN, of the Superior Court. Mr. PETER R. STRONG, the plaintiff, is a well-known lawyer of this city, and his wife, MARY E. STRONG, the defendant, is a daughter of Mr. JOHN AUSTIN STEVENS, a prominent banker, also of this city. The social relations and position ofthe parties, and the singular charges and countercharges published in the newspapers have attached to the case a wide-spread interest in private and professional circles. The court-room was densely packed yesterday morning with the friends of both parties, and many members of the bar.

abstract: tem of having schools for specific professional training is becoming more and more extended every year in new directions. In addition to the general development secured by the courses of study followed at colleges and academies, special schools for legal, medical, theological, military and naval training, have long been felt to be indispensable. And it is not at all strange that the same principle should be applied to preparation for the various departments of business. While it is doubtless true that the most effective training is that secured by practical experience, there are certain elements in every branch of business-life that can best be learned by systematic study under the direction of proper teachers. Hence it is that commercial schools have so rapidly increased and enlarged the sphere of their operations within the last few years. They now extend over the whole country and embrace instruction in nearly every department of active business life. Their results cannot fail to be beneficially felt upon the rising generation of business men.

abstract: SALE OF GOVERNMENT PROPERTY.--A large quantity of government property was sold at auction yesterday by Messrs. WILMERDINGS  MOUNT. The attendance at the sale was large but the prices realized were considered low.
lead_paragraph: SALE OF GOVERNMENT PROPERTY. -- A large quantity of government property was sold at auction yesterday by Messrs. WILMERDINGS & MOUNT. The attendance at the sale was large but the prices realized were considered low. The following is a list of the principal articles disposed of and the prices obtained: 800 barrels Oswego corn-starch, 9 cents; 96 cases Oswego corn-starch, 8 1/2 cents: 3,000 pounds condensed eggs, 13 1/2@14 cents; 800 cases condensed milk, 27 cents per pound; 250 cases army beef stock, 15 cents per pound; 393 pounds, with duplicates, of PRESTON's cocoa packages, 27 cents; 300 hair pillows, damaged, 50 cents each; 375 straw mattresses, 80 cents each; 29 lots more at same price; 900 pounds rags, 12 1/2 cents per pound; 1,000 oakum comacks, 10 1/4 cents; 1,300 gray blankets, at $5 10@$5 25; 12,746 white blankets, at $6@$6 30; an immense quantity of linen bed sacking and coverlets, at 28@40 cents; 1,434 yards of mosquito-netting sold at 10 cents; a great quantity of linen sheeting, 34 inches wide, was purchased at 55@63 cents per yard. The sale yielded about one quarter of a million of dollars.

abstract: Blissville, L. I., Cozens' Oil Factory--$50,000
snippet: Blissville, L. I., Cozens' Oil Factory--$50,000
lead_paragraph: DESTRUCTIVE FIRE AT BLISSVILLE, L.I. -- LOSS $50,000 -- THREE MEN INJURED. -- A fire of considerable magnitude took place at Blissville, Queens County, yesterday, involving a heavy loss of property, and throwing out of employment some two or three hundred men. About 11 o'clock, as some of the workmen employed in COZZENS & CO.'s kerosene oil factory were engaged in emptying some acids into the agitator, in the purifying house connected with the works, a volume of flame suddenly ascended, caused, it is believed, by impure chemicals, and in a few minutes, the whole building was filled with the roaring element. The terrified men stampeded in every direction, seeking for safety, and in a very few minutes a terrific volume of flame burst through the roof, rising to an altitude of at least three hundred feet, and measuring probably sixty feet in circumference. The dense smoke from the burning building obscured the atmosphere for miles around. Two hose companies and a truck from the Eastern District visited the scene of the fire, and were instrumental in saving all the buildings attached to the immense works, except that in which the fire broke out, which was entirely destroyed. By 2 1/2 o'clock the flames subsided. During the progress of the fire three of the men employed in the works were somewhat injured -- two by falling from a ladder and one by burns. The loss of oil is estimated at the value of $40,000, and the destruction of the building will involve a loss of about $10,000, including the machinery. There was no insurance. These oil works are probably the oldest in the country, and were originally erected for the manufacture of coal oil. They are owned by the brothers COZZENS, whose place of business is in Pearl-street, New-York.

abstract: Shenandoah, the, and the British Government
snippet: Shenandoah, the, and the British Government
lead_paragraph: The discharge of Capt. WADDELL and his crew by the British authorities was unconditional, and not restricted by parole as first reported. We should not be too quick in construing this to be an unfriendly act of the new Cabinet. The fact that our Minister did not ask the detention of any one connected with the ship is an indication that in his judgment no such claim could be sustained. In our present limited knowledge of the facts, it is our business to assume that he refrained from acting for good reasons. We cannot consistently blame the British Government for failing to make an extradition which was never demanded.

abstract: There were no convictions in the Court of General Sessions yesterday, and only two cases were tried. JOHN FOUNTAIN, a colored individual, accused of stealing a quantity of clothing from a lady residing at No. 59 Thompson-street, was acquitted, owing to the failure of proof.
lead_paragraph: There were no convictions in the Court of General Sessions yesterday, and only two cases were tried. JOHN FOUNTAIN, a colored individual, accused of stealing a quantity of clothing from a lady residing at No. 59 Thompson-street, was acquitted, owing to the failure of proof. The prosecution being compelled to rely on the uncorroborated evidence of an accomplice of the prisoner, the jury declined to take the responsibility of convicting him. JOSEPH POOL was tried upon indictment which charged him with stealing $85 from the pocket of one THOMAS BRADY, while BRADY was indulging in the luxury of a nap in the Grand-street ferry-house. The evidence in this case was also insufficient, and the accused was acquitted. The only plea taken was in the case of JAMES CUMMISKI, who pleaded to an assault with a dangerous weapon, and was remanded for sentence.

abstract: establishment, corner of Broadway and Twenty-second-street, are the famous Sewing-Machine Rooms, where the Wheeler & Wilson and Howe Sewing-Machines can be rented or purchased upon terms within easy reach of all -- payments by those whose circumstances require it being made in installments. This is a generous and worthy enterprise, as it enables many who, being poor, yet honest and respectable, to purchase a good Sewing-Machine, and have them kept in order by machinists of acknowledged skill, without charge. In connection with this praiseworthy institution, Mr. ELLIS, with characteristic energy and a desire to meet the wants of every class, has opened, at No. 896 Broadway, a bureau far family sewing. Ladies who have any sewing, or who are about to travel, can have their wardrobes completed in the shortest possible time, and in a style highly creditable to the manager. This bureau is under the immediate charge of a graduate from Mr. ELLIS' principal establishment. The rooms at the corner of Twenty-second-street being centrally located, should be more extensively patronized by cash purchasers, who may thus assist the working classes benefactor in widening the sphere of usefulness so heartily commenced. The machines kept on hand are precisely the same as those at the down-town stores, and are sold at the same prices. Mr. ELLIS' establishment -- a noble one -- deserves the hearty support of an appreciating public. -- Journal & Advocate.

abstract: An inquest was held yesterday morning by Coroner WILDEY, on the body of MARTHA THOMAS, a little girl aged 13 years, who was so severely burned on Tuesday evening last, by the explosion of a kerosene lamp, which she was trying to light, that death was the result. A younger sister was also burned, but slightly, at the same time, and some of the furniture in the room set on fire. The flames were speedily extinguished by persons who rushed in from the street.

abstract: A WOMAN ROBBED IN THE STREET.--Yesterday afternoon as Mrs. CHARLOTTE BLAKE, residing in Bergen, was passing through the tunnel under the New-Jersey Railroad, at Brunswick-street, Jersey City, she was approached, as is alleged, by a young man named WM. ERWIN, who snatched a pocket-book from her hand and ran into a building near by. Soon after, ERWIN came out into the street again, and was arrested by Officer GREADY.
lead_paragraph: A WOMAN ROBBED IN THE STREET. -- Yesterday afternoon as Mrs. CHARLOTTE BLAKE, residing in Bergen, was passing through the tunnel under the New-Jersey Railroad, at Brunswick-street, Jersey City, she was approached, as is alleged, by a young man named WM. ERWIN, who snatched a pocket-book from her hand and ran into a building near by. Soon after, ERWIN came out into the street again, and was arrested by Officer GREADY. A man named PATRICK attempted to arrest the prisoner just before the officer came up, and was badly beaten. The pocket-book was found in the street, where the accused was seen to throw it. ERWIN has served two years in the State Prison for robbing a soldier in Exchange-place.

abstract: The storm which commenced on Tuesday morning and continued throughout Wednesday, may be said to have fairly spent itself. The heavy northeast gale which blew during the whole of Tuesday calmed down somewhat toward the evening, the wind getting round more to the northward. During Wednesday and yesterday, however, the weather continued "dirty" as a sailor would say, and it is likely that disasters occurred at sea, the news of which has not yet come to hand. Of those which occurred in the immediate vicinity we hear that the pilot-boat Hornet, No 2, went ashore on City Island and filled. Her crew escaped. An unknown schooner went ashore on Hart's Island. Another was found floating bottom upwards in the Sound. The ship Washington, of New-York, while passing through Buttermilk Channel on Wednesday morning struck a sunken wreck and went down. Her crew escaped. The brig Eurus, from St. John's, N.B., with a cargo of lumber, while coming through Hell Gate, struck the Middle Channel Beef and filled in half an hour. The schooner McMurray was considerably damaged while lying at Willetts' Point. There were no arrivals from Sandy Hook on Tuesday, the inward-bound vessels preferring to ride out the storm in the lower bay. The steamships Baltic, Mississippi and Anna Maria left the city and anchored at Quarantine, their Captains considering them safer there than in the more crowded portion of the harbor.

abstract: A dispatch from San Francisco says that the State has suffered excessively during the past week from a severe rain-storm. Communication with the interior, except by water and telegraph, is cut off. The Central Pacific Railroad has suffered severely by the caving in of embankments.
lead_paragraph: A dispatch from San Francisco says that the State has suffered excessively during the past week from a severe rain-storm. Communication with the interior, except by water and telegraph, is cut off. The Central Pacific Railroad has suffered severely by the caving in of embankments. The mining districts have received considerable damage by the washing away of dams, flumes, wheels and bridges. Much of the country bordering on the Sacramento and Feather Rivers is flooded.

abstract: see it stated that the Missouri Legislature has under consideration a bill to prevent the city railroad companies from carrying more than twenty-five persons in each car. This would be a desirable reform in New-York. But we do not see how it is at all possible of achievement. The Third-avenue Company, we are assured, now run as many cars during the daytime as the road can carry. Yet these cars have often to take loads of fifty and sixty passengers, to accommodate the immense travel over this great central thoroughfare. What we want is more competition -- one or more through lines, which shall meet the wants of the large suburban population that do business in the city, and rush into the cars in such multitudes during the opening and closing hours of the day. Such lines, however, it is clear, must either be built underground, or over a viaduct sufficiently elevated not to incommode the street traffic. It is coming fast to the point when such an enenterprise will be so loudly demanded that our capitalists will have to set about it. It is bad enough to be jammed into ill-ventilated cars, for a slow ride of five or six miles; but it would be much worse were the car drivers to refuse to take passengers after all the seats are full.

abstract: Mayor N. Y. vs. 3d-av. Railroad; License on Cars
snippet: Mayor N. Y. vs. 3d-av. Railroad; License on Cars
lead_paragraph: A suit has been pending in the Court of Appeals for several years, brought by the Corporation of this city against the Third-avenue Railroad Company, for the recovery of license fees and penalties. The city endeavored to collect from the company the sum of $50 a year as the license fee for each car, which amount the company refused to pay. Other suits were brought at about the same time against the Second-avenue Railroad Company. These two companies, it appears, made their agreements with the Corporation before the ordinance providing for a $50 license fee was adopted, and they therefore resisted the collection of the fee on the ground that their agreement with the Corporation absolved them from its payment.

abstract: The, and the Union Party; National Intelligencer; National Intelligencer Promoting Discord Among the Administration Party
snippet: The, and the Union Party; National Intelligencer; National Intelligencer Promoting Discord Among the Administration Party
lead_paragraph: The National Intelligencer lends its powerful aid to the promotion of that division in the ranks of the administration party from which its enemies hope so much. It makes the recent speech of Mr. COLFAX the occasion for remarking that "the time has come to throw away disguises" and for demanding that "gentlemen range themselves fairly and squarely under their banners." The Intelligencer assumes that there is such a difference, not to say hostility, of sentiment in the Union party, as renders this division into hostile factions expedient and necessary.

abstract: On the complaint of ELIZABETH FLEMMING, of No. 11 Carroll-place, a man named HARRY CLARKE was arrested yesterday, charged with having stolen a trunk containing wearing apparel valued at $210, under the following circumstances: It appears that Mrs. FLEMMING was moving on the 18th inst. to her present residence, and employed a lad named MCKINNY to carry a trunk there for her. MCKINNY got the assistance of another boy and proceeded toward the place as instructed. Losing his way, however, he sought information from two men he met on the corner of Laurens and Bleecker streets, and in reply they told him to stay there, and probably the woman (Mrs. FLEMMING) would join him. Waiting there a short time, the prisoner, HARRY CLARKE, came forward and told him to go to his house in Thompson-street for another trunk, he remaining with this one till he returned. On going to Thompson-street to the number named, he was told there was no trunk there, and on his return to the place he had left CLARKE, found that he and the trunk had both disappeared. Searching for her property, Mrs. FLEMMING met a man named BARNEY AARON, who told her that he thought he knew where the trunk was, and that it might be had from CLARKE, in whose possession it then was, for $30. She gave the $30 to AARON, who procured her the trunk and its contents. She then made the complaint leading to the arrest of the prisoner. HARRY CLARKE, who is 31 years of age, and a native of Ireland, residing at No. 169 Laurens-street, where he kept a liquor-store, stated in his defence that a man left the trunk in his place for BARNEY AARON, and that AARON came there about four hours after and took it away. The prisoner was committed without bail.

abstract: -- We are always prepared to receive news from Texas of a more or less warlike character, however profound may be the reign of peace elsewhere on the continent. The latest bulletin is from Houston, under date of the 10th inst, and it positively announces that orders have been received from Washington not to muster out any more troops. This negative way of laying a belligerent notice before the world is a masterpiece of newspaper skill. There is so much left for the imagination to fill up -- armies marching into Mexico in terrible array, and Western Europe challenged to dispute with us the right and title to each particular State and Province from Cape Breton to Yucatan! A little more respecting that terrible siege of Matamoras will now be in order.

abstract: Gov. Parsons' Message; And the New Congress
snippet: Gov. Parsons' Message; And the New Congress
lead_paragraph: The President is required by the constitution to give to Congress "information of the state of the Union, and recommend to their consideration such measures as he shall judge necessary and expedient." This duty has never been so momentous as it will be on the occasion of the opening of the new Congress, now near at hand. As a consequence of rebellion, a part of the Union is in the most abnormal relation to the Federal Government. It is under a military rule, mild, to be sure, in its administration yet utterly at variance with every principle of our republican system. The great problem is how to terminate this, and revive the regular operation of the constitution consistently with future security, and with the obligations devolved by the war. It is the official duty of the President to gather all the data that bear upon this problem, and to work out the best conclusions he can in regard to it. This he has done, and the result will be seen in the information and recommendations he will submit to Congress in his coming message.

lead_paragraph: William Overton, Jr., who had pleaded guilty to a charge of making a plate for counterfeiting twenty-five cent stamps, was brought up for sentence. The Judge, after remarking to Overton that his crime was one which would probably warrant the extreme penalty of the law, because the means of employment were abundant in this country, and he must have gone into the business from the hope of gain, and the crime was not one which was committed from any sudden impulse of temptation, but deliberately, for which reason little could be said in behalf of those who committed it, sentenced him to pay a fine of one dollar, and to be imprisoned at hard labor at Sing Sing for the period of seven years.

abstract: Last evening the District-Attorney, Mr. S.D. MORRIS, and Police Surgeon COCHRAN, visited the man PELLICER, who is now confined in the Forty-fourth Precinct Station-house, on the charge of being implicated in the murder of Mr. ORTEGO. They examined his person, and found his right hand cut across the fingers, as indicated by the glove found in the Park. The cuts are clean, and show that they were made with a sharp instrument. His clothes were also examined, and they were found to be bloody. A young Spaniard named JUAN VELE, called to see the prisoner yesterday. He represented himself as a cook in a French boarding-house, and that he boarded at the Hotel de Cuba, in Bleecker-street, New-York. He stated that he had furnished PELLICER with money for ten days, in consequence of being out of employment, and in needy circumstances. Some days ago, he (the visitor) had invited several ladies to go to the theatre, and wished his friend PELLICER to go along. In order to make him look somewhat decent, he bought him a pair of kid gloves, and he (Mr. VELE) identified the gloves which were cut across the fingers as the ones he bought. Mr. VELE saw GONZALES at the Hotel de Cuba at different times. On Wednesday last, about 7 o'clock in the morning, GONZALES came there, and inquired for Mr. PELLICER, who came down to the door, and admitted him. GONZALES said he desired lodgings, and was then invited by PELLICER to his room up stairs. The servant girl was in the meantime directed to see the landlady, and ask her whether she could accommodate him. She sent word that she could. Mr. VELE occupied the same bed with PELLICER the night previous, and was present when GONZALES came to the room. GONZALES asked PELLICER to come one side, and they engaged in a private conversation, which continued for some time. The parties subsequently went down stairs. In the evening, about 7:30 o'clock, GONZALES and another man, supposed to be ORTEGO, called at the hotel. VELE was there at the time. GONZALES; said to PELLICER, "Come, let's go," and PELLICER answered, "Wait, I forgot something in my room," and he forthwith went up stairs into a room which bad previously been locked, and returned. The parties then took a walk toward Broadway. VELE found, from the action of the others, that he was not wanted in their company, and left them. GONZALES, ORTEGA and a young Spaniard continued their way down Broadway. That was the last that he saw of the deceased. PELLICER was not seen at the hotel after that evening. When he left the house he wore a spotted calico shirt, a white Derby hat, and dark mixed coat; vest and pantaloons. The clothing was found saturated with blood. The prisoner denies any knowledge of the murder, but refuses to look at the body of the murdered man. He pretends not to understand English, but will converse in Spanish with friends. Yesterday he was permitted to speak with an acquaintance, and it was ascertained that they communicated with each other in some other than the Spanish language. The conversation was cut short by Capt. WADDY, who was present.

abstract: On Wednesday Gov. PARSONS, of Alabama, delivered his message to the State Legislature. He urges the adoption of the Amendment to the Constitution of the United States abolishing slavery. He asks for the passage of laws for the protection of the freed negroes and their property, and he approves of the adoption of vagrant laws, to be applied to idlers of the black and white races alike. These are surely sensible suggestions and recommendations. Their adoption by the Alabama Legislature -- as Gov. PARSONS reasons -- must greatly tend to facilitate the admission of the representatives of that State into Congress. It needs but that the States temporarily alienated should show that they are acting in good faith, in accordance with the President's programme of reconstruction, to insure for them a cordial welcome to their old places in the national councils. Gov. PARSONS appears to understand this fact sufficiently well to be able to give the State Legislature sound advice.

abstract: The complimentary serenade, of which Gov. FENTON was the recipient, last night, at the Fifth-avenue Hotel, favored by the mildly beautiful night, was quite a popular ovation. Long before the hour named for the arrival of the serenaders every available spot within seeing distance of the facade of the hotel or of the fireworks opposite, was filled with eager expectants, with the usual average of less patient youths who, clinging to the railing or clambering up the trees of the Madison Park, cheered in squeaky tenor anything and everything affording them the ready inspiration. Rocket after rocket threw up its shower of tinted stars, flinging alternate flashes of azure and vermillion on the marble building, and on the upturned faces of the crowd.

abstract: Clamins vs. Town. -- This was an action of slander, damages laid at $500. From the opening of C.S. Spencer, Esq., plaintiff's counsel, it appeared that the plaintiff was a bar-tender for Mr. Fangado, who kept a liquor-store in West-street, in this city. While there the defendant, in June last, came in and asked him if he had paid that money over to his employer he had left with him, to which the plaintiff replied that he had received no money from him, (the defendant,) whereupon the defendant charged him with stealing the money, calling him a thief, &c. In consequence of these allegations his employer discharged him. The plaintiff when put on the stand corroborated the statement of his counsel, and under oath denied ever having received any moneys from the defendant to give to his employer. Mr. McMahon, on the part of the defendant, stated that on the 3d of June, 1865, the defendant, a sail-maker, borrowed of Mr. Fangado $20, to be returned to him in two hours. Being about to go out of town at the time appointed, the defendant came into the store of Fangado, and not finding him in, gave the money to the plaintiff to hand to his employer, in payment of his loan. On the 8th day of June following, Mr. Fangado asked the defendant about that money, and he said: "I gave the money to Dick," meaning the plaintiff. Fangado denied that the plaintiff had given it to him, whereupon defendant took him in and confronted plaintiff, who, after some hesitation, denied having received the money; whereupon the defendant said to him: "If you have not paid over that money to Augustus, (meaning Fangado,) you have put it in your pocket and stolen the money." The defendant, when put on the stand, corroborated this statement, and swore that he gave the plaintiff the money to give to his employer, Mr. Fangado was sworn, and testified that he had intended to discharge the plaintiff before this occurrence, and did not do so on account of this difficulty. Another witness was sworn, who testified that he saw Town in Fangado's store that day, talking with a sea Captain, and nourishing in his hand a greenback, but could not recollect anything further. The plaintiff introduced another witness, who testified that the words used were these: "If he (plaintiff) had not paid the man in the liquor-store the money he (defendant) had let him have, he (plaintiff) was a thief."

abstract: Evacuation Day
snippet: Evacuation Day
lead_paragraph: The parade of the First Division, New-York State National Guard, yesterday, in celebration of Evacuation Day, was a magnificent and imposing display of our city military. Fully ten thousand men were in line, and the appearance of the troops was very creditable to the respective commanders. The ceremonies of the day consisted of a review in Fourteenth-street, by Gov. FENTON, and a parade of the division through some of the principal thoroughfares up town, concluding with a marching salute to the Governor at the foot of the Worth Monument, at the intersection of Broadway with Fifth-avenue. The day was peculiarly adapted for the display, and the city was gaily decorated.

abstract: The steam frigate Colorado, the Frolic, her tender, and the sloop-of-war Kearsarge, are still cruising in French waters. The Navy Department has ordered our vessels not to proceed further up the Mediterranean, as the cholera is still prevalent in most of the ports. It is not definitely known where the squadron will Winter, but it is rumored that Lisbon is the port selected. The officers of the Colorado complain of discourteous treatment received from the naval authorities at Brest. At an entertainment given by the officers of our squadron to the officers of the Russian gunboat Askold, our squadron was strongly invited to visit Russia during the next Summer. We have no doubt that the invitation will be accepted should the department approve it. We have now quite a respectable naval force in European waters, and it will soon be increased by the arrival of the sloops-of-war Shenandoah, Canandaigua and Ticonderoga. The vessels already there are the Colorado, Frolic, Kearsarge, Shawmut, National Guard and Ino.

abstract: Yesterday there was quite an assortment of pistols, knives, slung-shots, &c., taken from the persons of prisoners, who, on the night previous, were arrested for using or threatening to use the same....Officer CLINE, of the Fourth Precinct, arrested a man named HUGH CUNNINGHAM, who at the time was quite drunk, and had in his hands a large and heavily loaded Colt's revolver, with which he was threatening to take away the life of the passers-by. Committed, and sent to Blackwell's Island for six months in default of $1,000 bail....JAMES HARRINGTON was charged by KATE CLARK, of No. 128 Greenwich-street, with being grossly intoxicated, and in that State threatening to shoot her with a revolver which he had concealed upon him. Officer MORAN, of the Twenty-seventh Precinct, made the arrest. HARRINGTON, in default of $1,000 bail, was sent to the penitentiary for six months....JAMES GRAHAM, claiming to be a merchant, while in a state of intoxication at the Howard Hotel, drew a revolver from his pocket, discharging one barrel of it, thus endangering the lives of the bystanders. GRAHAM was arrested by Officer Ross, of the Second Precinct, and unable to find bail in $1,000, he was sent to the Island for six months. ....JOSEPH FLANIGAN was arrested in Cherry-street by Officer MOFFAT, of the Fourth Precinct, on Tuesday night. When arrested he was much intoxicated, and in one of his pockets was concealed a large butcher's knife, with which he afterward threatened to strike the officer. FLANIGAN, unable to procure bail in $1,000, was sent to Btackwell's Island for six months....Officer JOLLY, of the Fourteenth Precinct, arrested RICHARD ENRIGHT, in the Revere House, on Thursday night, on the charge of having assaulted Mr. NILES F. SMITH, proprietor of the hotel. It appears Mr. SMITH received a blow in the face from ENRIGHT, who further threatened to shoot him with a Derringer pistol he had in his hand, and which he thrust in the face of Mr. SMITH. The prisoner was committed for trial in default of $1,000 bail....JOHN CONNELL, living at No. 11 Albany-street, a boatman, was arrested by Officer MORAN, of the Twenty-seventh Precinct, in the attempt to strike a man with a deadly-looking slung-shot. He was committed to the Tombs for trial....After the disposel of the above cases, numerous ward politicians and others appeared to intercede for the prisoners, but Justice DOWLING, determined to put an end to the carrying of deadly weapons upon the person, could not be wheedled into leniency, preferring to protect the lives of peaceful citizens to letting loose again without punishment these public enemies.

He was committed to the Tombs for trial....After the disposel of the above cases, numerous ward politicians and others appeared to intercede for the prisoners, but Justice DOWLING, determined to put an end to the carrying of deadly weapons upon the person, could not be wheedled into leniency, preferring to protect the lives of peaceful citizens to letting loose again without punishment these public enemies.

abstract: The Union Convention has nominated MARSHAL O. ROBERTS for Mayor, and MURRAY HOFFMAN for Corporation Counsel. Both these nominations are admirable. But Mr. ROBERTS is quite as likely to be elected Mayor as any other candidate, and, under existing circumstances, a good deal more so.

abstract: Later news from Matamoras states that the Liberals are in force eight miles from that city, and an unimportant skirmish had taken place, in which one Imperialist was killed and three taken prisoners.
lead_paragraph: Later news from Matamoras states that the Liberals are in force eight miles from that city, and an unimportant skirmish had taken place, in which one Imperialist was killed and three taken prisoners. The battle of the kegs, ludicrously famous in our Revolutionary war, was paralleled recently on the Rio Grande, when the Imperialist gunboats did heroic warfare for some time upon some barges laden with wood, which had broken away and were, floating down the stream. The innocent barges were mistaken for iron-clads; one of them had her rudder shot away. The dispatch says that "highly important communications had passed between the Imperial commander of the fleet and the Federal commander at Brownsville, which will cause considerable excitement in official circles." An official order was issued by MEJIA prohibiting any one from crossing from the American side, or vice versa. Upon the receipt of information that there was firing upon Antonio from the Texas side, the French Commodore dispatched a vessel to Vera Cruz with the particulars of the occurrence, and it is reported that a swift vessel will be dispatched to France for reinforcements. A gentleman lately from Matamoras says that the rebel force is much scattered, and the streets of the city have been fortified with earthworks. He also states that two flatboats came down on the night of the 14th and attacked the Imperialists gunboats, which succeeded in sinking both. Many of the Liberals were killed and drowned, and some captured. (Probably untrue.) The Matamoras Ranchero, of the 10th, says: "Despite the report to the contrary, there is not the slightest apprehension of another attack on the city."

abstract: -- Isn't it about time that Evacuation Day was allowed to take its place in the ordinary calendar? Have we not celebrated it about long enough? There is not one man in twenty, in the city or out of it, who knows what is meant by it, and so many much more important events have happened since that it seems scarcely worth while to go through the annual farce of its celebration. These military displays, at best have been sadly cast into the shade by the great and memorable deeds of the recent war, and no one looks now with any special admiration or awe upon their empty and pretentious pomp. The troops who are marched through our streets must feel abashed at the sight of the armless and legless veterans who have covered themselves and their country with glory, and we doubt not would gladly be relieved from this yearly farce.

abstract: -- EX CURSION TO-DAY. -- Philadelphia Fire Company No. 18, with their elegant steam fire engine, hose carriage and ambulance, arrived in Jersey City, at 7 o'clock, last evening, on their return home from Albany and Troy. They were escorted from the Hudson River Railroad depot by Chief Engineer MCLOUGHLIN, of Jersey City, NOAH D. TAYLOR, foreman of Steam Fire Engine No. 1 of Jersey City, and a delegation from that company. After housing their apparatus, the company proceeded to Taylor's Hotel, where they partook of a sumptuous collation, after which they spent the balance of the evening at the Broadway Theatre. To-day they will take an excursion up the East River in the steamer Matamora, chartered by Engine Company No. 1 of Jersey City, and will visit the institutions at Blackwell's and Randall's Islands, and will leave for home at 4 P.M. They will have a grand reception and torchlight procession in Philadelphia to-night.

abstract: -- The trustees of this deserving charity make their usual Thanksgiving appeal for aid. The trustees call attention to the fact that 1,284 women and children have been received and dismissed from the house to situations and friends, during the year ending the 1st of October; 1,633 children were taught in the schools; 333,436 meals have been given to the poor, mostly to children. A family of nearly 200 are constantly maintained in the house. To prevent suffering among the multitudes that throng to them, to feed the hungry, and clothe so many hundreds of children, the trustees ask all to contribute, though the amount be ever so small. Donations should be sent to S.B. HALLIDAY, Superintendent, No. 155 Worth-street.

abstract: -- The speculators in gold have had hard times for the last three months. During the first half of the current year, as during the two years preceding, they had very exciting times, and won or lost immense sums with lightning-like rapidity. The fluctuations were very great the volume of business was great, and a great multitude of people "took a hand in the game." But for three months past, gold has been steady, with only now and then a fractional fluctuation, and the mob of outside operators have left the street in disgust, and taken to labor which we hope is more productive -- it certainly could not be more severe. We might give the same remarks a more extended application to other branches of speculation; for though there have been some violent movements in stocks, there is on the whole a much steadier and quieter state of things than existed up to Midsummer.

abstract: -- The Fenian movement seems to be on the decline at present both in Ireland and America. There is no excitement about the matter, and there are no signs of any action of any kind in any direction. Even Canada is being quieted, and the fear of insurrection or invasion is passing away. In the mass of English newspapers which we received by the last mail, the subject is hardly mentioned. The London Times has ceased indulging in either threats of ridicule about it and the Irish papers treat it already as a thing of the past.

lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- There was another excellent house at the Academy last night, when "La Sonnambula" was given in a truly excellent manner. We have never heard Sig. IRFRE to better advantage than in the part of Elvino, and he fully deserved the great applause after the andante of the duet in the first act. He sang with truly artistic taste, and showed his fine high notes to great advantage. Sig. ANTONUCCI was very good as the Count, and his singing of the first aria was exceedingly good. Signora ORTOLANI did everything in her power to equal the artiste, who sang the part of Amina before her. Next week will be mainly taken up by the rehearsals and the performance of the "Africaine," which opera will be given positively on Friday next. In consequence of the necessity for rehearsals, no opera will be given on Tuesday, but an extra performance will be given on Saturday next. On Monday the favorite opera of the season, "Crispino e la Comare," will be given the last time. To-day "Fra Diavolo" is on the programme for the matinee.

The better style of residences have, of course, their private baths; but unfortunately not a tenth part of the population have the privilege of dwelling in the better class of houses, and for the great multitude there are hardly any conveniences of this essential kind. There ought to be a public bath on every block in the city in which the working classes live. Instead of this, hardly any are anywhere to be found. Were the people to be furnished with them, and to get accustomed to their use, they would never afterward do without them, and would be vastly benefited in health and morals by their use. The matter is so important that there ought to be some provision for their establishment.

lead_paragraph: From the returns of the government emigration officials it appears that a large and indeed sudden increase has taken place during the month of October in the exodus from the port of Liverpool. During the month there sailed from Liverpool to the United States, "under the act," 25 ships, with 798 cabin and 7,518 steerage passengers, of whom 2,096 were English, 118 Scotch, 3,184 Irish, and 2,120 foreigners. To Canada there were five ships, with 113 cabin and 1,886 steerage passengers, of whom 539 were English, 387 Irish, 17 Scotch, and 143 other countries. To Victoria there were two ships, with 47 cabin and 517 steerage passengers, of whom 201 were English, 35 Scotch, 267 Irish, and 16 other countries; making a total of 32 ships, with 958 cabin and 9,121 steerage passengers. In "short ships," or ships not sailing under the act, there sailed to the United States five ships and 526 passengers; to New South Wales one ship, with 28 passengers; to Victoria one ship, with 26 passengers; to the West Indies two ships, with 19 passengers; to South America four ships, with 123 passengers; and to Africa one ship, with 49 passengers; being an increase over the same month of last year of 3,261.

lead_paragraph: OSCAR SMITH, 28 years old, a native of this State, and residing at No. 52 Charles-street, was arrested yesterday morning by Officer O'BYRNE, on the complaint Of HENRY B. WARD, residing at No. 85 Laurens-street, a native of Connecticut. The complainant stated that he came here in September last in search of employment, and that on searching the advertisements in a morning journal ho found one in which a situation was offered at $18 per week, the sum of $400 to be deposited as security for the honesty of the employe; that he replied to this advertisement in person, by calling at the place named in the advertisement, No. 266 Broadway, Room No. 4. That there he met the prisoner, OSCAR SMITH, who explained to him the nature of the situation, that of grocery clerk, in a most respectable establishment. Complainant went with SMITH to a store No. 299 Fourth-street, where he was introduced to the alleged proprietor, HUGH W. GERN, ultimately agreeing to accept the situation on the terms proposed, an agreement being drawn out to that effect. He then went to a lawyer with SMITH, where the contract was made and signed, and he then handed SMITH $300, SMITH having agreed, as GERN's agent, to accept that sum, the complainant being unwilling to give more. On the day named for his going to business, on his reaching the store, GERN was not there, the place being in charge of a man pointed out to him by SMITH the day before as the wagon driver of the establishment. Waiting there all day, he found that the representations of SMITH as to the trade of the house was slightly overdone, as but five dollars instead of fifty were taken in. Next day he came again, with like results, but on this day a young man called to see GERN, and stated that he had been relieved of $400 by the same advertisement, and had come that day to take his situation. It appears that further evidence will show that these gentlemen have carried on this game with great success, making as much as $1,600 in a day by their conspiring and fraud. Justice LEDWITH committed the prisoner without bail.

abstract: AN ELOPEMENT. -- A few evenings since a young man, accompanied by a girl 18 years of age, arrived in the 11 P.M. Erie Railway train, and proceeding to a hotel in the vicinity, registered themselves as man and wife. After supper they retired to a sleeping apartment, and an hour later the girl came down stairs with her hat and bonnet on, and was rushing out of the hotel in the most excited manner, when she was stopped by the superintendent, who, suspecting something wrong, asked where she was going. She replied that she had been deceived and intended to jump off the dock. The superintendent told her that he could not allow that, and after further conversation the girl said that she was not married to the man with whom she came, but that she had eloped with him from Middletown, N.Y., under the promise of marriage on their arrival at Jersey City, but that as it was too late to procure the services of a minister, she had consented to pass as his wife until the following morning, when they were to have the ceremony performed; that after going to their room and engaging in conversation awhile, the young man said he could not fulfill the contract as he was already married. Upon this the young woman immediately left the room, and was leaving the hotel in a distracted manner when stopped as above stated. It appears that the young man was a soldier until recently, and the acquaintance sprung up by means of correspondence, and finally resulted in an elopement after two weeks of personal acquaintance. The superintendent told the girl he would see her righted, and after placing her under the surveillance of some of the domestics, he visited the young man in his room. The young man admitted that he was not married, when he was given the alternative of marrying the young woman, or a drubbing and chance for State Prison. The young man accepted the first proposition, and the young couple left the following morning on their return to Middletown, where they were to be united.

abstract: The New-York Association for Improving the Condition of the Poor have just issued their twentysecond annual report, from which it appears that the receipts of the association during the year were $43,975, and the disbursements, $49,300; excess, $5,324.
lead_paragraph: The New-York Association for Improving the Condition of the Poor have just issued their twenty-second annual report, from which it appears that the receipts of the association during the year were $43,975, and the disbursements, $49,300; excess, $5,324. The number of visitors employed last year was 366, who made 22,309 visits. The number of families relieved was 5,573, comprising 22,285 persons. In twenty-two years, the totals have been as follows: Visits, 678,882; receipts, $908,280; expenditures, $983,182: families relieved, 133,404; persons relieved, 654,063.

abstract: Actives New-York vs. Alerts, South Orange
snippet: Actives New-York vs. Alerts, South Orange
lead_paragraph: Of the many social games of base ball among the numerous very agreeable reunions of the season just passed, none have been marked with more pleasantness than the one played on Thursday, at South Orange, N.J., between the Actives of New-York, and the Alerts of Soyton Hall College, of the former place. The day was magnificent, and the atmosphere of that genial nature that Indian Summer alone gives us. The members of the New-York Club were met at the depot by a deputation of the College boys, escorted to their grounds, and after an excellent lunch the game at once commenced, the Actives taking the bat. This club were short three of their first nine, but their places were well filled by TILTON, HILLYER and CHRISTIE, of the second nine. The Alerts on this occasion played with more energy and better judgment than they did with the Unknowns the week before, the playing of one or two of their number being particularly good. Several ladies, and most of the faculty of the college were on the grounds during the game, imparting additional interest to it by their hearty applause. Upon the conclusion of the game, the Actives were treated to some excellent instrumental and vocal music by Messrs. REILLEY and RICHARDS, of Seyton Hall, and also to a bountiful repast, where many well chosen remarks were made by the Presidents of the Alerts and Actives, as also by Rev. Father MCCREADY, President of the college. At the parting at the depot, cheer after cheer were given by the departing club for the Alerts, their gentlemanly treatment and generous hospitality. We quite forgot to mention that "Redman," of the Actives, during the first innings played short stop, but the position did not suit the genial boy.

abstract: November, 1864, PETER J. CUCUEL, of Morristown, N.J., in a fit of madness caused by intoxication, deliberately murdered his wife, by stabbing her in the breast with a butcher-knife. He was tried at the last May term, convicted, and sentenced, in accordance with the law, to be hanged. Persevering efforts to obtain a new trial or a commutation of sentence were made, but they all failed, and on Friday, the 24th inst., just a year and a day after the commission of the crime, he was executed. The execution took place in the jail yard at Morristown. Some four hundred persons were admitted as spectators within the prison walls. A very large concourse of people were assembled outside. The drop fell at precisely 12:15 o'clock. The unhappy man slept five hours on the previous night, but was much prostrated the next morning. His children visited him on Thursday, and bade him farewell; but two of them, as if drawn by some irresistible affection, came again to his cell on Friday. When the hour fixed for the execution arrived, he was so greatly prostrated that he had to be carried out of his cell on a chair. His only words, previous to execution, were: "I am ready -- farewell." He died by strangulation, and without a struggle.

abstract: Precautions against Cholera
snippet: Precautions against Cholera
lead_paragraph: It is encouraging, now, that other cities at least are doing, what New-York neglects to do; that is, the preparing for the approach of the cholera. The City of Providence was attacked by all three visitations of this pestilence, but, owing to vigilant and energetic sanitary measures, she escaped with only some 150 deaths in each of the two latter. Under the advice of a skillful Superintendent of Health -- Dr. SNOW -- she is now preparing for a fourth. This scientific adviser but follows the majority of the profession in Europe and America, in denying that cholera is contagious, (though admitting that the seeds of the disease may be conveyed by the excreta of the sick,) and therefore lays little weight on quarantine -- which, indeed, in the case of a city like Providence, would be practically impossible. He accordingly calls the whole attention of the citizens to preventive measures. The experience of England, as Dr. SNOW well urges, shows that the condition of the drinking-water in a town is one of the chief causes or stimulants of the disease. Providence suffers under one of the curses of American cities, which ought to have gone out with the witches, or any abuse of the Middle Ages -- cesspools side by side with wells; the excreta of the one thus draining into the fluid of the other, and scattering wide the seeds of every kind of malady. Bad water and cholera inevitably go together. The Health Officer accordingly recommends a supply of pure water, and the draining of all cesspools and open privies, as an indispensable condition of safeguard.

abstract: Russia and the Monitor Ship System
snippet: Russia and the Monitor Ship System
lead_paragraph: The London Times has a convenient facility for forgetting disagreeable facts which must be very soothing and mollifying, now and then, to the anxieties of its readers. This tallent for forgetting, as it may justly be called, is particularly conspicuous wherever truths become public which tend to lower England's position among the nations. For example, while the Thunderer gave broadside after broadside to the glorification of the Cherbourg naval review -- now painting its details in the glaring colors of its correspondents, and anon lauding the tout ensemble in ponderous editorials -- not one word has it ever contained descriptive of the far more important iron-clad show at Stockholm. And yet, so far as scientific results are concerned, there can be no comparison between these two contemporaneous naval pageants. The greatest service the London Times could render its patrons would be to describe in one-tenth of the space which it gave to the affair at Portsmouth and Cherbourg, the sober lesson taught at Stockholm.

abstract: On Collector King and Auditorship
snippet: On Collector King and Auditorship
lead_paragraph: There is to us much mystery in a statement that Mr. KING "could not summon resolution enough to appoint an Auditor." Why not? What was peculiar about that office? It is well known that Mr. KING was inclined to appoint one of the three or four most suitable candidates whose names were presented to him, and who understood the duties of the office as well as Mr. WEED knows the doors and passages of the State Department. Who prevented such an appointment by insisting that a mere Republican politician should be selected, and thereby made the perplexity seem incapable of removal?

abstract: Last evening, Capt. WADDY, of Brooklyn, arrested GONZALEZ, the principal in the OTERO murder. It seems that the name of the victim is really OTERO, and not ORTEGA, as it has been given to our reporter. GONZALES was seated at a supper table...
lead_paragraph: Last evening, Capt. WADDY, of Brooklyn, arrested GONZALEZ, the principal in the OTERO murder. It seems that the name of the victim is really OTERO, and not ORTEGA, as it has been given to our reporter. GONZALES was seated at a supper table in a German boarding-bonse, at No. 217 Centre-street when Capt. WADDY and his men entered, and on seeing them he sprang for the door. His flight was intercepted, and he was at once taken to Brooklyn and incarcerated in the Forty-fourth Precinat Police Station.

abstract: and value of the oil trade of Pennsylvania may be inferred from the extensive railway facilities making to accommodate it. At a meeting of the managers of the Pennsylvania and Philadelphia and Erie Railroad Companies, in this city, yesterday, the details of a contract were agreed upon with MILLER & COURT-RIGHT, two experienced contractors, to construct a railroad from Irving to Oil City, a distance of fifty-three miles, with three miles of siding, and to furnish the same with locomotives and cars, the whole to be completed with the equipments in all of May, 1866, or in about five months from this time -- equal to about eleven miles per month. The parties are already negotiating for the iron at New-York. The necessary means are to be raised by the issue of $1,300,000 of 7 per cent. bonds by the Warren and Franklin Railroad Company, indorsed by both the Pennsylvania and the Philadelphia and Erie Railroad Companies. This proposed road will be an entirely new outlet for the oil production of our State, and as may naturally be inferred, the parties engaged in making it expect large advantage from it. The oil product from the region which it opens is estimated at from 5,000 to 7,000 barrels per day, and will require an equipment of from 900 to 1,000 cars. Each car carries some sixty barrels, the freight on which from Oil City to its junction with the Philadelphia and Erie Road, is $1 per barrel. From these movements over one comparatively small link of railroad, some idea may be formed of the importance of this new Pennsylvania staple. In this connection, on the authority of an officer of the company, we state that the Pennsylvania Railroad Company have now on the Philadelphia and Erie Railroad 300 cars, that cannot reach the oil region at Titusville by way of Corry, so jammed is that road with business. This new source of wealth will bring immense sums of money into a region of the state that has heretofore been esteemed the least valuable portion of our Commonwealth, and will beside add largely to the profits of existing railway improvements. -- Philadelphia Ledger, Nov. 23.

abstract: Advices from Brownsville, received via NewOrleans, corroborate the statement that the Imperialists fired on a United States boat drifting down the river, causing the crew to run her ashore and take safety in flight. The Im-...
lead_paragraph: Advices from Brownsville, received via New-Orleans, corroborate the statement that the Imperialists fired on a United States boat drifting down the river, causing the crew to run her ashore and take safety in flight. The Imperial fire did no harm to the boat, but the Captain of it had a narrow escape, a musket ball passing through his hat. It is understood that Gen. WEITZEL has demanded an explanation of the affair. The order of Gen. MEJIA, prohibiting intercourse with Brownsville, cannot last, as on the Liberals surrounding Matamoras they will be compelled to draw their supplies from Brownsville. As heretofore supposed, the order was issued to prevent the ingress of spies into Matamoras.

lead_paragraph: EVACUATION DAY. -- The day having been duly celebrated in advance, the only observance of the anniversary yesterday was the parade of the veterans of 1812, and the display of bunting on public and private buildings. The veterans, under the command of Gen. RAYMOND, marched down Broadway about 1 1/2 p.m., from their headquarters at the Mercer House. They numbered twenty-nine, sixteen of whom were officers. They were armed with swords and canes, but none of them carried gone. A drum-corps preceded them. They reached the City Hall about 2 1/2 p.m., where they were reviewed by the Mayor, when Gen. RAYMOND expressed to his Honor the pleasure he felt in greeting him once more on Evacuation Day. The Mayor complimented the General, telling him that he looked younger than he did last year, and that his corps deserved more honor than they got. The veterans then proceeded to Crook's saloon, where they partook of dinner.

abstract: Destitution and Public Meetings
snippet: Destitution and Public Meetings
lead_paragraph: We are afraid that very little will be accomplished for the suffering people of the South through the public meetings ostensibly held for that purpose in this city and elsewhere. There are altogether too many eloquent men figuring in the movement, who make altogether too many eloquent speeches, which are interrupted by altogether too much "laughter" and "applause." It is rare that much effective action is performed where there is so much of this sort of thing. Funny stories, amusing anecdotes, strong "hits" and rhetorical periods are all good enough in their place; they titillate the audience, and induce admiration of the orator. But we have observed that the great and successful movements in the way of beneficence and charity during the last few years have been introduced, accompanied and consummated with but a very limited amount of eloquent oratory.

abstract: on Party Prestidigation
snippet: on Party Prestidigation
lead_paragraph: The letter of President LINCOLN, written in 1859, and recently published, is a very characteristic one. It contains some sentences which are worthy to be remembered among the pithy utterances for which he will be always famous. "No party," says Mr. LINCOLN, "can command respect which sustains this year what it opposed last." The defeat of the Democratic party at the recent election points this moral, as was never done more thoroughly. The Democratic leaders undertook to do this very thing. They imagined they could make the people forget what they had said and done but one year ago. And we consider it one of the good results of the election that this attempt of theirs has not received the varnish which success would have given it. If this shift of theirs had commanded success, they would not have cared so much if it had not commanded respect. But their failure has brought out the truth of Mr. LINCOLN's remark in a most striking way, and the example will, we doubt not, be a useful one. Politicians will be taught again the old lesson that "consistency is a jewel" -- not merely an ornament, but a thing of value, which cannot be lightly thrown away without leaving the spendthrift so much poorer.

abstract: The New-Orleans Picayune states that JACOB BARKER, who has been elected to Congress from the Second District of Louisiana, including the largest portion of New-Orleans, is 85 years old. THAD, STEVENS,...
lead_paragraph: The New-Orleans Picayune states that JACOB BARKER, who has been elected to Congress from the Second District of Louisiana, including the largest portion of New-Orleans, is 85 years old. THAD, STEVENS, it says, who was the senior member of last Congress, is about 72 years. the Picayune is certain that no man of the same age ever entered a representative body who possessed the same amount of energy, capacity for active business, and all his faculties, intellectual and physical, so well as Mr. BARKER. Yesterday be could be seen behind his counter, attending to the large and multifarious business of his bank, and at the same time receiving the congratulations of his friends on his election, as lively, keen and ready as a young man of twenty-five. It has been a close and long race, says the Picayune, between old Lord PALMERSTON and Mr. BARKER, both having entered public life about the same time. Both, too, have led very active and eventful lives, have participated very earnestly in all the events of their era, and have always kept even with the current of ideas and movements. But Mr. BARKER comes out ahead in the race of life, and enters the political arena, four years older than the British Premier had reached on his departure from the stage on which he had played a conspicuous part for over fifty years. Mr. BARKER is a year or so older than Gen. CASS, who retired from public life eight years ago, and now lives in Detroit, Michigan, entirely withdrawn from all public or private cares. It is a notable fact, in regard to Mr. BARKER's longevity, that the last, thirty years have been passed in New-Orleans, the climate of which, in many parts of the world, is very erroneously regarded as not favorable to long life.

lead_paragraph: GEORGE WHITE and DANIEL O'BRIEN, seamen on board the ship Thomas Dunham, were arrested last evening, at the instance of Capt. YOUNG, of the same vessel, on a charge of having mutinied during the voyage just closed, from London to this port. They broke into the cargo, and helped themselves to liquor, under the influence of which they assaulted the Captain with knives. He escaped their attack by shooting them slightly. One of the prisoners was locked up at the Harbor Police-station; the other was put in the City Hospital.

abstract: -- A gentleman of the name of GILBERT, "from England," has announced in Dr. CHEEVER's church, that during the coming Winter we shall have a more fearful sectional conflict than ever. The rebels being all perjured persons, should not, according to Mr. GILBERT, "from England," ever be allowed to participate again in the government of the country. Without at all doubting the sincerity which appertains to utterances of Mr. GILBERT, "from England," we think it would be quite as becoming in him to allow his opinions to mature a little before thrusting them into the face of the community here, even under the shade and sanction of a reverend patron. Why should a stranger come here to glory over the prospect of new conflicts between the North and the South? Such conflicts are purely imaginary. There will be an earnest and sober discussion in Congress on the best and safest measures for the restoration of the lately insurgent States to the Union. But it is a vile and insane forecasting of evil to predict, as this Mr. GILBERT does, a conflict which will "rage more fiercely than ever." The whole tone of public opinion outside of certain small fanatical circles, clearly indicates the desire of honest men of all parties to take a calm estimate of the situation, and discard everything like sectional prejudice in dealing with the question of readmission. Irresponsible agitators have other ends to subserve than the restoration of good will between the North and the South; and the prophesying of evil is their last resort. In spite of this, the country refuses to be driven again into fierce and violent sectional controversy.

abstract: Magazines for December
snippet: Magazines for December
lead_paragraph: -- The Atlantic Monthly (Boston: TICKNOR & FIELDS,) for the coming month, winds up the old year with spirit, and is a number far above the average. It commences with the first installment of a story by CHARLES READE, (which is the "leading feature" of the new sixpenny London magazine The Argosy,) entitled "Griffith Gaunt, or Jealousy." It opens well, and the continuation will be looked for with interest. "William Blackwood," by JOHN NEAL, is a capital original chapter from the literary reminiscences of one who, having seen and done much, has much to tell. "The Chimney Corner" continues to show Mrs. STOWE's excellent good sense, applied to the amelioration of the every-day troubles of life. CHARLES DICKEN's feeling notice of Miss PROCTOR is given from the new illustrated edition of her Poems. The most remarkable paper is well described in its title: "Clemency and Common Sense; a Curiosity of literature with a Moral," by Hon. CHARLES SUMNER. In a dozen pages he painfully traces the literary history of a mediaval Latin poem, remarkable as being the source of the well known quotation: Incidis in Scyllam, cupiens evitare Charybdim, and then appends a moral on the dangers of the republic, between the Scylla of concession and compromise and the Charybdis of State Rights. The article is creditable to Mr. SUMNER's industry in a field possessing little general attraction, though it is strange that a scholar of his eminence should nod so far as to speak of "the Monastery of St. Gall in France," when referring to the famous ecclesiastical establishment in Switzerland. "The Parting of Hector and Andromache," is an Homeric translation by W.C. BRYANT, that will attract all lovers of poetry. In the "Reviews" we learn that "now Mr. HAWTHORNE is dead, America has not, perhaps a writer who is master of a more graceful prose than -- HIGGINSON." (!)

abstract: Presbyterian Church, Fortieth-street; Dedication
snippet: Presbyterian Church, Fortieth-street; Dedication
lead_paragraph: An edifice of unpretending exterior, situated at the junction of Fortieth-street and Lexington-avenue, was opened yesterday morning for divine service. In its interior arrangements the church is admirably adapted to the holy purpose to which it has been dedicated, and to the comfort of the congregation, who cannot but feel gratified at the extremely happy results of the labors of those to whom its construction and chastely modest decoration were intrusted. The corner-stone of the building was laid on the 6th day of July last, and the interior completed a few days since. The structure measures ninety feet by forty, and seats commodiously its congregation of four hundred and fifty persons. The pulpit, of graceful design and ornamentation, is a gift of a member of the congregation, alike creditable to his taste as to his charity. The organ is small, but of much sweetness of tone, and of compass sufficient for the space it is required to fill. The pews are painted in enamel, with framing of black walnut, and cushions of neutral-colored merino. The effect upon the stranger as he enters the edifice is that neatness and order lend their aid to sanctify the house of prayer. The service was opened by the young and eloquent pastor, Rev. CHARLES E. HART, who, after the staging of the opening hymn by the congregation, offered up with much fervor and devotion the dedicatory prayer. A sermon was then delivered of considerable power, with frequent passages of rhetorical beauty, by Rev. S.D. ALEXANDER, D.D., from the text, Isaiah, 59th chapter and 21st verse. The service closed by the singing of the 101st Psalm, the congregation rendering with much feeling the passage, pregnant with beauty and with promise, "Mine eyes shall be upon the faithful of the land, that they may dwell with me."

abstract: Dickens, Charles; Our Mutual Friend; (Harper); On Removal of Troops from Southern States
snippet: Dickens, Charles; Our Mutual Friend; (Harper); On Removal of Troops from Southern States
lead_paragraph: In his last dispatch to Gov. HUMPHREYS, of Mississippi, a full copy of which appears today in another column, the President shows how far removed is his policy from any approach to sectionalism or partisanship. The question of the withdrawal of the national troops was that on which the President's views were asked for. And the tone in which these views are stated for the guidance of the civil authorities of Mississippi -- apart altogether from the entirely moderate and reasonable character of the views themselves -- cannot but convince the rational-minded of the Southern people that the basis of Mr. JOHNSON'S policy is conciliation. Not conciliation of one class at the expense of justice to another -- but conciliation between all classes, as well as all sections. "The troops will be withdrawn," says the President, "when peace and order and the civil authority have been restored and can be maintained without them." Again he says: "Every step will be taken while they (the troops) are there to enforce strict discipline and subordination to the civil authority." No concession is to be required of the people of Mississippi, other than a loyal compliance with the laws and Constitution of the United States -- including "protection to all freedmen in person and property." The programme is simple and specific, and can only be considered arbitrary or tyrannical by those who do not loyally and in good faith purpose to return to their former allegiance.

abstract: Liquor and Crime
snippet: Liquor and Crime
lead_paragraph: Every day's police and criminal reports indicate anew the great and terrible agency of liquor in the production of crime. In the latest of our local horrors -- the murder of Senor OTERO in Brooklyn -- the perpetrators of the crime, (if we may infer that those under arrest as the culprits are really such,) first plied their victim and then filled themselves with hot and strong liquor, as a necessary preliminary to the commission of the atrocity. And nine out of ten of the murders that disgrace our community are committed under the same infernal influence. The same thing may be said of the lesser grades of criminality. In cases of violent assault, the assailants are nearly always excited by liquor; and in a large proportion of the personal outrages on the streets and elsewhere, the victim or the perpetrator is a victim of this unnatural stimulus. It is one of the chief causes of domestic quarrels and difficulties -- one of the fundamental agencies of degradation and vice. In fact, it would seem from our experience, that, but for liquor and its influences, the grosser forms of crime would, in great measure, cease to prevail.

abstract: -- The mild and genial weather we are having at this season is a great blessing to the poor, as well as of enjoyment to all. The poor do not shiver and suffer at night in their sorrowful houses, nor feel so keenly their lack of warm and comfortable clothing and covering. They are not compelled to spend so much of their earnings in the purchase of coal, and thus are enabled to fare better otherwise. This article of coal is still sold at an exceedingly high price, and to those who are compelled to buy it in small quantities, by the bushel or the "scuttle," it comes thrice or four times as high as to those who are able to purchase it by the ton. Rent and coal are heavy burdens to the poor of this city; and whatever tends to lighten the one or the other must be gratefully regarded as a Providential beneficence.

The poor do not shiver and suffer at night in their sorrowful houses, nor feel so keenly their lack of warm and comfortable clothing and covering. They are not compelled to spend so much of their earnings in the purchase of coal, and thus are enabled to fare better otherwise. This article of coal is still sold at an exceedingly high price, and to those who are compelled to buy it in small quantities, by the bushel or the "scuttle," it comes thrice or four times as high as to those who are able to purchase it by the ton. Rent and coal are heavy burdens to the poor of this city; and whatever tends to lighten the one or the other must be gratefully regarded as a Providential beneficence.

abstract: -- A man giving the name of WILLIAM SHERIDAN was arrested at an early hour on Sunday morning, charged with burglariously entering MCCABE's saloon. No. 239 Nowark-avenue. Jersey City. The saloon did not close until after midnight, and as Mr. MCCABE, wholives up stairs in the same building, was about retiring. he thought he heard some one in the saloon. After listening a few minutes he became convinced that his suspicious were correct, and proceeding cautiously down stairs he found the accused, who attempted to escape. Mr. MCCABE at once grappled with the burglar and succeeded in throwing him to the floor, where he hold him until the eries of the female members of Mr. MCCABE's family from the windows above brought policemen ROSE and MCNAMARA to the spot, who took the accused into custody. The prisoner was held for examination, which was sent down for this morning.

abstract: the Secretary of the Treasury; Plans of Must Not be Impeded
snippet: the Secretary of the Treasury; Plans of Must Not be Impeded
lead_paragraph: We met with but limited success in the war until our military action was characterized by unity of plan, method and direction. When we got these, under the Lieutenant-Generaley of GRANT, we began to move forward, steadily and systematically, to the final triumph. It is possible that GRANT's way of reaching Richmond by an overland march was not the best conceivable way; it is certain that the necessities imposed by the policy of concentration were attended by loss and suffering, and were otherwise liable to severe criticism; it is doubtful whether all the cooperative movements were wisely designed, and it is sure that several of them were failures in execution. But the great and important central fact remains that, with the governing unity referred to, it was possible to wield the entire forces of the nation harmoniously, and for the carrying out of a fixed purpose in a defined manner. It ended ambitious wranglings, rectified cross purposes, stopped the conflict of project and action, relegated military tyros and charlatans to limbo, and gave us the prime conditions of success, at the same time that it removed the main causes of failure.

abstract: A rather unpropitious week was brought to a brilliant musical termination on Saturday. On that day Mr. MARETZEK gave his patrons a matinee performance of "Fra Diaval." It was witnessed by one of the largest audiences ever assembled in the Academy ...
lead_paragraph: A rather unpropitious week was brought to a brilliant musical termination on Saturday. On that day Mr. MARETZEK gave his patrons a matinee performance of "Fra Diaval." It was witnessed by one of the largest audiences ever assembled in the Academy of Music, extending absolutely from the parquette to the amphitheatre. The sex was indeed irresistible, both in numbers and splendor. Such few specimens of the male animal as dared brave the ordeal, ranged themselves timidly in the lobbies, and, like TENNYSON's hero, "perused the matting." It is not necessary to speak of the performance.

Kennie, resulting in the victory of the former, in one hour and thirteen minutes the owners ...
lead_paragraph: It will be remembered that a trotting match for $2,000 of twenty miles, came off at the Fashion Course, L.I., on the 17th inst., between Mr. MULLIGAN's bay gelding, Butler, Jr., and Mr. PHYFE's black gelding Capt. Kennie, resulting in the victory of the former, in one hour and thirteen minutes -- the owners of the respective horses driving them. Both were what is technically termed green road horses, neither having been trained on the track, or publicly driven on it previously. The match created considerable interest in private trotting circles at the time, and little among the habitues of the course. The match was horse against horse, and not against time, hence there was no necessity for a display of speed, or the urging of either horse beyond his natural speed. Nevertheless, the winner was extremely distressed, and died the following forenoon. The black golding (the loser) exhibited much less fatigue, and his owner showed him to us a few days afterward, in his road wagon in New-York, looking little, if anything, the worse for his trot. Butler, Jr., was half brother to the celebrated trotting gelding General Butter, and was thought very highly of by his owner. Captain Kennie's pedigree is unknown, but there is evidently a great deal of blood in him, which is exhibited in his clean legs, the thoroughbred points in his quarters, and in his method of getting over the ground. He stands about 15 1/2, hands. All that his owner knows of him is that he was sired by a Canada stallion out of an imported English mare. The winner had the advantage of being driven on the road all the Summer, and was consequently full of hard food, whereas his opponent had been turned out to grass during the whole period, and was only taken up three weeks prior to the race, and was consequently in a sott, green condition -- the only training he had received being a gentle jogging on the road, added to which his driver weighed 40 pounds more than the driver of Butler, Jr., who was far below the regular Fashion Course weights, which caused a discussion among the judges as to whether he ought not to have been distanced for being short of weight. It was to be regretted that the judges did not take the time of the separate miles in so interesting a race, but the owner of the survivor asserts that without track-training he has driven him over the course in 2:36; and MACE, the professional driver, declares confidently that he will, if he is placed under his care, bring him down "among the twenties." It is a curious fact that he came from the same spot as the celebrated Auburn horse, recently purchased by Mr. BONNER for $17,000, who, by the way, was originally sold for $300.
