abstract: Mr. JOHN SACKMAN, residing at No. 39 Centre-street, appeared recently before Justice DOWLING, and made complaint against ANTHONY BRUMORGER, OSCAR TADE and JEREMIAH FALVEY, charging that these parties, on the 14th day of December, 1864, won from him, at one sitting, at the game of "faro," $300, in the house No. 90 Chatham-street. The charge was also made that this house is a common gambling-house. A warrant was issued for the arrest of the parties named, and Capt. JOURDAN, of the Sixth Precinct, arrested on Saturday, TADE and FALVEY. BRUMORGER is lying sick at his residence up town. The prisoners were taken before Justice DOWLING, and they were required to find bail to answer before the Court of Sessions in the sum of $500 each. Alderman BARNEY KELLY became bound for TADE, and PETER TRACY for FALVEY.

abstract: The Reports from the Rio Grande
snippet: The Reports from the Rio Grande
lead_paragraph: The Mexican bulletin from the Rio Grande, by the way of New-Orleans, is, this morning, many degrees more belligerent in tone than any we have had for several weeks. On the 7th inst., as was reported some days ago, the Franco-Mexican steamer Antonio was fired upon from the Texan side of the river by some fillibustering squad, of whose nationality, purposes or character nothing whatever is definitely known. An Imperial journal published at Matamoras, however, pronounces the assault "one of the most dastardly outrages ever perpetrated on the frontier." Only two persons were hurt in the engagement. But as the Antonio had on board a detachment of Franco-Mexican marines, and had been previously under heavy fire from the Mexican side of the river, the firing from the "neutral" side was looked upon at Matamoras as an exceedingly outrageous insult. The assailants are alleged to have been dressed in "Federal uniforms." And to this fact, it is left to be inferred, it was due that the French commander refrained from returning the fire from the "neutral" side of the river.

abstract: SEVENTY-FIRST REGIMENT NATIONAL GUARD SOCIETY.--Companies B and H, of the Seventy-first Regiment, who visited Boston last August, on their return from their delightful trip, resolved to present their kind escort and friends, the Boston Fusiliers, with a testimonial in the shape of a set of resolutions handsomely engrossed and framed.
lead_paragraph: SEVENTY-FIRST REGIMENT NATIONAL GUARD SOCIETY. -- Companies B and H, of the Seventy-first Regiment, who visited Boston last August, on their return from their delightful trip, resolved to present their kind escort and friends, the Boston Fusiliers, with a testimonial in the shape of a set of resolutions handsomely engrossed and framed. The frame which is to contain the resolutions will be seven feet high and five feet wide, and will have in a double-rowed circle around the resolutions the vignette of every member of the two companies who went on the excursion. As no pains or expense have been spared in getting the testimonials up, it promises to be one of the handsomest affairs of the kind that has ever left the city, and while it reflects creditably to the good taste of the excursionists, it cannot fail to be a source of great gratification to the worthy recipients. The picture, though relayed, rapidly approaching completion, and will be exhibited on Broadway for a short time, preparatory to its being sent to its destination.

abstract: National Protective Union
snippet: National Protective Union
lead_paragraph: Some days since a female operative in one of the numerous mills situate in Paterson, N.J., received a parcel of circulars embodying a scheme for the award of prizes, by an association entitled the "National Protective Union." This scheme of prizes was a very flattering one, the "capital" cash prize being no less than $5,000, with a "special" cash prize of $2,000, and a "surplus" prize of $1,000. These three magnificent prizes were attended by a troop of smaller prizes, ranging from $500 down. Inclosed with this attractive schedule was a specimen ticket, and all the necessary directions for obtaining any quantity of these tickets, and considerable gratuitous information regarding the modus operandi of the "Union" setting forth so dazzling a scheme for speedy wealth.

abstract: Both GONZALEZ and PELLICIER, the alleged murderers of OTERO, are still held in irons by Capt. WADDY, in the Myrtle-avenue Police-station, Brooklyn.
lead_paragraph: Both GONZALEZ and PELLICIER, the alleged murderers of OTERO, are still held in irons by Capt. WADDY, in the Myrtle-avenue Police-station, Brooklyn. They stood up stoutly until yesterday morning, maintaining a dogged stubbornness, and seemingly entertaining some hope of escape from the awful weight of evidence that Capt. WADDY and his officers have accumulated against them; but yesterday morning they broke down, and so sensibly was GONZALEZ affected, that for a time he was unable to stand erect in his cell. He was yesterday morning, in a close coach, accompanied by Capt. WADDY and an officer. The visit was made as secretly as possible; nevertheless, at the undertaker's, a number of persons having recognized Capt. WADDY, the inference was at once drawn that one of his companions was the murderer, and naturally quite a throng soon gathered in the street; but there was no disturbance. On catching a glimpse of the corpse, GONZALEZ blanched and turned away; and when drawn near the body he shuddered, but uttered not a word. He was almost immediately removed in the Masonic Building, in Fulton-street, and here -- as had been previously done in the case of PELLICIER -- his photograph was taken by Mr. WILLIAMSON. As at the undertaker's, so here, a multitude collected in front of the doors, and before Capt. WADDY was ready to take his departure, the multitude had been augmented to the number of more than a thousand persons, and it was with no little difficulty that Capt. WADDY replaced his prisoner in the coach. He was then rapidly whirled off to the Forty-fourth Precinct Police-station, and remanded to his cell in the basement Yesterday afternoon, of No. 1,703 South Sixth-street, Philadelphia, master of the bark Thomas, appeared at the Forty-fourth Precinct Station-house and identified both GONZALEZ and the old garments which he cast aside on the morning following the murder, and which Capt. WADDY's men seized on Saturday evening in the sleeping chamber which GONZALEZ had occupied in the German boarding-house, at No. 217 Centre-street. There was blood on the right coat-sleeve, blood on the shirt, blood spattered on the pantaloons, and blood in one of the pockets into which GONZALEZ, after committing the murder, thrust his hand, Having also identified GONZALEZ, Capt. PETERSON went to view the body of OTERO, and this also he identified. He then returned to the Myrtle-avenue Police-station, and there made concerning his knowledge of the murderer and the murdered. Captain PETERSON has been eighteen years in the Cuban trade, sailing from New-York to Cardenas. In both cities he has a large circle of acquaintances, particularly among commercial men. He knew OTERO in Cardenas as the keeper of a confectionery, restaurant and billiard saloon, and he says that OTERO was highly respected there. Last year OTERO drew a capital prize of $25,000 in the Royal Havana Lottery, and not $10,000 as was at first reported. With this money he undertook to erect a new theatre capable of seating 216 persons in the parquet; and he had progressed so far with this enterprise that at the time of his departure for New-York only the furniture and a few trilling fittings for the interior were needed to complete the house. He had expended nearly $20,000 on the theatre, and had only about $5,000 available funds left; but this he conceived to be sufficient, and with it he came to New-York. On board the Havana steamship he made the acquaintance of GONZALEZ, a Havanese rectifier, who had been thrown out of employment by the burning of a distillery, and who was bound for New-York to seek a position, as the TIMES has already said. Arriving in this city, OTERO sought Capt. PETERSON and arranged for the transportation of his purchases to Cuba, and the Captain being well acquainted in the city OTERO secured his services as a guide. GONZALEZ appears to have dogged his steps until, desiring to try the Philadelphia market, he accompanied the Captain to Philadelphia. GONZALEZ tarried behind during this trip, and spent most of his time in the Barcelona Hotel and at the Hotel de Cuba. In Philadelphia OTERO priced thirty-six iron columns for the interior of his theatre, an 1 bade Capt. PETERSON purchase a sewing-machine for his (OTERO's) sister-in-law in Cardenas. This machine was brought to this city yesterday, and stowed in the hold of Capt. PETERSON's vessel, at her pier at the foot of Dover-street.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. The announcement that the last performance of "Crispino e la Comare" would take place last night, filled the Academy of Music in such a degree that even "standing-room only" could not be had, and many of those who had not procured their tickets in time had to wend their way back to their homes.
lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The announcement that the last performance of "Crispino e la Comare" would take place last night, filled the Academy of Music in such a degree that even "standing-room only" could not be had, and many of those who had not procured their tickets in time had to wend their way back to their homes. It is unnecessary to mention again the merits of the singers, and we may be allowed to state only that the performance elicited the most genuine and best deserved applause. To-night the rehearsal of the "Africaine" will prevent the performance of an opera, but to-morrow "Faust" will be performed, when Miss PHILLIPS will resume her role of Isabel. On Friday the "Africaine" will be performed without fail. The demand for tickets is immense.

abstract: Jordan, Samuel H., New-York
snippet: Jordan, Samuel H., New-York
lead_paragraph: On Saturday night, shortly after 10 o'clock, a man named SAMUEL H. JORDAN called upon Mr. GEO. TAYLOR at the Frankfort House, corner of William and Frankfort streets, and asked for a room. No. 105 was assigned him, and about two hours afterward he retired. He was not again seen alive. During Sunday afternoon, BRIDGET SMITH, the chambermaid of that floor, went to the door of No. 105 for the purpose, of putting it in order; she found the door unlocked, and was about entering when she perceived that the bed was occupied. Receiving no answer to her request to be admitted, Bridget opened the door still wider and saw Mr. JORDAN lying in a nude state across the foot of the bed, evidently helpless. Becoming somewhat alarmed, the chambermaid communicated the fact to the clerk at the office, and on further examination it was discovered that JORDAN was dead.

lead_paragraph: The news from Matamoras, though of no later date, seems to confirm the report that the Imperial steamor Antonio had been fired upon from the Texas shore. The statement, though appearing in the Ranchero, the Imperialist paper, is explicit, to the effect, that on the 7th inst., as the Antonio was pushing her way up the river under heavy fire from the Liberal forces, she grounded, and when in this plight, received a fire from the opposite side, and that the hostile party were dressed in the uniform of United States soldiers. Two marines were wounded. The Ranchero asserts that the Antonio did not return the fire, and laments the occurrence as threatening the peaceful relations of Mexico and the United States. It will be remembered that the reported firing by the Imperialists on some barges that had broken loose from the Texas shore, and supposed to be Yankee rams or hostile engines of some kind, was subsequent to the attack on the Antonio, on or about the 14th inst.

abstract: Between two and three thousand people were attracted to the Capitoline Ball Ground, Brooklyn, yesterday afternoon, by the announcement of a "Grand Match between the Atlantic Nine and a picked Nine of New-York and New-Jersey." On arriving at the above lacality, however, it was found, as usual on these occasions, that only half of the expected "picked nine" had put in an appearance; besides which, it was discovered that, instead of the usual tariff of ten cents admission, a fee of twenty-five cents was demanded of every visitor to the grounds. This extra charge was made by the club, the proprietors of the ground having given the players the use of it for the day for their benefit. After waiting until an hour after the time announced for the commencement of play, a field nine was made up from those of the party originally selected who were present, and such others as would like to "take a hand in," and finally the match was made up in this way. Neither Messrs. WALKER. PAGE. MCMAHON or ZELLER took part in the match, and their absence of course materially weakened the team opposed to the Atlantics; in fact, the club nine had an easy thing of it, and the contest turned out to be a one-sided affair, hundreds leaving before the game was over. Some good play was shown in the course of the match, especially by the Atlantics, but the field nine labored under the disadvantage common to all amalgamated nines, viz.: unfamiliarity with each other's play. The contest proved to be one pecuniarily advantageous to the parties who got it up, and consequently it was a very satisfactory affair. We append the score:

abstract: The Supreme Court, Circuit, part two, Justice E. DARWIN SMITH, presiding, was engaged all day yesterday in the trial of the case of ANN CURRAN, Administratrix, , of MICHAEL CURRAN, deceased, vs. The Warren and Chemical Manufacturing Company.
lead_paragraph: The Supreme Court, Circuit, part two, Justice E. DARWIN SMITH, presiding, was engaged all day yesterday in the trial of the case of ANN CURRAN, Administratrix, &c., of MICHAEL CURRAN, deceased, vs. The Warren and Chemical Manufacturing Company. The defendants are a company organized for the purpose of refining petroleum and other oils. The deceased was employed by some boiler-makers to go to Hunter's Point, where defendants had an establishment, for the purpose of repairing a boiler. He worked inside the boiler for several hours, on the 13th of January last, and at noon went out to dinner, and was gone half an hour, leaving two Argand lamps burning inside. Immediately after entering, upon his return from dinner, he fell down and soon expired. The boiler in question, was, by means of some internal arrangements, connected with other boilers, and plaintiff claims that the poisonous gasses generated in the other boilers, were, by the negligence of the defendants' agents, allowed to enter the boiler in which deceased was at work. The action is brought by the mother of the deceased, and the claim is for $5,000, in pursuance of the statute in such case made and provided. CURRAN having died intestate, plaintiff sues as administratrix. The case is still on trial.

abstract: Trade and Commerce in
snippet: Trade and Commerce in
lead_paragraph: caused the sudden collapse of on enterprise which was some time ago projected, with the view of opening up direct steam communication between Genoa and New-York? The scheme had much in it to recommend it Every succeeding year, too, makes the trade of the Kingdom of Italy a larger prize to be aimed at and shared in. Genoa and Naples have especially shown an unparalleled commercial revival since the establishment of the new government. And the old decayed towns of the Adriatic are said to be waking up to on activity they have not known for centuries. It is true Italy is still far behind in her foreign trade, as compared with France, Belgium and other countries of Europe. But the sixty million dollars, which make up about the present value of her exports and imports, will be doubled within the next decade, if the stability of the government and the progress of liberal legislation are such as the history of the kingdom for the last five years gives promise of. What has become of the Genoa Steamship Line?

abstract: Roberts, M. O. and the Mayoralty
snippet: Roberts, M. O. and the Mayoralty
lead_paragraph: It is claimed that the fact that MARSHALL O. ROBERTS was one of the staunchest supporters of the war, gives him no title to the support of the Union party for the Mayoralty. Were it said no conclusive title, we might admit it. Were he dishonest and corrupt, or were he so weak as to be transformable into a mere tool for other men of that character, nothing he might have said or done in the war would make him fit to be our Mayor. Personal integrity and firmness are indispensable qualifications for the office. If absent, all other recommendations are worthless. But nobody pretends that Mr. ROBERTS is deficient in these respects. The first imputation against his personal character has not yet been made. It is conceded that in that point he is every whit as much beyond reproach as the best of his competitors. That being the case, we say that the fact that he has been a thorough-going Union man through the times which tried men's souls, when every one of his competitors was more or less derelict, made it right that he should be put in nomination by the Union party, and entitles him to the vote of every truly loyal man.

abstract: Riot by "Live-Oak Volunteers"
snippet: Riot by "Live-Oak Volunteers"
lead_paragraph: The peace of the good citizens of Astoria was outrageously violated, yesterday, by the riff-raff following of one of our Volunteer Target Companies. The result, however, thanks to the energetic action of the Metropolitan Police, was not such as to afford encouragement for future performances of a similar sort. About 12 A.M., the "Live Oak Volunteers," composed of the members of the old fire company No. 44, crossed the Hell-Gate Ferry, for a target excursion. There were fifty muskets, and accompanying them were from fifty to one hundred rowdies of the kind known as "runners" -- a class whose vocation seems to be nearly at an end in this city.

abstract: Mormon Question and Its Easy Solution
snippet: Mormon Question and Its Easy Solution
lead_paragraph: Our correspondent in Utah gave, through our issue of yesterday, a somewhat stimulating review of the present condition of things among the Mormons. He depicted the despotic power exercised by the Prophet BRIGHAM YOUNG; declared that YOUNG and the other hierarchs are treasonably disposed toward the United States Government; and not only this, but the Mormon people, under the advice of their leaders, are preparing for resistance, even to war, against any interference with what they call their religious faith -- which latter article, as appears from all they say and do, is reduced to but one item -- polygamy. The burden of the Mormon sermons to the people is to arm, and "arming they are." Nor is this the most impressive circumstance. There is actually an individual designated as "Drill-Master-General," who has been for a long time actively engaged in the business of arming and drilling the forces of the Church of Latter Day Saints for the great battle of Armageddon. Our correspondent gave some other items of Mormon news less portentous than these, but which, nevertheless, may deserve as much attention and more immediate action; such as, that there are Federal officials who take part in treasonable practices, who indulge extensively in polygamy, and who fail to do their duty as assessors and collectors of government taxes. We earnestly trust that the authorities at Washington will see that this last-mentioned matter is rectified, even before making preparations to meet the Mormon hosts on the final field of Armageddon.

abstract: Abroad and at Home
snippet: Abroad and at Home
lead_paragraph: lish papers report a better prospect of cotton next year from India and Egypt than at any previous time. The conditions of raising and transporting the staples in both these countries are greatly improving; and if the price could be kept up to the present figure for ten years longer, a permanent and sufficient supply for the European market might by that time be obtained. But it is here that the peril and the fear arises. For if cotton can be again raised in this country at anything near the old price, or even at the rate of fifteen to twenty cents a pound, then neither the Indian nor Egyptian growers can compete with us, and their prosperity will collapse. We think there is good reason for other countries to fear this. We believe that cotton will be planted over a very large surface next Spring; and by the year following next, when the South shall be well supplied with capital; when its labor and industry will be thoroughly organized; when emigration shall have poured thither, and when the use of new and improved machinery shall be extensively introduced, we shall probably give Europe all the cotton it needs at ten cents a pound, or less.

abstract: Hudson River; Train off Track; Misplaced Switch at Tivoli
snippet: Hudson River; Train off Track; Misplaced Switch at Tivoli
lead_paragraph: SWITCH-TENDER. -- The Cincinnati express train, due here at 6:30 this morning, ran off the track at Tivoli, on the Hudson River Railroad, smashing up the engine, tender and baggage-car, but fortunately no one injured. The switch was placed the wrong way, and the only excuse the man had to give was, "he didn't think it was time for the train to arrive yet." He very soon after was among the missing. The train was delayed between eight and nine hours.

abstract: The Approaching Session of
snippet: The Approaching Session of
lead_paragraph: All eyes are beginning to turn toward Washington, which is soon to be the scene of the most important legislation the country has ever known. During the war, the functions of Congress were comparatively limited. They were exercised mainly upon supply bills for the maintenance of the war, and upon other measures that were calculated only to meet the peculiar necessities of the times. Further than that they could not well go. The utter impossibility of forecasting either the length of the war or the condition in which it would leave the country, precluded the establishment of any comprehensive and definite plans. Congress could do little else than talk vague theories and vote half measures.

abstract: We have to-day another batch of the correspondence between Mr. ADAMS and Lord RUSSELL on the question of British neutrality during the war. There are no features in the letters now published that can be called new. But there are certain points which were involved
lead_paragraph: We have to-day another batch of the correspondence between Mr. ADAMS and Lord RUSSELL on the question of British neutrality during the war. There are no features in the letters now published that can be called new. But there are certain points which were involved in some obscurity in the former correspondence, now made intelligible and clear. Lord RUSSELL, in a previous communication, had stated that "Her Majesty's Government are ready to consent to the appointment of a commission, to which shall be referred all claims arising during the late civil war, which the two Powers shall agree to refer to the Commissioners." The British Minister now hastens to explain that, "if the United States were to propose to refer claims arising out of the captures made by the Alabama and Shenandoah to the Commissioners, the answer of Her Majesty's Government must be * * * For any acts of Her Majesty's subjects committed out of their jurisdiction and beyond their control the Government of Her Majesty are not responsible."

lead_paragraph: Yesterday morning Mr. S.D. Morris, District-Attorney of Kings County, called the attention of the Grand Jury to the fact that an atrocious murder had been committed in the City of Brooklyn, and he added that, thanks to the vigilance and energy of Capt. Waddy, of the Metropolitan Police, the murderers -- or two persons whom he had every reason to believe to have been guilty of the deed -- had been apprehended, and were in custody at the Forty-fourth Precinct Police-station, in Myrtle-avenue. Mr. Morris suggested, in view of the public indignation that had been roused by the crime, that the jury might do well to act upon the case at once; and concurring with the District-Attorney, the jurors adjourned to Capt. Waddy's station-house, and there saw the prisoners and their wounds, and viewed their clothing; after which they repaired to their rooms in the Kings County Court-house, and there examined several witnesses, and, it was rumored in Brooklyn last night, found true bills of indictment against both of the prisonera. It was further rumored that Gonzalez and Pellicier are to be arraigned.

SICKLES, of a squad of negroes charged with attacking and robbing a Mr. HOLTZCLAW, of that city, and threatening to take his life on Sunday last. Mr. HOLTZCLAW, in company with another gentleman...
lead_paragraph: The Savannah Republican, of the 25th inst., gives an account of the arraignment, on the 24th, before Col. SICKLES, of a squad of negroes charged with attacking and robbing a Mr. HOLTZCLAW, of that city, and threatening to take his life on Sunday last. Mr. HOLTZCLAW, in company with another gentleman and a colored man, were proceeding to a neighboring plantation for the purpose of exhuming the remains of a deceased son, when he was met by an armed crowd of negroes who ordered him to turn back. He and his companions did so, but they were followed by the crowd. They had not proceeded far when they were stopped by the negroes, and Mr. H. was compelled to give up his pistols and $70 in money. His companion was also compelled to give up all the money on his person. The negroes then took a vote as to whether they should murder HOLTZCLAW, but were persuaded not to do so by an old man among them. Col. SICKLES has ordered them to be tried before a military commission.

lead_paragraph: The trial of RACHEAL EBERLE vs. BREWSTER & SIMONSON was continued yesterday in the Supreme Court, Circuit, Part I., before Justice PECKHAM and a jury. The plaintiff claims about $5,000 damages for injuries done to her business in consequence of a disreputable saloon having been established in the lower part of the premises situated on Broadway, she having leased the upper part of the building for the manufacture and sale of hoop-skirts, stocking-supporters, &c. Her customers were principally ladies, and she alleges that her business was utterly ruined by reason of the acts of the defendants. Under a charge from the court the jury retired, and up to the time of the adjournment of the court they had not agreed. They will bring in a sealed verdict to-morrow.

abstract: Peto, Sir Morton's, Speech on his Return
snippet: Peto, Sir Morton's, Speech on his Return
lead_paragraph: who left this city on the 1st inst., delivered a speech in Bristol, Eng., on the 13th, which was brought to us last evening by the European mails. It is largely devoted to a narration of his observations and experiences in the United States, and is at once very able, very friendly, highly eulogistic and highly enthusiastic. He told his auditors that "to understand America they must go there," and "no man of business entering life," said he, "should consider his education complete, until he paid a visit to the United States." He expressed himself as astounded beyond measure at our greatness, growth and power, as they had displayed themselves in war and in peace. On the great questions of the reconstruction of the Union and the maintenance of peace between America and England, he expressed himself as satisfied with the prospects; and the London Times' report of the speech says that a protest which he made against the Christian people of the two countries imbruing their hands in each other's blood was followed by "loud applause, the whole assemblage rising to their feet, and cheering the honorable Baronet most enthusiastically." In the same direction, the Times remarks: "Sir MORTON PETO concluded his able speech by expressing a belief that England and America would in the future, now that the great blot of slavery was abolished, be better friends, and come to a better understanding; and the only thing required to accomplish that was that they should go to America as he had done, and feel their warmth of friendship as he had. [Loud and long-continued cheering."] It is probable that English, statesmen and scholars will largely follow this excellent advice in the coming years.

abstract: businesses and interests are making movements preliminary to appealing to Congress for a reduction of their taxation. They have a right to do this; but it would be well for them not to be over-sanguine as to the result in general. The same thing was tried to a large extent last Winter, but in most cases Congress was difficult to move, if not quite immovable. It would appear from the number and variety of appeals then and now that nearly every interest considers itself unduly taxed. Many, if not all, unquestionably are so; but as there is no other means beside taxation of meeting our heavy expenses, paying the large interest upon our great debt, and getting our finances into wholesome condition, it is evident that heavy taxation must be patiently borne. The fact that every business complains that it is disproportionately taxed in reference to all others, would seem to indicate that a pretty fair approach to justice has been made, upon the whole. The members of Congress will moreover remember that many of the appeals which will come before them have already been maturely considered by the Commission upon Revenue and Taxation, which has been in session in this city for the greater part of the year.

abstract: A discharged soldier, LOUIS FORGE, stopping at the Soldiers' Home, was brutally beaten and robbed on Tuesday evening, by WILHELM MEYER, a, barkeeper in a groggery corner of Church and Lispenard streets, who was assisted by an unknown man and a streetwalker named ANNIE JOHNSTON, alias "Slippery Annie." During the melee Forge was knocked down...
lead_paragraph: A discharged soldier, LOUIS FORGE, stopping at the Soldiers' Home, was brutally beaten and robbed on Tuesday evening, by WILHELM MEYER, a, barkeeper in a groggery corner of Church and Lispenard streets, who was assisted by an unknown man and a streetwalker named ANNIE JOHNSTON, alias "Slippery Annie." During the melee Forge was knocked down and dragged into the street, where a pistol-shot was fired, the ball taking effect in his right hand, and shattering the thumb and fore-finger, and a roll of bills amounting to $140 was taken from him. Subsequently the two whose names are given above were arrested, and yesterday they were committed by Justice DODGE for trial, without bail. The soldier is now at the House of Detention, awaiting the forthcoming trial.

abstract: SERIOUS SHOOTING AFFRAY IN JERSEY CITY. -- Yesterday afternoon a difficulty occurred between two canal boatmen named JOHN QUINN and AARON ROWLOF, at the Morris Canal basin, in Jersey City, which resulted in QUINN being shot by ROWLOF, and seriously, if not fatally wounded. The injured man was taken to the station-house, where he was attended by Dr. HADDEN. It appears that the gun was loaded with buck-shot, two of which penetrated the skull just over the left eye, and another entered the cheek. The doctor did not succeed in extracting the balls from the skull. ROWLOF was arrested by Constable STROBER, and was committed to the City Prison to await the result of the injuries. QUINN states that the difficulty originated in reference to tying up their boats; that he threatened to put a hole through ROWLOF's head, when the latter went into the cabin and brought out a gun and fired at him with the result above stated. Both men are rough and desperate characters.

abstract: The Poughkeepsie Eagle reports an accident on the Hudson River Railroad, on Wednesday, near Tivoli, caused by the misplacement of a switch. The Albany train down was run off into the rocky side of the road, upsetting the baggage and two passenger cars. The fireman was the only person injured, but the escape of the passengers was marvelous, as the train was under full headway, and it must be attributed to the check from the patent brakes, which the engineer had presence of mind enough to spring. The switchman has not since been heard from.

abstract: On What Shall we Drink
snippet: On What Shall we Drink
lead_paragraph: our protest the other day against the prevailing custom of drinking strong liquors, such as whisky, brandy, gin, &c., and also heavy beers and ales, the Tribune is anxious that we should furnish it specific information as to what it shall drink? We thought we had done our duty to inquirers, in giving warning against the articles we indicated, and such of their well-known congeners as are included in "et cetera." If all such drinks were properly handled by the community and the Tribune, there would be no need for our pointing such morals as we did on Monday. But, as the Tribune demands that, having condemned the profane and criminal liquors, we shall now indicate the proper beverage for its use, we shall not scruple to do so. We boldly say, then -- for ordinary use -- Croton, a liquid whose merits are appreciated both by men and beasts. If the inquirer should unfortunately be afflicted with any derangement of the stomach, we refer to the excellent advice given for such cases by St. Paul to Timothy.

abstract: The steamer Scotia, from Liverpool Nov. 18, via Queenstown Nov. 19, arrived at this port yesterday. It is stated that Mr. DUDLEY, our Consul at Liverpool, had decided to send the Shenandoah to New-York, and that the ship would probably leave the Mersey on the 21st. Files of Fenian documents are said to have been found at the residence of STEPHENS, the arrested Head Centre, and that Fenianism is now an open book to the administrators of the law. Full details of the revolt in Jamaica had been received in England, and the conduct of the military authorities in its suppression excited much comment. The News and Star condemn their severity in very strong language, while the Times and Herald regard it as entirely commendable. The news of the blockade of the Chilian ports by Spain, created great indignation in England. It was rumored that several blockade-runners were fitting out to test its effectiveness. The French army has been reduced about 40,000 men. The suppression of the rebellion in Algeria was progressing favorably. It is said that Austria has resolved to reduce her army in Venetia.

abstract: Thanksgiving Proclamation
snippet: Thanksgiving Proclamation
lead_paragraph: In accordance with the proclamations of the Chief Magistrates both of this State and the Federal Union, who have set apart Thursday, the 7th day of December next, as a day of general thanksgiving, I, C. GODFREY GUNTHER, Mayor of the City of New-York, hereby respectfully recommend to my fellow-citizens to observe the same by abstaining from secular avocations, by uniting in public worship, by enjoying in moderation the fruits of their honest toil, and by imparting to the poor and needy of their abundance.

lead_paragraph: The great success of life and fire insurance companies and their value, both to the insured and the stockholders, is so well understood and acknowledged as to render any argument in their favor superfluous. But there are several kinds of insurance which are comparatively new, and of which the community is not so well advised. Perhaps the most valuable, and destined to be the most popular of these, is the insurance against accidents.

abstract: Invitation to U. S. Alliance with France and England
snippet: Invitation to U. S. Alliance with France and England
lead_paragraph: The difficulty between Spain and Chili -- in which we Americans have no interest, except that we wish well to all the South American republics -- has raised a clamor in the English press for the joint intervention of the "three" Great Powers -- England, France and the United States -- against the pretensions of Spain. It would be exceedingly desirable, no doubt, that the three Powers named should come to an understanding on all questions relating to the different States and governments on this continent and all over the world. But there has never been any such common agreement heretofore, and we do not exactly see why the partnership should be entered into in the particular interest of Chili.

abstract: The new steamer Niagara, Capt. COUCH, of the New-York and Virginia Steamship Company, made her engineer's trial trip on Tuesday, returning late in the evening. This vessel and the Saratoga are precisely alike, and were built by D.D. WESTERVELT, at the Westervelt Shipyard.
lead_paragraph: The new steamer Niagara, Capt. COUCH, of the New-York and Virginia Steamship Company, made her engineer's trial trip on Tuesday, returning late in the evening. This vessel and the Saratoga are precisely alike, and were built by D.D. WESTERVELT, at the Westervelt Shipyard. They are, without doubt, the finest steamers in the coast trade, and are to replace the Yorktown and Jamestown, which were converted into rebel war vessels, and destroyed when Gen. GRANT took Richmond. They are 230 feet in length, 39 feet beam on deck, 15 feet hold, and measure about 1,100 tons. Their hulls are of peculiar construction, allowing great deck capacity; their fittings are neat, and in excellent good taste. Everything has been so arranged as to give the passengers all the comforts attainable on board ship. The engines of the Niagara, which are massive, and of fine finish, were built at the Allaire Work, and have a 60-inch cylinder, and 11 feet stroke of piston. A large donkey boiler and engines are located on the main deck, which furnishes power for pumping and hoisting cargo. The Niagara made full 15 miles per hour, running at the measured mile between Thirteenth and Thirty-third streets. The engine worked beautifully -- as smoothly as one that had been running a year. She sails on Saturday from Pier No. 21 for Richmond. The Saratoga will follow in about two weeks.

abstract: The Union electors of the Eleventh Assembly District met at Lincoln Hall, last night, and organized a Marshall O. Roberts Club. THERON R. BUTLER was elected President and GILEAD B. NASH Secretary. Resolutions were adopted naming MARSHALL O. ROBERTS and MURRAY HOFFMAN as the candidates of the club for Mayor and Corporation Counsel, GEORGE HETTRICK for Councilman, JONES L. HASTIE for School Commissioner, and GABRIEL VAN COTT for Trustee. It was also agreed to attend the ratification meeting on Friday night in a body. JOHN V. GRIDLEY was chosen Marshal for the occasion. A transparency was ordered, and committees on a ward meeting to provide for the canvass were appointed. The club will meet nightly, till Mr. ROBERTS is elected. There will be a ratification meeting at Lincoln Hall, at the corner of Thirty-third-street and Eighth-avenue to-night. The Twentieth Ward is around, and will increase her vote for the Union ticket.

abstract: THE CITY PARK MURDER -- ARRAIGNMENT AND COMMITTAL OF THE PRISONERS CHARGED WITH THE DEED. -- The two men accused of the murder of Mr. JOSE GARCIA OTERO, on Wednesday evening last, having been found guilty by a Coroner's jury on Tuesday night, were brought before the Kings County Court of Oyer and Terminer yesterday morning. They were brought to the office of Police Inspector FOLK at an early hour by Capt. WADDY and several of his men. It having become known that the prisoners were there a crowd of several hundred persons soon collected, all anxious to take a look at them. They were subsequently conducted to the new court-house, where they were arraigned before Judge LOTT in the Court of Oyer and Terminer -- an indictment having been found against them the day previous. The prisoners, heretofore known as JOSE GONZALEZ and THEODORE MARTINEZ PELLICIER, gave their names respectively, the first, as JOSE GONZALEZ FERNANDEZ, and the second as FRANCISCO GENE SALVADOR. FERNANDEZ is 38 years of age, and SALVADOR 22 years old. GONZALEZ, by which name he is best known, betrayed some nervousness on his arraignment, but PELLICIER showed very little, if any emotion. Both pleaded not guilty, and stated they were poor and had no counsel. PELLICIER said he had a friend in New-York, who he thought would pay his counsel fees, but did not know where to find him. The Judge stated that he would appoint counsel for them. The accused were then remanded to jail, and it is understood that they will be tried during the present term of the Court of Oyer and Terminer. There was some difficulty in conducting the prisoners to the jail in consequence of the crowd, but being strongly guarded they were safely conducted to their place of confinement.

Both pleaded not guilty, and stated they were poor and had no counsel. PELLICIER said he had a friend in New-York, who he thought would pay his counsel fees, but did not know where to find him. The Judge stated that he would appoint counsel for them. The accused were then remanded to jail, and it is understood that they will be tried during the present term of the Court of Oyer and Terminer. There was some difficulty in conducting the prisoners to the jail in consequence of the crowd, but being strongly guarded they were safely conducted to their place of confinement.

abstract: We have advices from the Rio Grande of the 19th inst., five days later than heretofore printed. The Ranchero says that two small boats, on leaving the American side of the river to attack the Antonio, were fired into, and the party probably killed or drowned.
lead_paragraph: We have advices from the Rio Grande of the 19th inst., five days later than heretofore printed. The Ranchero says that two small boats, on leaving the American side of the river to attack the Antonio, were fired into, and the party probably killed or drowned. Whether the assailants were armed with torpedoes, or what evidence there was of hostile intent on their part, is not stated. The same paper gives a current report that a Federal Paymaster, escaping into Mexico with a large sum of money, had been robbed and murdered by some of the Liberal troops. The amnesty offered by MAXIMILIAN is said to have been accepted by some of the Liberals.

abstract: ten years since the soft click of the Wheeler & Wilson Sewing-Machine was first heard. Simple, quiet and efficient, it made friends wherever seen. The highest honors were accorded it from the Atlantic to the Pacific, from the Lakes to the Gulf. For no other invention has the highest award in this country been so uniform and general. Industrial, mechanical and agricultural associations have crowned it with the highest honors, and hundreds of country and village fairs have been honored in honoring it. So uniform and certain have been these awards, that the company manufacturing them have, as a general thing, ceased to exhibit them here in competition with others.

abstract: ELLIS, one of the most enterprising of the sewing-machine men of our city, has just opened rooms for family and general sewing -- entirely distinct from his other up-town establishment, at the corner of Twenty-second-street and Broadway, for the rental and sale of the Wheeler & Wilson, and Howe's sewing-machines. This establishment is at No. 896 Broadway, between Nineteenth and Twentieth streets, in the same building with Mons. BLOT's well-known Cooking Academy. Mr ELLIS has made every arrangement in this new establishment to supply, at the shortest notice, all kinds of family sewing from the plainest to the most delicate work, so that a complete traveling outfit for a lady or an entire family can be prepared at a day's notice. It is but little more than two years since Mr. ELLIS opened this up-town store, for the rental and sale of WHEELER & WILSON's, and HOWE's sewing-machines. The enterprise, which was then projected as an untried and doubtful experiment has so rapidly grown in public favor, that from a limited business, conducted as a simple convenience, it has become a recognized necessity, and hundreds and thousands of machines have been and are being sold, to be paid for in small installments, to widows and daughters of soldiers and others unable to pay the full price of a machine at once, and of all these cases not one single woman has failed to comply with the very liberal conditions made by Mr. ELLIS. In this way hundreds of humble homes have become the possessors of the machines, and much want and suffering prevented, while remunerative employment has been given to many hundreds of operators -- gratuitously taught -- to work the machine. Many refined and intelligent ladies have sought independence in the respectable remunerative employment which Mr. ELLIS has organized and is now extending in his new enterprise. -- Tribune.

abstract: one of the phases of suffering and destitution in this city by an item in the annual police report for the year ending the coming month. It appears from the statistics there given that no less than 64,247 persons sought lodgings in the cells of the station-houses of the city during the year. Those who have had opportunity for observing the kind of accommodations furnished to lodgers in these places, can in some measure appreciate the depths of necessity and misery to which this vast body of unfortunate men and women were driven before they sought such shelter. We understand, of course, that the figures here given include a considerable number of what are called "revolvers," or individuals who appear and reappear from time to time at the station-houses as lodgers. But even making deductions for these, there are still enough left to appal us. Such a condition of things is a frightful commentary upon our civilization and morality -- and society. While it furnishes material for thought to the philosopher, it should also excite beneficence and charity in the Christian. Last night, for example, was a pitiless wintry night for the homeless and, penniless vagrant, and a pitiful one for those who had no lodging but the cell of a station-house.
